<L>To &thorn;at &thorn;e prophetus whilen . of oure lord sede.</L>
<L N="665">After &thorn;at ei&yogh;te dawes . fulfulled were iwis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> Postq(uam) consummati sunt dies octo; <I>s. Luc. 2, 21</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is child was circumsised, . his name iclepud is</L>
<L><ABBR>Jhc</ABBR>, as it was inempned . of &thorn;e angel bi fore,</L>
<L>Ar he were in his moder wombe . ikened o&thorn;er ibore;</L>
<L>I circumsised was &thorn;e child . as a &yogh;eres day,</L>
<L N="670">I corue of is ende of is membre, . as hit fel in &thorn;e lay.</L>
<L>&thorn;o schedde &thorn;is holi &thorn;ing furst . his blod for man,</L>
<L>&thorn;o he nas bote seueni&yogh;t old, . wel &yogh;ong he bigan;</L>
<L>&thorn;ei he hedde lengore abide, . he mi&yogh;te han ihed wo inow</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; inne III an &thorn;ritti &yogh;er, . &thorn;at &thorn;e folk him slow.</L>
<L N="675">Swete <ABBR>ihc</ABBR>, &thorn;e grete loue . &thorn;at &thorn;ow vs gonne sone schewe!</L>
<L>&thorn;at of &thorn;at &thorn;ow were on er&thorn;e . gode dawes heddest fewe,</L>
<L>And bi gonne &thorn;o for vs so &yogh;ong . to schede &thorn;i blod,</L>
<L>To kerue of &thorn;i tendre vlesch, . <ABBR>Jhc</ABBR>, &thorn;ow art god!</L>
<L>&thorn;ow nere bi &yogh;ete in none sunne, . wher fore me scholde &thorn;e for drawe</L>
<L N="680">And kerue of &thorn;e ende of &thorn;i membre, . as hit fel in &thorn;e lawe.</L>
<L>Alle men &thorn;at on er&thorn;e wrou&yogh;ten . &thorn;e sunne of sodomie</L>
<L>Dei&yogh;eden ek, &thorn;o god was bore . of his moder marie,</L>
<L>At otime &thorn;orw al &thorn;e world . at ode&thorn; vchon.
<PB REF="00000139.tif" N="95"></L>
<L>Oure lord ne nom neuer of sunne . so gret wreche non.</L>
<L N="685">&thorn;er me may seo : of alle sunne . &thorn;er a&yogh;en non nis,</L>
<L>So gret heo is &thorn;at men ne scholde it nempne . bote in warninge iwis;</L>
<L>So foul heo was &thorn;at god nolde . &thorn;at heo bi laften aliue</L>
<L>In mannes fourme, &thorn;at he nam; . &thorn;er fore he let hem to driue.</L>
<L>Sterren honureden oure lord, . &thorn;o he was ibore;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> Stella.</NOTE></L>
<L N="690">Vor balaam &thorn;e prophete seide . vele hondred &yogh;er bi fore:</L>
<L>&thorn;at asterre springe scholde . of Jacobs kuinde.</L>
<L>Euer eft &thorn;e hei&yogh;emen of &thorn;e lond . &thorn;e sterren hedden in muinde;</L>
<L>Heo beden &thorn;at among hem moste . som tokninge &thorn;er of come.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e hexte men of &thorn;e lond . a conseil hedden inome:</L>
<L N="695">Twelf stalewarde men to wake . vche ni&yogh;t heo toke</L>
<L>Vpon an hei&yogh; hul al longe ni&yogh;t, . after &thorn;ulke sterre loke.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> loke <I>fehlt</I> to.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o oure lord was ibore, . as he wolde &thorn;at it were,</L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;reo kinges come for &thorn;ulke sterre . to loke &thorn;er after &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if heo mi&yogh;ten ou&yogh;t &thorn;er of iseo; . &thorn;e oking het Jaspar,</L>
<L N="700">&thorn;e o&thorn;er het melchior, . &thorn;e &thorn;ridde baltazar.</L>
<L>In orisons heo weoren longe . &thorn;at oure lord hem sende</L>
<L>Som tokninge of &thorn;ulke sterre, . ar heo hamward wende.</L>
<L>&thorn;o sei&yogh;en heo in heuene a sterre . swi&thorn;e bri&yogh;t, as heo stode,</L>
<L>A midde &thorn;e sterre achild . al blodi on &thorn;e rode.</L>
<L N="705">&thorn;o bigan &thorn;at child to speke: . go&thorn; now bi liue, he sede,<MILESTONE N="35" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e lond of Jude! . ano&thorn;er sterre ow schal lede;</L>
<L>&thorn;er &yogh;e schulen finde achild ibore, . king of alle kinge,</L>
<L>Of whom &yogh;e desire&thorn; so muche . to wite som tokninge.</L>
<L>&thorn;o lokeden heo, as it est ward were, . ano&thorn;er sterre heo sei&yogh;e;</L>
<L N="710">So cler &thorn;ing ne so bri&yogh;t . heo ne sei&yogh;e neuer wi&thorn; ei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Glade heo weren, &thorn;o heo sei&yogh;e . &thorn;at heo wilneden so longe.</L>
<L>Vpe dromedaries heo wenden for&thorn;, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> swifte be&thorn; and stronge</L>
<L>And best duringe of alle bestes, . for no&thorn;er hors ne muile</L>
<L>Ne scholde so gret awei habbe igo . in so lute while.</L>
<L N="715">Al how heo sou&yogh;ten oure lord, . &thorn;e gospel telle&thorn; vs</L>
<L>&thorn;at me rat atwelf&thorn;e day; . &thorn;at bigynne&thorn; &thorn;us:</L>
<L>&thorn;o <ABBR>ihc</ABBR> was ibore . in bedleem of Jude,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> Cum natus &emacr;et <ABBR>ihc</ABBR> in bedleem; <I>s. Math. 2, 1</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bi eroudes day &thorn;e king, . lo &thorn;e kinges &thorn;reo<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> Hieroudes.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="96"></L>
<L>Comen out of &thorn;e lond of estlond . to ierlm iwis</L>
<L N="720">And seiden: whar is &thorn;e king of giwes . &thorn;at now iboren is?</L>
<L>Vor in &thorn;e estlond ver . his sterre we isei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &yogh;iftus we be&thorn; icome . vorte honuren him hei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e king heroudes herde &thorn;is, . destourbed he was,</L>
<L>And vch mon of ierlm . mid him vor is cas.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> is <I>st.</I> &thorn;is.</NOTE></L>
<L N="725">And alle princes &amp; &thorn;e hexte . prestes of &thorn;e lawe</L>
<L>And &thorn;e maistres of &thorn;e volk . to gadere he let drawe,</L>
<L>And enquerede of hem . whar crist were ibore.</L>
<L>And heo seiden: in bedleem; . vor &thorn;us it was bi fore</L>
<L>&thorn;orw &thorn;e prophetes iwrite . as in antiquite:</L>
<L N="730">And &thorn;ow, bedleem, &thorn;at art . lond of Jude,<NOTE PLACE="foot">in &thorn;e <I>fehlt vor</I> lond.</NOTE></L>
<L>A mong &thorn;e princes of Jude . lest ne artow nowt;</L>
<L>Vor &thorn;er wor&thorn; &yogh;et a duk . out of &thorn;e ibrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;at gouerne schal . &thorn;e volk of israel.</L>
<L>Eroudes &thorn;o al stilleliche . enquerede fol wel</L>
<L N="735">Of &thorn;e kinges ententifliche . &thorn;e time of &thorn;e sterre,</L>
<L>How longe heo hire hedden isei&yogh;e, . &thorn;at heo sei&yogh;en from ferre.</L>
<L>He sende hem &thorn;o to bedleem . and sede hem wordes milde:</L>
<L>Go&thorn; now ententifliche . &amp; enquere&thorn; of &thorn;e childe!</L>
<L>And whanne &yogh;e him habbe&thorn; ifounde, . bringe&thorn; me a&yogh;en tidinge,</L>
<L N="740">&thorn;at i<SUP>c</SUP> come ek and onure him . and &yogh;iftes him bringe.</L>
<L>&thorn;o heo hedden iherd &thorn;e king, . he wenden hem for&thorn; lo.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sterre, &thorn;at heo sei&yogh;en er . in &thorn;e estlonde so,</L>
<L>Wende euer bi fore hem, . vorte heo cam and stod</L>
<L>Euene ri&yogh;t ouer &thorn;e stude . &thorn;er &thorn;e child was so god.</L>
<L N="745">Glade, &thorn;o heo sei&yogh;en &thorn;e sterre, . wi&thorn; grete ioie heo were,</L>
<L>And, &thorn;o heo comen wi&thorn; inne &thorn;e hous, . &thorn;e child heo founde &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Mid marie is moder, . and adoun heo vellen to grounde</L>
<L>And kneleden and honoureden him . &amp; here tresor vnbounde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">honour. <I>Nach 648 folgen dann noch die 2 Verse:</I> &amp; &thorn;us ende&thorn; &thorn;e gospel : a myd winter ny&yogh;t Now&yogh; crist vs sende helpe of soule : &thorn;at al may dele &amp; dy&yogh;t. amen.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;iftes heo offreden to him . of stor and mirre and golde;<NOTE PLACE="foot">stor (= <I>Weihrauch</I>) ist richtige Lesart. [note alted based on Berichtigungen (p. XLIV); note originally read: <I>Ms.</I> tor; <I>ist</I> flor <I>zu lesen?</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="750">And &thorn;o a venge here onswere . in slepe, &thorn;at heo ne scholde</L>
<L>As &thorn;e angel hem het bi eroudes . a&yogh;en wende for ei&yogh;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> Hic finitur euang(elium).</NOTE></L>
<L>To here kinedom turne a&yogh;en . al bi ano&thorn;er wei&yogh;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ac <I>fehlt vor</I> To.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000141.tif" N="97"></L>
<L>In &thorn;is manere &thorn;e &thorn;reo kinges . oure lord out sou&yogh;te</L>
<L>In bedlem vrom here owne lond, . &amp; presaunt him brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L N="755">Of &thorn;e lond of arabie . and of perse heo were.</L>
<L>So fer est be&thorn; &thorn;ulke londes . &thorn;at nomon ne wone&thorn; now &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>A gret water &thorn;at me clepe&thorn; saba . in &thorn;e lond of perse is,</L>
<L>&thorn;er fore &yogh;et monie men . al &thorn;at lond clepe&thorn; iwis.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Statt</I> al <I>ist</I> also <I>zu lesen</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er fore dauid bi oure lord . in &thorn;e sauter whilen sede</L>
<L N="760">&thorn;at kinges of arabie &amp; saba . &yogh;iftes him scholden lede.</L>
<L>Heo ladden presaunt, vor he was king, . &amp; nomon sou&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> De donis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne to hem com in &thorn;e olde lawe, . bote he presaunt brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Gold and mirre and encense . &thorn;re kinges him laadde:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> en censense; laadde <I>st.</I> ladde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vch of &thorn;e &thorn;reo presauns . gret tokninge hadde:</L>
<L N="765">Gold is &thorn;ing of gret nobleie, . &thorn;at falle&thorn; ri&yogh;t to akinge;</L>
<L>&thorn;er fore oure lord as a king . gold heo gonnen bringe.</L>
<L>Encense valle&thorn; to holi chirche, : &amp; vor god was, heo &thorn;ou&yogh;ten,</L>
<L>Preost and maister of holi chirche, . encense heo him brou&yogh;ten.</L>
<L>Mirre is swi&thorn;e bitter &thorn;ing, . and akuinde hit ha&thorn; also:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms. doppelt</I> it hit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="770">&thorn;at no&thorn;ing ne schal rotie, . &thorn;at hit is bi ido;</L>
<L>&thorn;er fore whan an hei&yogh; mon dei&yogh;ede, . bi olde dawe me wolde</L>
<L>In his buriles mirre do, . &thorn;at e rote ne scholde.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bitter hede of &thorn;e mirre, . &thorn;at heo oure lord brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Bitoknede &thorn;e bittere de&thorn; . &thorn;at &thorn;e giwes him wrou&yogh;te;</L>
<L N="775">&thorn;at hit wi&thorn; aded mon . hol at is buriinge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wi&thorn; = wite&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Godes buriing hit bi tokne&thorn; . wi&thorn; oute rotiinge.</L>
<L>&thorn;is &thorn;re kinges wenden for&thorn; . &amp; &thorn;is &yogh;iftes wi&thorn; hem nome</L>
<L>Vrom &thorn;e ferreste lond of bieste, . vor heo to ierlm come,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor <I>st.</I> vor te.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at in &thorn;e middel is of &thorn;e world: . &thorn;ider heo weren brou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="780">In twelf dawes, &amp; manie foles . &thorn;er fore ne leue&thorn; it nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ac as for dromedaries, . &thorn;at vpon wende,(!)<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> vpon <I>fehlt</I> heo.</NOTE></L>
<L>Swifte weren, and godes grace . sone hem &thorn;ider sende.<NOTE PLACE="foot">heo <I>fehlt nach</I> swifte.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o heo comen vurst to ierlm, . &thorn;e sterre hem was ihud,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> De stella.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vor heo scholden axe after god, . &thorn;at is bur&thorn;time were ikud,</L>
<L N="785">&thorn;at &thorn;e giwes ne of soke it nou&yogh;t . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> e was among hem ibore;</L>
<L>Ac anon, &thorn;o heo wenden vrom eroudes, . &thorn;e sterre was hem bi fore,
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="98"></L>
<L>And wende euene &thorn;e wey for&thorn;, . quik &thorn;ing as hit were,</L>
<L>To techen hem to bedleem, . &thorn;at heo bi giled nere.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kuinde heo hedde of quik &thorn;ing, . &amp; as heo cou&thorn;e wit and god;</L>
<L N="790">Vor whan &thorn;e kinges scholde astonde, . &thorn;e sterre bi fore hem stod,</L>
<L>And whanne heo scholden wenden for&thorn;, . vor&thorn; heo wende also,</L>
<L>And wisede hem cuere in &thorn;e wey, . what heo scholden do.</L>
<L>In &thorn;ilke sterre bi fore alle o&thorn;ere . &thorn;e &thorn;re kinges seo mi&yogh;te<MILESTONE N="36" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of hire stude &amp; of hire wendinge . &amp; al so of hire li&yogh;te;</L>
<L N="795">Of hire stude, vor heo was . in &thorn;e eir her so lowe,</L>
<L>And nou&yogh;t wi&thorn; o&thorn;ere in &thorn;e welkene, . vor me scholde hire iknowe;</L>
<L>Of hire wending, for heo wende . as &thorn;ow sist a quik best gon,</L>
<L>To lede hem euene in &thorn;e wey; . so ne dede neuer non;</L>
<L>Of hire li&yogh;t, vor so cler . no sterre neuer nas;</L>
<L N="800">Heo nas no&yogh;t to bri&yogh;t to honure him . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> on er&thorn;e ibore was.</L>
<L>Me &thorn;inke&thorn; heo ne mi&yogh;te clerore beo, . ne more schine bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e kinges hire mi&yogh;ten seo aday . ase wel ase ani&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;o &thorn;e &thorn;re kinges comen to bedleem, . as &thorn;is child lay,</L>
<L>&thorn;e sterre bi cam al to nou&yogh;t, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> neuer eft me hire ne say.</L>
<L N="805">&thorn;e kinges founden &thorn;at swete child . mid is moder marie,</L>
<L>Ac iosep ne founden heo nou&yogh;t, . leste heo hedden &thorn;ou&yogh;t folie,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e child hedde is sone ibeo, . &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;e child hedde beo vnclene;</L>
<L>Ne sei&yogh;en heo nou&yogh;t bote god, . to mis &thorn;enche nou&yogh;t ene.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e angel hem hedde ised . &thorn;at heo ne scholden wende</L>
<L N="810">Bi eroudes, vor e&thorn;ou&yogh;te . &thorn;e child vor to schende,</L>
<L>At thars heo hureden schipes, . &amp; &thorn;er for&thorn; &thorn;ene wey toke,</L>
<L>And wenden hom al bi watere nor&thorn;, . &amp; &thorn;en hei&yogh; wei for soke.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> nor&thorn;, <I>wol st.</I> uor&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o heo comen to here oune lond, . &thorn;at cas heo tolden wide,</L>
<L>And wisseden muche of &thorn;e folk . to oure lord in vche side.</L>
<L N="815">Se&thorn;&thorn;e thomas &thorn;e apostel . to &thorn;ulke londe com</L>
<L>And &thorn;is &thorn;reo kinges &amp; moni o&thorn;er . brou&yogh;te to cristendom.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e cite of meluns . se&thorn;&thorn;e iburied heo were,</L>
<L>And longe as holimen . &thorn;e bodies lei&yogh;e &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Vor te &thorn;ilke cite se&thorn;&thorn;e . was brou&yogh;t to grounde;</L>
<L N="820">&thorn;e erche bisschop of coloine . &thorn;o &thorn;is bodies vounde,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e hei&yogh;e chirche of coloine . he let hem lede also</L>
<L>And among o&thorn;er martirs . wel faire an er&thorn;e do.
<PB REF="00000143.tif" N="99"></L>
<L>&thorn;er &yogh;et to &thorn;is dai&yogh;e . wi&thorn; gret honour heo be&thorn;,</L>
<L>And as holi relikes iholde, . as men alday se&thorn;,</L>
<L N="825">Holi men as heo were, . and elles it were wow,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> s. l. Postquam impleti f(uerun)t, <I>s. Luc. 2, 22.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And of pilgrimes and o&thorn;er men . honured be&thorn; inow.</L>
<L>Of oure lord &thorn;at was ibore . somwat tellen imay,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e gospel vs de&thorn; lere . acandelmasse day.</L>
<L>After &thorn;e dawe were folfulled . of maries clansinge</L>
<L N="830">&thorn;orw &thorn;e lawe of moises, . <ABBR>ihc</ABBR> heo let bringe</L>
<L>To ierlm, to setten him . bifore oure lord iwis,</L>
<L>As it in oure lordes lawe . iwrite was and is:</L>
<L>&thorn;at ech &thorn;ing, &thorn;at hedde . his moder wombe ido,</L>
<L>To oure lord holi&thorn;ing . me scholde hit clepie so; &mdash;</L>
<L N="835">And &thorn;at heo &yogh;eue an offring . vor him wel vawe,</L>
<L>Vpe word &thorn;at is iseid . in oure lordes lawe:</L>
<L>A peire briddes of tortlen, . o&thorn;er coluer briddes to.</L>
<L>And in ierlm an old man . &thorn;er was i do,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> is do <I>st.</I> i do.</NOTE></L>
<L>His name was symeon; . god he doutede wel</L>
<L N="840">And ri&yogh;tful was, &amp; he abod . &thorn;e begginge of isrl,</L>
<L>And in him was &thorn;e holi gost; . &amp; onswere him was ibrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e holi gost, &thorn;at he ne scholde . de&thorn; i seo nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;at he isei&yogh;e er . oure lordes kinedom.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;orw &thorn;e holigost . to &thorn;e temple he com;</L>
<L N="845">And &thorn;e kun of child ih&umacr; . let vor&thorn; drawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> let <I>fehlt</I> ih&umacr; <I>oder</I> him.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vor to do vor him &thorn;o . vpe &thorn;e costom of &thorn;e lawe;</L>
<L>&thorn;e olde mon symeon . his armes gan sprede</L>
<L>A brod, and nom &thorn;is child <ABBR>ihc</ABBR>, . and heriede him and sede:</L>
<L>Lord, &thorn;in owne hine . vpe &thorn;i wordes now let,</L>
<L N="850">Vor min ei&yogh;en habbe&thorn; isei&yogh;e . &thorn;in holi bodi so gret,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> Nunc dimittis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at bi fore &thorn;e face of al folk . &thorn;ow hast i&yogh;arked ari&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;at to &thorn;e schewing of al folk . of paynime is cler si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e fol ioie . of &thorn;i folk of israel also.</L>
<L>&thorn;e gospel acondelmasse day . yn &thorn;is wordes is ido.</L>
<L N="855">Cler li&yogh;t oure lord was . to men of painime:</L>
<L>Vor heo ne herde nou&yogh;t . of him ar his bur&thorn;time,
<PB REF="00000144.tif" N="100"></L>
<L>Ne hadden to him non hope . ne bi heste non,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e giwes hadden abrod . &thorn;orw prophetus moni on;</L>
<L>&thorn;er fore god was cler li&yogh;t, . &thorn;o he was ibore,</L>
<L N="860">To schininge of &thorn;e painimes, . &thorn;at heo sei&yogh;e nou&yogh;t bifore.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bote, &thorn;at seide ek symeon . &thorn;at he &thorn;er isei&yogh;,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was oure bote godes sone, . &thorn;at was him wel nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>After &thorn;is child <ABBR>ihc</ABBR> was ibore, . &thorn;e vourti&thorn;e day</L>
<L>Oure ledi dude hire churche &yogh;ong, . as hit fel in &thorn;e lay;</L>
<L N="865">Vor oure lord hadde ihote . in &thorn;e olde lawe bifore</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e fourti&thorn;e day, . &thorn;at asone were ibore,</L>
<L>Me scholde hit to &thorn;e temple bcre . &amp; bi fore auter bringe</L>
<L>And offren hit to oure lord . wi&thorn; afair offringe;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at a wommon scholde, . &thorn;at of richesse were,</L>
<L N="870">A lomb offre wi&thorn; hire child, . to &thorn;e temple whan heo it bere;</L>
<L>Ac o&thorn;er pore wimmen, . &thorn;at o&thorn;er whar of nadde,</L>
<L>Offre coluerren o&thorn;er tortlen, . wel vawe &thorn;at heo it hadde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> coluerren <I>mit</I> rr, <I>da trotz der Abk&uuml;rzung f&uuml;r</I> er <I>noch ein</I> r <I>zugesetzt ist.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Oure lord, vrom &thorn;at he was ibore . &thorn;e while he was here,</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue ensample, he siwede . &thorn;e pore in vche manere.</L>
<L N="875">&thorn;e offring he tok of tortlen, . vor lomb nadde he non,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; colueren &amp; wi&thorn; tortlen . to &thorn;e temple heo gonnen gon;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at vor &thorn;e nede to halewe . &thorn;at child more,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> vor &thorn;e nede <I>fehlt jedenfalls</I> nou&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vor holi hit was inow . al wi&thorn; oute here lore;</L>
<L>Al it was to volfulle . &thorn;e lawe &thorn;at was bi fore,</L>
<L N="880">&thorn;at he nolde wi&thorn; sigge nou&yogh;t, . &thorn;o he was ibore.</L>
<L>Of gret elde he was inow, . &thorn;is olde mon symeon,<MILESTONE N="37" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> De Symeone.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of an hundred &yogh;er an twelue, . &thorn;at vnne&thorn;e he mi&yogh;te gon.</L>
<L>I wilned he hedde al is lif . and oure lord ibede fore,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he moste neuer dei&yogh;e, . ar he sei&yogh;e oure lord ibore.</L>
<L N="885">So gret wille he hedde to him . &thorn;at wismon come,</L>
<L>Vor hope of tidinge of him . axen he wolde ilome:</L>
<L>Wenestow ou&yogh;t he wole (beo) bore? . weneste ischule him seo?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> bore <I>fehlt</I> beo.</NOTE></L>
<L>Weneste &thorn;at ich dure mowe, . vorte he ibore beo?</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e holi gost he hedde onswere, . as we seide bi fore,</L>
<L N="890">&thorn;at he ne scholde neuer &thorn;ene de&thorn; &thorn;ole, . ar he sei&yogh;e god ibore.</L>
<L>&thorn;ilke biheste he abod so longe, . &thorn;at inelde he was ibrou&yogh;t;
<PB REF="00000145.tif" N="101"></L>
<L>Ac na&thorn;eles for &thorn;e grete hope . his elde ne greuede him nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>He was glad, &thorn;o he isay . &thorn;is child and is moder marie,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e wordes &thorn;at ich abbe itold . seide in his prophecie.</L>
<L N="895">And &thorn;e wordes &thorn;at he seide &thorn;o, . &amp; &thorn;e schepherdes bi fore,</L>
<L>Gret wonder brou&yogh;te to al &thorn;e lond . of ih&umacr;, &thorn;at was ibore.</L>
<L>Marie and iosep wondreden ek, . as &thorn;e gospel telle&thorn; vs</L>
<L>A seint siluestres eue &thorn;at is irad, . &thorn;at bi gynne&thorn; &thorn;us:</L>
<L><ABBR>Ihc</ABBR> moder and iosep, . &thorn;at as his fader was,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> Erant pater et mater ih&umacr;; <I>s. Luc. 2, 33</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="900">Wondreden &thorn;at was iseid . of him and of &thorn;at cas.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> &thorn;at <I>fehlt</I> of.</NOTE></L>
<L>Symeon blessede hem . and seide to marie,</L>
<L>&thorn;at is swete moder was, . as in prophecie:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> modes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lo &thorn;is child is iset . as in doun vallinge</L>
<L>To monie men in isrl, . &amp; to monie in vprisinge,</L>
<L N="905">And in tokninge, &thorn;at wor&thorn; . wi&thorn; seid of moni mon,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e swerd schal of him . &thorn;orw &thorn;i soule gon,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;t of manie herte . &thorn;orw &thorn;e ischowed beo.</L>
<L>&thorn;o tokninge of &thorn;is prophecie . somwhat we moten iseo:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> &thorn;o <I>st.</I> &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e doun vallinge was tokninge . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> oure lord was ibrou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="910">Aner&thorn;e, to bringen hem to helle . &thorn;at on him ne leuede nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Vor heo ne mi&yogh;ten neuereft . vinde non encheson,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ne bou&yogh;te hem dere inow . wi&thorn; is passion.</L>
<L>&thorn;at he seide &thorn;at oure lord cam . in moni monnes vprisinge,</L>
<L>What was, bote he wolde . alle vs to heuene bringe?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> was <I>fehlt</I> hit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="915">&thorn;at scholde er as bi eritage . in deope helle dei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Vrom helle he made hem vp arise . in to heuene an hei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&thorn;at symeon bi oure ledi seide, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hire sone swerd wel kene</L>
<L>&thorn;orw hire soule passe scholde, . hit was se&thorn;&thorn;e wel sene:</L>
<L>Vor &thorn;is swerd was oure lordes de&thorn;, . &thorn;at &thorn;orw hire herte wende</L>
<L N="920">Vnder &thorn;e rode, &thorn;o heo isay . &thorn;e giwes him to rende.</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is scholde beo . wi&thorn; said of moni mon,</L>
<L>&thorn;at were &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere giwes . him wolden wi&thorn; sigge anon.</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;orw him ischewed scholde be . moni monnes &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP>, er he come, . siker nas hit nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="925">Whuch men were wi&thorn; him . o&thorn;er a&yogh;en him wolde beo;</L>
<L>Ac anon &thorn;o he was icome on er&thorn;e, . &thorn;at so&thorn;e me mi&yogh;te iseo;
<PB REF="00000146.tif" N="102"></L>
<L>As &thorn;e kinges &thorn;at honoureden him, . and o&thorn;er mani on,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> &thorn;e kinges <I>fehlt</I> of.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of erodes &amp; of o&thorn;ere ek . &thorn;at a&yogh;en turnden anon.</L>
<L>Anne a wommon prophete . &thorn;ulke time was &thorn;er,</L>
<L N="930">Heo was ffanuelus dou&yogh;ter . of &thorn;e kunde of asser.</L>
<L>In gret elde heo was igo . vor&thorn; mid hire spoushod,</L>
<L>And leuede wi&thorn; hire hosbonde . seue &yogh;er after hire maidenhod,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;e heo hedde widue ibeo . vourscore and vour &yogh;er.</L>
<L>Heo ne partede no&yogh;t from &thorn;e temple, . ac euere bilafte &thorn;er,</L>
<L N="935">In fastinge and in biddinge . bo&thorn;e ni&yogh;t and day.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo com &thorn;ulke time . and oure lord isay,</L>
<L>To him heo was anon iknowe, . and spak ful wel</L>
<L>To alle &thorn;at abiden &thorn;o . &thorn;e begginge of israel.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o heo hedde do alle &thorn;ing . &thorn;orw oure lordes lawe,</L>
<L N="940">&thorn;e childes frendus to galilee . wi&thorn; him gonnen drawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> frende <I>mit der Abk&uuml;rzung f&uuml;r</I> us.</NOTE></L>
<L>To heore oune cite of nazareth. . &amp; &thorn;is child wel wex &thorn;o</L>
<L>And conforded was, &amp; godes grace . in him was ido.</L>
<L>&thorn;is prophecie of symeon . and of &thorn;is holi anne</L>
<L>Was sone aboute wide ibrou&yogh;t . from manne to manne,</L>
<L N="945">And to heroudes among o&thorn;ere. . &thorn;o dradde he him sore,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;at &thorn;e kinges him seiden er . he &thorn;ou&yogh;te wel &thorn;e more.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o alle &thorn;reo ano&thorn;er wey . to ward here londe nome</L>
<L>Al bi watere, as iseide er, . and bi him ne come,</L>
<L>Sori he made him &thorn;er fore . and abod hem ilome;</L>
<L N="950">Of annes wordes and symeon . he nam ek gret gome,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;e schepherdes seiden also, . &thorn;at oure lord was ibore;</L>
<L>In gret &thorn;ou&yogh;t he was ni&yogh;t and day, . oure lord to sle &thorn;er fore.</L>
<L>He hedde ek six lu&thorn;er sones, . &thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh;ten him euele di&yogh;te,</L>
<L>To bi nimen him is kinedom . o&thorn;er quellen him, &yogh;if heo mi&yogh;te.</L>
<L N="955">&thorn;o eroudes it vnder&yogh;at, . he drof hem awey anon;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e emperour &thorn;o lu&thorn;ere sones . to pleinte gonnen gon.</L>
<L>I not what scholde a lu&thorn;er fader . bote lu&thorn;er sones bi&yogh;ete!</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e emperour &thorn;is pleint iherde, . &thorn;e so&thorn;e he wolde iwite;</L>
<L>He let sompne &thorn;e king heroudes, . &thorn;at hit ne bi leued nou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> hit <I>fehlt</I> he, <I>oder</I> were <I>nach</I> ne.</NOTE></L>
<L N="960">&thorn;at he were bi fore him . at acertein day ibrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&thorn;o was eroudes sore adrad, . &amp; somdel for &yogh;at so
<PB REF="00000147.tif" N="103"></L>
<L>&thorn;e wreche &thorn;at he hedde i&thorn;ou&yogh;t . bi oure (lord) to do.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> oure <I>fehlt</I> lord.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e emperour sori e wende . &amp; &thorn;er to brou&yogh;te is strif,</L>
<L>&thorn;at is sones him scholde abowe, . &amp; he be king al is lif.</L>
<L N="965">Swi&thorn;e hardi he was &thorn;o, . and hamward he gan wende.</L>
<L>Al his &thorn;ou&yogh;t and his red was . how he mi&yogh;te oure lord schende.</L>
<L>He com bi &thorn;e see of thars, . and &thorn;e schipes &thorn;at e founde</L>
<L>To douste he let hem brenne anon, . o&thorn;er hakke to grounde,</L>
<L>&thorn;e wra&thorn;&thorn;e of &thorn;e kinges &thorn;reo . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er vor&thorn; gonnen wende.<MILESTONE N="38" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e <I>st.</I> &thorn;orw <I>verschrieben oder es fehlt</I> vor.</NOTE></L>
<L N="970">&thorn;at seind daui&thorn; in is sauter, . ibrou&yogh;t it was to ende:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> seind <I>st.</I> seide seint.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e kingus here of er&thorn;e . to gadere be&thorn; ibrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And wondreden, whanne heo sei&yogh;e oure lord, . &amp; destorbed were in here &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And also imeued ek, . and muche drede hem nome &thorn;ere</L>
<L>And sor, as of awommon . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> in trauail of child were,</L>
<L N="975">And deol foliche &thorn;e schipes of thars . wi&thorn; wel hasti bre&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> deol foliche <I>st.</I> defoulede <I>verschrieben, oder</I> defoulede <I>ist zu erg&auml;nzen.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is was seid bi eroudes, . as it mi&yogh;te wel e&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&thorn;at destourbed was and imeued, . &amp; in anguise &amp; in drede</L>
<L>Defoulede &thorn;e schipes of thars . wi&thorn; wel hasti rede.</L>
<L>&thorn;at was, me &thorn;inke&thorn;, afeble wreche . &amp; gret lu&thorn;er hede ido,</L>
<L N="980">&thorn;at vor heo hedden &thorn;er for&thorn; iwend, . &thorn;e schipes defouli so.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at vor <I>umzusetzen</I> vor &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o he nuste how he mi&yogh;te more . of &thorn;e kinges him awreke,</L>
<L>How he mi&yogh;te oure lord slee, . he bi&thorn;enchen and speke.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> bi&thorn;enchen <I>fehlt</I> gan.</NOTE></L>
<L>E nuste, whar oure lord was, . bote as men him hadden itold,</L>
<L>Ac wel he wuste &thorn;at e nas . nour (!) nei&yogh; to &yogh;er old.</L>
<L N="985">&thorn;er fore he let sle alle &thorn;e children . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> wi&thorn; inne to &yogh;er were,</L>
<L>A boute al &thorn;e contrei of bedleem, . &thorn;at oure lord forbore nere.</L>
<L>How oure lord ascapede, . &thorn;e gospel telle&thorn; vs</L>
<L>&thorn;at is irad achilder masse day, . &thorn;at bigynne&thorn; &thorn;us:</L>
<L>Oure lordes angel in slep . to iosep cam &thorn;o</L>
<L N="990">And seide: aris &amp; nim &thorn;ichild . &amp; is moder, &amp; go<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> s. M. Angelus dm appar(uit); <I>s. Math. 2, 13.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Ynto egipt and beo &thorn;er, . vorte &thorn;at i<SUP>c</SUP> &thorn;e telle,</L>
<L>Vor certein it is &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> heroudes . wol seche &thorn;is child to quelle.</L>
<L>He aros vp and nom &thorn;is child . and &thorn;e moder &thorn;o,
<PB REF="00000148.tif" N="104"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ene wey toward egipt . al bi ni&yogh;te gan go,</L>
<L N="995">And was &thorn;er, vorte heroudes . his lif an er&thorn;e lete,</L>
<L>To folfulle &thorn;at of oure lord . iseid was &thorn;orw &thorn;e prophete,</L>
<L>&thorn;at seide: out of egipt . ichabbe icleped mi sone.</L>
<L>&thorn;at word hedde &thorn;er bifore . longe ben in mone.</L>
<L>&thorn;o heroudes isay . &thorn;at he bigiled was,</L>
<L N="1000">Of &thorn;e kinges wro&thorn; inow . he was for &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L>And sende and slow al &thorn;e children, . in bedleem &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er were</L>
<L>And in al &thorn;e contrei &thorn;er aboute, . wi&thorn; inne &thorn;e elde of to &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>&thorn;at were of to &yogh;er and lasse, . he ne bileuede non &thorn;er,</L>
<L>Vpe &thorn;e time &thorn;at he of askede . of &thorn;e kinges er.</L>
<L N="1005">&thorn;o was it folfulled . &thorn;at of Jeremie</L>
<L>&thorn;e prophete was iseid, . &thorn;at he seide in prophecie:</L>
<L>&thorn;e vois anhei&yogh; is iherd, . muche wep and morninge;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> vox in rama.</NOTE></L>
<L>Rachel bi wep hire sones . and nolde no gladinge,</L>
<L>Vor &thorn;at heo ne be&thorn; nou&yogh;t. . &thorn;is is &thorn;e ende lo.</L>
<L N="1010">Vor &thorn;is wordes harde be&thorn;, . me mot hem a lute vndo:</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is cri was iherd an hei&yogh;, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> was of sorwe and sore</L>
<L>&thorn;at modres vor here children made, . ne mi&yogh;te be na more.</L>
<L>&thorn;at rachel hire sones scholde biwepe . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> so longe was ded er,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &thorn;at moni of &thorn;e children, . &thorn;at were aslawe &thorn;er,</L>
<L N="1015">Of rachelus kunne were icome, . &amp; for rachel al so</L>
<L>I buried was biside bedleem, . &thorn;er &thorn;is dede was do.</L>
<L>&thorn;at heo nolde habbe no gladinge, . vor &thorn;at heo be&thorn; nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &thorn;at heo lete here lif . &amp; to de&thorn;e were ibrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Twelf mon&thorn;es after and four dawes, . &thorn;at god was ibore,</L>
<L N="1020">Was &thorn;at heo weren islawe, . so &yogh;ong heo weren icore.</L>
<L>I cristned heo weren in here blod, . vair was &thorn;e companie;</L>
<L>Reu&thorn;fol and sori was &thorn;e cri . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> here modres gan crie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e mestedel of &thorn;e children . iburied su&thorn;&thorn;e were</L>
<L>&thorn;re milen bi side bedleem . in &thorn;e sou&thorn;half &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="1025">Alas seli &yogh;onge &thorn;inges, . gulteles heo weren dede!</L>
<L>Mid hem he hedde lute milce . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> dude so lu&thorn;er hede.</L>
<L>A wei, heroudes, &thorn;ow wrecche king, . &thorn;ow hontest aboute nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Sore &thorn;ow draddest &thorn;orw him beo . of &thorn;i kinedom ibrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ac na&thorn;eles &thorn;ow mi&yogh;test wite wel . &thorn;at hit nas no&yogh;t is ri&yogh;te,
<PB REF="00000149.tif" N="105"></L>
<L N="1030">&thorn;i wrecche kinedom here to holde, . vor he was of more mi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Whi slowe &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> for hate of him . &thorn;e children &thorn;at gultles were?</L>
<L>Wrecche, he wuste wel &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t, . ne foundeste him nou&yogh;t &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>Vrom &thorn;i power he is ilad, . ac na&thorn;eles vor drede nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ac vor he wolde his time abide, . ar he were to de&thorn;e ibrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="1035">As iosep and marie . &thorn;is swete child vor&thorn; ladde<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> De miraculis in itinere.</NOTE></L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e lond of egipt, . as &thorn;e angel hem radde:</L>
<L>As heo &thorn;orw tounes wende, . &yogh;onge children come</L>
<L>And siwede &thorn;is swete child . &amp; maden him ioie ilome.</L>
<L>Lute wyt &thorn;ei&yogh; heo cou&thorn;en, . &yogh;et heo mi&yogh;ten for beren nou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1040">To solacen heore &yogh;onge lord, . &thorn;at &thorn;er was ibrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&thorn;o heo comen in to egipt, . in here wey stod a treo<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> De arbore uertuosa.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at of gret vertue was, . non more ne mi&yogh;te beo:</L>
<L>&thorn;at, whose &thorn;er of eni &thorn;ing . aboute is nekke bere,</L>
<L>ffruit o&thorn;er rinde o&thorn;er lef . o&thorn;er eni&thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;er of were,</L>
<L N="1045">Vnne&thorn;e was eni vuel, . &thorn;at he nas hol anon.</L>
<L>So gret vertue hedde &thorn;e treo; . hit helede monie on.</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;o oure lord and is moder . in to egipt wende,</L>
<L>&thorn;e treo bowede &thorn;e crop to grounde . &amp; &thorn;e middel narwe bende;</L>
<L>Adoun hit aloutede to oure lord . bo&thorn;e crop and more,</L>
<L N="1050">And vpri&yogh;t stod se&thorn;&thorn;e a&yogh;en, . &thorn;o oure lord was &thorn;er for&thorn; ibore.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e cite heo comen &thorn;o, . ac herbarwe nadden heo non.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> De simulacris in templo.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e hei&yogh;e temple heo wenden, . &thorn;er vch mon mi&yogh;te in gon.</L>
<L>&thorn;re hondred maumetes and fiue &amp; fourti . in &thorn;ilke temple were;</L>
<L>To grounde heo vellen euer vch on, . anon &thorn;o oure lord com &thorn;ere;</L>
<L N="1055">Stonden ne mi&yogh;ten heo no lengore, . &thorn;an he among hem cam,</L>
<L>&thorn;at here maister was imad . &amp; here power bi nam.</L>
<L>In egipte was &thorn;is swete child . and is moder also<MILESTONE N="39" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> De uita illorum in egipto.</NOTE></L>
<L>And Josep in meseise inow, . vorte seue &yogh;er were ido.</L>
<L>Mid spinninge and sewinge . oure swete ladi milde</L>
<L N="1060">Bi wan here mete &thorn;ulke time . to hem and to here childe.</L>
<L>I seo &yogh;e now, wuch gret pruide . he drow for&thorn;, &thorn;e hei&yogh;e king,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> wuch <I>fehlt</I> wi&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at he nadde whar bi libbe, . &thorn;e lord of alle &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Bote mid spindle and mid nelde . his moder hi(m) bi wan?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> hi <I>st.</I> him.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000150.tif" N="106"></L>
<L>God ensample &thorn;is may beo, . me &thorn;inke&thorn;, to pore man:</L>
<L N="1065">Whan &thorn;e king of alle kinges . to such pouerte gan drawe,</L>
<L>Me &thorn;inke&thorn;, whose him vnderstode, . of pouerte au&yogh;te be vawe.</L>
<L>Su&thorn;&thorn;e heroudes &thorn;e king, . as oure lord grace sende,</L>
<L>In serwe and wrecchede inow . out of is lif wende.</L>
<L>He was king seuene and &thorn;ritti &yogh;er, . ac &thorn;er nou&yogh;t to vewe,</L>
<L N="1070">Al to muche bi vche day, , vor he was euere aschrewe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> De mortis Herodis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Muche wo an er&thorn;e he dude, . &amp; &thorn;o he hedde al ido,</L>
<L>His owne sones he slow &thorn;reo, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> schrewen weren al so,</L>
<L>&thorn;at awaiteden hire (fader) to sle . vor is kinedom,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> hire <I>fehlt</I> fader.</NOTE></L>
<L>And was fel and cam bi fore . &amp; here lif hem bi nom.<NOTE PLACE="foot">he <I>fehlt vor</I> was.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1075">In such anguise he was him self . &amp; in torment so,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wolde him self habbe islawe, . &yogh;if emi&yogh;te ha come &thorn;er to<NOTE PLACE="foot">ha <I>st.</I> han.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ate laste he &thorn;ou&yogh;te wel . &thorn;at ehedde be such aschrewe,</L>
<L>And men wolde be glade vor his de&thorn;, . &amp; lute sori vewe,</L>
<L>And ri&yogh;t hit were to plaine . &thorn;e de&thorn; of aking;</L>
<L N="1080">And, &yogh;if heo nolden for is lif, . he &thorn;ou&yogh;te heo scholden for o&thorn;er &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>&thorn;er fore &thorn;o he scholde dei&yogh;e, . &thorn;e hexte of is londe</L>
<L>Bifore him he let to de&thorn;e do . in serwe inow and schonde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at hei &thorn;at bilafte a liue . of here frendes iwis</L>
<L>Vor heore de&thorn; maden deol, . whan heo nolden for his:</L>
<L N="1085">So &thorn;at in o manere o&thorn;er in o&thorn;er . deol were at is de&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Al mest ibischrewe him, . ich vor bere vnne&thorn;e.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e schrewe was of liue, . archelaus is sone<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> Et quo|modo archelaus regnabat post ipsum. <I>Nach</I> and <I>fehlt</I> &thorn;o.</NOTE></L>
<L>King was imad after him, . as lawe was and wone.</L>
<L>&thorn;e furste &yogh;er, as god wolde, . of is kinedom</L>
<L N="1090">Josep wi&thorn; &thorn;e swete child . out of egipte com.</L>
<L>In whuche manere he &thorn;enne wende, . &thorn;e gospel de&thorn; vs lere</L>
<L>&thorn;at biginne&thorn; at twelf&thorn;e eue, . &amp; is mad on &thorn;is manere:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> s. M. Defuncto herode; <I>s. Math. 2, 19</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at heroudes was ded, . oure lordes angel ali&yogh;te</L>
<L>In slep to Josep in egipt, . and seide him in si&yogh;te: . . .<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlen mehrere Verse</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1095">Into &thorn;e lond ecom of isrl . . &thorn;o herde he tidinge</L>
<L>&thorn;at after heroudes is fader . Archelaus was kinge
<PB REF="00000151.tif" N="107"></L>
<L>In &thorn;e lond of Jude: . he dradde &thorn;ider wende;</L>
<L>I hote he was ek in his slep . of &thorn;e angel atenende,</L>
<L>And com into galilee, . &amp; wonede &thorn;o &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="1100">In &thorn;e cite of nazareth; . &thorn;at hit folfulled were</L>
<L>&thorn;at of &thorn;e prophetes was iseid: . &thorn;at escholde icleped beo</L>
<L>Of nazareth and bere &thorn;e name. . &thorn;e encheson me may seo:</L>
<L>Vor oure ledi was &thorn;er ibore . and also bi&yogh;ete,</L>
<L>And oure lord &thorn;ere in hire ali&yogh;te, . as we finde&thorn; iwrite;</L>
<L N="1105">And vor heo eke to nazaret . vrom egipt wende iwis,</L>
<L>&thorn;er fore ih&umacr; of nazareth . oure lord iclepud is.</L>
<L>&thorn;is child <ABBR>ihc</ABBR> wax ful wel . &amp; iconforted was also,</L>
<L>And fol was of wisedom, . &amp; godes grace in him was do.</L>
<L>And is frendes to ierlm . wenden euer vch &yogh;er,</L>
<L N="1110">Ate feste of Aster . to siwe &thorn;e lawe &thorn;er.</L>
<L>&thorn;o <ABBR>ihc</ABBR> was of twelf &yogh;er old . and twelf &yogh;er were ido,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> s. M. (<I>st.</I> L.) Cum ihs &emacr;et XII annorum; <I>s. Luc. 2, 42</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Heo wenden for&thorn; to ierlm . vpe &thorn;e custom &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> was &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Vpe &thorn;e feste of ester day. . &amp; &thorn;o &thorn;e dawes ido were:</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo wende hom a&yogh;en; . and &thorn;e child <ABBR>ihc</ABBR> &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="1115">Bilafte in ierlm, . &amp; is kunesmen nusten it nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>A wenden he were hamward . among &thorn;e volk ibrou&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> A <I>st.</I> An.</NOTE></L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo wenden and sou&yogh;ten him . hammard a iorneie</L>
<L>Among his cu&thorn;&thorn;e and is kun, . and also bi vche wei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>To ierlm heo turnden a&yogh;en, . &thorn;o heo ne mi&yogh;ten him no&yogh;t seo,</L>
<L N="1120">And sou&yogh;ten him &thorn;er in vche side; . &amp; after dawes &thorn;reo</L>
<L>Amidde &thorn;e maistres heo founden him . in &thorn;e temple sitte,</L>
<L>And herknede and apposede hem, . so &thorn;at of is witte<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> asposede <I>st.</I> apposede.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of is answere al so . and of is queintise</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at herden him . wondreden in here wise.</L>
<L N="1125">Sone, qua&thorn; oure ledi, . what hastow vs ido?</L>
<L>Wel sori we &thorn;e habbe&thorn; isou&yogh;t, . &thorn;i fader and i<SUP>c</SUP> also.</L>
<L>What is &thorn;at, qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, . &thorn;at &yogh;e me habbe&thorn; isou&yogh;t?</L>
<L>Neste &yogh;e &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> in mi fader &thorn;ing . i moste nede be brou&yogh;t?</L>
<L>&thorn;is word &thorn;at he spak to hem . heo ne vnderstode nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1130">Vor hit was al of his god hede; . &thorn;er fore heo weren in &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&thorn;is child ali&yogh;te adoun to hem, . &amp; to nazareth cam,
<PB REF="00000152.tif" N="108"></L>
<L>And was in here warde for&thorn;. . &amp; his moder nam</L>
<L>God &yogh;eme of alle is wordes . &amp; in hire herte hem hedde ido.</L>
<L><ABBR>Ihc</ABBR> wex wel in elde . and in wisedom al so</L>
<L N="1135">And in grace a&yogh;en god . and a&yogh;en men iwis.</L>
<L>&thorn;e ende as me rat in churche . of &thorn;ulke gospel is &thorn;is.</L>
<L>&thorn;at word of his fader &thorn;ing, . of whom &thorn;is child sede,</L>
<L>Was &thorn;at it fel to is fader . of wisedom speke and rede;</L>
<L>And vor &thorn;e temple wi&thorn; ri&yogh;te eke . was of is fader fe,</L>
<L N="1140">&thorn;er fore he seide he moste nede . in is fader &thorn;ing be.</L>
<L>&thorn;o marie nom so god &yogh;eme . of is wordes vchon,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was, whan (men) axeden out, . to tellen hit hem anon.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> whan <I>fehlt</I> men.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is child was for lore, for me . criede in &thorn;e temple faste</L>
<L>&thorn;at vche mon stode bi is per, . &thorn;e while &thorn;e feste laste,</L>
<L N="1145">Man bi man and child bi child . and wommon bi o&thorn;er also;<MILESTONE N="40" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So stod vch &thorn;ing bi is per, . vorte feste were ido.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> feste <I>fehlt</I> &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>So &thorn;at <ABBR>ihc</ABBR> vrom is frendes . among children was ibrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And heo nusten whar he bicam, . ar he were wide isout&yogh;.</L>
<L>&thorn;o archelaus hadde . ni&yogh;e &yogh;er king ibeo,</L>
<L N="1150">So proud he was &amp; so lu&thorn;er, . as vche mon mi&yogh;te seo,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is it nolde &thorn;olie nou&yogh;t, . ac is power him bi nome</L>
<L>And heroudes, is bro&thorn;er, maden king . &thorn;orw ri&yogh;te dome.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e heo weren heroudes sones, . &thorn;at king was bi fore,</L>
<L>&thorn;at fondede oure lord to sle, . &thorn;o he was ibore.</L>
<L N="1155">Heroudes, &thorn;is newe king, . and pilatus, &thorn;e Justise,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e bisschop anne &amp; caiphas, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> of &thorn;e lawe were wise,</L>
<L>Alle foure heo weren ate red . to bringe oure lord of dawe.</L>
<L>Pilatus hadde &thorn;er bifore . vnder eroudes e beo;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> e beo <I>st.</I> ibeo.</NOTE></L>
<L>To rome he wende to &thorn;emperour . &amp; &yogh;af him of is feo,</L>
<L N="1160">Vor to holde of &thorn;e emperour . &thorn;at he of eroudes huld er.</L>
<L>&thorn;e emperour &thorn;us furst binam . eroudes ri&yogh;te &thorn;er.</L>
<L>&thorn;er fore eroudes and pilatus . in wra&thorn;&thorn;e weren ibrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ar god were to de&thorn;e ido, . acorded nere hi nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Vor &thorn;e gile &thorn;at pilatus . a&yogh;en him hedde ido</L>
<L N="1165">And &thorn;orw streng&thorn;e of &thorn;e emperour . his lond inome so.
<PB REF="00000153.tif" N="109"></L>
<L>So proude were &thorn;is giwes euere, . &thorn;at &thorn;e emperour was wro&thorn;.</L>
<L>Heore pruide he wolde abati, . he swor is more o&thorn;.</L>
<L>Eroudes kinedom, &thorn;e olde, . e delede a vour partie,</L>
<L>And tok eroudes and phelip . &amp; here bro&thorn;er lisanie</L>
<L N="1170">Vchone apartie &thorn;er of, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> eroudes sones were,</L>
<L>And pilatus &thorn;e ver&thorn;endel, . vort heo hem betre bere.</L>
<L>Phelip hedde al iturie, . heroudes galile,</L>
<L>And lisanie abiliue, . and pilatus Jude.<NOTE PLACE="end">(Hier schliesst das Gedicht mitten auf der Seite ab, die andere H&auml;lfte sowie die R&uuml;ckseite von fol. 40 ist leer. Das Ged. ist wol nicht vollst&auml;ndig.)</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000154.tif">
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="3" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000155.tif">
<HEAD>III. Barlam und Josaphat<LB>aus Ms. Bodl. 779.</HEAD>

<PB REF="00000156.tif">

<PB REF="00000157.tif">
<HEAD>Barlaam &amp; Josaphat.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Der Titel fehlt im Ms., ist aber so vorn im Inhaltsverzeichnisse angegeben</I>.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>(I)hon of damascene : telle&thorn; vs &thorn;e stori&yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Die Initiale</I> I <I>in</I> Ihon <I>fehlt ebenfalls, doch es ist Raum daf&uuml;r gelassen.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Of barlaam &amp; iosaphat, : to haue hem Im memory&yogh;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> Im <I>st.</I> In, <I>wie v. 163.</I> [Berichtigungen (p. XLIV) add: <I>Das im Ms. h&auml;fige</I> i m <I>st.</I> in <I>is wol nur also Verschreibg. anzus.</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Barlaam tornyd Iosaphat, : &thorn;e king&es; sone of egipte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Die Abk&uuml;rzung</I> &es; <I>f&uuml;r die Endung des Nom. Plur. und Gen. Sgl. wird zwar sonst in der Regel nur f&uuml;r</I> us <I>gebraucht, jedoch ist es sehr wahrscheinlich, dass sie in diesem Gedicht f&uuml;r</I> is <I>gebraucht ist, da, wenn nicht abgek&uuml;rzt, sich nur</I> is <I>als Endung findet und auch meist in den Endungen des Verbs und in den Ableitungssilben</I> i <I>statt</I> e <I>gebraucht ist; nur im Adv.</I> &thorn;&es; <I>scheint</I> &es; <I>f&uuml;r</I> us <I>gebraucht, wie V. 108, 251, 902, 1060, 1084, u. &ouml;., wie es auch V. 211, 1164 ausgeschrieben</I> &thorn;us <I>lautet, obgleich sich auch</I> &thorn;is <I>in derselben Verbindung (mit</I> seide) <I>findet, z. B. 721, 754, 851, und</I> &thorn;&es; <I>stets mit</I> is <I>reimt; v. 419 findet sich</I> &thorn;is <I>durch</I> &thorn;<SUP>s</SUP> <I>ausgedr&uuml;ckt;</I> vs <I>reimt mit</I> iwis <I>v. 1238</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; fro fals be leue : to cristindom hym kipte.<MILESTONE N="289" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5">In &thorn;e lond monk&es; : &amp; cristinmen were.</L>
<L>Auenne heet &thorn;e king : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> wonyd &thorn;o &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>Monk&es; he hatid more : &thorn;an I of telle may,</L>
<L>&amp; euerymon &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> willuid : to here abbay;<NOTE PLACE="foot">willuid <I>f. st.</I> willnid <I>verschreiben zu halten, hindert d. Schreibung</I> wilwid V. 492, <I>welches doch wol dieselbe Bedeutung hat.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Cristinmen he harmyd: &amp; monk&es; wit his my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> al his conseyl : he &thorn;ou&yogh;t hem euil dy&yogh;t.</L>
<L>It be fel &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> anobil mon, : &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>o</SUP> wit hym was,</L>
<L>Went in to wildirnes : &amp; monk com by cas;<NOTE PLACE="foot">com <I>st.</I> bicom.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ey he were in king&es; hous : &amp; gret honour hadde,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he gan forsak, : for he &thorn;ou&yogh;t it badde.</L>
<L N="15">&thorn;o &thorn;e king herde &thorn;is, : sory he was &amp; wro&thorn;,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he scholde be sou&yogh;t : &yogh;erne he swor his o&thorn;.</L>
<L>ffor&thorn; he sente messager&es;, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> haue hym I sou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&thorn;ey founde hym &amp; to &thorn;e king : &thorn;ey haue hym I brou&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="114"></L>
<L>&thorn;e king hym be held &thorn;o : In a foul cirtil;</L>
<L N="20">On him he schok his heed : &amp; seyd: hastou do wel?</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> &thorn;at were wonyd wit me : be in clo&thorn;&es; ryche,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast tornyd &thorn;y self : &amp; gost vylliche;</L>
<L>Lene be&thorn; &thorn;y chekis : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> feyr were wonyd to be;</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast maad a childis pley, : Iwis, so &thorn;inke&thorn; me.</L>
<L N="25">&thorn;yn honour &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast tornyd : al in to foly&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&amp; me &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> dost : &thorn;er of no cortesy&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt, &thorn;is good mon seyd, : &thorn;e so&thorn;e wit of me,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou most &thorn;y fomon anon : dryue fro &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng seyde : my fomon? : telle woche be &thorn;o!</L>
<L N="30">&thorn;e gode mon answerde : &amp; hym seyde two:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; &amp;, <I>doppelt</I>. two = to.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wra&thorn;&thorn;e &amp; couetyse : draue&thorn; men be hinde,</L>
<L>&amp; for &thorn;ey ne schold &thorn;e so&thorn;e se, : make&thorn; hem alle blinde;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> far <I>st.</I> for.</NOTE></L>
<L>But tak to &thorn;y conseyl : so&thorn;nesse &amp; queintyse,</L>
<L>ffor to knowe so&thorn;nesse : &thorn;ey &thorn;e wolle wyse.</L>
<L N="35">Myldelych answerid : &thorn;e king to hym &thorn;o:</L>
<L>After &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast seyd, : I wis, I wille do;</L>
<L>Sey what &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt, : I wolle &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> nou here<NOTE PLACE="foot">t <I>in</I> wolt <I>aus</I> d <I>corrigirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at I nele wra&thorn;&thorn;e me : in no manere.</L>
<L>ffolis wole, qua&thorn; &thorn;is good mon, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> lasting is forsake,</L>
<L N="40">&amp; &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ne duri&thorn; nou&yogh;t long : &thorn;ey streng&thorn;i&thorn; hem to take;</L>
<L>&amp; I &thorn;e segge forso&thorn;e, : ry&yogh;t ne knowi&thorn; &thorn;ey nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ne ha&thorn; in lore wit sorw&yogh; : be fore it I bou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&thorn;us it fari&thorn;, leue syre, : I segge &thorn;e, by me:</L>
<L>Heuin I wold knowe, : forso&thorn;e I segge &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="45">Who so wil it knowe, : &thorn;is world he moot for saake,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;is <I>aus</I> &thorn;es <I>corrigirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at ne last but a whyle, : &amp; hard lyf to hym taake;</L>
<L>ffor wit oute hard lyf, : &thorn;olyd in world &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Ne may no mon wit ry&yogh;t : come to heuin blis;</L>
<L>For ih&umacr; crist oure lord, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> god of heuin is,</L>
<L N="50">&thorn;o he was on cr&thorn;e, : &thorn;olid pyne I wis;</L>
<L>ffor hym self he dede it nou&yogh;t, : for vs it was do;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore we scholle w<SUP>t</SUP> his help : for hym doon also.</L>
<L>I wis, qua&thorn; &thorn;e king to hym, : nadde I be hote &thorn;e
<PB REF="00000159.tif" N="115"></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I schold wra&thorn;&thorn;e &amp; couetyse : dryue fro me,</L>
<L N="55">Of &thorn;e I wold a wreke : In wra&thorn;&thorn;e be,</L>
<L>&thorn;at me schold &thorn;y reed blood : on grounde se.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore swy&thorn;e of my lond : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> now fle!</L>
<L>Or w<SUP>t</SUP> pyne &amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> wo : for doon &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt be.</L>
<L>ffor&thorn; went &thorn;is good mon : in moche sorw&yogh; &amp; wo,</L>
<L N="60">For he hopid ful wel : to de&thorn;e ben I do.</L>
<L>In &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ilke tyme : &thorn;e king nadde eyr none;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore he was sory : &amp; made moche mone.</L>
<L>God hym sente a knaue child, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> was swy&thorn;e feyr,</L>
<L>Josaphat it was I hote, : &amp; scholde ben his eyr.</L>
<L N="65">To &thorn;e temple &thorn;ey went, : his offring for to doon.</L>
<L>&amp; after astronomyis : &thorn;e king leet sende anon,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ey schold stody&yogh;e : in eueryche syde</L>
<L>&amp; telle hym what his sone : on er&thorn;e schold be tyde.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ey answerid: : gret lord he schold be,</L>
<L N="70">&amp; agreet mayster swy&thorn;e wit al, : &yogh;if he most I &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&thorn;o seyd on, but nou&yogh;t &thorn;orw him self : but &thorn;orw &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> holy gost:<NOTE PLACE="foot">t <I>in</I> gost <I>und</I> wost <I>hat ein Schleifchen, welches</I> e <I>be|deuten k&ouml;nnte, hier aber wol bedeutungslos ist</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is child schal be conquerour : of &thorn;ing &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wost,<NOTE PLACE="foot">t <I>in</I> gost <I>und</I> wost <I>hat ein Schleifchen, welches</I> e <I>be|deuten k&ouml;nnte, hier aber wol bedeutungslos ist</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ing &thorn;ou louist most(!) : &thorn;is child haue chal,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er &thorn;orw&yogh; oure hy&yogh;e god&es; honour : he schal doun fal.</L>
<L N="75">&thorn;is &thorn;ing of hym self : ne seyde he no &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>But &thorn;orw &thorn;e holy gost, : &thorn;at tau&yogh;t hym &thorn;is tokenyng.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> tokenyng <I>ist</I> tyding <I>wegpunktirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;is ilke king : was in wra&thorn;&thorn;e &amp; in care,</L>
<L>For he nyste no&thorn;ing : how he scholde fare,</L>
<L>Ne he nyste on lyue : wher he my&yogh;t hym do.</L>
<L N="80">A chaumbir ondir er&thorn;e : he leet make &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&amp; anon his &yogh;onge sone : he leet do &thorn;er inne,</L>
<L>For he ne schold of crist here : be no maner gyinne.</L>
<L>&thorn;e feyreste childrin of &thorn;e lond : he leet to hym do,</L>
<L>&amp; bad nomon to hym spek, : of no maner sorw ne wo,</L>
<L N="85">Ne of no &thorn;ing : &thorn;at my&yogh;t do hym care,</L>
<L>But in alle wyse : make hym mery to fare.</L>
<L>Of ih&umacr; crist he for bad : me scholde speke nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Lest he in any tyme : tornyd to hym his &thorn;ou&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000160.tif" N="116"></L>
<L>Of seknesse &amp; of elde : he heet hem al so</L>
<L N="90">&thorn;at &thorn;ey ne speke, &amp; &yogh;if any : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> w<SUP>t</SUP> hym were I do</L>
<L>Were in syknesse or in sorw&yogh;, : do a wey &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; nym an o&thorn;er in his sted, : &thorn;at ne ferd nou&yogh;t so:</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he were In ioy&yogh;e : &thorn;orw alle &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he &thorn;ou&yogh;t nou&yogh;t : on no&thorn;ing to comyng.<MILESTONE N="290" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="95">In &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> tyme was wit &thorn;e king : amon wel preue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Dieser Mann heisst im Mhd. Ged</I>. Barachias.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at preuely louid wel ih&umacr; crist, : as &thorn;e book telle&thorn; me.</L>
<L>Wit &thorn;e king on aday : he went on hontyng.</L>
<L>By &thorn;e wey &thorn;ey founde : apore mon gronyng;</L>
<L>Of abest he was hort : in his foot wel sore.</L>
<L N="100">Help he hym be sou&yogh;te : &amp; seruise, for godd&es; ore.</L>
<L>&thorn;e king rood for&thorn; his wey, : &amp; no kep ne took,</L>
<L>But lou&yogh; &amp; made game, : &amp; vtterliche hym for sook.</L>
<L>&thorn;is o&thorn;er aly&yogh;te of his hors : anon in &thorn;ilke stounde</L>
<L>&amp;, as he my&yogh;t, : bond vp his soor wounde.</L>
<L N="105">&thorn;e pore hym be sou&yogh;t : seruise pur charyte,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd: I may par awenture : in some &thorn;in helpe &thorn;e. &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;in <I>st.</I> &thorn;ing.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ou I &thorn;e vndirfong, : I not what &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> ca(n)st do. &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> cast <I>st.</I> canst.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e pore mon hym answerid : &amp; &thorn;&es; he seyd hym two:</L>
<L>I am leche of word&es;, : &amp; &thorn;er of helpe I can;</L>
<L N="110">&YOGH;if any man Is hort : of word of man,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou he be so hurt : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hym greue sore,</L>
<L>I hym wole hele, : &amp; he do be my lore.</L>
<L>&thorn;is kny&yogh;t hym ondirfong, : &amp; told &thorn;is for nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; sent hym to his hous : &amp; ha&thorn; hym to hele brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="115">Wit &thorn;e king were men &thorn;o : ful of enui&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&thorn;at gonne &thorn;is good kny&yogh;t : wel foule be ly&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Of some &thorn;ing &thorn;ey seyde soo&thorn;, : as I &yogh;ow telle can:</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey seyd &thorn;at he was : a cristin man;</L>
<L>But wel I woot &thorn;ey seyde lees : of an o&thorn;er &thorn;ing:</L>
<L N="120">&thorn;ey seide he was aboute to nym : &thorn;e kingdom of &thorn;e king,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he procurid &thorn;e baroun&es; of &thorn;e lond</L>
<L>ffor to putte out &thorn;e king : w<SUP>t</SUP> schame &amp; wit schond.</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt, &thorn;ey seyde, : &thorn;er of wite &thorn;e so&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Send after hym to morw&yogh; : &thorn;at he come to &thorn;e;
<PB REF="00000161.tif" N="117"></L>
<L N="125">Tel hym: &thorn;is world, : as &thorn;e &thorn;inke&thorn;, is nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore to holy lyf : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt torne &thorn;y &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp;, for &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> leuist on ih&umacr; crist, : monk &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt be come:</L>
<L>So &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> my&yogh;t his wille : knoue al &amp; some;</L>
<L>Wel &thorn;ou wost, leue syre, : &yogh;if he rad &thorn;er to,</L>
<L N="130">&thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;ing is al soo&thorn; : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> we &thorn;e tel to.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e king hadde al do : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;ey gonne hym rede,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kny&yogh;t fel to &thorn;e king&es; feet; : sore weping he sede:</L>
<L>Ih&umacr; cr&iacute;st of heuin, &thorn;onkid moot &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> be,</L>
<L>&thorn;at hast my lord soch reed I sent, : as he here telle&thorn; me.</L>
<L N="135">I wis, he seyde, leue syre, : triste me ne may</L>
<L>To &thorn;is false world : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> chaunge&thorn; ech day:</L>
<L>Nou &yogh;e se&thorn; &thorn;e wedir is hoot &amp; now cold,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlt: nach der ersten Halbzeile, wie v. 121. 289. 295. 477. 480. 513.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Now aman in his &yogh;ou&thorn;e is : &amp; now he is old,</L>
<L>Now aman is ryche : &amp; now in pouert I sete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">pouert <I>st.</I> pouerte <I>auch v. 164 und 166, aber</I> pouerte <I>v. 162</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">Nou aman is in gret chele : &amp; nou brenne&thorn; for hete,</L>
<L>Now me is in gret wele : &amp; now me is in wo;</L>
<L>&thorn;is world is vnstedfast, : ffor al &thorn;ing fary&thorn; so;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nach</I> is <I>ist</I> vs <I>wegpunktirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;erfore me &thorn;inke&thorn; I wis : it is &thorn;e beste reed,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> folwe &thorn;y &thorn;ou&yogh;t : &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> me hast I seed.</L>
<L N="145">&thorn;e king answerid: : I wene wel &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> do,</L>
<L>Worse &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> woldist do by me, : &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> my&yogh;tist come &thorn;er two.</L>
<L>Hom he wente to his hous, : &amp; be &thorn;ou&yogh;t anon</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e king in wra&thorn;&thorn;e : tok his word&es; echon,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;t he scholde be harmyd : &thorn;orw &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ilke speche,</L>
<L N="150">But he were holpe of hym : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> was of word&es; leche.</L>
<L>To hym he gan segge : &thorn;e wra&thorn;&thorn;e of &thorn;e king,</L>
<L>&amp; how his oune word&es; : were &thorn;e be ginnyng.</L>
<L>Wete it wel, qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, : &thorn;e king ha&thorn; ondirstonde</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art aboute : to dryue hym out of londe;</L>
<L N="155">Arys vp to morwe erlich, : &amp; kot about &thorn;in ere,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;y clo&thorn;&es; chaunge : &amp; clo&thorn;e &thorn;e in here!</L>
<L>Go erliche to &thorn;e king : in &thorn;e morw&yogh; tyde!</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;ou comyst to his bed, : stonde a whyle be syde,</L>
<L>&amp; aske hym wel fayre : wher he redy be,
<PB REF="00000162.tif" N="118"></L>
<L N="160">&amp; sey: syre, redy I am, : here &thorn;ou my&yogh;t se;</L>
<L>In mer&thorn;e we haue longe, : &thorn;ou wost, to gedir be,</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore I am redy to go : w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e to pouerte;</L>
<L>For im my rychesse : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast me feyr founde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> im <I>st.</I> in.</NOTE></L>
<L>I am redy wit &thorn;e : in pouert to be bounde;</L>
<L N="165">Wel &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wost in &thorn;y wele : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> madist me &thorn;y make,</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore in &thorn;y pouert : I nele &thorn;e forsake;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;er any &thorn;ing be : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> greuous is to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; we to gedir ben, : &thorn;e ly&yogh;ter it schal be.</L>
<L>As &thorn;is good mon tau&yogh;t : &thorn;is kny&yogh;t ha&thorn; I do,</L>
<L N="170">&amp; seyd he was al redy : wit &thorn;e king to go.</L>
<L>&thorn;e king lay &amp; herde : how he seyde &thorn;is;</L>
<L>Moche wondir hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t : of &thorn;is &thorn;ing I wis,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd: artow redy : for to go wit me?</L>
<L>fforso&thorn;e, qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, : syre, &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> my&yogh;t se &yogh;e;</L>
<L N="175">Me for to go wit &thorn;e, : I woot it is ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;er fore &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> my&yogh;t se : &thorn;er to I am dy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;er o&thorn;er wey be : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wilt to take,</L>
<L>I segge &thorn;e forso&thorn;e, : I nele &thorn;e forsake.</L>
<L>Wend a&yogh;en, qua&thorn; &thorn;e king, : I wille be &thorn;enke me;</L>
<L N="180">Haue &thorn;is in conseyl stille, : til I speke more w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&thorn;e king wel ondirstood : by &thorn;is ilke &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle here word&es; : nere but lesing,</L>
<L>&amp; euer he gan &thorn;e kny&yogh;t : &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> more honour do,</L>
<L>&amp; euer more &thorn;er after : &thorn;e more trist hym to.</L>
<L N="185">Iosaphat, &thorn;e king&es; sone, : maystris hadde of lore,</L>
<L>&thorn;at, &thorn;ou he were so be loke, : tau&yogh;t hym euere more.</L>
<L>On &thorn;is world he gan &thorn;enche, : &thorn;ou he it say selde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms. scheinbar</I> ho <I>st.</I> he.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he was ny of tyme : of fyftene &yogh;er elde.<MILESTONE N="291" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> &yogh;er <I>ist</I> er <I>wegpunktirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>A child &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hym was preue : wit speche swy&thorn;e softe,</L>
<L N="190">Whan he was in preuete, : he gan aske ofte,</L>
<L>Why he was so be schit : &amp; ne moste out go,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd: whan he &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;er on, : his herte was ful wo.</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;er nys mete ne drink &thorn;er fore : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> me do&thorn; gode.</L>
<L>&thorn;e child hym answerid : wit wel mylde mode:
<PB REF="00000163.tif" N="119"></L>
<L N="195">Syre, of &thorn;is reson, : I woot, &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> most be stille;</L>
<L>ffor I woot &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art here : &thorn;orw&yogh; &thorn;y fadir wille,</L>
<L>&amp; wel &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wost a&yogh;en hym : we ne mowe nou&yogh;t be;</L>
<L>&thorn;er fore, syre, make &thorn;e glad, : for loue I bidde &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Mafey, qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, : I wille gon out &amp; pley&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="200">Er I ete mete, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> I for hongur dey&yogh;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Die Abk&uuml;rzung</I> ur <I>st.</I> er <I>ist sehr selten, vgl</I>. wondur <I>256, 288</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e child dede &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> king to wit : of &thorn;is ilke &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>How nomon my&yogh;t his sone : bring in glading.</L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e sory was &thorn;e king, : &thorn;o he herde &thorn;is.</L>
<L>His sone he sette a day : to wende out I wis.</L>
<L N="205">Bo&thorn;e hous&es; &amp; stretis : so feyr he leet dy&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ne scholde finde no &thorn;ing : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> greuid his sy&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Fayre hors he purueyed, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he on ryde scholde,</L>
<L>&amp; grey&thorn;id hym to his wil : al &thorn;at he haue wolde.</L>
<L>As he rood on atym, : twey seke men he mette,</L>
<L N="210">Ablind mon &amp; amesel, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ful fayr hym grette.</L>
<L>Anon he clepid his mayster : &amp; &thorn;us seyde hym two:</L>
<L>Sey me for my loue, : what be&thorn; &thorn;ese ilke two?</L>
<L>Seke men, he seyde, : &thorn;ey be&thorn; bo&thorn;e I wis.</L>
<L>Schal ech mon, qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> leue&thorn;, &thorn;ole &thorn;is?</L>
<L N="215">Nay forso&thorn;e, qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er. : &thorn;e child seyde &thorn;o:</L>
<L>May me knowe &thorn;ilke men, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> it schal come two?</L>
<L>Nay I wis, qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, : &thorn;e so&thorn;e of &thorn;is &thorn;ing</L>
<L>No man may wite : but god, heuin king.</L>
<L>Hom &thorn;ey went w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> word. : &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> child was sory,</L>
<L N="220">ffor he ne knew nou&yogh;t &thorn;is &thorn;ing; : he nyst what do &thorn;er by.</L>
<L>But euer, whan his fadir : &amp; he to gedir were,</L>
<L>In as moche as he my&yogh;t : he made glad chere.</L>
<L>On a tyme as he rood, : an old mon he fond,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wlaffing <I>ist richt. Lesart, v.</I> wlaffen = blaffen, to stammer. [Note added from Berichtigungen (p. XLIV); original note read: <I>Ms.</I> wlaffing <I>mit unten verdicktem</I> l, <I>als ob dieses aus oder in</I> e <I>oder</I> a <I>corrigirt w&auml;re; ist</I> waffing <I>oder</I> waaffing = wavering (ags. vafjan) <I>zu lesen?</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Bleryid &amp; wlaffing : &amp; stouping to &thorn;e ground,</L>
<L N="225">Schabbid he was, his nose dropping, : lo&thorn;liche on to se.</L>
<L>&thorn;is child askid anon, : what &thorn;is my&yogh;te be.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> be <I>ist</I> se <I>wegpunktirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>His maystir hym answerde: : so old mon he is,</L>
<L>&thorn;at for pure elde : hym is come al &thorn;is.
<PB REF="00000164.tif" N="120"></L>
<L>&thorn;e child askid anon: : schal ech mon &thorn;&es; be falle?</L>
<L N="230">Nay I wis, qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, : but ofte it do&thorn; valle;</L>
<L>Whan aman leuid so long, : &thorn;&es; he wole fare.</L>
<L>Schal he leue long, qua&thorn; &thorn;is child, : er he come to &thorn;is care? &mdash;</L>
<L>In foure score &yogh;er or an hondrid, : &thorn;ow men it leue selde,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e after, to so&thorn;e, : we wyty&thorn; of elde.</L>
<L N="235">&YOGH;e moot me segge, qua&thorn; &thorn;is child, : &thorn;e ende of &thorn;is &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>I wis, <I>he</I> seyde, to so&thorn;e : de&thorn; is &thorn;e ending.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> &thorn;ey seyde <I>st.</I> he seyde.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o seyde &thorn;is good child: : scholle men dey&yogh;e echon?</L>
<L>&YOGH;e I wis, qua&thorn; his mayster, : &thorn;er may ascape non.<NOTE PLACE="foot">his <I>aus</I> &thorn;is <I>corri|girt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Her on &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;is &yogh;ong child : bo&thorn;e ny&yogh;t &amp; day;</L>
<L N="240">So moche was his care : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> telle it I ne may.</L>
<L>Whan he was afore his fadir, : he made good chere,</L>
<L>&amp; pleyid &amp; gamyd, : as hym no &thorn;ing nere;</L>
<L>Whan he was by hym self, : he gan to syke sore,</L>
<L>&amp; of &thorn;is ilke &thorn;ing : fayn he wold lerne more.</L>
<L N="245">A monk &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> wonyd in desert, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> wel holy lyf ladde,</L>
<L>Barlam he was hote, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> moche god dradde,</L>
<L>He wiste &thorn;orw &thorn;e holygost : al &thorn;e child&es; &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Abyt of marchaund he hym nom, : &amp; god hym &thorn;edir brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&thorn;e wey toward &thorn;is gode child : so longe he ha&thorn; nome,</L>
<L N="250">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> to &thorn;e child&es; mayster : ry&yogh;t he is I come.</L>
<L>Wel fayre he hym grette, : &amp; seyde to hym &thorn;&es;:</L>
<L>Aryche marchaunt I am, : of ferne lond I wis;</L>
<L>Apresyous ston I haue, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &yogh;eue&thorn; &thorn;e blinde sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Deue men to here, : my ston ha&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="255">Doume men for to speke, : halte men to goon,</L>
<L>Fol&es; for to make wyse; : ne is &thorn;is a wondur stoon?</L>
<L>Hedir I it haue brou&yogh;t : for &thorn;e child&es; sake;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms. urspr&uuml;nglich</I> wyuis sake; <I>dies ist wegpunktirt und</I> child&es; sake <I>dahinter geschrieben</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> makist me speke wit hym, : I wole it hym be take.</L>
<L>&thorn;e child&es; mayster answerid: : bro&thorn;er, leet me se</L>
<L N="260">&amp; aproue &thorn;at ston, : &yogh;if he soch be,</L>
<L>So &thorn;ou hast me fore told; : ffor erst, be my leute,</L>
<L>To take hym to iosaphat : tit &thorn;e no leue of me.</L>
<L>Do wey, qua&thorn; &thorn;is good mon, : I swere be my sleue:
<PB REF="00000165.tif" N="121"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> sey &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ston, : he &thorn;e wold greue;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e <I>&uuml;bergeschrieben</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="265">ffor, &thorn;ey my ston in some kind : be bo&thorn;e good &amp; ryche,</L>
<L>In an o&thorn;er kind he harmy&thorn;, : I segge &thorn;e trewelyche:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> segegge.</NOTE></L>
<L>He &thorn;at se&thorn; my stoon : in clene lyf moot be,</L>
<L>&amp; clene y&yogh;en &amp; gode haue, : or, I segge &thorn;e,</L>
<L>He hym wole make blind anon, : or don hym harm more;</L>
<L N="270">&amp; me &thorn;inke&thorn; to so&thorn;e : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;yn y&yogh;en be&thorn; sore.</L>
<L>Wel, qua&thorn; &thorn;is child&es; mayster, : se&thorn;&thorn;e it so is,</L>
<L>In clene lyf am I nou&yogh;t, : I know it wel I wis,</L>
<L>&amp; myn y&yogh;en be&thorn; sore, : wel I woot, al so,</L>
<L>&thorn;er fore I nele &thorn;y ston se, : lest he me harm do;</L>
<L N="275">To my lord I wille go : &amp; do &thorn;e hym come to;</L>
<L>&thorn;an my&yogh;tow &thorn;y fayre ston : schewe ry&yogh;t so.</L>
<L>&thorn;o he com to Iosaphat, : &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> child fayre hym grette,</L>
<L>&amp; vppon &thorn;e bench : fayre he hym sette.</L>
<L>Of o &thorn;ing, qua&thorn; barlam, : syre, &thorn;ou has wel wrou&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="280">&thorn;at to &thorn;ing &thorn;at semy&thorn; feyr : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> &yogh;euist &thorn;y wille nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>ffor a ryche king was sumtyme, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> rood in his chare<MILESTONE N="292" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Nobeliche about, : bo&thorn;e her &amp; &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Pore men he mette aday : by &thorn;e wey gon.</L>
<L>&thorn;ou he were ryche king, : to hem he leep anon,</L>
<L N="285">&thorn;ow &thorn;ey were pore : &amp; lo&thorn;lich on to se.</L>
<L>&thorn;e king to hem wel myldelich : sat adoun a kne,</L>
<L>&amp; dede hem wel gret honour. : &thorn;e men &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> w<SUP>t</SUP> hem were</L>
<L>&thorn;er of hadde wondur : &amp; speke to gedir &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>&thorn;at soche a king as he was ne scholde nou&yogh;t do so;</L>
<L N="290">But &thorn;er was non of hem : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> dorst ondirneme hym &thorn;o.</L>
<L>To his bro&thorn;er &thorn;ey told : afterward &thorn;is &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e bro&thorn;ir askid se&thorn;&thorn;e, : why he did so, &thorn;e king.</L>
<L>&thorn;e king answerid: to morwe : come hedir erliche to me,</L>
<L>&amp; I wille of &thorn;is &thorn;ing : &thorn;e so&thorn;e telle &thorn;e.</L>
<L N="295">&thorn;is king hadde a wondir wone to hy &amp; to lowe:</L>
<L>Whan aman damnyd be, : &thorn;e king wolde blowe</L>
<L>At his &yogh;ate, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> were dampnyd, : atrompe; &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> fel &thorn;er two,</L>
<L>To schewe &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he were tretour, : &amp; dampnyd al so.</L>
<L>&thorn;e king anon on euin : his troumpour ha&thorn; sent
<PB REF="00000166.tif" N="122"></L>
<L N="300">To bloue at his bro&thorn;er &yogh;ate, : to schewe his iugement.</L>
<L>Allas, qua&thorn; his bro&thorn;er, : what haue I mys do nowe?</L>
<L>I here my lord&es; trompour : at my &yogh;ate blowe,</L>
<L>Now I woot to so&thorn;e : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I wor&thorn; vndo;</L>
<L>God woot &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I haue : nou&yogh;t agilt &thorn;er to.</L>
<L N="305">&thorn;is mon gan hym dy&yogh;te : &amp; mad his testament,</L>
<L>ffor he wend to so&thorn;e : to be hangid or schent.</L>
<L>In foule clo&thorn;&es; on morw&yogh; : to &thorn;e king&es; &yogh;ate he com.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e portor it wist, : fayre he him in nom,</L>
<L>&amp; ha&thorn; hym fayre anon ry&yogh;t : to fore &thorn;e king brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="310">To fore &thorn;e king he fel on kne, : &amp; fayre hym be sou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>I noot what I haue &thorn;e agilt : in word ne in &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Haue mercy on me : for his loue &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e bou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>&thorn;an seyde &thorn;e king: : arys! what eyli&thorn; &thorn;e?</L>
<L>I noot no&thorn;ing &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast : mys do a &yogh;en me;</L>
<L N="315">Syre, me &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> dredist : &thorn;e blast of my beme,</L>
<L>I au&yogh;t to dred sorere, : &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> took &yogh;eme,</L>
<L>&thorn;ilke lord&es; beme : &thorn;at god &amp; mon is,</L>
<L>To whom bo&thorn;e ny&yogh;t &amp; day : I do to moche amys;</L>
<L>I may deme &thorn;y body, : of &thorn;y soule haue I no my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="320">&amp; he may bo&thorn;e body &amp; soule : to his wille dy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&thorn;y bodylich pyne : wold be doon in a day,</L>
<L>But &thorn;e pyne of &thorn;e soule, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wost wel, lasti&thorn; ay.</L>
<L>&thorn;ou me askedist &yogh;ister day : a wel wondir &thorn;ing:</L>
<L>Why I honourid pore men, : &amp; I am so hy a king?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Im Ms. ist</I> was <I>wegpunktirt und</I> I am <I>&uuml;bergeschrieben</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="325">&thorn;at my lord&es; trompour&es; : I woot to so&thorn;e it were,</L>
<L>&thorn;at bo&thorn;e day &amp; ny&yogh;t : bloue&thorn; in myn ere,</L>
<L>&amp; biddi&thorn; me &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I schold : come to mendement,</L>
<L>Lest I be to helle dampnid : &thorn;orw&yogh; pure iugement.</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;ilke hard doom, : &thorn;at mon schal so be schent,</L>
<L N="330">Whan &thorn;e wrecche soule : is to helle went!</L>
<L>Now wost &thorn;e reson, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> me askedist er;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hinter</I> wost <I>fehlt</I> &thorn;ow.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sykir, leue bro&thorn;er, : I dede it for fer.</L>
<L>&thorn;e king leet make : foure fatis anon.</L>
<L>&thorn;e twey&yogh;e he leet gilde wit out : &amp; feyr be goon,
<PB REF="00000167.tif" N="123"></L>
<L N="335">Of stinking bon&es; : &thorn;eke he leet fille,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hinter</I> he <I>fehlt</I> hem.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;e me dede hem &thorn;er in, : so foul it gan smelle.</L>
<L>&thorn;e o&thorn;er twey he leet smere : wit pych &amp; ter al so,</L>
<L>&amp; wit gold &amp; ryche ston&es; : filde hem bo.</L>
<L>After &thorn;ilke wreyeris : he leet sende &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="340">&amp; askid, of &thorn;e fatis : woch &thorn;e rycher were.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ey hym answerid : &amp; seyd anon:</L>
<L>&thorn;ilke two &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> were : wit gold so be gon.</L>
<L>&thorn;e king heet anon ry&yogh;t : &thorn;at &thorn;ey were vndo;</L>
<L>Soche asmel &thorn;er com out : of &thorn;o fatis two,</L>
<L N="345">&thorn;at vnne&thorn;e anyman : my&yogh;t &thorn;er a boute byde.</L>
<L>&thorn;us it fari&thorn;, qua&thorn; &thorn;e king, : by &thorn;is world&es; pryde;</L>
<L>Feyr it glori&thorn; w<SUP>t</SUP> oute, : wit inne it is nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Mony monn&es; soule : to helle it ha&thorn; brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&thorn;o leet &thorn;e king anon : vndo &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> o&thorn;er two;</L>
<L N="350">Gold ryche &amp; ston&es; : me fond in hem &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&thorn;us it fary&thorn;, qua&thorn; &thorn;e king, : by pore men I wis,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> wit gode verteuis : winny&thorn; heuin blis;</L>
<L>Wit oute &thorn;ey be&thorn; lo&thorn;lich, : w<SUP>t</SUP> inne ryche,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey leue hard lyf : &amp; hat sinne treuliche.</L>
<L N="355">Here &yogh;e mowe &thorn;e so&thorn;e : alle men I se,</L>
<L>Whey&thorn;er of &thorn;ese two vesselis : schold honourid be;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hinter</I> two <I>ist ein</I> w <I>wegpunktirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>But &thorn;e world do&thorn; a mys : &amp; honouri&thorn; rychesse,</L>
<L>&amp; taki&thorn; wel lyte kep : to come in any goodnesse;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore mon moot nede, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> wole to god be take,</L>
<L N="360">Leue his oune wille : &amp; &thorn;is world forsake.</L>
<L>After &thorn;at &thorn;is king seyd, : Iosaphat, I rede &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> loue ih&umacr; crist, <I>:</I> &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> deyde on &thorn;e tre.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it barlam hym told : an o&thorn;er &thorn;ing I wis:</L>
<L>Ih&umacr; crist hym selue, : &thorn;at god &amp; man is;</L>
<L N="365">He ha&thorn; in hym self : fayr kynd&es; &thorn;re,</L>
<L>Holy writ w<SUP>t</SUP>nessi&thorn; it : &amp; ha&thorn; I told it me:<NOTE PLACE="foot">I <I>vor</I> told <I>ist undeutlich</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffadir he is, &amp; ek sone, : &amp; ek holy gost;</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;ing he made : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> seyst &amp; wost.<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyst = siehst, <I>wie v. 437</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mon he made to haue be : euer in paradys,
<PB REF="00000168.tif" N="124"></L>
<L N="370">Amon it a gilte : &thorn;orw an appil I wis;</L>
<L>God hym seyde &thorn;at he schold : euere leue in wele &amp; blisse,</L>
<L>&amp; of his oune wille : neuere more to mysse;</L>
<L>But an o&thorn;er &thorn;ing &thorn;er to : god to mon be heet:</L>
<L>&thorn;at he scholde dey&yogh;e, : &yogh;if he &thorn;e appil eet,<MILESTONE N="293" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="375">&amp; lese alle mer&thorn;e : &amp; &thorn;ole alle wo.</L>
<L>&amp; out of paradis I cast : sekir he was so,</L>
<L>ffor he ete &thorn;e appil : &thorn;orw &thorn;e deuelis spelle;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> ete <I>ist ein</I> h <I>wegpunktirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>God hym &yogh;af an hard doom, : his soule went to helle,</L>
<L>&amp; al &thorn;at of hym com, : for so&thorn;e ich segge &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="380">So wro&thorn; was god w<SUP>t</SUP> mon, : &thorn;at he nold hym se.</L>
<L>Mon hadde god for&yogh;ete, : &thorn;at on hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t he nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>But w<SUP>t</SUP> his oune hondin : he ha&thorn; hym I wrou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&amp; honouri&thorn; &yogh;it, so &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> sest, : his oune werching,</L>
<L>&amp; forsaki&thorn; &thorn;ilke god : &thorn;at made alle &thorn;ing.</L>
<L N="385">A boue mon wente atyme : &amp; wit his bowe pleyde;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ff. <I>Diese Erz&auml;hlung fehlt im Mhd. Gedicht</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alytil brid he cau&yogh;te, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> reuelich to hym seyde:</L>
<L>I bidde &thorn;e for &thorn;y lord&es; loue, : haue mercy on me!</L>
<L>For lytil good &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt winne, : &thorn;o<SUP>u</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> me sle;</L>
<L>Leet me freliche leue : &amp; in my wey fle,</L>
<L N="390">&amp; I &thorn;e wole teche anon : wisdom&es; &thorn;re;</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hem holde, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt &thorn;e beter be.</L>
<L>Do sey, qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, : &amp; &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt haue lyf of me. &mdash;</L>
<L>Ne leue &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> neuer alle &thorn;ing : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> my&yogh;t here,</L>
<L>For men lye&thorn; ofte moche, : whan &thorn;ey speke I fere;</L>
<L N="395">Ne sorwe &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> nou&yogh;t to sore : for &thorn;ing &thorn;at is lore,</L>
<L>&yogh;if it ne may be found, : ne sorw &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> nou&yogh;t &thorn;er fore;</L>
<L>Ne desire &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> neuer &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;ing : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> my&yogh;t haue nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For I wis al soche wil : comy&thorn; of idil &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Mafey, qua&thorn; &thorn;is good mon, : so&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> seyst to me.</L>
<L N="400">&amp; wit &thorn;ilke word : &thorn;e brid he leet fle.</L>
<L>&thorn;o it was vp on hy, : &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> brid hym seyd to:</L>
<L>I wis &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> dedist gret foly&yogh;e, : &thorn;o &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> leet me go,</L>
<L>ffor among my gott&es; : I haue aryche ston,</L>
<L>Also gret as an ey&yogh;, : gret verteu is &thorn;er on;
<PB REF="00000169.tif" N="125"></L>
<L N="405">Hadde &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> me slaue : &amp; &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ston take,</L>
<L>Euere &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> haddist be ryche : for &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> ston&es; sake;</L>
<L>But for &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast &thorn;e ston lore, : I wis &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast mys do.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> mon &thorn;is herd, : sykir hym was ful wo,</L>
<L>&amp; for &thorn;e lore of &thorn;is ston : he gan to syke sore,</L>
<L N="410">&amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;te how&yogh; he my&yogh;te : &thorn;e brid cacche more.</L>
<L>Brid, he seyde, cum to me, : &amp;, whil &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art alyue,</L>
<L>I wole &thorn;e finde at &thorn;y nede, : at hom w<SUP>t</SUP> my wyue;</L>
<L>Afeyr cage I wille make : for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; in ioy &amp; in myr&thorn; : &thorn;er in &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt be;</L>
<L N="415">Moche &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt her after : haue &thorn;y wille;</L>
<L>Ne be &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> no&thorn;ing a drad : &thorn;at me schal &thorn;e spille!</L>
<L>ffor&thorn; fley &thorn;is lyte brid, : &amp; nold no leng abyde.</L>
<L>&thorn;is &yogh;ong mon wente wit his bou&yogh; : euere be syde,</L>
<L>&amp; prouid al &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he my&yogh;t, : &thorn;<SUP>s</SUP> bryd for to sle.</L>
<L N="420">&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> wisdom&es;, qua&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> bryd, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I &thorn;e tau&yogh;t : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast lore alle &thorn;re;</L>
<L>Herkene now how, : &amp; I &thorn;e wolle telle.</L>
<L>Beter Is haue &thorn;an weche(!),: &amp; go, &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt dey&yogh;e, &thorn;a<SUP>n</SUP> dwelle.</L>
<L>A ston, so gret as an ey, : how my&yogh;t in my wombe be?</L>
<L>Al my body is nou&yogh;t so gret, : as ech mon may se.</L>
<L N="425">&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schet for to haue &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP>, : &thorn;ou ne my&yogh;t come &thorn;er two,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> <I>fehlt wol</I> &thorn;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L>For I &thorn;e segge &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> ne schalt : haue me neuere me.</L>
<L>Wel I woot &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art sory, : for &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> me hast lore;</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> dost &thorn;er of foly&yogh;e, : I for bede it &thorn;e be fore.</L>
<L>&thorn;&es; it fari&thorn; be men of &thorn;is world, : &thorn;at leue&thorn; amys</L>
<L N="430">Vppon here false god&es;, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> here oune werk is;</L>
<L>&thorn;ey seke&thorn; help of here god&es;, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> mowe nou&yogh;t do,</L>
<L>&amp; bydde of hem mony &thorn;ing, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;ey ne mowe come two;</L>
<L>Wel me may wite to soo&thorn; : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;ey be&thorn; deue &amp; doumbe,</L>
<L>&amp; hem selue helpe ne mowe, : sekir, in no stounde.</L>
<L N="435">&thorn;is world is to hem lych; : who so trist &thorn;er two,</L>
<L>Moche he wor&thorn; be gylyd, : al day we fynde so;</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> seyst &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;is world : torny&thorn; vp so doun;</L>
<L>Now mon is in feld, : &amp; now he is in toun,</L>
<L>I ne finde nomon : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> may dayis &thorn;re</L>
<L N="440">ffor no&thorn;ing &thorn;at he may do : in one stede be;
<PB REF="00000170.tif" N="126"></L>
<L>For &thorn;e flesch is so lostful : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> synny&thorn;, ech day</L>
<L>It falli&thorn; in to sinne, : forso&thorn;e telle I may.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at mon moot hym self : &amp; &thorn;is world forsake,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he wille hym self : redy to god make.</L>
<L N="445">I woot &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;ey be&thorn; I lyche, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;is world loui&thorn; &thorn;&es;,</L>
<L>To amon &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> me telle&thorn; of : in prouerbis I wis.</L>
<L>Amon wente atyme, : so we fynde in geste,</L>
<L>Hym self for to pley&yogh;e, : in wilde foreste.</L>
<L>An vnycorn hym mette, : &thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh;t hym to sle.</L>
<L N="450">For doute of &thorn;e de&thorn; : &thorn;is mon gan to fle.</L>
<L>&thorn;e vny corn ran swy&thorn;e, : &thorn;e mon fley&yogh; euer mo;</L>
<L>So &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he com to a dep pit; : he fel wel ny&yogh; &thorn;o.</L>
<L>By abou&yogh; of a lyte tre : anon he hym hent,</L>
<L>&amp; held hym swy&thorn;e faste, : &thorn;at he a doun ne went.</L>
<L N="455">To &thorn;e ground of &thorn;e pit : he gan to loke &thorn;o:</L>
<L>Aswy&thorn;e grisliche dragoun : he sey on grounde go;</L>
<L>For to cacche &thorn;is mon : he &yogh;enede faste;</L>
<L>Fer com out of his mou&thorn; : at eueriche ablaste.</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> rote of &thorn;e tre : twey mees he sey&yogh;,</L>
<L N="460">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hadde al &thorn;e rote : frete wel ny&yogh;;</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> o mous was whit, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> o&thorn;er blak was;</L>
<L>Me &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;is mon : was in a wondir cas.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at stede &thorn;er he stood : he say&yogh; addris foure,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> pot out of &thorn;e er&thorn;e here hedis : &amp; on hym gonne loure.</L>
<L N="465">In &thorn;e crop of &thorn;e tre : he say an honys drope;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e swetnesse &thorn;er of : &thorn;er on he cast his hope;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e peril for &yogh;at he, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he was in I do,</L>
<L>For &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> swetnesse of &thorn;e hony : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he say &thorn;er &thorn;o.</L>
<L>Who my&yogh;te aske &thorn;ilke mon, : &yogh;if he ne did foly&yogh;e?</L>
<L N="470">I wene neuer mon, : but he wolde ly&yogh;e.</L>
<L>By &thorn;e ony corn, &thorn;at I of telle, : de&thorn; I ondirstonde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at honty&thorn; bo&thorn;e man &amp; best, : &amp; al &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> is in londe;<MILESTONE N="294" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;ou he fle neuer so fast, : ech mon dey&yogh;e schal;</L>
<L>De&thorn; ne spari&thorn; no&thorn;ing, : I woot, it chasti&thorn; al.</L>
<L N="475">&thorn;e pit is &thorn;is world, : &thorn;at is so ful of wo,</L>
<L>Of couetyse &amp; enui&yogh;e : &amp; of wra&thorn;&thorn;e al so,</L>
<L>&amp; of o&thorn;er sinn&es;, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> be&thorn; many &amp; fale;</L>
<L>Nys nomon on lyue : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hem may telle by tale.
<PB REF="00000171.tif" N="127"></L>
<L>&thorn;e lytil tre is monn&es; lyf, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> is so vnstedefast,</L>
<L N="480">&thorn;at wit mony perilis a doun is I cast:</L>
<L>Wit syknesse &amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> elde : &amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> slau&yogh;t also;</L>
<L>Nys no mon on lyue : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> may triste &thorn;er two.</L>
<L>&thorn;e dragon in &thorn;e pitt&es; ground, : helle mou&thorn; it is,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;eny&thorn; after mann&es; soule : ny&yogh;t &amp; day I wis;</L>
<L N="485">&thorn;er is bo&thorn;e pyne &amp; wep, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> lasti&thorn; w<SUP>t</SUP> oute ende;</L>
<L>Wo is hym on lyue : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;edir schal wende.</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyte mous &amp; &thorn;e blak, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> han &thorn;e tre I bete,</L>
<L>Be&thorn; &thorn;e ny&yogh;t &amp; &thorn;e day, : ech man may wite;</L>
<L>Ech of hem amossel taki&thorn; : of monn&es; lyf;</L>
<L N="490">How he may be glad, : I not, for child ne wif.</L>
<L>&thorn;e foure addrin be&thorn; foure element&es;, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> be trende &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>&amp; by here my&yogh;t wilwid : &thorn;at it I schortid be;</L>
<L>Foure tym&es; of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> &yogh;er : &thorn;ey mowe be al so,</L>
<L>&thorn;at euerich schorti&thorn; monn&es; lyf, : go wher euer he go.</L>
<L N="495">&thorn;e lytil hony, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he say, : is &thorn;is world&es; blis,</L>
<L>&thorn;at wel lytil is wor&thorn;, : ech mon woot &thorn;is;</L>
<L>For &thorn;er was here ne ellis whare : neuer no mon<NOTE PLACE="foot">: <I>doppelt, nach</I> ne <I>und nach</I> whare.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at leuid on er&thorn;e &thorn;re dayis : wit oute care non.</L>
<L>Lo &thorn;ese &yogh;onge childrin : &thorn;at ondirstonde nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="500">By here wep me may wite : In care &thorn;ey be brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Whan me se&thorn; it is lyte wor&thorn;, : &thorn;is wikkid wor(l)d&es; blis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> word&es; <I>st.</I> world&es;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Me &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> eche mon do&thorn; : al to moche amys,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he for a lyte swetnesse : trist to moche &thorn;er two,</L>
<L>&amp; for&yogh;ete &thorn;e perelis : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he is in I do.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> perelis, e <I>scheint in</I> i <I>corrigirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="505">How man may triste lyte to &thorn;is world, : by on lytil spelle,</L>
<L>Who so wole vndirstonde, : forso&thorn;e I may telle.</L>
<L>Aman lyuid a tyme : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hadde frend&es; &thorn;re;</L>
<L>More he louid &thorn;at on &thorn;an hym self, : &yogh;if it my&yogh;te be;</L>
<L>As moche as hym self : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> o&thorn;er he louid &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="510">&amp; wold by his my&yogh;t : euere for hym do;</L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;ridde he louid a lyte : &amp; for hym he did.</L>
<L>&thorn;is good mon was bayly : of aryche sted,</L>
<L>&thorn;er he lyuid long, &amp; hadde his wille I wis<NOTE PLACE="foot">long <I>&uuml;berge|schrieben</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000172.tif" N="128"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ilke ryche stede : &amp; alle &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er inne is.</L>
<L N="515">I wreyid was se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;is good mon : to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> king wel faste.</L>
<L>&thorn;e king hym ofscnte, : his acount&es; to caste.</L>
<L>&thorn;o nyste &thorn;is good mon : what on er&thorn;e to do;</L>
<L>He caryd bo&thorn;e ny&yogh;t &amp; day, : &amp; &thorn;olid moche wo,</L>
<L>By hym self he wep : &amp; made moche mone,</L>
<L N="520">ffor he ne hadde of his acount&es; : knowleche none.</L>
<L>&thorn;er nas clerk &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> coude &thorn;o : help hym &thorn;er two,</L>
<L>&amp; nedis his a count&es; : he moste &yogh;eue &thorn;o.</L>
<L>To my frend&es;, he &thorn;ou&yogh;t, : I wille anon go</L>
<L>&amp; look, wher &thorn;ey wole now&yogh; : any help me do;</L>
<L N="525">My frend&es; &thorn;ey were, : &thorn;ey seydin er &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Whil I hadde my wille : of &thorn;ese world&es; blis;</L>
<L>&yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ey be&thorn; kynde, : &yogh;it &thorn;ey be&thorn; al so,</L>
<L>&thorn;ey nelle me nou&yogh;t forsake, : &thorn;ou I be falle In wo.</L>
<L>Anon to &thorn;ilke frend : he wente be fore.</L>
<L N="530">&thorn;at he louid as hym self, : &amp; aparty more.</L>
<L>Ly&yogh;tliche he was wel comyd, : as hym &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;are,</L>
<L>So men be&thorn; comeliche : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> be&thorn; falle in care.<NOTE PLACE="foot">comeliche <I>st.</I> comenliche.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is mon seyd : leue frend, : moche I triste to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> me helpe in my (nede) : for loue I bidde &thorn;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hinter</I> my <I>fehlt</I> nede <I>im Ms.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="535">&thorn;enk vppon &thorn;e gret loue, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast louid me,</L>
<L>In my grete nede, : for loue I bidde &thorn;e;</L>
<L>For I me drede sore : lest &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I be schent,</L>
<L>To &yogh;ild myn acount&es; : &thorn;e king me ha&thorn; of sent.</L>
<L>&amp; he hym answerid schortly: : what is &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> to me?</L>
<L N="540">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou hast wel I do, : &thorn;e bet &thorn;ou schalt be;</L>
<L>Euil moot he falle : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> afoot wit &thorn;e go!</L>
<L>I knowe &thorn;e nou&yogh;t, : what schold I wit &thorn;e do?</L>
<L>O&thorn;er frend&es; I haue, : to dwelle w<SUP>t</SUP> I wis,</L>
<L>Hem I wille glade, : &amp; make ioy &amp; blis,</L>
<L N="545">For w<SUP>t</SUP> me &thorn;ey dwelli&thorn; : al &thorn;is longe day;</L>
<L>Good mon, dwelle nou&yogh;t, : but go for&thorn; in &thorn;y way!</L>
<L>&thorn;is good mon be &thorn;ou&yogh;t hym, : &amp; was aschamyd sore,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> to &thorn;ilke frend : he my&yogh;te triste na more.
<PB REF="00000173.tif" N="129"></L>
<L>&YOGH;ern he bad godd&es; help, : sykir hym was ful wo;</L>
<L N="550">&amp; to his o&thorn;er frend sekir : he gan go.</L>
<L>To hym he seyde : leue frend, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wost wel, or &thorn;is</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> me louedist moche, : &thorn;o I was in my blis;</L>
<L>Help me in my tene, : for loue I bidde &thorn;e!</L>
<L>To &yogh;ilde myn a count&es; : &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> king ha&thorn; sent for me.</L>
<L N="555">Sertis, qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er frend, : &thorn;y tene greue&thorn; me sore;</L>
<L>&amp; wel &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wite to so&thorn;e : &thorn;at I nele do na more:</L>
<L>To &thorn;e castel &yogh;ate : wit &thorn;e I wille go,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e torne hom a &yogh;en, : whan I haue do so;</L>
<L>So moche I haue to done, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I ne may tent to &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="560">&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> most do &thorn;y beste, : &yogh;if it &thorn;y wille be,</L>
<L>ffor, be &thorn;ou sykir, I nele, : for no maner sake,</L>
<L>Let be myn oune werk : &amp; to an o&thorn;er take.</L>
<L>Carful was &thorn;is good mon : &amp; wente &thorn;enn&es; &thorn;o;</L>
<L>Helples he was in his nede : for hem bo&thorn;e two.</L>
<L N="565">Me &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> his loue : was euil be sette;</L>
<L>I rede ech man his loue : to be set bette.</L>
<L>To his &thorn;ridde frend : &thorn;is sely mon is go,</L>
<L>&amp; al ha&thorn; to hym told : his care &amp; his wo.</L>
<L>Leue frend, he seyde, : it greue&thorn; me wel sore,<MILESTONE N="295" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="570">Whyl I was of my&yogh;t, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I ne did for &thorn;e more;</L>
<L>But for &thorn;e lyte loue, : &thorn;at I haue louid &thorn;e,</L>
<L>In my grete nede I : bidde &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> helpe me;</L>
<L>My lord ha&thorn; after me sent, : &thorn;er of me stont drede,</L>
<L>&amp; I woot, wit oute &thorn;e : ne may I nou&yogh;t spede.</L>
<L N="575">Be stille, qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, : &thorn;er of is non ey&yogh;e;</L>
<L>I wole &thorn;e helpe : by alle &thorn;ilke wey&yogh;e:</L>
<L>Be fore &thorn;e lord my self : I wole wit &thorn;e go,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;ilde &thorn;e &thorn;y mede, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast for me do;</L>
<L>For ech peny wor&thorn; good, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast me do,</L>
<L N="580">I wole &thorn;e &yogh;eue an hondrid, : se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast nede &thorn;er two,</L>
<L>&amp; I wole &thorn;e helpe, : be &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> nou&yogh;t a gast!</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> ne schalt for no &thorn;ing : In presoun ben I cast;</L>
<L>&amp; be sykir euere mo, : whil &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I may stond,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou ne schalt be take : in to &thorn;y fomen hond.</L>
<L N="585">&thorn;is was a good frend, : for to triste to;</L>
<L>Leuere I hadde soch afrend : &thorn;an &thorn;e o&thorn;er two.
<PB REF="00000174.tif" N="130"></L>
<L>&thorn;e ferste frend &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> was so fals, : &thorn;at I of told,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> amon more &thorn;an hym self : on er&thorn;e loue wold,</L>
<L>It is world&es; catel, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> fayli&thorn; at &thorn;e nede;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fayli&thorn; <I>aus</I> falli&thorn; <I>corrigirt; Ms. urspr</I>. ne nede, <I>zu</I> nede <I>cor|rigirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="590">He &thorn;at most it gadirit : most liue&thorn; in drede,</L>
<L>ffor worldis good hem do&thorn; : in peril &amp; in wo,</L>
<L>&amp; mony mon for world&es; good : be&thorn; to de&thorn;e do;<NOTE PLACE="foot">mon <I>st.</I> men.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ou amon it loue moch, : it &yogh;ildi&thorn; li&thorn;er mede,</L>
<L>&amp; mon &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> it serui&thorn; : ne may to heuin spede,</L>
<L N="595">ffor mon ne may I fere, : for nou&yogh;t &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he may do,</L>
<L>Serue wel &thorn;e false world : &amp; oure lord also;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore mon ha&thorn; fre wille, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he may wel chese</L>
<L>ffor to winne heuin : o&thorn;er to lese.</L>
<L>&thorn;at o&thorn;er frend &thorn;at I of spak : ofte me se&thorn;,</L>
<L N="600">ffor monn&es; wif &amp; childrin : &amp; er&thorn;elich &thorn;ing it be&thorn;;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e pitt&es; brinke : wit &thorn;e dede &thorn;ey wille go,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e torne hom, : here ded&es; for to do.</L>
<L>Gold, seluer, &amp; lond : &thorn;ou he haue be &yogh;ete,</L>
<L>Wit inne twey &yogh;er or &thorn;re : sone he wor&thorn; for &yogh;ete.</L>
<L N="605">Asely almesse bred for hym : o&thorn;er whyle me wole &yogh;eue,</L>
<L>Wher&thorn;oru &thorn;e sely soule : mow &thorn;e beter leue;</L>
<L>So may &thorn;e sely soule : ligge wel long</L>
<L>In &thorn;e pyne of purgatory, : &amp; be pynyd strong,</L>
<L>Er eny of his frend&es; : ary&yogh;t hym wil helpe.</L>
<L N="610">&thorn;at &thorn;ey be&thorn; gode frend&es;, : I not he may &yogh;elpe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>undeutlich, ob</I> he <I>oder</I> ho.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;ridde frend &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I of spak, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> was trewe &amp; gode,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is mon In is wele : wel lyte ondirstode:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I> is In wele, <I>st.</I> In is wele.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hope loue &amp; tru&thorn;e : &amp; o&thorn;er almes dede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlt</I> it be&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at mon scholde loue wel : &thorn;at scholde good lyf lede.</L>
<L N="615">But &thorn;ese gode &thorn;euis : of lond be&thorn; dreue echone</L>
<L>&thorn;orw&yogh; wra&thorn;&thorn;e pride &amp; couetyse, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> be&thorn; here fone;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore &thorn;is fals world : go&thorn; by experment;</L>
<L>&amp; men for defaute of loue : ofte be&thorn; I schent.</L>
<L>&thorn;e preson, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he schold in be do, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> is &thorn;e pyne of helle,</L>
<L N="620">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> for defaute of acount&es; : mon schal in dwelle.</L>
<L>&thorn;e dedis of his lyf : schal his acount&es; be;
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="131"></L>
<L>&thorn;er to ech mon mot tak kep : &thorn;at hopi&thorn; sauid to be.</L>
<L>Good is &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ech mon &thorn;enk, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he ne fayle nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>How he ha&thorn; his lyf leuid, : in werk word &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="625">&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> soumme of his a count&es; : man mot a &yogh;er take</L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e mony tym&es;, : good acount&es; to make;</L>
<L>For at euery tyme : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> mon ha&thorn; sinne do,</L>
<L>Forme of a count&es; : he moot make &thorn;er two;</L>
<L>ffor euery mys dede : In dette he is I wis</L>
<L N="630">For to &yogh;eue acount&es;, : &amp; ellis he do&thorn; amys.</L>
<L>But &thorn;e tayl be to broke : &amp; &thorn;e gilt for &yogh;eue,</L>
<L>Monn&es; soule may nou&yogh;t : in heuen blisse leue.</L>
<L>Ech day mon be houi&thorn; : his tayl to breke,</L>
<L>Er, I woot to so&thorn;e, : in helle he schal be steke;<NOTE PLACE="foot">er <I>st.</I> or.</NOTE></L>
<L N="635">O&thorn;er at on a count&es; : amon may breke echon,</L>
<L>But beter it were, me &thorn;inke&thorn;, to breke on &amp; on.</L>
<L>&thorn;e fomen, fro whom he wold hym kep, : &thorn;e deuelis be&thorn; I wis,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> maki&thorn; monn&es; soule : euer to don amys;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ist</I> bodi <I>st.</I> soule <I>zu lesen?</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> &thorn;e soule it witsegge, : &amp; &thorn;e dede be I do,</L>
<L N="640">For &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ilke dede : to pyne &thorn;ey scholle bo;</L>
<L>Worse fon &thorn;er be&thorn; none, : &thorn;an &thorn;ey be&thorn; I wis,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey fondi&thorn; w<SUP>t</SUP> here my&yogh;t : to make men don amys.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore I rede ech man : kepe hym fro his foon,</L>
<L>&amp; purchase soche frend&es; : &thorn;at he mowe triste vppon.</L>
<L N="645">How mon hym schal dy&yogh;te : her in world &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he wole wit hele : come to heuin blis,</L>
<L>By atale me my&yogh;t lerne, : who so wold here,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> here <I>ist</I> lerne <I>wegpunktirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at he my&yogh;t his lyf lede : in &thorn;<SUP>c</SUP> beter manere.</L>
<L>A maner was in a contre, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ech &yogh;er chese &thorn;ey wold</L>
<L N="650">A prince, astrong mon : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hem gouerne schold;</L>
<L>&thorn;at man king scholde be, : ac at serteyn tyme I wis,</L>
<L>But nomon scholde wite : woch were tyme his;</L>
<L>For &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> men of &thorn;e contre, : whan here tyme com,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e lond hym wold fleme : al w<SUP>t</SUP> oute doom</L>
<L N="655">In to aserteyn yle, : &thorn;er he schold dwelle,</L>
<L>To suffre sorwe &amp; wo : more &thorn;an I may telle.</L>
<L>On atyme it be fel, : astrong mon &thorn;ey tokin
<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="132"></L>
<L>&amp; made hym king of &thorn;e lond, : hem alle for to lokin.</L>
<L>&thorn;is man hym so be louid : w<SUP>t</SUP> men of &thorn;e contre,</L>
<L N="660">&amp; suffrid ech of hem : his mayster to be:</L>
<L>Al &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;ey wold rede, : al &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;ey wold do,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> &thorn;ey <I>in der letzten Hlbz. st.</I> he.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; wende hem fynde frend&es;, : &amp; fond hem as fo;</L>
<L>For, &thorn;o &thorn;ey sey here tyme, : &thorn;ey nom hym at &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> last</L>
<L>&amp; wit moche schame : out of &thorn;e lond hym cast.</L>
<L N="665">&thorn;er he lay wel longe : &amp; &thorn;olyd pyne &amp; wo,<MILESTONE N="296" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> rorw&yogh; <I>st.</I> sorw&yogh;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne my&yogh;te nomon telle &thorn;e sorw&yogh; : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he &thorn;olid &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;is man was out cast, : an o&thorn;er &thorn;ey ches anon</L>
<L>To be king of &thorn;e lond : &amp; weld hem ech on.</L>
<L>&thorn;e king, &thorn;o he was chose, : was wel war</L>
<L N="670">By &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> king afore hym, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> was mad so bar :</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e yle, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I of spak, : &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tresour he hent,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> <ABBR>Ihc</ABBR> <I>st.</I> he <I>verschrieben</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wit wel trewe messager&es; : anon &thorn;edir it sent,</L>
<L>In moche wele &amp; ryches : for he wolde lyue,</L>
<L>Whan he were par auenture : in to &thorn;is yle I dreue;</L>
<L N="675">&thorn;erfore he ha&thorn; in &thorn;e yle : his tresour I do.</L>
<L>Al redy he it fond, : &thorn;o he com &thorn;er two.</L>
<L>&thorn;e contre &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I of told, : &thorn;e foule world it is;</L>
<L>&thorn;e borgeys of &thorn;e contre : sinn&es; it be&thorn; y wis,</L>
<L>As pride gloteny &amp; couetys, : &amp; o&thorn;er sinn&es; also,</L>
<L N="680">&thorn;at euere dwelli&thorn; in &thorn;is world, : go mon wher he go.</L>
<L>&thorn;e strong mon &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> is king, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> is, I ondirstonde,</L>
<L>Euerymon &amp; woman : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> leui&thorn; in &thorn;is londe.</L>
<L>Kyng &thorn;ey be&thorn; chose I wis : hem self for to gy&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&amp; to do wel o&thorn;er wro&thorn;erhele : he hadde &thorn;e maystry&yogh;e.</L>
<L N="685">&thorn;is yle, wel I woot, : purgatory&yogh;e is,</L>
<L>&thorn;at mon schal inne dwelle, : after he do&thorn; amys.</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tresour is worldis good, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ech mon w<SUP>t</SUP> his my&yogh;t</L>
<L>Streng&thorn;ith hym to winne : bo&thorn;e day &amp; ny&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he send his tresour : be fore in to &thorn;e yle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> int <I>mit weg|punktirtem</I> t.</NOTE></L>
<L N="690">By pore men for godd&es; loue, : he noot woch whyle</L>
<L>Ech peny &amp; penewor&thorn; : &thorn;er he schal fyinde,</L>
<L>&amp; he may loke after &thorn;at, : &thorn;at he leue&thorn; be hinde.
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="133"></L>
<L>I rede &thorn;erfore &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> nomon : triste to haue socoure</L>
<L>Of non er&thorn;eliche frend, : ne of non secatoure,</L>
<L N="695">But do so &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he mowe : his tresour finde wel,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he leue&thorn; be hinde hym : he lese&thorn; ech a del;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou me wele hym ou&yogh;t &yogh;eue, : it wor&thorn; late &amp; long,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> soule ligge : in peyne swy&thorn;e strong.</L>
<L>&thorn;o he hadde al &thorn;is I seyd, : &thorn;e child hym answerid anon:</L>
<L N="700">Syre, god &yogh;ilde &thorn;e &thorn;y reed! : w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> I wele goon,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if it be &thorn;y wille, : I nele neuere mo</L>
<L>Parte out of &thorn;y company, : for wele ne for wo.</L>
<L>Barlam hym answerid : : &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> do &thorn;is,</L>
<L>To aryche monn&es; sone : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art lych I wis:</L>
<L N="705">A gret lord&es; dou&yogh;ter : to wyue <I>he schold</I> take.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt <I>st.</I> he schold.</NOTE></L>
<L>He answerid &amp; seyd, : he nolde haue no make.</L>
<L>&amp; for he nold in no wis : to here I spousid be,</L>
<L>Out of his fadir lond : wel fer he gan fle.</L>
<L>For&thorn; he went in his wey, : as god hym had dy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="710">&amp; at alyte pore hous : his in he took any&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&thorn;o it be fel to &thorn;e tyme, : he to his bed gan go;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o he hadde a whyle I ley&yogh;e, : be syde he lokid &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; sey &thorn;e pore monn&es; dou&yogh;ter, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &yogh;he knelid a doun</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;onkid god swy&thorn;e : in here orysoun.</L>
<L N="715">Moche wondir hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t : &thorn;at &yogh;he dede so,</L>
<L>For hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> god here had : lyte good do.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> hele <I>st.</I> here.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e mayde he spak &thorn;er of, : &amp; askid, how it were</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &yogh;he &thorn;ankid so god : for lytil good &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>&amp; seyd to here : &thorn;ou &thorn;y god : &thorn;e hadde &yogh;oue gold &amp; fe,</L>
<L N="720">&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> ne my&yogh;tist hym more &thorn;onk, : al so &thorn;inke&thorn; me.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pore mayde answerde : &amp; seyde to hym &thorn;is:</L>
<L>&thorn;e hy&yogh;e god of heuene : I wile honoure I wis,</L>
<L>For, as lytil medesyne : gret euil do&thorn; a wey,</L>
<L>Al so alyte world&es; good : wel moche helpe may.</L>
<L N="725">To maner godis, I find, : &thorn;er be&thorn; in world &thorn;is :</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> on nys nou&yogh;t oure, : I woot wel I wis,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> o&thorn;er is oure oune, : whil godd&es; wille is:</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> be&thorn; oure fyf wittis, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he lene&thorn; vs I wis;
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="134"></L>
<L>To some men he leny&thorn; some, : &amp; to some men echon;</L>
<L N="730">&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> more &thorn;at he vs leny&thorn;, : &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> more &thorn;onk is &thorn;er on.</L>
<L>&thorn;e worldis good is nou&yogh;te oure, : for nou&yogh;t it wele go,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> it nou&yogh;te:, <I>mit wegpunktirtem</I> n, <I>u</I>. t <I>in</I> nou&yogh;te <I>aus</I> r (oder &thorn;) <I>corrigirt; es ist wol zu lesen</I> is nou&yogh;t(e); <I>in der 2. Hlbz. sollte es heissen</I> for for nou&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; for it wole by on whyle : a&yogh;en come vs two;</L>
<L>&amp; now it wole al clene : er&thorn;elich men forsake,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>u</I>. 4 <I>Im Ms. nicht deutlich ob</I> wole <I>oder</I> wele <I>zu lesen</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; now it wole holliche : to aman hym be take.</L>
<L N="735">To an heep of snow&yogh; : likene it I may,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> is to day wel breme, : &amp; to morw molt a way.</L>
<L>Er&thorn;eliche good he ha&thorn; me be nome, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> me ne trist nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>But myne fyf witt&es; : he ha&thorn; be nome nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>After his lyk nesse : he ha&thorn; mad me,</L>
<L N="740">&amp; to my seruise &yogh;oue : al &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I may se;</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; me grantid : &thorn;at I haue knowleching</L>
<L>Of good &amp; of harm, : to kepe me fro sinnyng.</L>
<L>To his blis he ha&thorn; me clepid : &thorn;orw his holy grace,</L>
<L>&amp; in heuin he ha&thorn; mad : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I haue aplace.</L>
<L N="745">&thorn;erfore I hym wole honoure, : as ry&yogh;t is,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ilke grete &yogh;(i)ft&es;, : ellis I dede amys.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> &yogh;ft&es; <I>st.</I> &yogh;ift&es;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o he &thorn;is herd, : his wil com hym wel blyue</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is pore mayde : he wold haue to wyue.</L>
<L>To here fadir he went, : &amp; ha&thorn; of hym I bede</L>
<L N="750">&thorn;at he hym to wyue &yogh;eue : his dou&yogh;ter in &thorn;e stede.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pore mon answerid: : vnkinde it were to &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Hinter</I> to <I>ist</I> me <I>wegpunktirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Soche apore womon : &thorn;y wif for to be.</L>
<L>Euer more &thorn;is child : bad wel &yogh;erne I wis;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e fadir answerid : &amp; seyde to hym &thorn;is:</L>
<L N="755">I ne may &thorn;is mayde : &yogh;eue &thorn;e nou&yogh;t to spouse,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> here wole lede : to &thorn;y fadir house;</L>
<L>For I ne haue no dou&yogh;ter, : &thorn;ou wost wel, but here on,</L>
<L>&amp; I woot wel &thorn;at gret eld : is come me vppon;<MILESTONE N="297" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt here haue, : sekir I segge &thorn;e</L>
<L N="760">&thorn;at &yogh;e moot bo&thorn;e : dwelle here wit me.</L>
<L>&thorn;is &yogh;ong mon answerid : wit speche wel stille:</L>
<L>Wit &thorn;e I wille be leue : &amp; be at &thorn;y wille.
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="135"></L>
<L>His ryche clo&thorn;&es; he of did, : &amp; o&thorn;er abit to hym nom,</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;is old pore mon : wel bouxum he be com.</L>
<L N="765">&thorn;is &yogh;ong mon he be tok : his dou&yogh;ter to wyue.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;ey hym seruid : wit here my&yogh;t wel blyue.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;is old man had : &thorn;is &yogh;ong mon asayid</L>
<L>&amp; in his seruise : swy&thorn;e wel apayid,</L>
<L>In to his chaumbir on a day : &thorn;is &yogh;ong mon he ladde,</L>
<L N="770">&amp; scheuid hym &thorn;e tresour : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he &thorn;er in hadde.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;is &yogh;ong mon it say, : to wondre he be gan;</L>
<L>Hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t rycher tresour : hadde neuer no man.</L>
<L>Now&yogh;, qua&thorn; &thorn;is old mon, : for &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast seruid me,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is tresour anon : I wole it &yogh;eue &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="775">&thorn;at &amp; moche more : I wille her after schewe;</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast seruid me, : ne schal &thorn;e no&thorn;ing rewe.</L>
<L>Allas, qua&thorn; Josaphat, : &thorn;is is seyd be me,</L>
<L>&amp; wel I woot to so&thorn;e, : it au&yogh;te wel to be,</L>
<L>&amp; wel I woot to so&thorn;, : of me &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> my&yogh;t it make;</L>
<L N="780">&thorn;erfore, &yogh;if it were &thorn;y wille, : I wold me be take.</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if it were &thorn;y wille, : I wold wyte of &thorn;e</L>
<L>Of hou mony &yogh;er&es;: &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> old be.</L>
<L>I wot, qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, fyf &amp; sixty &yogh;er : myn elde is.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e I wis, qua&thorn; iosaphat, : &amp; more I wis,</L>
<L N="785">ffor I it may segge : al wit oute wene</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art of elde : sixty &yogh;er &amp; tene.</L>
<L>Sykir, qua&thorn; barlam, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast wel ondirstonde I wis</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e &yogh;er&es; &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I haue : leuid in world &thorn;is;</L>
<L>But fyue &amp; syxty &yogh;er : I haue cristin mon be:</L>
<L N="790">&thorn;ilke I au&yogh;t acounte, I wis, : so &thorn;inke&thorn; me;</L>
<L>&thorn;e o&thorn;er a counte I nou&yogh;t, : ne nele neuere mo,</L>
<L>For I woot &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I was : in mys be leue &thorn;o;</L>
<L>&amp; I wone forso&thorn;e : in &thorn;e wildirnes of samar.</L>
<L>Wolde god, qua&thorn; iosaphat, : &thorn;at we were bo&thorn;e &thorn;ar!</L>
<L N="795">&amp; &thorn;edir I wole now&yogh; : wit &thorn;y leue go w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Wite it wel, qua&thorn; barlam, : it may nou&yogh;t so be,</L>
<L>ffor wel I woot to so&thorn;e, : fro me &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> worst take,</L>
<L>&amp; mony holy men slawe : schol be for &thorn;y sake;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou schalt at &thorn;y wille : come &thorn;edir to me;</L>
<L N="800">But cristni &thorn;e I wille, : &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt it so be.
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="136"></L>
<L>I wis, qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, : al redy I am &thorn;er two;</L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e glad were I, : were &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I do.</L>
<L>Josaphat was cristenyd : &thorn;<SUP>o</SUP> of barlam.</L>
<L>&amp; after he hym kiste, : &thorn;o he his leue nam:</L>
<L N="805">In to desert he went, : godd&es; wil to abyde.</L>
<L>&thorn;at Josaphat was cristenyd : anon me wiste wyde.</L>
<L>So &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> it com sone : to auenne &thorn;e king.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Im Anfange, vor</I> so, <I>steht im Ms. ein</I> o, <I>welches zu tilgen</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel I woot, sory he was, : &thorn;<SUP>o</SUP> he herd &thorn;e tyding.</L>
<L>Allas, seyde auenne, : my sone is for lore;</L>
<L N="810">Me for &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> euer : he was I bore;</L>
<L>&amp; I ne haue, wel &yogh;e wite&thorn;, : sone but hym on,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou I wolde, qua&thorn; &thorn;e king, : &thorn;at his lyf dayis were doon.</L>
<L>I wold, qua&thorn; &thorn;e king, : he were brou&yogh;t afore me,</L>
<L>&thorn;at I my&yogh;t &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> so&thorn;e wite, : what his encheson be.</L>
<L N="815">Anon wit &thorn;ilkc word : Josaphat me nam</L>
<L>&amp; askid, who hym tau&yogh;te. : he seyde: barlam.</L>
<L>Arachis het a gret lord : &thorn;at w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e king was &thorn;o.</L>
<L>I woot, he seyde to &thorn;e king, : ful wel what &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt do:</L>
<L>An old ermyte I knowe, : in &thorn;y lond nys non soche,</L>
<L N="820">In body he is &amp; in spech : barlam I liche,</L>
<L>He be leue&thorn; trewliche : on oure lawe;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> after hym send, : he wole be wel fawe;</L>
<L>Send after hym quiklich : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he come &thorn;e two,</L>
<L>&amp; al &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> barlam ha&thorn; seyd, : I woot he wol vn do;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vor</I> vndo <I>ist</I> do <I>wegpunktirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="825">fferst he schal him feyne : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he cristin is,</L>
<L>&amp; after he schal ben ouer come, : &amp; wel suffre &thorn;is.</L>
<L>Arachis &amp; &thorn;e king &thorn;o : in to wildirnesse gan wende,</L>
<L>For to nyme barlam, : &yogh;if &thorn;ey my&yogh;t come hym hende.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;ey sey &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;ey ne my&yogh;t : barlam finde nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="830">Nacor for hym &thorn;ey haue nome : &amp; to &thorn;e court brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he schold do : &thorn;ey tau&yogh;t hym be &thorn;e wey&yogh;e.</L>
<L>He seyde, he wold gladlich, : &amp; leue for non ey&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;o &thorn;e king was : hom to court I come,</L>
<L>Me tolde to Josaphat : hou barlam was I nome.</L>
<L N="835">Sore wep &thorn;is &yogh;ong mon : &thorn;o for &thorn;ilk tydinge,
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="137"></L>
<L>His y&yogh;en he cast vp to heuin : &amp; his hondin gan wringe.</L>
<L>Lord, he seyde, ih&umacr; crist, : what schal barlam do?</L>
<L>I woot, my fadir wold fayn : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he were for do;</L>
<L>I nold in no wise : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he deyd for me,</L>
<L N="840">Fayn I wold hym helpe : on lyue to be.</L>
<L>Wit &thorn;at ilke word : an aungel to hym aly&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&thorn;e &yogh;ong mon was a gast, : for he schon so bry&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Josaphat, he seyde, : ne drede no &thorn;inge &thorn;e!</L>
<L>Barlam is in &thorn;e stede : &thorn;er he au&yogh;t to be;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> barlan <I>st.</I> barlam.</NOTE></L>
<L N="845">It is nou&yogh;t barlam, : but it nacor is,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;y fadir ha&thorn; of sent, : to gyle &thorn;e I wis;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore do&thorn; god &thorn;e to wit : &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> ne be a gast,</L>
<L>For &thorn;orw&yogh; &thorn;e schal nacor : of &thorn;is lyf be cast.</L>
<L>Wit &thorn;at ilke word : &thorn;e aungel to heuin went.</L>
<L N="850">Josaphat &thorn;onkid god : of grace &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he sent.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vor</I> grace <I>fehlt</I> &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e fadir wente to his sone : &amp; to hym seyde &thorn;is:</L>
<L>I haue nome barlam, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> tau&yogh;t &thorn;e of ihesus;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e <I>aus</I> me <I>corrigirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>I noot wher &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> it finde : to anoy&yogh;e so me:</L>
<L>So feyr I haue be my my&yogh;t : euer honourid &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="855">Wel &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wost how &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast : chaungid my fare,<MILESTONE N="298" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast my moche wele : tornyd in to care;</L>
<L>Myn hore lokk&es; &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast mad : me for to drawe,</L>
<L>&amp; I ne may &thorn;onk &thorn;e more : &thorn;an &thorn;ou me haddist slawe;</L>
<L>&thorn;e ly&yogh;t of myn y&yogh;en : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast mad aslake,</L>
<L N="860">For &thorn;ou hast take to god : &amp; myne god&es; forsake.</L>
<L>ffadir, qua&thorn; iosephat, : god &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> &thorn;onke my&yogh;t:</L>
<L>I haue forsake derknes : &amp; am I come to ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L>ffro al manere falsnesse : I me haue dy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;orw &thorn;e help of ih&umacr; crist : I am take to ry&yogh;t;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> il&umacr; <I>st.</I> ih&umacr;.</NOTE></L>
<L N="865">&thorn;erfore I &thorn;e bidde, : on ydil trauayl &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt fro ih&umacr; crist : neuere torne my &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> my&yogh;t heuin : areche wit &thorn;in hond</L>
<L>&amp; drey&yogh;e &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> water of &thorn;e se, : so &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> se al lond,</L>
<L>&thorn;an my&yogh;tow, forso&thorn;e, : fadir, I segge &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="870">ffro crist&es; seruise : ry&yogh;t so bringe me.
<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="138"></L>
<L>Allas, sone, qua&thorn; &thorn;e king, : who ha&thorn; do me &thorn;is sorwe?</L>
<L>But I &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> haue foluid &thorn;y wil : on euin &amp; on morwe?</L>
<L>Nas neuer king &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> my&yogh;t : his sone do</L>
<L>More &thorn;an I haue do to &thorn;e, : &amp; &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> seruist me so!</L>
<L N="875">&thorn;erfore, I se, &thorn;ou art : a&yogh;en myn heed aryse;<NOTE PLACE="foot">se <I>aus</I> so <I>corrigirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel au&yogh;t here afterward : o&thorn;er men by me agryse</L>
<L>ffor to do his sone honour, : as I haue do &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Lest he aryse a&yogh;en hym, : as &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art a &yogh;en me.</L>
<L>Wel seyde &thorn;e clerk&es;, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> tolde me fore</L>
<L N="880">In &thorn;e tym &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wer : of &thorn;y modir bore:</L>
<L>Vn buxum, &thorn;ey seyde, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> scholdist be al &thorn;y lyf,</L>
<L>&amp; a&yogh;en alle oure god&es; : w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;y my&yogh;t strif.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore I segge: : but &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> do after me,</L>
<L>Euer more her after : &thorn;y foman I wole be;</L>
<L N="885">&thorn;er was neuer fomon to o&thorn;er : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> dede so moche wo,</L>
<L>As I wole her after : wit my my&yogh;t &thorn;e do.</L>
<L>Josaphat answerid: : &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art fadir myn,</L>
<L>&yogh;if I torne to gode : it is manschipe &thorn;in;</L>
<L>But ech fadir for his sone : ou&yogh;t glad be,</L>
<L N="890">Whan &thorn;e sone to gode tornyd, : I wis, so &thorn;inke&thorn; me;</L>
<L>&amp; I &thorn;e segge for so&thorn;e: : &yogh;if &thorn;e rui&thorn; my gode,</L>
<L>I ne hold &thorn;e nou&yogh;t my fadir, : but I hold &thorn;e wode;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore I &thorn;e segge, : &amp; wite it to so&thorn;e:</L>
<L>&yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> me greuist her after, : I nele nau&yogh;t come to &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="895">But, as &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> were an addre : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> woldist me stinge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlt wol &amp; in der 2. Hlbz., oder</I> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> <I>st.</I> &thorn;<SUP>t.</SUP></NOTE></L>
<L>I wole &thorn;e fle, but &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> chast : of &thorn;is ilke &thorn;inge;</L>
<L>Ne I nele neuere more : fadir clepe &thorn;e;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore do what &thorn;y wille is, : &amp; tak no kep of me!</L>
<L>&thorn;an wente &thorn;e king, : &thorn;o (he) herde &thorn;is,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vor</I> herde <I>fehlt</I> he.</NOTE></L>
<L N="900">What for sorw &amp; for wra&thorn;, : ny wood I wis.</L>
<L>To arachis, his gode frend, : he told al &thorn;is &thorn;ing;</L>
<L>&amp; he wit fayre word&es; : &thorn;&es; seyde to &thorn;e king:</L>
<L>For I wene me schal : childrin w<SUP>t</SUP> fayr speche</L>
<L>Beter chastise, &thorn;an me schal : wit beting &amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> wreke . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlt ein Verspaar</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="905">&thorn;o on morwe be king com, : &amp; kyste his sone swete,
<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="139"></L>
<L>&amp; bad hym &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he schold : his foly for lete.</L>
<L>Leue sone, he seyde, : lo myn hed is hor;</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> me hast gramyd : &thorn;in hert au&yogh;t be sor;</L>
<L>Woldistou leue &thorn;y foly&yogh;e : &amp; do after me,</L>
<L N="910">Bo&thorn;e vs my&yogh;t on lyue : &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> beter &thorn;anne be;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou wost wel &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;y be leue : au&yogh;t be ry&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For who &thorn;er on be leui&thorn;, : to de&thorn;e he is sone brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&amp; ech sone to his fadir au&yogh;t buxum be;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore let be &thorn;y pride, : &amp; be buxvm to me!</L>
<L N="915">Loue me, &amp; I wolle &thorn;e (do) : as ry&yogh;t is to done,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hinter</I> &thorn;e <I>fehlt</I> do.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; but &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt, an o&thorn;er &thorn;ing : I wil do wel sone.</L>
<L>Josaphat hym answerde: : tyme to loue it is,</L>
<L>&amp; tyme is to hate, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> wot ech man I wis;</L>
<L>Of werre &thorn;er is tyme, : &amp; of pes also;</L>
<L N="920">&amp; &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> falli&thorn; to tyme : ech mon au&yogh;te to do;</L>
<L>Schame it were, &yogh;if aman : schold fro god wende</L>
<L>To a deuil of helle, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> wold his soule schende;</L>
<L>For god sey&thorn; hym self: : fadir &amp; modir he is,</L>
<L>Who so fro hym torny&thorn;, : I wis, he do&thorn; amys.</L>
<L N="925">&thorn;o answerde &thorn;e fadir: : now&yogh; I &thorn;e so&thorn;e se,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> nelt in no wise : worche after me,</L>
<L>Wole we go I fere : doun in to &thorn;e toun,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er we mowe here afayr : disputacioun</L>
<L>Of barlam, &thorn;y mayster : In game &amp; in plawe,</L>
<L N="930">&thorn;at schal despute wit clerk&es; : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> be&thorn; of &thorn;e lawe;</L>
<L>Amessager al so : fram me schal out wende,</L>
<L>By whom I wole clerk&es; : of oure lawe of sende;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er &thorn;ey scholle despute : fulle dayis &thorn;re.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if barlam &thorn;orw&yogh; his queintys : mowe mayster be,</L>
<L N="935">I wole my self &amp; my lond : torne &thorn;an to &thorn;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sind im Ms. umgestellt.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if barlam be ouer come, : torne &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> &thorn;an to me.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sind im Ms. umgestellt.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>ffor&thorn; went &thorn;is good child : wit his fadir &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o &thorn;ey come to &thorn;e stede : &thorn;er &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> ded schold be do,</L>
<L>&thorn;e child seyde to nacor: : a(r)tow barlam?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> atow <I>st.</I> artow.</NOTE></L>
<L N="940">&YOGH;e I wis, qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wost wel I it am.
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="140"></L>
<L>Barlam, qua&thorn; iosephat, : o&thorn;ing I warne &thorn;e:</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt despute for &thorn;e fey : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast tau&yogh;t me;</L>
<L>Lok &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> despute : for &thorn;e fey ary&yogh;t,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er, be &thorn;ilke lord : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> made day &amp; ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="945">&YOGH;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> in &thorn;is desputasioun : now ouer come be,</L>
<L>I wole al myn anoy : my self wreke on &thorn;e,</L>
<L>I wole draw out w<SUP>t</SUP> myn hond : &thorn;in herte &amp; &thorn;y tonge</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;rowe hem to hound&es;, bo&thorn;e olde &amp; &yogh;onge;<MILESTONE N="299" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>O&thorn;er scholle euere her after : be war be &thorn;e</L>
<L N="950">To be gyle any man, : as &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> be gylist me;</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> in &thorn;e lawe : haue &thorn;e maystry&yogh;e,</L>
<L>I wole euer more : loue &thorn;y company&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Nacor of &thorn;ese word&es; : gan &thorn;o to be a gast,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;t, hym was beter, : to be stedfast</L>
<L N="955">&amp; be leue wit &thorn;e child : &amp; leue in goodnesse,</L>
<L>&thorn;an suffre ben ouer come : &amp; dey&yogh;e in schennesse.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore in his herte : he gan to syke sore,</L>
<L>&amp; wel sore a&thorn;ou&yogh;t : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he be gan &thorn;is lore.</L>
<L>Vp ros a gret clerk, : &thorn;at wit &thorn;e king was &thorn;o:</L>
<L N="960">Artow &thorn;ilke barlam : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hast wrou&yogh;t &thorn;is wo?</L>
<L>&thorn;e king&es; sone, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> here is, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast brou&yogh;t in foly&yogh;e</L>
<L>&thorn;at he forsaki&thorn; oure god&es;, : &amp; &thorn;at is velany&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Wel I woot, qua&thorn; nacor, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I am barlam;</L>
<L>ffro foly in to tru&thorn;e : &thorn;e king&es; sone I wan,</L>
<L N="965">ffor wel I wot to so&thorn;e : &thorn;at foly is it non</L>
<L>To honoure ih&umacr; crist : &amp; forsake &thorn;e dede ston.</L>
<L>How is &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP>? qua&thorn; &thorn;e clerk, : I here a wondir &thorn;ing:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> hele <I>st.</I> here.</NOTE></L>
<L>Houre god&es; honouri&thorn; : erl, baroun, &amp; king,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> spekist of anewe god : &amp; of anewe lawe;</L>
<L N="970">&thorn;er fore ha&thorn; mony mon : be brou&yogh;t of dawe;</L>
<L>How is it &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> darst : oure god&es; do deshonour?</L>
<L>Artow beter &thorn;an any erl, : king, or emperour?</L>
<L>Qua&thorn; nacor: I wis, &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> most lern : to preche &thorn;y gyge,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;is ilke resoun : nys nou&yogh;t wor&thorn; afyge;</L>
<L N="975">Some men honouri&thorn; god&es; : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> be&thorn; wit hond&es; wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Of ston, tre, gold, &amp; seluer; : here be leue is nou&yogh;t;
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="141"></L>
<L>Dede men in some contre : me clepi&thorn; god&es; al so,</L>
<L>As iubyter &amp; plato, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> is mys I do;</L>
<L>&amp; I be leue on ih&umacr; crist, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> is ful of my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="980">&thorn;at wold fro heuin for vs in to er&thorn;e aly&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&amp; of amayde he was bore, : &thorn;o he hidir com;</L>
<L>Of seint ihon, &thorn;e baptist, : he fong cristindom;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e blis of heuin moche he gan preche,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he was so&thorn;fast god : w<SUP>t</SUP> fayre meraklis teche;</L>
<L N="985">At &thorn;e last men hym nome : &amp; dede hym on &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L>Gilt, I woot, had he non, : it was for oure gode.</L>
<L>&thorn;&es; prechid nacor al day : of &thorn;e fey wel ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;er nas no sara&yogh;yn : &thorn;at hym answere my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;is predycacyoun was : Josaphat glad &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="990">&thorn;at cristindom was prechid : &thorn;orw&yogh; ih&umacr; crist&es; fo.</L>
<L>&thorn;e king was for &thorn;is dede : in herte ful wo,</L>
<L>&amp; bad &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e company : departid were in two,</L>
<L>To fond a &yogh;en on morw&yogh; : to be &thorn;enche more,</L>
<L>To torn &thorn;is child&es; &thorn;ou&yogh;t : &thorn;orw&yogh; nacor Is lore.</L>
<L N="995">&thorn;o seyde iosephat: : my mayster &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> most me take,</L>
<L>&thorn;at we mowe to gedere : of &thorn;is &thorn;ing speche make;</L>
<L>&amp; tak wit &thorn;e &thorn;y conseyl, : as &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> au&yogh;tist to do,</L>
<L>Some conseyl &yogh;e mowe make, : &yogh;if &yogh;e senti&thorn; &thorn;er to;</L>
<L>But &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> graunte &thorn;is, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> worchist nou&yogh;t &thorn;e ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="1000">Wel &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> my&yogh;t vs dele a two : &thorn;orw&yogh; &thorn;y grete my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Now&yogh; &thorn;e king granti&thorn; : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> nacor wit hym go,</L>
<L>&amp; nau&yogh;t but for he hopi&thorn; : his beleue he schal vn do;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> ho&thorn;i&thorn; <I>st.</I> hopi&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e king &thorn;an granty&thorn; : &thorn;at &thorn;ey go her in fere,</L>
<L>&amp; come on morw to &thorn;e court, : for he hem wold here.</L>
<L N="1005">So &thorn;ey went to gydere. : Josaphat to hym seyde:</L>
<L>I woot &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art nau&yogh;t barlam, : as my fadir seyde,</L>
<L>Nacor is &thorn;y ry&yogh;te name; : drede is in &thorn;e steke,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> stoke <I>st.</I> steke.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> ne darst for al &thorn;e world : a word a&yogh;en me speke;</L>
<L>&thorn;ow&yogh; &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> haue al day : prechid cristindom,</L>
<L N="1010">I woot wel, of &thorn;y good wil : no &thorn;ing it ne com;</L>
<L>But &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt, nacor, : do by my lyste</L>
<L>&amp; lete &thorn;y false god&es; : &amp; leue on ih&umacr; criste,
<PB REF="00000186.tif" N="142"></L>
<L>&thorn;ou my&yogh;t saue &thorn;y self, : &amp; &thorn;y soule al so;</L>
<L>I wot &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt dey&yogh;e, : but &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> it wolt do;</L>
<L N="1015">For I woot &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt : nou&yogh;t ascape fro me</L>
<L>In no maner wyse, : but it &thorn;y wille be</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> leue on ih&umacr; crist, : &amp; do after my lore,</L>
<L>&amp; be trewe cristin man : here after euer more.</L>
<L>Apreue prest he hadde, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> to hym gan gon</L>
<L N="1020">&amp; &thorn;orw here beyre reed : cristenyd nacor anon.</L>
<L>Nacor for&thorn; went, : &thorn;o he had moche of age,</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e desert of samar, : &amp; tok an ermytage.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e king herde &thorn;is, : sykir hym was ful wo.</L>
<L>A, mahound, he seyde, : lord, what schal I do?</L>
<L N="1025">My sone me ha&thorn; smyte : wit acarful wounde,</L>
<L>&amp; noman me helpe can : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I were &thorn;er of vn bounde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vor</I> vnbounde <I>ist</I> bound <I>wegpunktirt.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Theodas, a gret lord, : herd telle of &thorn;is cas;</L>
<L>Abeter clerk in &thorn;at lond be &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> tyme ne was.</L>
<L>Syre, he seyde to &thorn;e king, : &thorn;o he to hym com,</L>
<L N="1030">I can make &thorn;y sone : leue his cristin dom;</L>
<L>&yogh;if I make, to &yogh;oure god&es; : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he torne a&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Sey me wit good wil : what &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt &yogh;eue me.</L>
<L>&yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt do &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP>, qua&thorn; &thorn;e king, : I wole lete make an image,</L>
<L>To whom men scholle aloute : of alle maner age,</L>
<L N="1035">&amp; I my selue wille make : to &thorn;e offringe &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>In alle manere wyse, : as &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> a god were.</L>
<L>Wel &thorn;an, qua&thorn; teodas, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> most &thorn;y sone bring</L>
<L>After my red : in to an o&thorn;er wonyng;</L>
<L>&thorn;e fayresse women of &thorn;e lond : to hym &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;ey brou&yogh;t be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">fayresse <I>st.</I> fayreste.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1040">So &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he haue no &thorn;ing : but hem on to se;</L>
<L>A sprit I wole hym sende, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hym schal tempte so,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vor</I> so <I>ist</I> sore <I>wegpunktirt.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at he ne schal haue no &thorn;ou&yogh;t : but lechery to do;</L>
<L>&thorn;er is nomon on lyue : &thorn;at so torny&thorn; monn&es; &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>As wyme, whan aman : among hem is I brou&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyme <I>st.</I> wymen.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1045">ffor a kyng was a tyme, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> a sone hadde,</L>
<L>&amp; lest he lore his son&es; lyf, : sore he hym dradde.</L>
<L>Lechis he of sente, : &thorn;at scholde hym consayle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">lechis <I>aus</I> leshis <I>corrigirt.</I></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="143"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ey to hym seyde, : sykir w<SUP>t</SUP> oute fayle,<MILESTONE N="300" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at, &yogh;if his sone sey&yogh;e : sonne o&thorn;er mone,</L>
<L N="1050">&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> ly&yogh;t of his y&yogh;en : he scholde lese sone.</L>
<L>&thorn;e king in an er&thorn;e hous : let his sone do.</L>
<L>So &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he ne say sonne ne mone : neuer mo</L>
<L>Ten &yogh;er o&thorn;er more, : so &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he knew no &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Name of man ne best. : &amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;orw&yogh; &thorn;e king</L>
<L N="1055">He was fro &thorn;e stede brou&yogh;t: : me let hym &thorn;ing&es; se,</L>
<L>For he schold to so&thorn;e wite : what ech &thorn;ing scholde be.</L>
<L>Women me brou&yogh;t afore hym; : he askid what &thorn;ey were.</L>
<L>Me seyde: it were deuelis : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he say &thorn;o &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&thorn;at gyli&thorn; mann&es; soul&es; : &amp; bringe&thorn; hem in wo,</L>
<L N="1060">For moche in &thorn;is world : &thorn;ey haue harm I do.</L>
<L>&thorn;e king clepid his sone : &amp; seyde to hym &thorn;&es;:</L>
<L>Woch &thorn;ing louistow mest : of &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> sey er &thorn;is?</L>
<L>&thorn;e child seyde : &thorn;ilke deuelis : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I say er whyle,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> wole mann&es; soule : w<SUP>t</SUP> here my&yogh;t be gyle,</L>
<L N="1065">For at &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> ferste tyme : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> I hem sy&yogh;,</L>
<L>Me &thorn;ou&yogh;t of wit I was : for lore wel ny&yogh;.</L>
<L>By &thorn;at I woot to so&thorn;e : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he (ne) wor&thorn; ouer come,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> so&thorn;e <I>mit der Abk&uuml;rzung f&uuml;r</I> er. <I>Vor</I> wor&thorn; <I>fehlt</I> ne.</NOTE></L>
<L>But his &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;orw&yogh; women : mowe hym be by nome.</L>
<L>As &thorn;is clerk ha&thorn; seyd, : al me ha&thorn; I do;</L>
<L N="1070">&thorn;e fayreste women of &thorn;e lond : hem me brou&yogh;t hym two.</L>
<L>&thorn;e sprit, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> was hym sent, : brende w<SUP>t</SUP> inne hym fast,</L>
<L>&thorn;e women hym tempte so wit oute, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he was sore a gast.</L>
<L>Oft he be sou&yogh;te god, : help hym for to sende;</L>
<L>He fond &thorn;at his flesschis lost : &thorn;er wit a wey wende.</L>
<L N="1075">A ryche king&es; dou&yogh;ter : his fadir hym gan sende,</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &yogh;he was fadirles, : his &thorn;ou&yogh;t for to wende.</L>
<L>&thorn;is child here prechid of crist : &amp; of heuin blis,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;he hym answerid : &amp; seyd anon I wis:</L>
<L>&thorn;ou ne schalt neuer mo : to &thorn;y laue torne me,</L>
<L N="1080">But &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> &amp; I to gedere : ra&thorn;er spousid be;</L>
<L>ffor spoushod is grauntid, : cristin men witi&thorn; &thorn;is:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sind im Ms. umgestellt, aber ihre richtige Folge ist mit</I> b a <I>bezeichnet.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Patryark&es; &amp; prophetis : spousid were I wis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sind im Ms. umgestellt, aber ihre richtige Folge ist mit</I> b a <I>bezeichnet.</I></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000188.tif" N="144"></L>
<L>&amp; seynt peter, &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> apostil, : spousid was al so.</L>
<L>&thorn;e &yogh;onge mon answerde : &amp; &thorn;&es; seyde here two:</L>
<L N="1085">Of al &thorn;ing &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> seyst : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> seyst so&thorn; to me,</L>
<L>But of hem &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> han auouid : to hold vergynyte:</L>
<L>&thorn;ilke ne mowe in no wyse : to womon spousid be,</L>
<L>For holywrit it for bit, : sykir, I segge &thorn;e.</L>
<L>For al &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP>, qua&thorn; &thorn;is woman, : &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt &thorn;at I sauid be,</L>
<L N="1090">&thorn;ou most on&es; haue : fleschlich to don w<SUP>t</SUP> me,</L>
<L>For, &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> haue wit me to done, : to morw erlyche</L>
<L>I wole afong cristindom, : I segge trewliche;</L>
<L>For of &thorn;ing &thorn;at is write : in oure lawe so&thorn; is:</L>
<L>For o sinful man : heuen is in more blis,</L>
<L N="1095">Whan he torny&thorn; to good : &amp; lat his sinne be</L>
<L>&amp; vndirfongi&thorn; penaunce : &amp; lyue&thorn; in charyte,</L>
<L>&thorn;an for an hondrid holy men, : &thorn;at nede naue&thorn; non</L>
<L>For non of here synn&es; : penaunce to don.</L>
<L>Moche my&yogh;tou to heuin : of ioy &amp; blys bring,</L>
<L N="1100">&YOGH;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> my&yogh;t torne &thorn;e synful : w<SUP>t</SUP> so lyt a&thorn;ing.</L>
<L>Moche wondir &thorn;is mon : had of &thorn;is wenche,</L>
<L>&amp; here for to helpe : &yogh;erne he gan hym &thorn;enche.</L>
<L>&thorn;e sprit, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> w<SUP>t</SUP> inne hym was, : &yogh;erne hym atende;</L>
<L>&thorn;o he &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;is &thorn;ing do, : so &thorn;is wenche hym blende.</L>
<L N="1105">Glad was &thorn;is mayde, : &thorn;<SUP>o</SUP> &yogh;he &thorn;is sy&yogh;.</L>
<L>To here felauis &yogh;he seyde: : we haue hym wel ny&yogh;;</L>
<L>Go we aboute hym quikliche, : I woot we mowe spede,</L>
<L>ffor I haue wel ny : I do alle oure nede.</L>
<L>To &thorn;is &yogh;ong mon : &thorn;ey wente alle quikliche.</L>
<L N="1110">&thorn;o he sey&yogh; here fayrnesse, : sore he gan to syche,</L>
<L>ffor he nyste on lyue : how here to helpe &thorn;o;</L>
<L>Lo&thorn; hym were his maydinhood : scholde be vndo.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vor</I> lo&thorn; <I>fehlt wol</I> &amp;.</NOTE></L>
<L>In to an herne preuiliche : he went hym &thorn;er fore,</L>
<L>&amp; bad help of ih&umacr; crist, : &amp; gan to wepe sore.</L>
<L N="1115">So he wrong his hond&es; : &amp; his &thorn;ou&yogh;t to heuin cast,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> amydde his sorwe : he fil on slepe fast.</L>
<L>Amon, hym &thorn;ou&yogh;te as he slep, : &thorn;enne hym gan lede</L>
<L>Wit flour&es; &amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> gras : to a wel fayr mede;
<PB REF="00000189.tif" N="145"></L>
<L>Tres &thorn;er were many : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> nobil frut bere;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> maiy <I>st.</I> many.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1120">Noman may telle &thorn;e ioy : &thorn;at he fond &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e sote was &thorn;e smel, : &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> eyr was ful gode,</L>
<L>Rychere frut &thorn;an he say : ne my&yogh;te be, he ondur stode.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne <I>im Ms. doppelt; hinter dem ersten</I> ne <I>ist ein</I> b <I>wegpunktirt.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Segis &thorn;er were set, : &thorn;at were swy&thorn;e ryche,</L>
<L>Hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t in al &thorn;e world : nas non hem lyche;</L>
<L N="1125">Welle strem&es; &thorn;er among, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ronne wel stille;</L>
<L>Bedd&es;, &thorn;at were ryche, : to restin on at wille.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e he lad hym for&thorn; : as in to a toun;</L>
<L>Of swy&thorn;e mery song&es; : &thorn;er he herde &thorn;e soun;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e wall&es; were of gold : &amp; of ryche stone;</L>
<L N="1130">Hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t in al &thorn;e world : soche toun nas &thorn;er none.</L>
<L>To hym he scyde : &thorn;is sted, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> my&yogh;t here se,</L>
<L>&thorn;is is &thorn;e stede &thorn;at &thorn;ey scholle in wone : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> scholle sauid be.</L>
<L>&thorn;o me wold hym &thorn;enne lede, : Josaphat seyde : pur charyte,</L>
<L>Lede me nou&yogh;t henn&es;, : but let me here be!<NOTE PLACE="foot">let <I>aus</I> het <I>corrigirt.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="1135">Do wey, qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> ne hast nou&yogh;t so wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> mowe dwelle her, : &thorn;erfore &thorn;ou spekist for nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> mowe &thorn;y selue chast, : I segge &thorn;e at &thorn;e frome,</L>
<L>ffro sinne &amp; fro veleny&yogh;e, : hedir &thorn;ou schalt come;</L>
<L>Moche is &thorn;e penaunce : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> most &thorn;ole er,</L>
<L N="1140">&amp; so do&thorn; alle o&thorn;er : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> wilue&thorn; to wone her.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e he nom iosaphat : &amp; for&thorn; hym ladde</L>
<L>To aswy&thorn;e derk stede, : &thorn;er of he hym dradde;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e sorw&yogh; &amp; &thorn;e wo : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> man of telle may,</L>
<L>In &thorn;at grisliche stede : hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at he say.</L>
<L N="1145">&thorn;an seyde &thorn;e man, : &thorn;at was w<SUP>t</SUP> hym &thorn;o:</L>
<L>Sestou &thorn;is stede : &thorn;at is so ful of wo?</L>
<L>I &thorn;e sey&yogh;e for so&thorn;e, : her inne &thorn;ey schulle be pult<MILESTONE N="301" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at han vppon er&thorn;e : wit sinne god agylt;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> my&yogh;t chese : here after, leue bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="1150">Whey&thorn;er &thorn;e is leuer &thorn;is stede, : or ellis &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> o&thorn;er;</L>
<L>ffor, &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> lyuist in sinne, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt winne &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&amp;, &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> lyuist in clene lyf, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> o&thorn;er &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> getist I wis.</L>
<L>After &thorn;is ilke word : iosephat gan a wake.
<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="146"></L>
<L>&thorn;e fool semblaunt of &thorn;e women : clene he gan for sake.</L>
<L N="1155">&thorn;ese wome cam aboute hym : &amp; gonne hym clippe faste;<NOTE PLACE="foot">cam <I>&uuml;bergeschrieben</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here hond&es; he sore handlid : &amp; gan hem fro hym caste.</L>
<L>He be took hym to ih&umacr; crist, : &amp; blessid hym wel swy&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> women &thorn;is sy&yogh;, : iwis &thorn;ey were vnbly&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&thorn;e wikkede gost&es;, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> to hym were I sent</L>
<L N="1160">&thorn;orw&yogh; teodas nygremauncy, : to don hym turment,</L>
<L>&thorn;o iosaphat hym hadde blessid, : &thorn;ey held hem schent echon.</L>
<L>&amp; to teodas, here mayster, : a &yogh;en &thorn;ey be&thorn; a gon.</L>
<L>Teodas hem askid, : what &thorn;ey hadde don.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ey hym answerid : &amp; seyde &thorn;us anon:</L>
<L N="1165">Er he hym gan blesse, : we hadde ny &thorn;e maystry&yogh;e;</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> cros he vs ouer com, : wher to scholde I ly&yogh;e?</L>
<L>We segge&thorn; &thorn;e for so&thorn;e, : we ne mowe &thorn;e nou&yogh;t do;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e <I>in der 2. Hlbz. wol st</I>. hym.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffonde &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP>, &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> my&yogh;t, : whan &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt to hym go.</L>
<L>To Josaphat wente &thorn;o : &thorn;e king &amp; teodas.</L>
<L N="1170">Josaphat preched so, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> teodas cristned was,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vor</I> so <I>ist</I> &thorn;o <I>wegpunktirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; good lyf gan lede : &amp; his folyis for sook.</L>
<L>&thorn;&es; he was take w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e fysch, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he &thorn;ou&yogh;t take w<SUP>t</SUP> crok.</L>
<L>&thorn;orw&yogh; conseyl of his frend&es; : &thorn;e king gan do wel,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;af Josaphat his sone : &thorn;e kingdom haluendel.</L>
<L N="1175">Sumdel a &yogh;en his wille : &thorn;e lond&es; he took:</L>
<L>&thorn;o he hem fong bodyliche, : wit soule it for sook;<NOTE PLACE="foot">he <I>fehlt vor</I> it.</NOTE></L>
<L>He took hem, for he wolde : echin godd&es; lawe,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e false god&es; : out of his lond drawe.</L>
<L>ffayre emagis of &thorn;e cros : in ech toun he leet verche,</L>
<L N="1180">&amp; ordeynyd bysschop&es; &amp; prest&es;, : to singe in holy cherche.</L>
<L>&thorn;e meste party of &thorn;e lond : to crist he ha&thorn; brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&amp; euere he fondid day &amp; ny&yogh;t : to torne his fadir &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>So at &thorn;e ende, : as god &yogh;af &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> cas,</L>
<L>&thorn;e king tornyd to god : &amp; cristenyd was.</L>
<L N="1185">Now ha&thorn; iosaphat : moche to his wille;</L>
<L>&thorn;er of he &thorn;onkid god : bo&thorn;e loud &amp; stille.</L>
<L>&thorn;e king &yogh;ald vp &thorn;o : al &thorn;e kingdom</L>
<L>In to his son&es; hond, : &amp; he it nom.
<PB REF="00000191.tif" N="147"></L>
<L>&thorn;is olde king sone after : drou&yogh; to his ende,</L>
<L N="1190">&amp; &thorn;orw&yogh; godd&es; grace : his soule to heuin wende.</L>
<L>Josaphat &thorn;orw&yogh; godd&es; my&yogh;t : &thorn;e folk to heuin gan wyse,</L>
<L>&amp; bad hem do here wel : to godd&es; seruise.</L>
<L>To barachy&yogh;e, an o&thorn;er king, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> good mon was &amp; fre,</L>
<L>(&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP>) &thorn;orw&yogh; destene of erytage : his eyr scholde be,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Im Anfange fehlt &amp; oder</I> &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1195">Hym he sente to segge : preuilich in consayle,</L>
<L>How he wold to wildirnesse : wende w<SUP>t</SUP> oute fayle,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he was in wille : al &thorn;is world for sake;</L>
<L>&amp; bad hym to &thorn;e kingdom : good kep take,</L>
<L>&amp; tech wel cristin dom, : as he hadde er do.</L>
<L N="1200">But of &thorn;is be stille he bad, : fort he were ago.</L>
<L>Ofte he &thorn;ou&yogh;t ascape, : but long it was for nou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vor</I> it <I>ist</I> he <I>weg|punktirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For euer of his oune men : a&yogh;en he was I cau&yogh;t.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e last he scapid, : &amp; went for&thorn; his way,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> in to &thorn;e wildirnes : of samar ry&yogh;t lay.</L>
<L N="1205">As he wente in his way, : apore man he mette,</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> fayr speche : anon he hym grette,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd: leue bro&thorn;er, : for loue now&yogh; I bidde &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vor</I> for <I>ist</I> anon <I>wegpunktirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> &thorn;y clo&thorn;&es; to day : chaunge wit me;</L>
<L>&thorn;o<SUP>u</SUP> myne be &thorn;e beter, : I hem &thorn;e wille &yogh;eue;</L>
<L N="1210">&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> my&yogh;t hem dere selle, : &amp; longe &thorn;e beter lyue.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pore mon took &thorn;e king : his clo&thorn;&es; anon I wis,</L>
<L>&amp; wente for&thorn; in his way : myldeliche sy&thorn;.</L>
<L>&thorn;e fend brou&yogh;te Josaphat : anon in gret doute,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e desert of samar : &thorn;<SUP>o</SUP> he went aboute:</L>
<L N="1215">Ofte in fourme of man : grislich he hym mette,</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> swerd I drawe : of his wey hym lette,</L>
<L>&amp; swor grete o&thorn;&es; : &thorn;at he hym wolde sle,</L>
<L>But he to his kingdom : tornyd hom a &yogh;e.</L>
<L>In fourme of a wilde best : he hym turnyd al so,</L>
<L N="1220">Al redy w<SUP>t</SUP> his my&yogh;t : to don hym alle wo.</L>
<L>He hym blessid al wey, : whan hym by fel so,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er wit cuere more : he ouer com his fo.</L>
<L>Ofte Josaphat seyd: : whyl &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> god helpi&thorn; me,
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="148"></L>
<L>I ne drede nomon ne best, : what euer he be.</L>
<L N="1225">Twey &yogh;er in desert : Josaphat wente so,</L>
<L>Er he fond barlam, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he was wery of go.</L>
<L>&thorn;o he com to &thorn;e caue : &thorn;at he in was,</L>
<L>Josaphat seyde for ioy&yogh;e: : deo gracyas.</L>
<L>Wit oute &thorn;e dore he stood, : &amp; loude gan to cri&yogh;e:</L>
<L N="1230">Blesse me, fadir, blesse me, : for &thorn;y cortesy&yogh;e!</L>
<L>&thorn;o barlam herde &thorn;is, : out he gan gon,</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> moche blisse : kissid hym anon.</L>
<L>&YOGH;osaphat told barlam : how&yogh; he hadde fare,</L>
<L>&amp; hou he hadde at hom : lyuid in sorw&yogh; &amp; care.</L>
<L N="1235">&thorn;ere he lyuid w<SUP>t</SUP> barlam : &yogh;er&es; many &amp; fale,</L>
<L>In fasting &amp; in orysonys, : In hete &amp; in cale.</L>
<L>Barlam deyde se&thorn;&thorn;e, : I woot wel I wis,</L>
<L>&thorn;re hondrid &yogh;er &amp; ey&yogh;ty, : after god was bore for vs.</L>
<L>&amp; fyue &amp; twenty &yogh;er Josaphat : was in his king dom,</L>
<L N="1240">&amp; fyue &amp; &thorn;ritty &yogh;er In desert, : after he &thorn;er to com.</L>
<L>After, &thorn;o he deyde, : his holy body me nom</L>
<L>&amp; beryid it be his mayster, : &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> gode barlam.</L>
<L>&thorn;o barachy&yogh;e, &thorn;e gode king, : her of herde telle,</L>
<L>Wit his company&yogh;e &thorn;edir : he wente wel snelle;</L>
<L N="1245">Bo&thorn;e bodyis he nom vp, : w<SUP>t</SUP> ioy &amp; wit blis,</L>
<L>&amp; brou&yogh;t hem to toune, : as ry&yogh;t was I wis.</L>
<L>He beryed hem rychely : in &thorn;orw mad of ston.<MILESTONE N="302" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;er god ha&thorn; for here loue : many merakle don.</L>
<L>Now&yogh; bidde we god of heuin, : &thorn;at euer was &amp; is,</L>
