<HEAD>IV. Das Fegfeuer des h. Patrick.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Der Text des Gedichtes ist dem Ms. Ashmol. 43, aus dem Anfang des 14. Jahrh., entnommen, welches nach Ms. Harl. 2277 wol die &auml;lteste der vorhandenen Legendensammlungen ist und der urspr&uuml;nglichen Fassung der Legenden, oft mehr als selbst Ms. Harl., welches ebenfalls nur eine Abschrift ist, nahesteht und an innerer G&uuml;te die andern Mss. &uuml;bertrifft. Im Ms. Harl. ist das Gedicht mit den ersten Bl&auml;ttern ausgefallen. &mdash; Von diesem Ms. weichen die Mss. Laud 108 und Egerton 1993, beide aus dem ersten Viertel des 14. Jahrh., mehr oder minder mit Bewusstsein ab; Ms. Laud unterscheidet sich durch gr&ouml;ssere Breite und Freiheit (im Gebrauch von Partikeln und F&uuml;llw&ouml;rtern, Gebrauch des pronomen pers. neben dem Subst., Hinzuf&uuml;gung, Vertauschung, Versetzung von W&ouml;rtern), so dass das urspr&uuml;ngliche Versmass h&auml;ufig gesprengt erscheint; Ms. Egerton hingegen durch gr&ouml;ssere K&uuml;rze, Sparsamkeit im Gebrauche der Partikeln und Vereinfachung des Ausdrucks. &mdash; Dem Ms. Ashmol. am n&auml;chsten steht Ms. Cotton. Jul. D. IX, welches, trotz vieler Besonderheiten der Orthographie, im Ganzen und Einzelnen mit diesem Ms. &uuml;bereinstimmt und eine (freie) Abschrift desselben ist. Die Varianten dieses Ms. sind unter dem Texte angegeben; Ms. Egerton und Ms. Laud sind ganz abgedruckt. Ausserdem ist noch Ms. Bodl. 779, aus dem dritten Viertel des 15. Jahrh., benutzt, welches bereits dem Mittelenglischen angeh&ouml;rt.</P><P>Die Varianten des Ms. Cotton. Jul. D. IX erstrecken sich nur vereinzelt auf die Orthographie, die sehr verwildert ist. Zu den Besonderheiten der Orthographie geh&ouml;rt vor allem die Vertauschung von d, &thorn; <I>und</I> t, <I>indem statt</I> d <I>meistens</I> &thorn; <I>gebraucht ist (z. B. endet das Impf. sehr h&auml;ufig auf</I> e&thorn;e, e&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> e&thorn;; <I>andere Beispiele sind:</I> be&thorn; <I>V. 5</I> ba&thorn; <I>24 st.</I> bad, &thorn;o <I>st.</I> do, bi&thorn;&thorn;e, ne&thorn;&thorn;ren, wil&thorn;, an&thorn;, sto&thorn; <I>u. s. w.)</I>, d <I>st.</I> &thorn; <I>(z. B.</I> dole&thorn; 5, de, din, de&thorn; = &thorn;at 5, de&thorn;er = &thorn;eder, erde, moud <I>u. a.), zuweilen</I> t <I>st.</I> &thorn; <I>(z. B.</I> hi wollet 168, schollet, dawet, bet), <I>selten</I> t <I>st.</I> d <I>(z. B.</I> deliueret 5, aschamet 23, ynailet) <I>und</I> t <I>st.</I> &thorn; <I>(z. B.</I> wit <I>meist statt</I> wi&thorn;, sy&yogh;t 80). v <I>wird seltener als in Ms. Ashmol. statt</I> f, <I>h&auml;ufiger statt</I> w <I>gebraucht (z. B.</I> touard, droue, knoue, sorue); f <I>statt</I> v <I>findet sich in</I> fois 35, faleie 236. k <I>wird auslautend gew&ouml;hnlich</I> c, <I>(z. B.</I> donc 200, loc, blac, worc, dorc), <I>verdoppelt</I> kk, <I>nicht</I> ck <I>geschrieben. Ein unorganisches</I> h <I>im Anlaut vor Vokalen ist zugef&uuml;gt in</I> hi here&thorn; 56, hende 146, herde 252, hauter 608, hour 619, <I>aber</I> aswe <I>statt</I> haswe 299. <I>Statt</I> i, u = <I>ags.</I> y <I>findet sich meist</I> e <I>gebraucht, (z. B.</I> fer <I>st.</I> fur, pet <I>st.</I> put, hel, abegge, bregge, sennen), <I>aber nur</I> lite. <I>Statt</I> sc <I>in Ashm. ist gew&ouml;hnlich</I> sch <I>geschrieben, statt</I> w <I>f&uuml;r</I> wh <I>immer</I> wh. <I>Statt</I> world <I>findet sich nur</I> worl. <I>Der Plur. endet gew&ouml;hnlich auf</I> es (<I>zuweilen</I> en); <I>auf</I> is <I>in:</I> baneris 521, monkis 523, <I>auf</I> in <I>zuweilen bei</I> deuelin. <I>Der Comparativ und Superlativ enden gew&ouml;hnlich auf</I> ore <I>und</I> ost: <I>z. B.</I> caldore, fer|rore, deppore, braddore, smallore, innore, hardiore, grettore, no|blore; lengost, fairost. <I>F&uuml;r</I> &yogh;ou <I>findet sich zuweilen</I> &yogh;o, <I>f&uuml;r</I> hi hij, <I>f&uuml;r</I> it <I>gew&ouml;hnlich</I> hit, <I>f&uuml;r</I> is his, <I>f&uuml;r</I> hor &yogh;hare.</P></HEADNOTE>


<DIV2 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000195.tif">
<HEAD>a) aus Ms. Ashmol. 43.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEyn patric com &thorn;oru godes grace : to preci in irlonde,<MILESTONE N="34" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot1">preci <I>st.</I> prechi.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">Seint. &thorn;orou. prechi. yrlond.</NOTE></L>
<L>To teche men hor ri&yogh;te bi leue : on Ih&umacr; to vnderstonde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&yogh;hare ri&yogh;t. of ih&umacr; crist. on&thorn;er|stonde.</NOTE></L>
<L>So uol of wormes &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> lond he fond, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> nomon my&yogh;te gon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fol. ne my&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>In some stude uor wormes, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he nas Iuenymed anon.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">stede. for. y uenemid.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">S. patric bed our lord crist : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e lond deliuered were<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sein patrich. oure. de&thorn; lond.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;ulke foule wormes, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> non ne come &thorn;ere.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">none.</NOTE></L>
<L>Our lord hurde is bone anon, : &thorn;er ne my&yogh;te neuereft come<NOTE PLACE="foot2">herde his.</NOTE></L>
<L>No foul worm in Irlond, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> is lif him nas bi nome.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">him <I>fehlt.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Ech tre &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> in &thorn;e lond growe&thorn;, : &amp; er&thorn;e of &thorn;e lond also,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> lond.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10">Ne &thorn;ole&thorn; no uenym in no stude : nei him be ido;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ben.</NOTE></L>
<L>No foul worm come&thorn; &thorn;erto : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> nys anon lifles,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;er ney. lif les.</NOTE></L>
<L>bbote alute schort euete, : &amp; &yogh;ut heo is tailes.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> tailes <I>st.</I> tailles.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">lite. &yogh;et he. tail les.</NOTE></L>
<L>Muche clannes &amp; muche good, : hoso de&thorn; him vnderstonde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Moche clannesse. god.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vor &thorn;e loue of s. patric : our lord dude to al Irlonde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">dede. to alle yrlond.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">A good mannes scep was istole, : to s. patric com tydynge;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">a god man schep. tidyng.</NOTE></L>
<L>He het, hoso hit hadde Inome, : a&yogh;en it scholde bringe.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hit <I>fehlt.</I> bring.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is gode mon het at chirche so ofte, : ac a&yogh;en ne com it no&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">so at cherche ofte. h<SUP>t</SUP> nou&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>In an heie day, as al &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> folc : to chirche was ibro&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">a hei dai.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="152"></L>
<L>S. patric het, &yogh;if in &thorn;e chirche : eny mossel were<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&yogh;et in &thorn;e cherche &yogh;if. morsel.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">Of &thorn;e scep, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> it scholde blete : among hem alle &thorn;ere.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hit stele (!) blete. &yogh;am <I>st.</I> hem.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o gon it blete in is wombe : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hadde &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> scep istole,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">gan.</NOTE></L>
<L>Among alle &thorn;is men, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> it ne my&yogh;te : noleng be ihole.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">longer. hole.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sore was &thorn;e &thorn;eof aschamed : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> men uor &thorn;eof him knewe;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> def. for men &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;ef.</NOTE></L>
<L>He was iknowe, &amp; mercy bad, : &amp; bicom good &amp; triwe.</L>
<L N="25">Nou hadde s. patric awone, : ofte &amp; ilome<NOTE PLACE="foot2">now. lome.</NOTE></L>
<L>To aloute to euerich crois, : war he euer come.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">eny cros. whare.</NOTE></L>
<L>A day, as he wende aboute : prechynge in &thorn;e londe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wente. preching.</NOTE></L>
<L>S. patric loutede to euerich crois : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he sei owar stonde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">patrik. loute. eueri. ower.</NOTE></L>
<L>A crois &thorn;er stod, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> men iseie, : ac he ne sei it no&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">cros. seie&thorn; no&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L N="30">&thorn;er uore ne aloutede he no&yogh;t &thorn;er to. : men wondred in hor &thorn;o&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">loute&thorn;. wondre&thorn;<SUP>e.</SUP> &yogh;hare do&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; ecste wi he nolde aloute : to &thorn;e crois bi him &thorn;ere.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">eske&thorn;e whi.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is gode mon bi huld aboute : &amp; escte wer it were :<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;is holiman. bihel&thorn;e. exse&thorn;e whare.</NOTE></L>
<L>He ne my&yogh;te &thorn;e croys no&yogh;t ise; : in gret &thorn;o&yogh;t he stod.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ne <I>fehlt.</I> cros. &thorn;o&yogh;te.</NOTE></L>
<L>Gret wonder hadde &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> folc &thorn;o, : &amp; wende he were wod.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wen&thorn;e &thorn;<SUP>t.</SUP></NOTE></L>
<L N="35">&thorn;o sede auois vnderer&thorn;e: : ne mys &thorn;enche &yogh;e no&yogh;t!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e erde.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e holi mon ne se &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> crois, : no&yogh;t ne wondre &yogh;e in &yogh;oure &thorn;o&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;ei &thorn;e holiman sei nou&yogh;t &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> cros ne wondre &yogh;o ri&yogh;t no&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vor it is uor myne sunnen : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> myne bones ligge&thorn; here,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fore min senne. myn.</NOTE></L>
<L>As i<SUP>c</SUP> was ibured, &amp; wi&thorn; &yogh;ou speke : &thorn;is holi mon to skere;<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>vor</I> speke <I>fehlt</I> i<SUP>c</SUP> <I>auch in Cott. u. Bodl.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">ich. wit &yogh;o.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saraceyn i<SUP>c</SUP> was wule aner&thorn;e, : in helle my soule, is;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">a sarsin. wule <I>fehlt.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="40">Vor myne bones be&thorn; so ney &thorn;e crois, : he ne suc&thorn; it no&yogh;t iwis.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">min. cros. seiet no&yogh;t y wis.</NOTE></L>
<L>As preching &thorn;is holi mon : &thorn;e contrei out sou&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>fehlt</I> : <I>im Ms., wie V. 55. 84. 232. 237 u. &ouml;.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">contre.</NOTE></L>
<L>A wilde stude he fond &amp; bar, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> no frut uor&thorn; ne bro&yogh;te;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">a wil&thorn;e stede he vond wil&thorn; &amp; bar. fruit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ei me sewe &amp; sette &thorn;er alle &thorn;ing, : &thorn;er com no&thorn;ing uor&thorn; &thorn;ere.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;ere al &thorn;yng. &thorn;er ne com nout for&thorn; no&thorn;ing dere.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">tokning whi.</NOTE></L>
<L>S. patric bed our lord &yogh;erne : toknynge, wi it were.
<PB REF="00000197.tif" N="153"></L>
<L N="45">In &thorn;e er&thorn;e he made wi&thorn; is staf : a sercle al aboute:<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> serche.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">cercle.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er bicom aput swi&thorn;e dep, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> men hadde of gret doute.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">pet. sui&thorn;e. dowte.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is gode mon nuste wat it was, : ac an angel him sede:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">what.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er was aput of purgatorie, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ech mon mi&yogh;te of drede;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">pette. man.</NOTE></L>
<L>Somme soules were &thorn;er Inne ido, : hor sunnes uorte bete<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;er som soules were inne ido hore sennes for to bete.</NOTE></L>
<L N="50">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hi ne betten no&yogh;t aner&thorn;e, : ar hi &thorn;is lif lete;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bette nou&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp;, were aman quic o&thorn;er ded : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er Inne come,</L>
<L>He ne scholde habbe o&thorn;er purgatorie : uorte &thorn;e day of dome,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nou&yogh;t <I>st.</I> uorte.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac aftur he scholde to heuene, : &yogh;if he were good, iwende,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">heuen. god wende.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; also, &yogh;if he lu&thorn;er were, : to helle wi&thorn;&thorn;outen ende.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; as god as he lu&thorn;er were (!). w<SUP>t</SUP> oute.</NOTE></L>
<L N="55">Our lord tok s. patric : &thorn;en staf is owe honde,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Im Ms. fehlt : nach der Hlbz. Auch Ms. Cott</I>. his owe honde, <I>ohne</I> wi&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he fond wi&thorn; &thorn;ulke purgatorie, : ihered be is sonde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;ilke. hi here&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>In Irlond is &yogh;ut &thorn;ulke staf : wi&thorn; nobleie iwust Inou&yogh;,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;ilk. wist y now.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; for relik iholde, : &amp; elles it were wou&yogh;.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">riche relik. wo.</NOTE></L>
<L>S. patric in &thorn;ulke stude, : as &thorn;is purgatorie is,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Am Rande:</I> patric purgatory.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">Of religion bigan an hous, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &yogh;ut stont iwis,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">stond y wis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; chanouns &thorn;er Inne made, : as &yogh;ut be&thorn; also.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> chanons.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;en put he let wel uaste close, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> nomon necome him to.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">com <I>st.</I> come.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e chirche&yogh;ard is &thorn;ulke put, : ri&yogh;t toward &thorn;e est side,</L>
<L>Euene est fram &thorn;e heie weued, : as men seche&thorn; wide.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">euen est fram fro (!). schete&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L N="65">l walled he is uaste aboute, : &amp; uaste iloke &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &yogh;at;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fast. &yogh;ate.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; uaste &thorn;e prior wite&thorn; &thorn;e keie, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> nomon come&thorn; In &thorn;er at.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ne com.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al bi s. patrikes daie : men wende &thorn;er In I lome,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">patrichis dai. wente &thorn;er inne lome.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e also monyon, : ac vewe up &thorn;er come.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">su&thorn;&thorn;e. op.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac &thorn;ulke &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er com a&yogh;en, : of &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hi seie, tolde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">come. of &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> y seie.</NOTE></L>
<L N="70">As it is in &thorn;e hous iwrite : &amp; priueliche iholde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">priuiliche.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e maner is of ech man : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er Inne wend,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">euer ich. wen&thorn;e.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000198.tif" N="154"></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> it be to bete is sunne, : &yogh;if our lord him grace send.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sinne. sende.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e biscop of &thorn;e lond : he schal him uerst scriue,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bischop. schriue.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; bidde leue to do &thorn;e wei, : to amendement of is lyue.</L>
<L N="75">Ac &thorn;e biscop him rat &thorn;er a&yogh;en, : &amp; resons him wole scewe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">rad. wol&thorn;<SUP>e.</SUP></NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; segge &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> mony &thorn;uder wende&thorn;, : &amp; come&thorn; a&yogh;en uewe.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">de&thorn;er wente.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac, &yogh;if he is stable in is &thorn;o&yogh;t, : uor al &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he ha&thorn; ibede,<MILESTONE N="35" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot2">bi <I>st.</I> is. for alle alle (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e biscop wole him littres make : to &thorn;e maister of &thorn;e stede.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">him wil lettres.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e prior him wole ek rede Inou&yogh; : uorte chaunge is &thorn;o&yogh;t;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wil. ek <I>fehlt</I>. chonge.</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">Ac, wenne he suc&thorn; him studeuast, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he nele it bileue no&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">ff. <I>Im Ms. Laud folgt nach V. 80 zuerst 83 u. 84, dann 82, 81; letztere Reihenfolge ist gewiss die richtige, wie auch aus der folgenden Erz&auml;hlung (vgl. V. 117. 119. 120. 126) hervorgeht; doch haben die and. Mss. dieselbe Reihenfolge, wie Ms. Ashm</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">whan, sy&yogh;t. bileue hit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret procession of prestes : to &thorn;e put he wor&thorn; ibro&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">pette. wer&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac &yogh;if me ne may &thorn;e &yogh;ut : uor no&thorn;ing chaunge is &thorn;o&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">change.</NOTE></L>
<L>In to chirche hi wolle&thorn; him lede : &amp; sette him adoun akne;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ere he schal viftene dawes : in Orisons be.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Im Ms. fehlt : nach der Hlbz</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">daues.</NOTE></L>
<L N="85">&thorn;e procession schal turne a&yogh;en, : as ri&yogh;t is to done,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">torne.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; amorwe &thorn;ulke tyme : &thorn;uder come efsone;</L>
<L>&amp;, bote he be &thorn;anne icome, : wi&thorn; gret deol &amp; sore<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;an.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hi turne&thorn; a&yogh;en, &amp; siker be&thorn; : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he ne come&thorn; nammore.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">com&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hit biuel bi kyng steuenes dai, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> nou late was,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Am Rande ist</I> nota <I>klein nebengeschrieben</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">bi steuene kynges day.</NOTE></L>
<L N="90">Of aknyit, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> het Owen, : a wel wonder cas.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">oweyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e biscop to scrifte : owen, &thorn;is knyt, com,</L>
<L>&amp; gret repentaunce uor is sunnen : &amp; deol &amp; sorwe nom.<NOTE PLACE="foot2"><I>fehlen</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e biscop bi gan to chide him uaste : of &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he hadde mysdo,</L>
<L>&amp; sede, he was mon worst, : uorte sunegi so,<NOTE PLACE="foot2"><I>fehlen</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="95">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> me ne my&yogh;te do him so muche wo, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he nere wor&thorn;i more.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">him do. ne wor&thorn;e nere.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e kny&yogh;t sat wi&thorn; deo(l)uol herte, : &amp; si&yogh;te &amp; weop sore.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> deouol <I>st.</I> deoluol.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2"><I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wenne, he sede, icham mon worst, : &amp; manne worst habbe ido,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">whanne. he sede <I>fehlt</I>. &amp; man.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="155"></L>
<L>&amp; to sunne &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> grettest is : mest penaunce mot be to,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>In Mss. Eg. u. Laud fehlt &amp; im Anfang</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">mot to, be <I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wenne i<SUP>c</SUP> among alle men : mest sunuol am, alas,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">whan. most.</NOTE></L>
<L N="100">&thorn;e strengost penaunce icholle take : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> euer ifounde was:</L>
<L>Ichulle take godes grace : &amp; in is name wende<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Icholle.</NOTE></L>
<L>In s. patric purgatorie, : sende wat he me sende.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">patrikes.</NOTE></L>
<L>O, beu frere, qua&thorn; &thorn;is biscop, : be stille! wi saistou so?<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ou. whi seistu.</NOTE></L>
<L>Crist uorbede &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> neuer : such folie ne do!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fore for be&thorn;e (!).</NOTE></L>
<L N="105">Vnne&thorn;e eny come&thorn; a&yogh;en : of &thorn;ulke &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;uder do&thorn; wende;</L>
<L>Nolde god &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> &thorn;e dede dust, : bodi &amp; soule to scende!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">to (!) de&thorn;e dest.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac wend in to religion, : &amp; bilef &thorn;er &thorn;in lyues ende:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;er <I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt wel &thorn;in sunne bete, : &amp; god wole &thorn;e grace sende.</L>
<L>Certes, sire, qua&thorn; &thorn;is kny&yogh;t, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> my&yogh;t as wel be stille,</L>
<L N="110">Vor ichulle &thorn;e dede do, : do god bi me is wille;</L>
<L>Vor so muche as i<SUP>c</SUP> habbe of serued, : Ine mi&yogh;te no&yogh;t habbe of wo;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ichabbe y serue&thorn;. my&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er uore say wat i<SUP>c</SUP> schal do, : uor ichulle siker it go.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sei. sal. siker icholle.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e biscop prechede him uaste Inou&yogh;: &amp; sede him resons Inowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Im Ms. fehlen hier durch Versehen des Schreibers 4 Verse nach der 1. Hlbz., die in den &uuml;brigen Mss. stehen, s. u.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2"><P>Cott. <I>hat hier, wie die and. Mss., 4 Verse mehr:</I></P><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e bischop preche&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> him fast ynow . for to change his dou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Ac at laste &thorn;o he i sey . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hit was al for nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>To &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> prior of &thorn;e stede . his lettres he made sone</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he schol&thorn;e bi him do . as bi such man was to done</L>
<L>&thorn;e prior preche&thorn;e him faste y now . &amp; se&thorn;<SUP>c</SUP> him resons y nowe . . .</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L N="115">&YOGH;if he mi&yogh;te chaunge is &thorn;o&yogh;t, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he him wi&thorn; drowe.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">alle for nou&yogh;t. at ende.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac is preching was al uorno&yogh;t, : as he sei wel aten ende:</L>
<L>He nolde bileue uor no&thorn;ing : &thorn;en perilous wei to wende.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">be <I>st.</I> bi.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e prior him nom bi &thorn;e hond : &amp; in to chirche him bro&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&thorn;ere he uel adoun akne : &amp; our lordes grace biso&yogh;te;</L>
<L>In uastynge &amp; in orisouns : uortene ny&yogh;t he lay,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fasting.</NOTE></L>
<L N="120">To bidde our swete lordes grace; : &amp; (&thorn;e) vifte&thorn;e day<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Im Ms. fehlt</I> &thorn;e <I>vor</I> vifte&thorn;e.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">oure suete. &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> vifte&thorn;<SUP>e.</SUP></NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e couent com aboute him, : &amp; o&thorn;er prestes also
<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="156"></L>
<L>&amp; clerkes wi&thorn; &thorn;e procession, : &thorn;e seruice to do.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&thorn;e <I>vor</I> procession <I>fehlt in den and. Mss. u. ist zu tilgen</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">w<SUP>t</SUP> procession.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vor him (hi) songe an heie masse : &amp; on god cride uaste,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Nach</I> him <I>fehlt</I> hi <I>im Ms</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">him hi song. hei.</NOTE></L>
<L>Our lordes flecs &amp; is blod : hi toke him ate laste,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">flesch. atte.</NOTE></L>
<L N="125">&amp; sprende him wi&thorn; holi watur, : &amp; hor orisons sede.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; sperng (!) him wyt. &yogh;hare.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; crois &amp; procession : to &thorn;e put hi gonne him lede,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">putte. him gonne, hi <I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; heieliche songe &thorn;e letanye, : &amp; holi water wi&thorn; hem bere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">heilich song. wi&thorn; hem <I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; godes halwe alle bede : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hi is help were.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">alle godes halwe.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e prior vnlek &thorn;e puttes dore, : &amp; among hem echon:<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>&amp; vor</I> among, <I>nur noch in Ms. Cott., fehlt in d. and. Mss</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">vnlok. hom <I>st.</I> hem.</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">Beu frere, he sede, her is &thorn;e wei : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> (&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP>) seist &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt gon;<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Im Ms. fehlt</I>. &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> <I>nach</I> &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> seist &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u.</SUP></NOTE></L>
<L>Ac &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt do bi oure rede, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt &thorn;i &thorn;o&yogh;t wende<NOTE PLACE="foot2">be.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; in o&thorn;er manere &thorn;i sunne bete, : as god wole &thorn;e grace sende;</L>
<L>Vor uewe &thorn;er come&thorn; a&yogh;en of hem : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> her Inne wende biuore,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hom. here.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac were uor torment &amp; uor wo : bodi &amp; soule uorlore.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">tormens. lif &amp; soule were lore (were doppelt).</NOTE></L>
<L N="135">Certes, sire, qua&thorn; &thorn;is kny&yogh;t, : rede wat &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> me rede,</L>
<L>I<SUP>c</SUP> nyme &thorn;en wei agodes name : to bete myne mysdede;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;en wei ich nime.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac, uor his loue &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ous dere abou&yogh;te, : bidde&thorn; uor me echon!</L>
<L>Lyf &amp; soule i<SUP>c</SUP> him bi take, : &amp; in is name In gon.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">in gon <I>lesen auch die and. Mss., nur Laud hat</I> ichulle in gon.</NOTE></L>
<L>He blessede him, &amp; wende him In, : &amp; bi tok god flesch &amp; bon.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">blesse&thorn;. wente.</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">&thorn;e prior him sprende wi&thorn; holi watur, : &amp; lek &thorn;e dore anon.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">spreng&thorn;e. loc.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is gode kny&yogh;t him wende uor&thorn;, : baldeliche &amp; uaste,</L>
<L>bbi an holwe wei vnder er&thorn;e, : &amp; vp god is herte caste;</L>
<L>He ne sei no&thorn;ing uor derchede, : ac na&thorn;eles no&yogh;t him agaste.<NOTE PLACE="foot2"><I>&amp; st</I>. ac. ne a gaste.</NOTE></L>
<L>So longe, him &thorn;o&yogh;te, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he sei : wel uair li&yogh;t ate laste.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">long. feir. atte.</NOTE></L>
<L N="145">&thorn;uderward he wende baldeliche, : so &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he com &thorn;er ney.</L>
<L>&thorn;e uairest feld &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> mi&yogh;te be : at &thorn;e weies ende he isei.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fairost. atte. hende. sey.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er Inne he wende murie Inou&yogh;; : amydde &thorn;e feld he fond<NOTE PLACE="foot2">merie.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e noblest &amp; uairest halle : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> my&yogh;te be In eny lond.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> noblestc, <I>mit angefangenem aber nicht ausgeschriebenem</I> e.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e nobleste &amp; &thorn;e fairost.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="157"></L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t cler nas &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> weder no&yogh;t, : bote ri&yogh;t as it were nei eue.</L>
<L N="150">To biholde &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> noble work, : an stounde he gan bileue;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e <I>st.</I> &thorn;<SUP>t.</SUP> a <I>st.</I> an.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e walles nere no&yogh;t &thorn;er on Ihol, : ac &thorn;er aboute iwis<NOTE PLACE="foot2">dorou <I>st.</I> &thorn;er on.</NOTE></L>
<L>Queynt pylers &amp; arches were, : as monekes cloister is.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">quinte. monkis cloistre.</NOTE></L>
<L>In he wende agodes name, : &amp; sat him al one an hei,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">al a lone.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; bihuld aboute in ech hurne : &amp; &thorn;is quinte werk isei.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bi hel&thorn;. in euerich angle. worc.</NOTE></L>
<L N="155">As he bihuld al &thorn;us aboute, : &thorn;er com In at on ende<NOTE PLACE="foot2">aten on.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tuelf men in wite uestimens, : swi&thorn;e uair &amp; hende,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">white vestimentes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hor crounen alle newe iscore. : swi&thorn;e uaire hi him grette,<MILESTONE N="36" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot2">&yogh;hare. nwe y schore.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; sete hem alle uaire adoun, : &amp; &thorn;is kny&yogh;t bi hem sette.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sette ham al fair. bi hom.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o spak on, as hor prior, : mildeliche &amp; stille:</L>
<L N="160">bbeu frere, ihered be god, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> sende&thorn; &thorn;e such wille,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bi god.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; lete &thorn;e &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;ou hast bigonne : uor is grace wel ende!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;<SUP>u.</SUP></NOTE></L>
<L>Beu frere, wen &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolst &thorn;es wei : uor &thorn;yne sunnen wende:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">wolst <I>ist Imperf., daf&uuml;r sonst auch</I> wost; <I>vgl</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">whan &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wost &thorn;is. &thorn;in.</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;er &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> most be studeuast : &amp; in none manere turne &thorn;i &thorn;o&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">in no.</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;ur &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> worst lif &amp; soule : a deuelwei i bro&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="165">Vor, as sone as we be&thorn; henne iwend, : &thorn;e deuelen lu&thorn;er &amp; wicke<NOTE PLACE="foot2">i went. deuele.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wolle&thorn; come anon aboute &thorn;e : In &thorn;is hous wel &thorn;icke,</L>
<L>&amp; do &thorn;e tormens &amp; wo Inou&yogh;, : &amp; bihote &thorn;e wel more,</L>
<L>Ac hi wolle&thorn; bi hote &thorn;e Ioie Inou&yogh;, : &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt leue on hor lore;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wollet. y leue.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if hi &thorn;e &thorn;oru eny biheste : mowe &thorn;e ouercome,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&thorn;e <I>doppelt, wie auch in Ms. Cott.; das erste</I> &thorn;e <I>ist zu tilgen</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">ac &yogh;if.</NOTE></L>
<L N="170">Siker &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> worst lif &amp; soule : adeuelwei Inome;</L>
<L>Ac &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art stable of bileue, : &amp; in ih&umacr; crist dest &thorn;enche,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;ost.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne uor heste ne uor wo : fram him nelt blenche,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">uor biheste.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> worst quit of alle &thorn;in sunnen : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast er iwro&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wost. sinne. euer <I>st.</I> er.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt ise alle &thorn;e Ioien : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> godemen be&thorn; Inne ibro&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ioie.</NOTE></L>
<L N="175">&amp; &thorn;e pyne &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> lu&thorn;ermen habbe&thorn; : uor hor mysdede;</L>
<L>Ac, in wat wo &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art, : &thorn;ench on god, i<SUP>c</SUP> rede,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">in what wo so. &thorn;en <I>st.</I> &thorn;ench.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp;, wanne hi &thorn;e turmente&thorn; muche, : cri ih&umacr; mylce &amp; ore,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">whan.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot1">dust <I>st.</I> dudest.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="158"></L>
<L>&amp;, &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art studeuast in &thorn;i bileue, : hi ne scholle&thorn; &thorn;e defouli namore;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">scholle. nammore.</NOTE></L>
<L>We bitake&thorn; &thorn;e ih&umacr; crist; : i<SUP>c</SUP> rede, do our lore.</L>
<L N="180">&thorn;o nuste &thorn;e kny&yogh;t war hi bicome. : he sat &amp; si&yogh;te sore,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">whare.</NOTE></L>
<L>Elyng he bileuede al one, : &amp; cride on godes mi&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">elenge.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; armede him wi&thorn; holi beden, : a&yogh;en &thorn;e deuel to fi&yogh;te;</L>
<L>On &thorn;e holi gost he criede uaste, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he ne scholde him no&yogh;t faile.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">cride.</NOTE></L>
<L>He lokede, wen &thorn;e deuelen come, : him uorto asaile.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">whan.</NOTE></L>
<L N="185">As he sat &thorn;us in godes name, : as bataile uorto abide,</L>
<L>&thorn;er com a sori reuuol cri : aboute in eche side,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">rufol. in euerich.</NOTE></L>
<L>As &thorn;ei al &thorn;e world to borste, : &amp;, as him &thorn;o&yogh;te, also,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">alle &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> worle to borste &amp; breke:</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP>, &thorn;ei al &thorn;e bestes of &thorn;e world : to gadere were ido<NOTE PLACE="foot2">alle. worl.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; as grisliche as hi mi&yogh;te : &yogh;ollynge alle were,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">grislich. &yogh;ollinde.</NOTE></L>
<L N="190">Hi ne mi&yogh;te among hem alle : make so grislich bere;</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP>, &yogh;if is herte on Ih&umacr; crist, : &amp; is hope &thorn;e more nere,</L>
<L>Anon he hadde wod bicome : &amp; ilore is wit uor fere.</L>
<L>&thorn;o come hi alle aboute him : &thorn;icke &amp; grisliche &thorn;ere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hi In, alle <I>fehlt</I>. &thorn;ik.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;onede &amp; grennede ek : wi&thorn; wel sori chere.<NOTE PLACE="foot2"><I>&amp; im Anfang fehlt</I>. &yogh;oniinde &amp; grenning.</NOTE></L>
<L N="195">Belamy, qua&thorn; on of hem, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast ri&yogh;t ido;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;ou. a ri&yogh;t a do (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel au&yogh;te we honouri &thorn;e, : uor alto vewe do&thorn; so,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">we alle honoure. alle to few.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vor alle o&thorn;er men wolle&thorn; abide, : forte hor lif hem be bynome,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fol <I>st.</I> vor. for to. hom.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;ut it is a&yogh;en hor wille, : ar hi wolle&thorn; to ous come;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&yogh;it. wollet.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> comst al by &thorn;yne lyue, : &amp; bi &thorn;yne gode wille also;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">comest. be &thorn;in. bi dyn. asso.</NOTE></L>
<L N="200">Wel au&yogh;te we &thorn;yne mede &yogh;ulde : &amp; gret &thorn;onk &thorn;e do;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;in.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wen &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast bo&thorn;e bodi &amp; soule : bitake ous by &thorn;yne lyue,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bi dyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sauns faile we were vnkunde, : bote we it &yogh;olde &thorn;e blyue;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&thorn;e <I>fehlt in den and. Mss., Cott. hat</I> &yogh;ol &thorn;e <I>st.</I> &yogh;olde.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">saun. vnkende. &yogh;ol &thorn;e (!) bliue.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac na&thorn;eles, &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt aner&thorn;e : habbe &yogh;ut Ioie more,</L>
<L>Vor &thorn;e kunhede, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> to us comst : al by owe lore,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>sind im Ms. Laud umgestellt</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">ken&thorn;e&thorn;e. &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;u to ous come alle be din owe lore.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="159"></L>
<L N="205">Siker ous an hond &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt : on oure seruyce bileue,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">sind im Ms. Laud umgestellt</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; we wolle&thorn; to &thorn;e er&thorn;e &thorn;e lede a&yogh;en, : al sauf, ar it be eue:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">to erde. saf er.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt habbe &thorn;er Ioie Inou&yogh;, : in halle &amp; ek in boure,</L>
<L>Vor none men be&thorn; so murie &thorn;er : as &thorn;ulke &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> be&thorn; of oure;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nommen. dere. &thorn;ilk.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hei mon &amp; noble &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> worst, : &amp; men scholle&thorn; honouri &thorn;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">scholle.</NOTE></L>
<L N="210">&amp; wen &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art ded &amp; to ous comst, : &thorn;e tid as good as we.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">comest.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is kny&yogh;t &thorn;o&yogh;te euer on ih&umacr; crist, : he nolde chaunge enes is wille,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e knyt &thorn;oute. chonge.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vor prechinge ne uor uair bi heste, : ac sat him euer stille.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">for &thorn;reting ne fair.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o he nolde hem granti no&yogh;t : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he wolde to hem wende,</L>
<L>Hi &yogh;onede &amp; grennede on him foule, : &amp; astrong fur gonne tende.</L>
<L N="215">&thorn;is kny&yogh;t hi bounde hond &amp; fot, : &amp; amydde &thorn;e fur him caste;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fet. fer caste, him <I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; irene oweles &amp; wi&thorn; pikes : hi to drowe him wel uaste.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">owles.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is kny&yogh;t, wan he sei is neode, : loude he cride anon:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&yogh; <I>in</I> kny&yogh;t <I>&uuml;bergeschrieben</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;<SUP>o</SUP> <I>st.</I> wan. nede.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ih&umacr;, (Ih&umacr;), help me nou, : &amp; schulde me fram myne fon!<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> Ih&umacr; <I>einmal, so auch Ms. Cott.; die and. Mss. haben</I> Ih&umacr; Ih&umacr; (<I>oder</I> Ih&umacr; crist. <I>Bodl</I>.), <I>wie auch das Versmass fordert; s. V. 574</I> alas.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">schil &thorn;e me fro my fon.</NOTE></L>
<L>Anon so &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> word was ised, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> fur quente ech spronke;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">euerich.</NOTE></L>
<L N="220">&thorn;e deueles ne drowe him namore. : our lord he gan &thorn;onke,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> &thorn;euelin him droue nommore, ne <I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e hardiere was Inou&yogh;, : &thorn;o he &thorn;is isei,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">he <I>st.</I> &thorn;e. hardiore.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e lasse of &thorn;e deuelen dradde, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> were him so nei.</L>
<L>Wel grisliche &thorn;e screwen &yogh;olle, : &thorn;o hem failede hor my&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">grislich. hore.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; flowe echone out of &thorn;is halle, : &amp; drowe wi&thorn; hem &thorn;is kny&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">flow echon. &thorn;row.</NOTE></L>
<L N="225">Hi drowe him wel harde a&yogh;en &thorn;e gronde : bo&thorn;e fet &amp; honde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">droue.</NOTE></L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e ver, him &thorn;o&yogh;te, &amp; longe, : al in awaste londe.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">longe aboute.</NOTE></L>
<L>So blac &amp; derk was al &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> lond, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> no&thorn;ing he ne sei<NOTE PLACE="foot2">dorc.</NOTE></L>
<L>bbote &thorn;e deuelen &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> him drowen, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> so &thorn;icke were him nei.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">deuelin. drowe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac asofte wynd &thorn;er was, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he hurde vnne&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="230">&amp; so scharp &amp; cold he bleu : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> it bro&yogh;te him nei to de&thorn;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hit blew.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t cold it wende nei &thorn;oru&yogh; is herte, : &amp; &thorn;oru is bodi also,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">nei <I>findet sich in keinem Ms. und ist wol aus dem vorigen V. eingedrungen</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">col&thorn;e. nei <I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000204.tif" N="160"></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> him were leuere &thorn;en al &thorn;en world, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e pyne were ido.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">leuer &thorn;an alle &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> worle.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;us colde hi drowe him, as him &thorn;o&yogh;te, : ri&yogh;t uor&thorn; est iwis,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e sonne arist in somer, : wen &thorn;e day lengost is.</L>
<L N="235">&thorn;o hi come &thorn;uder, as him &thorn;o&yogh;te, : ri&yogh;t to &thorn;e wordles ende,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&thorn;uder <I>nur noch in Ms. Cott.; Ms. Bodl. hat</I> &thorn;ere.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hi turnde hem bi abrod ualeie, : &amp; sou(&thorn;)ward gonne wende,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> souward <I>st.</I> sou&thorn;ward.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">turne&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> him. faleie. sout ward.</NOTE></L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e stude as &thorn;e sonne : at mydwynter de&thorn; arise,<MILESTONE N="37" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> wo was &thorn;e kny&yogh;t uor drawe : &amp; ipyned on alle wise.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;is <I>st.</I> &thorn;e. an <I>st.</I> on.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;o&yogh;te him &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he hurde uer, : bi uore him as it were,</L>
<L N="240">Swi&thorn;e deluol cri &amp; wop, : &amp; swi&thorn;e reuuol bere;</L>
<L>Euer &thorn;e ner &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hi come, : &thorn;e reuloker was &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> cri.</L>
<L>So longe hi drowe him, as him &thorn;o&yogh;te : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hi were ri&yogh;t &thorn;er bi.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Statt</I> as <I>haben die and. Mss</I>. &thorn;at.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">long.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o come hi in to awilde feld; : non more ne my&yogh;te be,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">l <I>in</I> feld <I>ist &uuml;bergeschrieben</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">so <I>st.</I> &thorn;o. a <I>vor</I> wilde <I>fehlt</I>. mi&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>So longe he was in euerich side, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> me ne my&yogh;te non ende ise.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">long. eueri. mi&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L N="245">Of men &amp; wemmen &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> feld was : fol in ech syde,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> fold <I>mit wegpunktirtem</I> d.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">wimmen. eueri side.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e wombe naked toward &thorn;e gronde : abrod isprad wel wide,</L>
<L>&thorn;e fet &amp; honden al abrod : to &thorn;e er&thorn;e uaste ibounde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hond.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; nailes of ire, al a fure, : ismyte &thorn;oru out &thorn;e gronde.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Auch Ms. Cott. liest</I> &thorn;oro ut &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> grounde; <I>die and. Mss. richtiger</I> &thorn;orw to &thorn;e grounde, <I>Laud</I> &thorn;oru&yogh; heom to grounde.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is wreche gostes, al uor pyned : wi&thorn; ire &amp; wi&thorn; fure,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">pine&thorn;<SUP>e.</SUP></NOTE></L>
<L N="250">So deoluol cri &amp; bere made, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> deol it was to hure;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">delfol.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hi criede mercy deoluoliche, : ac me nolde hem non do;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">cride.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vor anguise h(i) gnowe &thorn;e colde er&thorn;e : &amp; hor tonge also.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> h <I>st.</I> hi.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">anguische. knoue (!). herde. tong.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e deuelen orne al aboute, : &amp; pulte hem to gronde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ourne. : &amp; op on hom to grounde.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; kene oweles hem to drowe : wi&thorn; mony adeope wounde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; <I>fehlt</I>. dep.</NOTE></L>
<L N="255">Alas, wi ne be&thorn; we her iwar : our sunnes her to bete,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">be we er. here to.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ar we come to purgatorie : &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;e lu&thorn;er gostes Imete?<NOTE PLACE="foot2">gestes mete (<I>ohne</I> I).</NOTE></L>
<L>Vor in purgatorie &thorn;e screwen be&thorn; : as wel as in helle,</L>
<L>&amp; wor&thorn;e&thorn; uorte dai of dome, : telle wat me telle.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">forte &thorn;e.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="161"></L>
<L>&thorn;e deuelen seden : as &thorn;is men : pyne &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt also,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sede. schat <I>st.</I> schalt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="260">bbote &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt &thorn;i &thorn;o&yogh;t wende : &amp; aftur our red do.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wolle.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o he nolde in none manere, : to gronde hi him caste,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">in no.</NOTE></L>
<L>To tormenti him, as &thorn;e o&thorn;er were, : &amp; to naili him uaste.</L>
<L>Ac he cride to ih&umacr; crist anon, : &thorn;o him smerte sore:</L>
<L>&thorn;er nas non of &thorn;e screwen &thorn;o : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> my&yogh;te him greuy more.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">mi&yogh;the.</NOTE></L>
<L N="265">&thorn;o &thorn;e screwen ne mi&yogh;te no&yogh;t : hor wille habbe &thorn;o,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">mi&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hi drowe him in to ano&thorn;er feld, : uol of wel more wo:</L>
<L>Of men &amp; wemmen he was uol, : up ri&yogh;t isprad to gronde,</L>
<L>ffet &amp; honden upri&yogh;t to drawe, : to &thorn;e er&thorn;e uaste ibounde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">honde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; furi nailes of ire, : ynailed uaste &thorn;erto;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nailes fol of ire.</NOTE></L>
<L N="270">Al furi neddren up hem sete, : &amp; crapoudes also:</L>
<L>Somme of &thorn;e neddren hem bi clupte : so uaste al aboute,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">som. be clepte.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hem &thorn;o&yogh;te hi scolde to berste, : so uaste hi gorden wi&thorn;oute;<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Im Ms. nicht deutlich, ob</I> gorden <I>oder</I> gerden.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">breste. gur&thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>Somme seten on oueward hem, : &amp; hor wreche flesch uor gnowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">som sete anoward. wrecche.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; kene te&thorn; al furi : wombe &amp; breste to drowe;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">womb.</NOTE></L>
<L N="275">Somme nome hor scharpe tonge : &amp; &thorn;oru &thorn;e herte smyte,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">some. tong.</NOTE></L>
<L>Somme bounde, somme stonge, : &amp; somme gnowe &amp; bite.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">some bounde &amp; some stong. som.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e crapoudes ek, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> were so foule, : on ouerward &thorn;e herte sete,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">anoward.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; stonge hem &thorn;oru out &thorn;e herte : wi&thorn; hor wrottes so grete.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">stong. &thorn;orou <I>ohne</I> out. hore.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e lu&thorn;er gostes ournen also : aboute hem Inowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">gestes ourne. &amp; aboute.</NOTE></L>
<L N="280">&amp; wi&thorn; oweles &amp; wi&thorn; scourges : &thorn;e wreches al to drowe.</L>
<L>&thorn;e wreche gostes, al uorpyned, : in such torment ibro&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; in suich.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hi &yogh;olle &amp; cride deoluolliche; : ac al ne halp hem no&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">del|folliche. alle ne help.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e deuelen nome &thorn;is seli kny&yogh;t, : &amp; wolde him pyny also,</L>
<L>Ac, &thorn;o he cride on ih&umacr; crist, : hi ne bro&yogh;te him no&yogh;t &thorn;erto.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ac &thorn;o hi (!).</NOTE></L>
<L N="285">&yogh;ut &thorn;e deuelen eft him nome : &amp; to &thorn;e &thorn;ridde feld him drowe.</L>
<L>&thorn;er he sei in strong turment : wreche gostes Inowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sei ek.</NOTE></L>
<L>I sprad to &thorn;e er&thorn;e al abrod, : &amp; ismyte &thorn;oru out echon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;oro ut.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; as &thorn;icke nailes in ech syde, : as &thorn;er my&yogh;te stike on,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">eche stede. stiki.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000206.tif" N="162"></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> me ne scholde fynde an empti place : in al &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> bodi so lute,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ampti. &thorn;e bodi so lite.</NOTE></L>
<L N="290">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> me my&yogh;te uor &thorn;icke nailes : an vyngres ende pute.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">putte.</NOTE></L>
<L>A smart ek wynd to o&thorn;er wo : on hem bleu so uaste,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">ek <I>hinter</I> wynd <I>zu versetzen</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">wynd ek.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hem &thorn;o&yogh;te hi uorbarnde : &thorn;oru out at eche blaste.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">for brende.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e deuelen ornen al so aboute : fram ech to o&thorn;er Inowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ourne.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; hor wreche flesch to o&thorn;er wo : wi&thorn; oweles to drowe.</L>
<L N="295">&thorn;is wreche gostes, so uorpyned, : in such turment ibro&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">for pine&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> &amp; in suich.</NOTE></L>
<L>Reuliche cride as hi my&yogh;te, : ac vnne&thorn;e me hurde hem ou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">reulich. herde hom nou&yogh;t(!).</NOTE></L>
<L>Vor hi were so clene ouercome, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hi my&yogh;te vnne&thorn;e</L>
<L>Brynge eny uois, bote as aman : up &thorn;e poynt of de&thorn;e:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bring.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al in &thorn;e &thorn;rote hi cride hasewe, : as hor streng&thorn;e hem were bynome<NOTE PLACE="foot2">aswe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="300">Myd &thorn;e muche pyne, as no wonder : &thorn;ei hi were ouercome.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">w<SUP>t</SUP> moche, &thorn;e <I>fehlt</I>; as nas no.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e deuelen nome &thorn;is seli kny&yogh;t : &amp; to gronde him caste,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sek <I>st.</I> seli.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; swore, bote he turnde is &thorn;o&yogh;t, : among hem to naili uaste.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Nach</I> naili <I>fehlt</I> him, <I>so auch in Ms. Bodl. u. Cott.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">suore. a mong ham wold naili faste (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac he cride on Ih&umacr; crist, : &amp; nempnede is holi name,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nemde.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e deuelen nadde no pouwer : to do him &thorn;o more schame.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">poer.</NOTE></L>
<L N="305">Hi nome him &thorn;o &amp; drowe him &yogh;ut : to &thorn;e uer&thorn;e felde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;o <I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vol of brunston, al brennynge, : hei sprong &thorn;e spelde.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> Vor <I>(so auch Ms. Cott.) st.</I> vol.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">for. brenning. heie.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ech maner pyne &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> my&yogh;te be : in &thorn;ulke felde he sei:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;ilk feld.</NOTE></L>
<L>Somme wi&thorn; iren raketeien, : al furi, honge an hei,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">some. raketeie. heng.</NOTE></L>
<L>Somme bi armes, &amp; somme bi fet, : &amp; bi &thorn;e swere monyon,</L>
<L N="310">An honge were in stronge fure : &amp; pich &amp; brunston;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">an <I>wol st.</I> and, <I>oder &amp; fehlt. &amp; vor</I> pich <I>st.</I> of <I>(in Ms. Cott. Eg. Laud</I>, ful of <I>Bodl.)</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">an hong. strong fure of pich &amp; of.</NOTE></L>
<L>Somme honge bi stronge oweles, : iput in ei&thorn;er eie,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">som heng. strong.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;oru &thorn;e &thorn;rote somme, : &amp; somme &thorn;oru ei&thorn;er ere wel heie,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> eie <I>st.</I> ere <I>(Ms. Cott. u. Laud.)</I>; eie <I>scheint bereits in der Originalhandschrift gestanden zu haben, daher die Umgehungen in Ms.Eg.u.Bodl.&mdash;: nach dem 2</I>. somme <I>zu versetzen</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">som &amp; som; : <I>erst nach d. 2</I>. som. ere <I>st.</I> eie.</NOTE></L>
<L>Somme &thorn;oru hor derne lymes, : &amp; somme &thorn;oru hor tete,
<PB REF="00000207.tif" N="163"></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hem were leuer &thorn;en al &thorn;en world, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hi mi&yogh;te &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> lif lete;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">alle.</NOTE></L>
<L N="315">Somme up on gredires of ire : irosted were also:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">some op &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> gridels.</NOTE></L>
<L>Somme, as ges, wi&thorn; spites of ire : &thorn;oru out hem ido,</L>
<L>Somme lye upard fram &thorn;e gronde, : &yogh;onynde wel uaste,<MILESTONE N="38" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot2">leie opward fro.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e deueles welde led &amp; bras : &amp; in hor mou&thorn; caste.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; <I>fehlt</I>. &thorn;e deuelen welle&thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>He ne my&yogh;te &thorn;enche nammore pyne, : &thorn;en he sei &thorn;er.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nomore. &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he ne sei &thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L N="320">Him &thorn;o&yogh;te he sei monyon : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he kneu aner&thorn;e her.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">him &thorn;ou&yogh;te ek. er <I>st.</I> her.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e deuelen him caste amydde &thorn;is pyne : among &thorn;e o&thorn;er echon;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e <I>vor</I> o&thorn;er <I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; he cride on Ih&umacr; crist, : &amp; deliuerd was anon.</L>
<L>&yogh;ut &thorn;e deuelen &thorn;is seli kny&yogh;t : in to ano&thorn;er place drowe.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> Ironne <I>st.</I> iriue <I>in den and. Mss.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er Inne he sei agrislich weol : wi&thorn; longe spoken Inowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">long.</NOTE></L>
<L N="325">&thorn;e one side heng toward &thorn;e gronde, : &thorn;e o&thorn;er up an hei,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">on. hung.</NOTE></L>
<L>Aboute it was uol of pykes, : as he &thorn;er isei;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;ere.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is hokes &amp; &thorn;is pikes were : uaste Ironne also<NOTE PLACE="foot2">iriue.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wreche gostes al aboute, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er Inne were ido.</L>
<L>Al brennyng was &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> weol, : &amp; stynkynde of brunston;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">brennig. &thorn;is wheol. stinging of bremston (!).</NOTE></L>
<L N="330">&thorn;e gostes &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er on henge : brennynge were echon.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;er Inne.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is deuelen wende uor&thorn; anon : &amp; hor hokes &thorn;er on caste<NOTE PLACE="foot2">went fort.</NOTE></L>
<L>In ei&thorn;er side, &amp; turnde aboute : &thorn;is sori weol wel uaste,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fol faste.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> of gostes &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er on henge : no&thorn;ing hi ne seie,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hunge. sei.</NOTE></L>
<L>So uaste hi turnde &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> weol aboute, : bote brennynge lye;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">tourne&thorn;e. hi ne seie bote brennig leie.</NOTE></L>
<L N="335">Ac deluolliche hi cride &amp; &yogh;olde, : euerich in is ende.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> &yogh;olde <I>st.</I> &yogh;olle.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">&yogh;olle.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alas, wi nelle men be awar, : ar hi henne wende,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">be war. hen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wen hi mi&yogh;te her myd alute pyne : bete hor mysdede,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">whanne. her <I>fehlt</I>. w<SUP>t</SUP> <I>st.</I> myd.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er hi scholle so bittere abugge, : alas, &thorn;e wrechede?<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;ere. biter. wrecche&thorn; hede.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e deuelen nome &thorn;is kny&yogh;t : &amp; on &thorn;is weol caste,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;is seli . on his (!).</NOTE></L>
<L N="340">&amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er wreche gostes : turnde him aboute uaste;
<PB REF="00000208.tif" N="164"></L>
<L>Ac he cride on ih&umacr; crist, : &amp; deliuerd was anon.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">deliuere&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e deuelen stode &amp; &thorn;is bihulde : wi&thorn; dreri mod echon.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">dredi <I>st.</I> dreri.</NOTE></L>
<L>&yogh;ut hi nome bitterliche : &amp; verrere him ladde,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Hinter</I> nome <I>fehlt</I> him, <I>welches freilich auch in Ms. Cott. u. Eg. fehlt</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">ferror.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hi harled him, &amp; grenned ek, : &amp; loude &yogh;olle &amp; gradde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hij harle&thorn;e. &amp; &amp;, <I>doppelt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="345">A gret hous he sei biuore him stonde, : long &amp; brod Inou;</L>
<L>&thorn;e stench &amp; hete, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er of com, : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te al mest him slou.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">slow.</NOTE></L>
<L>He wi&thorn;stod, &amp; nolde is stonkes : uor stenche go non ner.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> is stonkes <I>st.</I> is &thorn;onkes.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">his &thorn;onkes. for stench go no fer.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vir &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt, &thorn;e deuelen sede, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> ne schalt abide her;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Vir <I>ist</I> Compar., (<I>Cott.</I> ver); <I>Bodl. u. Eg. lesen</I> for&thorn;, <I>Laud</I> ferrore.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">ver.</NOTE></L>
<L>A ba&thorn; it is &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> isucst, : &thorn;er Inne &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt be<NOTE PLACE="foot2">i sikst : &amp;. sch <I>st.</I> schalt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="350">&amp; ba&thorn;ie wi&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er hynen; : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> ne schalt no&yogh;t henne fle.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hine. schalt hen ne fle, no&yogh;t <I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e gostes &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er Inne were : wel deluolliche cride</L>
<L>&amp; loude &yogh;olle, as he hurde, : aboute in ech side.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">i herde. in euer ich.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is kny&yogh;t wi&thorn; &thorn;is foule wi&yogh;tes : in to &thorn;is house com.</L>
<L>Of tormentes, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he &thorn;er isei, : gret gome he nom;<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Das letzte</I> t <I>in</I> torment <I>ist hier mit einem nach unten gehenden Strich versehen, der sich sonst auch an</I> g <I>u.</I> k <I>findet, so bei</I> brennyng <I>v. 330. 334. 407</I>, wonyng <I>413</I>, preching <I>212</I>, strong <I>389</I>, smok <I>406</I>, stonk <I>404, bei</I> torment <I>noch 356. 358. 359; der Strich scheint meist</I> e <I>und</I> es <I>zu bezeichnen</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">tormens. gret gome w<SUP>t</SUP> alle he nom.</NOTE></L>
<L N="355">Vor uol of puttes &amp; of diches : &thorn;is hous wi&thorn;&thorn;inne was,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">pittes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle hi were uolle of strong tormentes, : empti non &thorn;er nas:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">al hi. fol.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of wellynde bras ifuld hi were, : of led &amp; brunston,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hi feld were.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of eoly &amp; o&thorn;er strong tormentes, : bo(i)lynde euerichon.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> bolynde <I>st.</I> boilynde.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">boilinde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wreche gostes &thorn;er Inne sete, : &thorn;e tormentes tilde wel heie:</L>
<L N="360">Somme aboute &thorn;e heued, : &amp; somme up to &thorn;en eie,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> aboute <I>st.</I> aboue, <I>so die and. Mss.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">some al a boue &thorn;e hed.</NOTE></L>
<L>Somme to nese, &amp; somme to mou&thorn;, : &amp; somme to &thorn;e swere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nose. op to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> swere.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; somme up to &thorn;e wreche breste, : &amp; abou&yogh;te hor sunne dere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">up <I>fehlt</I>. wel dere.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; somme up to &thorn;e nauele, : &amp; somme dounere more,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nauel.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000209.tif" N="165"></L>
<L>&amp; somme stode up to &thorn;e kne, : &amp; cride &amp; wope sore.</L>
<L N="365">&amp; somme stode In bo&thorn;e vet, : &amp; somme bote bi on;<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>fehlen in Ms. Eg. Vor</I> bo&thorn;e vet <I>(so auch Ms. Cott.) fehlt</I> bi; <I>Mss. Laud u. Bodl. lesen</I> wi&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac deluolliche hi cride &amp; wepe : euerichon.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>fehlen in Ms. Eg. Vor</I> bo&thorn;e vet <I>(so auch Ms. Cott.) fehlt</I> bi; <I>Mss. Laud u. Bodl. lesen</I> wi&thorn;.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Hinter</I> cride <I>fehlt jeden|falls</I> inou&yogh;, <I>und</I> : <I>als Zeichen des Halbverses ist hinter</I> inou&yogh; <I>zu setzen, (so in Ms. Cott. u. Bodl.)</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">ac deluolliche hi cride y nou &amp; wope euerich on.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nou &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> such, qua&thorn; &thorn;e deuelen, : war Inne &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt gon,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sekst. &thorn;is deuelen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bote &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolle ano&thorn;er speke : &amp; to us turne anon.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ous.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hi nome &amp; caste him In aput; : in Ih&umacr; anon he cride,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">in <I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="370">&amp; com vp anon hol &amp; sound, : him ne luste no leng abide.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">leste no&thorn;ing.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e deuelen anon in grete wra&thorn;&thorn;e : harlede him uerrore more,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">gret. verror.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; bro&yogh;te him up aswi&thorn;e gret hul, : uol of sorwe &amp; sore.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">brou&yogh;t. hel.</NOTE></L>
<L>He stod &amp; bihuld aboute, : &thorn;o he com up an hei;</L>
<L>Him wondred of &thorn;e uele gostes : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he &thorn;er isei,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wondre&thorn;e. &thorn;er up.</NOTE></L>
<L N="375">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> alle &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he isei er : &thorn;er a&yogh;en no&yogh;t nere;<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Hinter</I> he <I>ist</I> &thorn;er <I>wegpunktirt</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> alle er isei (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>Vp hor ton hi sete al uorclu&yogh;t, : &amp; quaked al uor fere.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">uer cluyt.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e sou&yogh;&thorn; half of &thorn;e hul : a deop water &thorn;er was &amp; lou&yogh;,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">lou.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> foule stonck &amp; caldore was : &thorn;en eny is o&thorn;er snou&yogh;;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">stonc. &thorn;an.</NOTE></L>
<L>A nor&thorn;erne wynd so uaste bleu, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> him &thorn;ou&yogh;te is flech to rende.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">a nor&thorn;er wynd. blew. rente.</NOTE></L>
<L N="380">Euere sete &thorn;is seli gostes : &amp; a&yogh;en &thorn;e wynd hem wende,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">euer. holi (!) gostes. &thorn;is wynd.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; quaked &amp; chiuered uaste, : &amp; dredde &thorn;e pyne stronge,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>ist wol zu lesen:</I> in drede &amp; pyne.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">quake&thorn;e. chiuere&thorn;e. in drede &amp; pine strong.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; a bide as hose sei&thorn; hor tyme, : hor de&thorn; uorte auonge.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">as wo sei&thorn;. afong.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lo, qua&thorn; on of &thorn;e deuelen, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> nost no&yogh;t wat is &thorn;is;</L>
<L>bbote &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> &thorn;i &thorn;o&yogh;t &thorn;e sonore turne, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt sone iwite iwis.</L>
<L N="385">He nadde bote &thorn;is word ised, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er ne com awynd blowe</L>
<L>&amp; smot alle &thorn;is seli gostes : in &thorn;is deope water wel lowe.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">dep.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e nor&thorn;erne wynd hem drof a doun, : &amp; al myd one blaste<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nor&thorn;er. &amp; alle mid on.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is gostes &amp; &thorn;is kny&yogh;t : amydde &thorn;e water caste.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> kyn&yogh;t <I>st.</I> kny&yogh;t.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; alle &thorn;is gostes. &thorn;is water.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000210.tif" N="166"></L>
<L>Nammore pyne ne my&yogh;te (be) : of stronge (chele) &amp; stenche,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Hinter</I> my&yogh;te <I>fehlt</I> be, <I>hinter</I> stronge <I>fehlt</I> chele.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">no more. mi&yogh;t be. of strong chele &amp; of stenche.</NOTE></L>
<L N="390">&thorn;en &thorn;is gostes &thorn;er Inne hadde,: hem ne my&yogh;te non at blenche.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hou <I>st.</I> hem. ablenche.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e kny&yogh;t &thorn;is stronge pyne : of &thorn;is water uelde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;is kny&yogh;t. strong.</NOTE></L>
<L>He gan to crie on ih&umacr; crist, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> failede him swi&thorn;e selde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fale&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> (!). wel selde.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; anon wi&thorn;&thorn;oute eny lette : out of &thorn;is water he drou.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">any.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac &thorn;is gostes bileuede &thorn;er : wi&thorn; wo &amp; sorwe Inou,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">gost. &thorn;ere. soruy y now (!)</NOTE></L>
<L N="395">Vor in &thorn;is water, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> was so cold : &amp; so uoule stonck also,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">foul stonk.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is gostes swomme up &amp; doun, : hor wo nas neuer ido;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">wo <I>aus</I> was <I>corrigirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e deuelen orne ek up &thorn;e watere, : so mon de&thorn; alonde;<MILESTONE N="39" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot2">&yogh;ourne. water.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; wen eny wolde clemeri up : wi&thorn; fet o&thorn;er wi&thorn; honde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">clemen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Anon hi drowe him doun a&yogh;en, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er ne of scapede non;</L>
<L N="400">&thorn;er was wo &amp; sorwe Inou : among hem euerichon.</L>
<L>&thorn;is deuelen wende uor&thorn; anon, : &amp; &thorn;is seli kny&yogh;t eft nome<NOTE PLACE="foot2">went.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; drowe him in asori stude, : &thorn;er hi neuer er ne come.</L>
<L>Hi come &amp; stode ouer aput, : wid &amp; deop Inou,</L>
<L>&amp; brennynge smoke, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> foule stonk, : out of &thorn;e putte drou,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Der Strich hinter</I> k <I>in</I> stonk <I>kann hier wol nichts bedeuten</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">a brenning. foul stong (!). &thorn;is putte.</NOTE></L>
<L N="405">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e kny&yogh;t vnne&thorn;e stod : uor sori stench &thorn;er nei.</L>
<L>Wreche gostes up &thorn;is put : in &thorn;is sori smoke he sei<NOTE PLACE="foot2">op of.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffle up &amp; doun, al brennynge, : as spelden do&thorn; of fure,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">brennind. spiltren (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; in to &thorn;e put eft uelle adoun, : wen hi ne mi&yogh;te no leng dure.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">pette. fulle. mi&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>Him &thorn;o&yogh;te he was nei ouercome : uor &thorn;e blast &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er of drou,</L>
<L N="410">&thorn;er bi he wuste &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> in &thorn;e gronde : was pyne &amp; wo Inou.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wiste. wo &amp; pine.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hou stondestou? &thorn;e deuelen sede, : &thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;e her of wonder,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">stondestu. &thorn;enchet.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e swote smoke &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> her blowe&thorn;, : &amp; wat put be her vnder?<NOTE PLACE="foot2">herof <I>st.</I> &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> her. bloue&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;is put is oure wonynge, : uor &thorn;e put of helle it is,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">pette. woniing.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp;, uor &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> ous hast iserued wel, : her &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt wonye iwis,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">haste <I>st.</I> hast. here.</NOTE></L>
<L N="415">Vor alle &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ous serue&thorn; wel : her Inne scholle wende,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fo <I>st.</I> vor. here. schollet.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000211.tif" N="167"></L>
<L>&amp;, be &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> Inne her wi&thorn; ous, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> worst her wi&thorn;oute ende;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; be &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> her Inne wit ous. here.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er uore we rede&thorn; turne &thorn;i &thorn;o&yogh;t : &amp; do uous her monrede,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> uous <I>st.</I> ous.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">torn. here.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; we scholle&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;en wei as &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> come : al sauf a&yogh;en lede,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> a wei. saf.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e tid aner&thorn;e al &thorn;i lif : richesse &amp; Joie also,</L>
<L N="420">Vor we scholle&thorn; euer &thorn;e fynde Inou, : as ri&yogh;t is &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> we do.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">scholle&thorn;e &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> euer.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;is kny&yogh;t uorsok hor bi heste, : as he hadde er ilome,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ylome.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hi smyte hem adoun in to &thorn;is put, : &amp; &thorn;is kny&yogh;t wi&thorn; hem nome.</L>
<L>&thorn;e deppere &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hi &thorn;er Inne come, : &thorn;e braddere &thorn;e put was,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">deppore. braddore.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> al &thorn;e wo, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he sei er, : &thorn;er a&yogh;en no&yogh;t nas.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">alle.</NOTE></L>
<L N="425">Wi&thorn; stench &amp; wi&thorn; o&thorn;er wo : &thorn;is kny&yogh;t was so ouercome,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">alle o&thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> is &thorn;o&yogh;t toward ih&umacr; crist : him was nei bi nome;</L>
<L>So muche pyne nas neuer iseie, : him &thorn;o&yogh;te, as he uelde,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he was al up &thorn;e poynt : &thorn;en gost uorto &yogh;elde.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> a&yogh;elde; a <I>fehlt in den and. Mss. u. ist wol verschrieben</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">pointe. &yogh;elde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac our lord among al is wo : his grace him &yogh;ef atelaste,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">suich grace him. at.</NOTE></L>
<L N="430">So &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he &thorn;o&yogh;te on ih&umacr; crist : &amp; on him cride uaste.</L>
<L>A smoke &thorn;er com up smyte anon, : &amp; myd an stronge blaste<NOTE PLACE="foot2">w<SUP>t</SUP> a strong.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is kny&yogh;t an hei aboue &thorn;is put, : &amp; mony gostes, caste;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">a boue an hei &thorn;is pet.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is kny&yogh;t wirlede in &thorn;is blast, : so spelden do&thorn;, wel wide,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wirle&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ate laste he li&yogh;te adoun : aboue &thorn;e put biside.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">at.</NOTE></L>
<L N="435">&thorn;er he stod &amp; bi huld aboute : as mon &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> witles were,</L>
<L>Vor pyne &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he hadde ihad, : he nuste hou he com &thorn;ere.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ihed. neste how.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o he hadde &thorn;er longe istonde : &amp; al one biholde aboute,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;ere long. bihold.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er com blaste out of &thorn;is put : of deuelen agret route,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">come blast. deuele.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; stode bi him aboute, : nywe as &thorn;ei it were;<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Statt</I> it <I>haben die and. Mss</I>. hi <I>oder</I> heo, <I>Ms. Eg</I>. e.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">sto&thorn;. al aboute. nwe. hi <I>st.</I> it.</NOTE></L>
<L N="440">He ne sei hem, as him &thorn;o&yogh;te, : neuer bote &thorn;o &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Hi bihulde him wel grisliche, : &amp; grennynde al aboute:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; grenne&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi stondestou &thorn;us al one? hi sede, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt come to oure route!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">al alone. our rou&yogh;te.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wat, tolde oure felawes &thorn;e : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e put of helle &thorn;is is?<NOTE PLACE="foot2">our felaues. is &thorn;is.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000212.tif" N="168"></L>
<L>It nys no&yogh;t so; ac &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt : iwite war it is;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hit is nout so. whare.</NOTE></L>
<L N="445">Nostou no&yogh;t, it is oure ri&yogh;te : to lie euermo,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>fehlen in Ms. Eg.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">nostu. ri&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> we myd lesynges men bitraie, : bote it mowe o&thorn;er go?<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>fehlen in Ms. Eg.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">w<SUP>t.</SUP></NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; also oure felawes lowe &thorn;e : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;is was &thorn;e put of helle;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">our.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt &thorn;uder come wi&thorn; ous,: &amp; &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> so&thorn;e (we) wolle&thorn; &thorn;e telle.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Vor</I> wolle&thorn; <I>fehlt</I> we <I>im Ms.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">we wolle&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e deuelen harlede &thorn;is kny&yogh;t uor&thorn;, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> wo was him of drawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">harled. to drawe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="450">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> him were leuer &thorn;en eny &thorn;ing : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he were of lif dawe.</L>
<L>So &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hi come to agret water, : deop &amp; brod Inou&yogh;;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Inou&yogh; <I>aus</I> Inow <I>&ccedil;orrigirt</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">a suide gret.</NOTE></L>
<L>A strong myst, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> stonc swi&thorn;e stronge, : up of &thorn;is water drou&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">stonk sui&thorn;e foule.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of brunston &amp; of o&thorn;er wo, : so strong stenc neuer he ne sei,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">stenche.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> myd al &thorn;e pyne of &thorn;e world : he mi&yogh;te enes stonde &thorn;er nei.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wit alle pine.</NOTE></L>
<L N="455">A brugge &thorn;er was ouer &thorn;e water, : smallere ne my&yogh;te non be;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bregge. smallore.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e smoke was so &thorn;icke aboute, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> vnne&thorn;e me my&yogh;te hire ise.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">he h<SUP>t</SUP> mi&yogh;t i se.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lo, sede &thorn;e sori deuelen, : we segge&thorn; &thorn;e iwis</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> vnder &thorn;is water dep Inou&yogh; : &thorn;e put of helle is;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt sone iwite, : uor &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt uor&thorn; anon</L>
<L N="460">&amp; ouer &thorn;is water : up &thorn;is brugge gon,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Vor</I> water <I>fehlt</I> suete <I>(Cott.)</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;is suete water. brigge.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; we &thorn;e scholle sende awynd, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> schal &thorn;e amydde caste,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">send.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; our felawes, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> be&thorn; byne&thorn;e, : scholle&thorn; &thorn;e holde uaste</L>
<L>&amp; drawe &thorn;e uor&thorn; wi&thorn; hem : to helle gronde anon;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">draue.</NOTE></L>
<L>Com nou for&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt : up &thorn;is brugge gon.</L>
<L N="465">Hi nome &thorn;is seli kny&yogh;t anon : &amp; up &thorn;is brugge drowe,</L>
<L>&amp; made him go &thorn;er is vn&thorn;onkes : wi&thorn; wrechedes Inowe.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">dere. wit wrecches y nowe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vor &thorn;re &thorn;inges vuele Inou&yogh; : up &thorn;is brugge were:</L>
<L>&thorn;e on was &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> heo was so hei, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> vnne&thorn;e me my&yogh;te for fere<NOTE PLACE="foot2">he.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er up go &amp; so deop adoun : habbe so grisliche si&yogh;te;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">grislich.</NOTE></L>
<L N="470">&thorn;e o&thorn;er was &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> heo was so narw, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> vnne&thorn;e me my&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nare.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er upe sette eny fot, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he ne uel adoun anon;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">op.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;ridde was &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> heo was so slider, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> me ne scholde &thorn;er on no&yogh;t gon,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">schol&thorn;. no&yogh;t <I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000213.tif" N="169"></L>
<L>Bote me slide &amp; uelle adoun, : so wis neuer he nere.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">slidde. fel.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;es &thorn;re &thorn;inges &thorn;is seli kny&yogh;t : bro&yogh;te in gret fere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;is. &thorn;ingis.</NOTE></L>
<L N="475">Vor heo was narw, slider, &amp; hei; : he ne scholde him so bi telle,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">he. nare &amp; sli&thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; he glide in eny half, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he ne uelle in to helle.</L>
<L>&thorn;er uppe he was wi&thorn; streng&thorn; ibro&yogh;t : &amp; Imad &thorn;er up gon.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">op.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="40" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So gret drede, as him &thorn;o&yogh;te, : nadde neuer man non.</L>
<L>Ac sone he &thorn;o&yogh;te on ih&umacr; crist, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> so ofte him sauede er,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">so ou&yogh;te (!) him saue&thorn; er.</NOTE></L>
<L N="480">&amp; cride on is holi name, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he hulpe him &thorn;er;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hol&thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; gon to go baldeloker, : &amp;, &thorn;e Inner more he com,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">gan. &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> baldeloker. &thorn;e Innore more. cam.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e hardiere him &thorn;o&yogh;te he was : &amp; &thorn;e betere herte nom,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hardiore. beter.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e braddere was is wei; : so longe uor&thorn; he eode,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">braddore. &amp; so long ford.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> heo was so brod, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er my&yogh;te : gon up a cart uor neode,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">he. a carte. nede.</NOTE></L>
<L N="485">&amp; so longe &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> twei cartes my&yogh;te : mete hem wel Inou&yogh;.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Von hier ab fehlen in Ms. Bodl. 80 Verse, bis V. 565 des Ms. Eg.; der n&auml;chste Vers ist:</I> &thorn;is place &thorn;at we Inne be&thorn; : I wene &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> knowest it nou&yogh;t.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">long.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is kny&yogh;t &thorn;o wel baldeliche : as maister uor&thorn; him drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&thorn;e deuelen stode byne&thorn;e &thorn;e brugge : &amp; iseie him so uaste gon,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fast.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> of al &thorn;e wo &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hi him dude : ne ouercome him no&yogh;t on,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>im Ms. fehlt :; hinter</I> ne <I>ist ein zweites</I> ne <I>wegpunktirt</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">alle &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o&yogh;te, it was uor no&yogh;t : after him to honte more;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;<SUP>t.</SUP> honti.</NOTE></L>
<L N="490">Wel grisliche hi gonne &yogh;elle, : &amp; cride &amp; wepe sore,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> criide; <I>trotz der Abk&uuml;rzung f&uuml;r</I> ri <I>ist noch ein</I> i <I>gesetzt</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">&yogh;olle. wope.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> of &yogh;ellynde &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hi made : him &thorn;o&yogh;te grettere fere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&yogh;olling. grettore.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;en of al &thorn;e pyne &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he hadde er, : so grisliche was &thorn;e bere.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">alle &thorn;e. hi <I>st.</I> he. grislich.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hor oweles hi nome &amp; crokes, : &amp; toward him caste an hei,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;er nas non &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> my&yogh;te him touche, : ne non come him nei.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">non <I>vor</I> come <I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="495">So &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> al sauf wi&thorn; alle Ioie : ouer &thorn;e water he drou&yogh;,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;is water. drow.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e deuelen bi hynde were : wi&thorn; sorwe &amp; sore Inou&yogh;,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Im Ms. Laud ist hier ein Vers zugesetzt</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">bi hinde him. soru.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; lette him go wider he wolde, : &amp; ne fondede him nammore,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">let. vu&thorn;er. fonde&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; helden hem clanliche ouercome, : &amp; &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hem a&thorn;o&yogh;te sore.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hel&thorn;.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000214.tif" N="170"></L>
<L>&thorn;e kny&yogh;t wende uor&thorn; sauf Inou&yogh;, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he hadde er dere abo&yogh;t;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wend.</NOTE></L>
<L N="500">He &thorn;onkede uaste ih&umacr; crist : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hi ne siwede him no&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fast. swe&thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> water he passede sauf Inou&yogh;, : &amp; verrere &thorn;en wei nom;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">passe&thorn;. ferror.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e contreie him &thorn;o&yogh;te murie Inou&yogh;, : &thorn;o he &thorn;er on com;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">contrei. &thorn;er ouer.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e uerrere &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he wende, : &thorn;e more Ioie he sei.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">for&thorn;er. wente for&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>So longe &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he sei awal, : swi&thorn;e noble &amp; hei;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">long. an wal.</NOTE></L>
<L N="505">So noble work nas neuer isei, : as him &thorn;o&yogh;te &thorn;er on was;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">was. y seie.</NOTE></L>
<L>A noble &yogh;at he sei &thorn;er on, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> noblere non nas;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">noblore.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &yogh;at scynde swi&thorn;e bri&yogh;te, : of gold as &thorn;ei it were,</L>
<L>Vol of &yogh;ymmes presious, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> richere none nere.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">precious. non.</NOTE></L>
<L>Him &thorn;o&yogh;te, ar he &thorn;uder come, : is wei longe ilaste.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">long.</NOTE></L>
<L N="510">&thorn;o he com alute ner, : he stod &amp; bihuld uaste.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">biheld.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e &yogh;at wende up a&yogh;en him, : &amp; anon myd &thorn;e dede<NOTE PLACE="foot2">w<SUP>t</SUP> <I>st.</I> myd.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er sprong out aswote smul, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> wide bigan to sprede,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">suete smel.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> him &thorn;o&yogh;te, &thorn;ei al &thorn;e world : swote spices were,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>steht im Ms. am Ende der Seite hinter V. 515; seine Stellung vor 514 ist durch a und</I> b <I>bezeichnet. &mdash; Nach V. 540 folgen in d. Mss. Eg. Laud (und Bodl.) &uuml;ber 80 Verse, die hier, sowie in Ms. Cott., fehlen; in Ms. Eg. sind es die Verse 540-625, in Ms. Laud 496-584.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">alle. sote spises.</NOTE></L>
<L>So muche swotnesse ne my&yogh;te &yogh;eue : as &thorn;ulke bre&thorn; &thorn;ere.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sotnesse. &yogh;iue. &thorn;ilk.</NOTE></L>
<L N="515">In so gret Ioie him &thorn;o&yogh;te he was, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP>, &thorn;ei he hadde be ibro&yogh;t</L>
<L>In al &thorn;e wo &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he was on, : hit nolde him greue no&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">alle. greuy.</NOTE></L>
<L>In he bihuld at &thorn;is &yogh;at, : &thorn;o he com &thorn;er nei:</L>
<L>More clernesse ne mi&yogh;te be, : him &thorn;o&yogh;te, &thorn;en he sei.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;an <I>st.</I> &thorn;en.</NOTE></L>
<L>As he wolde &thorn;er Inne wende, : a&yogh;en him &thorn;er com gon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">com som (!).</NOTE></L>
<L N="520">A procession uair Inou&yogh;, : of noble men echon,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; crois &amp; wi&thorn; taperes, : wi&thorn; baners swi&thorn;e clere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">baneris.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> folc bi hynde ireuested, : ech bi is Iuere:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wit folc bi hinde resteue&thorn; resteue&thorn; euerich bi his iuere (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>Biscops somme &amp; erchedekenes, : &amp; monekes &amp; frere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bischopes some. erchedeknes. monkis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; ech, him &thorn;o&yogh;te, in &thorn;e abit : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hi werede aner&thorn;e here.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; euerich. he <I>st.</I> hi.</NOTE></L>
<L N="525">Mit &thorn;e meste Ioie &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> mi&yogh;te be : &thorn;is kny&yogh;t hi gonne auonge,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Mi&thorn;. mi&yogh;t. afong.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000215.tif" N="171"></L>
<L>&amp; ladde him In wi&thorn; Ioie Inou&yogh; : of solas &amp; of songe.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In <I>fehlt</I>. song.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;is murie song was ido, : to him sone &thorn;er come<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; &thorn;o. meri.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tweie, as it maistres were, : &amp; bi &thorn;e hond him nome,</L>
<L>Hi wilcomede him wel mildeliche, : &amp; &thorn;onked our lord uaste,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hij welcome&thorn;e. &thorn;onke&thorn;<SUP>e.</SUP></NOTE></L>
<L N="530">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &yogh;ef him so good bileue, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> so studeuastliche ilaste.</L>
<L>Hi ladde him aboute &amp; scewede him : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> lond uer &amp; nei:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hij.</NOTE></L>
<L>So muche clernesse &amp; o&thorn;er Ioie : him &thorn;o&yogh;te neuer he ne sei;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ne of ioie (!). him &thorn;o&yogh;te him (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>Vor, as &thorn;e sonne bi neme&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> li&yogh;t : of &thorn;e candele aboute mydday,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">candle.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al so it bynom &thorn;e sonne leom, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> li&yogh;t &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he &thorn;er isay.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e li&yogh;t. &thorn;ere.</NOTE></L>
<L N="535">So brod &amp; long &thorn;e place was, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he ne mi&yogh;te non ende ise,</L>
<L>Al murie med &amp; suote fluores, : swettere ne mi&yogh;te non be,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">al meri. sote. swetter.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tren also wi&thorn; noble frut, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> swote smulde Inou&yogh;.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">tres. fruy&yogh;t. smel&thorn;e sote.</NOTE></L>
<L>So gret swotnesse al aboute : of ech place drou&yogh;,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">suetnesse of al aboute of eche.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er wi&thorn;oute mete &amp; drynke, : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, euermo</L>
<L N="540">He mi&yogh;te libbe wi&thorn; alle Ioie, : &yogh;if he mi&yogh;te &thorn;er among go.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&yogh;if he mi&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ne laste bote lute stounde, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e leme ne wi&thorn;drou&yogh;;</L>
<L>Ac na&thorn;eles, &thorn;ei it lute laste, : hi were alle uolle Inou&yogh;.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fol y nou.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is kny&yogh;t stod &amp; bihuld aboute, : &amp; ri&yogh;te stat vnder stod;<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Vor</I> ri&yogh;te stat <I>fehlt</I> his.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">bihol&thorn;. &amp; his ri&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>So uol he was of &thorn;is holi leom, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> so dilicious was &amp; good,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">leme. delicious.</NOTE></L>
<L N="545">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP>, &thorn;ei he lyuede, him &thorn;o&yogh;te, euermo : &amp; neuereft mete ete,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ne ete.</NOTE></L>
<L>He ne scholde neuer to mete luste, : so good was &thorn;e leom &amp; swete.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">him ne scholle. leste.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lo, sede &thorn;is o&thorn;er gost : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> him scewede al &thorn;is place,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">schewe&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nou &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast somdel iseie : of our lordes grace:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">oure.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of pynes &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> wreche gostes : habbe&thorn; uor hor mysdede,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">of pine. wrecce.</NOTE></L>
<L N="550">&amp; of Ioie &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> gode gostes : In parays do&thorn; lede,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">paradis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; somdel ek of &thorn;e grete Ioie : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> In heuene is;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">heuen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; ech day we be&thorn; yued enes : wi&thorn; such Ioie &amp; blis,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">eche dai.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;enne be&thorn; we al day uolle Inou&yogh;, : uorte our lord ous more sende:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;an be we. for <I>st.</I> uolle. for&thorn; oure.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000216.tif" N="172"></L>
<L>Ac such Ioie hi &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> in heuene be&thorn; : habbe wi&thorn;oute ende,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Vor</I> such Ioie <I>ist</I> in <I>wegpunktirt; die Originalhandschrift las wol</I> : in such Ioie &mdash; be&thorn;, <I>wie Mss. Cott. Laud u. Bodl.; darauf deutet auch in Ms. Eg.</I> in <I>vor</I> more.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">ac in such ioie hi &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> in heuen be&thorn;: be&thorn; wit oute ende.</NOTE></L>
<L N="555">&amp; &yogh;ut somdel more, : uor hit ne wone&thorn; hem neuermo;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">in more. wane&thorn; him (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; we ne be&thorn; aday bote enes Iued, : uorte &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> we &thorn;uder go,</L>
<L>&amp;, wenne &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> we &thorn;uder come&thorn;, : we scholle&thorn; wi&thorn;outen ende,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">whan we, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> <I>fehlt</I>. wit oute nende.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="41" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP>, &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> it wolt aseruy : &thorn;uder uorte wende;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hit wolt of serui. forto.</NOTE></L>
<L>As &thorn;i wille is &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> mi&yogh;t do, : wen &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> comest to er&thorn;e iwis,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wil.</NOTE></L>
<L N="560">&amp; &thorn;uder &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> most a&yogh;en, : uor al tyme it is;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">alle.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt &thorn;er good lif lede, : &thorn;i mede &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> mi&yogh;t ise,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> lete <I>st.</I> lede.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;ere. lede.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; also, wat pynes &thorn;e abide&thorn;, : &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wolt lu&thorn;er be.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; <I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>A&yogh;en &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> most wende anon; : go uor&thorn; a godes name,</L>
<L>&amp; go sikerliche, uor &thorn;e deuelen : mowe do &thorn;e nammore schame:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ne mowe &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> do namore.</NOTE></L>
<L N="565">Adrad hi be&thorn; wel sore of &thorn;e, : &amp; aschamed in ech side;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">of schamet.</NOTE></L>
<L>A godes name go uor&thorn; &thorn;i wei, : uor &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> ne mi&yogh;t no leng abide!</L>
<L>A, sire, mercy! qua&thorn; &thorn;is kny&yogh;t, : wat so me euer bitide,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">what me so.</NOTE></L>
<L>A fot Inele fram &yogh;ou go, : wrechede go&thorn; so wide,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">i nel fro &yogh;o gon. wrechede <I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac let me bileue wi&thorn; &yogh;ou her, : uor, &yogh;if i<SUP>c</SUP> fram &yogh;ou wende,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">me let. w<SUP>t</SUP> &yogh;ow &yogh;er (!). fro &yogh;e.</NOTE></L>
<L N="570">Adrad icham of &thorn;e deuel : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he myd sunne me scende.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">me <I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nai, beu frere, qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> mi&yogh;t as wel be stille;</L>
<L>A&yogh;en &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt to er&thorn;e anon, : &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> mi&yogh;t do &thorn;er &thorn;yn wille;<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>steht unten am Ende der Seite; der Anschluss ist mit</I> a &mdash; b <I>bezeichnet. Nach V. 572 fehlen hier durch Versehen des Schreibers 2 Verse, die in allen and. Mss. stehen; die erste Halbz. von V. 573 muss heissen</I> : a godes half wend a&yogh;en anon, <I>so in d. and. Mss.</I> &mdash;</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2"><P>dere. <I>Nach 572 folgen die Verse:</I></P><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> seruest wel our lord siker &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> mi&yogh;t be</L>
<L>a&yogh;en come hider to ous &amp; su&thorn;&thorn;e to heuen fle</L>
<L>a godes half wen&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> a&yogh;en a non . for siker &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt so.</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L>A&yogh;en &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt to er&thorn;e anon, : uor siker &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt so.</L>
<L>Alas, (alas,) qua&thorn; &thorn;is kny&yogh;t, : wat schal i<SUP>c</SUP> nou do?<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> alas <I>ein|mal; alle and. Mss.</I> alas alas, <I>wie auch das Versmass verlangt</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">alas alas. now.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000217.tif" N="173"></L>
<L N="575">Al &thorn;e Ioie &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> i<SUP>c</SUP> habbe iseie, : nou it wor&thorn; me bynome,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">alle. ich abbe.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e wrechede &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> is aner&thorn;e, : alas, schal i<SUP>c</SUP> come.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">schal ich nou come.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al wepynde out ate &yogh;ate : hi bro&yogh;te him ate laste;<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>hat Ms. Laud je einen Vers mehr.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">weping. atte. at laste.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; anon, so he was wi&thorn;oute, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &yogh;at hi made uaste.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>hat Ms. Laud je einen Vers mehr.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; <I>fehlt.</I> &thorn;er wit oute.</NOTE></L>
<L>As he com er, wi&thorn; dreri mod : &thorn;e wei a&yogh;en he nom.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;en wei.</NOTE></L>
<L N="580">Ac, wen eny deuel &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> pyned him er : a&yogh;en him awer com,</L>
<L>As wode screwen (hi) flowen him uaste, : hi ne dorste abide him no&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Im Ms. fehlt</I> hi <I>vor</I> flowen.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">hi flowe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Atelaste &thorn;is kny&yogh;t was : to &thorn;e halle ibro&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Im Ms. fehlt</I> :.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">at &thorn;e laste.</NOTE></L>
<L>As &thorn;e holi companye : &thorn;uderward to him wende.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">company.</NOTE></L>
<L>Adoun he sat softe &thorn;er, : uorte our lord him grace sende.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sente.</NOTE></L>
<L N="585">As he sat &amp; bi huld aboute, : &thorn;er come In sone &thorn;er</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is noble companye, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> a&yogh;en him com er.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">compani. come.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle hi honourede him uaire : &amp; herede him wel uaste,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wel faire.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; ih&umacr; also, godes sone, : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> is bileue so wel ilaste.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">laste.</NOTE></L>
<L>Beu frere, he sede, wen &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast : so strong penaunce idriue,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">he sede <I>auch in Mss. Bodl. u. Eg.; Cott. hat</I> hi, <I>Laud</I> heo sede; hi <I>ist wol richtiger</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">hi sede. such <I>st.</I> so.</NOTE></L>
<L N="590">Siker be &thorn;e &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;yne sunnes clanliche : be&thorn; uor&yogh;iue;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&thorn;e <I>auch in Ms. Eg.; die and. Mss</I>. &thorn;ou.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">siker &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> be. &thorn;in sinnes. &thorn;e be&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Loke, wen &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> comst to er&thorn;e a&yogh;en, : clene lif &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> lede,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">lok. comest.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> neuereft in pyne come : uor sunne ne mysdede;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ne come. ne for mis dede.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> most do &thorn;e henne anon, : uor atom in &thorn;yne londe<NOTE PLACE="foot2">athom. dyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>It dawe&thorn; cler, &amp; is nei day, : as i<SUP>c</SUP> vnderstonde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">dawet clere.</NOTE></L>
<L N="595">&amp; &thorn;e priour wi&thorn; procession : to &thorn;e &yogh;ate come&thorn; sone,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">prior.</NOTE></L>
<L>To loke war &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> be icome, : as ri&yogh;t is uorto done;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wher.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp;, bote he &thorn;e fynde &thorn;er, : he wole make &thorn;e &yogh;at anon</L>
<L>&amp; be siker &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> ne comest nammore, : &amp; hamward dreri gon.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ne <I>fehlt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is kny&yogh;t hi bro&yogh;te out of &thorn;is halle, : &amp; blessed him echon,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">blesse&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP></NOTE></L>
<L N="600">&amp; biteite him god, lif &amp; soule, : uel &amp; flesch &amp; bon.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bi tok.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vor&thorn; he wende dreriliche, : bote as he moste nede do.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wente.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000218.tif" N="174"></L>
<L>&amp;, ri&yogh;t as he com to &thorn;is &yogh;at, : &thorn;e priour com also</L>
<L>A&yogh;en him wi&thorn; procession, : to loke hou it were.</L>
<L>Anon so he hadde &thorn;e &yogh;at vnloke, : &thorn;e kny&yogh;t he fond &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="605">&thorn;er was Ioie &amp; blisse Inou&yogh;, : &thorn;o hi to gadere come.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hij.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; song &amp; wi&thorn; orisons : &thorn;en kny&yogh;t out hi nome,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> orisous.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; ladde him to chirche anon, : &amp; herede our lord uaste.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">him for&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is kny&yogh;t biuore &thorn;e heie weued : akne adoun him caste,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">a fore &thorn;e heie hauter. anon <I>st.</I> adoun.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; uaste in is orisons : viftene dawes he lay,<NOTE PLACE="foot1"><I>Ms.</I> orisous.</NOTE></L>
<L N="610">&amp; herede our swete lord uaste : bo&thorn;e ny&yogh;t &amp; day.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bo&thorn;e <I>fehlt.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; su&thorn;&thorn;e in is bare flech : &thorn;e holi crois he nom<NOTE PLACE="foot2">flesch.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; wende to &thorn;e holi lond, : &amp; holi mon bicom,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wente.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; ne tolde neuer of &thorn;e world, : bote as he were in &thorn;o&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">neuereft. as he euer were in &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; wende him uor&thorn; er simpliche, : as him no&thorn;ing rou&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">er, <I>in Ms. Cott. fehlend</I>, = euer.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">went. er <I>fehlt.</I> ne rou&yogh;te.</NOTE></L>
<L N="615">Al ofte he tolde of alle men : &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> in parais were;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Al <I>wol st.</I> ac.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">ac ofte.</NOTE></L>
<L>As him &thorn;o&yogh;te, greie monekes : in mest Ioie he sei &thorn;ere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">grei monkes.</NOTE></L>
<L>None men in so gret Ioie, : ne in so gret honur he ne sei:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">non men. hous <I>st.</I> honur.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne no wonder sikerliche, : uor &thorn;e ordre is noble &amp; hei.</L>
<L>Wen &yogh;e habbe&thorn; nou alle ihurd, : hou our lord send is grace<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ou hour (!) lord sende.</NOTE></L>
<L N="620">S. patric, &thorn;ulke purgatorie : to vynde in &thorn;ulke place,</L>
<L>Vorte warny men aboute : hor sunnes her to bete,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">for to. hor <I>st.</I> her (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>Vor &thorn;e loue of ih&umacr; crist : &amp; is moder suete:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; of his.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bete&thorn; alle &yogh;oure sunne her, : as god wole &yogh;ou grace sende,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> we wi&thorn;&thorn;oute o&thorn;er pyne : to parais henne wende.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">we <I>st.</I> &yogh;e.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &yogh;e.</NOTE></L>
</LG>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000219.tif" N="[175]">
<HEAD>b. aus Ms. Egerton 1993.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seint patrik com &thorn;orw god . to prechi in yrlonde,</L>
<L>To teche &thorn;e ri&yogh;te bileue . of ih&umacr; to vnderstonde.</L>
<L>So fol of wormes was &thorn;e lond, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> mon ne mi&yogh;te gon</L>
<L>In som stude for wormes, . &thorn;at nas wemmed an on.</L>
<L N="5">Seint patrik bad oure lord . &thorn;at lond deliuered were<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> lond <I>fehlt</I> &thorn;e <I>oder</I> &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e foule wormes, . &thorn;at non ne come &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Oure lord herde is bone, . vor &thorn;er mi&yogh;te neuer eft come</L>
<L>No foul worm in &thorn;at lond, . &thorn;at is lif nas bi nome.</L>
<L>Gras &thorn;at growe&thorn; in &thorn;e lond, . ne er&thorn;e of &thorn;e lond al so,</L>
<L N="10">Ne &thorn;ole&thorn; no venim in &thorn;e lond . nei&yogh; hem beo ido;</L>
<L>No worm ne come&thorn; &thorn;er, . &thorn;at he nis anon lif les,</L>
<L>Bote alute schort euede, . &amp; &yogh;ut it is tail les.</L>
<L>Muche clannesse and muche god, . whose vnderstonde,<MILESTONE N="120" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vor &thorn;e loue of seint patrik . oure lord dude in &thorn;at londe.</L>
<L N="15">A god monnes schep was stole; . to seint patrik com tidinge;</L>
<L>He het, whose it hedde istole, . a&yogh;en hit to bringe.</L>
<L>&thorn;e gode mon het so ofte, . ac a&yogh;en com hit nou&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Am Rande :</I> Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>In an hei&yogh; day, as &thorn;e folk . to chirche was ibrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Seint patrik het, &yogh;if in &thorn;e chirche . ani mossel were</L>
<L N="20">Of &thorn;e schep, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> it scholde blete . among hem alle &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&thorn;o gan it blete in is wombe . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hedde &thorn;e schep istole,</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e men, &thorn;at it ne mi&yogh;te . no leng ben ihole.</L>
<L>Sore he was aschamed . &thorn;at men for &thorn;ef him knewe;</L>
<L>He bad milce and ore, . and bicom wel trewe.</L>
<L N="25">Now hadde seint patrik . awone, ofte ilome</L>
<L>To aloute to ech crois, . whar so he euer come.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ueber</I> crois <I>ist im Ms.</I> &dagger; <I>geschr</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>A day, as he wende aboute . prechinge in &thorn;e londe,</L>
<L>Seint patrik aloute to ech crois . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he sei&yogh; owhare stonde.</L>
<L>A crois &thorn;er stod, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> men sei&yogh;e, . ac he ne sei&yogh; it nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="30">&thorn;er fore he loutede not &thorn;er to . . men wondrede in here &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And ashte whi he loutede no&yogh;t . to &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> crois &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&thorn;is holi mon bi heol aboute . and ashte whare it were:<NOTE PLACE="foot">bi heol <I>st.</I> bi heold.</NOTE></L>
<L>He ne mi&yogh;te &thorn;is crois seo; . in gret &thorn;ou&yogh;t he stod.</L>
<L>Gret wonder hedde &thorn;e volk, . and wende he were wod.
<PB REF="00000220.tif" N="176"></L>
<L N="35">&thorn;o seide a vois to hem: . ne misbileue &yogh;e nou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>&thorn;ei&yogh; he ne mowe hit iseo, . ne wondre&thorn; in oure &thorn;ou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">oure = &yogh;oure, <I>vgl. V. 259.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Vor hit is vor mi sunne . &thorn;at mine bones ligge&thorn; here,</L>
<L>And mid &yogh;ow i speke, . &thorn;is holi mon to skere;</L>
<L>A sarzin ich was on er&thorn;e, . mi soule in helle is;</L>
<L N="40">Vor mine bones ligge&thorn; so nei&yogh;, . he si&thorn; not &thorn;e crois iwis.</L>
<L>Euere &thorn;e gode mon prechinde . &thorn;e contrei out sou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>A stude he fond bare, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> no fruit for&thorn; ne brou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>&thorn;au&yogh; me sewe and sette, . &thorn;er ne com for&thorn; non &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Seint patrik bad oure lord . tokninge, whi it were.</L>
<L N="45">In &thorn;e er&thorn;e mid is staf . he made a cerle aboute:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> cerle <I>st.</I> cercle.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> he made a cerle he made; <I>das 2.</I> he made <I>zu tilgen</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er bicom a deop put, . &thorn;at men hedden of gret doute.</L>
<L>&thorn;is godemon wondrede whi it was, . ac angel him sede:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> angel <I>fehlt</I> an.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;er was apurgatorie, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ech mon mi&yogh;te of drede;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> &thorn;at <I>mit Zeichen der Abk&uuml;rzung von</I> er <I>&uuml;ber</I> &thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Soulen weren &thorn;er inne ido, . here sunnes vorto bete</L>
<L N="50">&thorn;at heo ne betten not on er&thorn;e, . ar heo here lif lete;</L>
<L>And, were aman quik o&thorn;er ded . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er inne come,</L>
<L>He ne scholde habbe o&thorn;er purgatorie . ar &thorn;e day of dome,</L>
<L>Ac after he scholde to heuene, . &yogh;if he were god ifounde,</L>
<L>And al so, &yogh;if he lu&thorn;er were, . into helle grounde.</L>
<L N="55">Oure lord tok seint patrik a staf . wi&thorn; is owne honde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a staf <I>auch in Ms. Bodl. (u. Laud).</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at he fond wi&thorn; purgatorie, . iheried beo godes sonde.</L>
<L>In yrlonde is &yogh;et &thorn;at staf . wi&thorn; nobleie inow,</L>
<L>And vor relike iholde, . and elles were wow.</L>
<L>Seint patrik in &thorn;ulke stude, . as &thorn;is purgatorie is,</L>
<L N="60">Of religion bi gan an hous, . &thorn;at &yogh;ut stont iwis,</L>
<L>And chanons made &thorn;er, . as &yogh;et be&thorn; also.</L>
<L>&thorn;e put he lette vaste close, . &thorn;at nomon come &thorn;er to.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e chirch&yogh;ard &thorn;e put is, . toward &thorn;e est side,</L>
<L>Est vram &thorn;e hei&yogh;e weued, . as men schewe&thorn; wide.</L>
<L N="65">Walled hit is aboute, . and vaste loke &thorn;e &yogh;at;</L>
<L>&thorn;e prior wite&thorn; &thorn;e kei&yogh;e, . &thorn;at non come &thorn;er at.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> nom <I>st.</I> non.</NOTE></L>
<L>Biseint patrikes dai&yogh;e . men wende &thorn;er inne ilome,</L>
<L>And su&thorn;&thorn;e also moni on, . ac fewe a&yogh;en &thorn;er come.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ilke &thorn;at come a&yogh;en, . of &thorn;at heo sei&yogh;en, tolde,</L>
<L N="70">As hit is in &thorn;e hous iwrite . and priueliche iholde.</L>
<L>&thorn;e manere is of ech mon . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er inne went,</L>
<L>&thorn;at it beo to amende is sunne, . &yogh;if oure lord him grace sent.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e bischop of &thorn;e londe . he schal him vurst schriue,</L>
<L>And bidde leue to go &thorn;at wei, . to amende is liue.
<PB REF="00000222.tif" N="178"></L>
<L N="75">Ac &thorn;e bischop rat a&yogh;en, . and resons wole schewe,</L>
<L>And se&thorn; &thorn;at vele &thorn;ider go&thorn;, . ac a&yogh;en come&thorn; bote fewe.</L>
<L>&yogh;if &thorn;e mon be stable . of &thorn;at he ha&thorn; ibede,</L>
<L>&thorn;e bischop wole lettres make . to &thorn;e priour of &thorn;e stude.</L>
<L>&thorn;e priour wole eke rede . vorto change is &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="80">Ac, whanne he si&thorn; him studefast, . &thorn;at he nele leuen nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Mid gret procession . to &thorn;e put he wor&thorn; ibrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if me ne mai &thorn;ere . &yogh;ut change is &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Into chirche hi wolen him lede . &amp; setten him on kneo;</L>
<L>&thorn;ere he schal vif(t)ene dawes . in is orison beo.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> vifene.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="85">&thorn;e procession schal turne a&yogh;en, . as ri&yogh;t is to done,</L>
<L>And after &thorn;e fiftene dawes(!) . bringen him &thorn;ider eft sone.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Anders die and. Mss.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Bote he come in certein time a&yogh;en, . wi&thorn; gret deol and sore</L>
<L>Heo torne&thorn; a&yogh;an, &amp; siker be&thorn; . &thorn;at he ne come&thorn; na more.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> a&yogh;an <I>st.</I> a&yogh;en.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HJt bi fel bi king steuens day, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> now late was,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms. Eg. u. Bodl. haben hier eine Initiale.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="90">Of akni&yogh;t, &thorn;at het owein, . awel wonder cas.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e bischop to schrift . &thorn;at kni&yogh;t owein com,</L>
<L>And repentaunce of is sunne . &amp; deol and serwe nom.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bischop him gan to chide . vor &thorn;at he hedde mis do,</L>
<L>And seide, he was manne worst, . vorto sunge so;</L>
<L N="95">Me ne mi&yogh;te do him such wo, . &thorn;at he nere wor&thorn;i more.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kni&yogh;t mid sor herte . wep and si&yogh;te sore.</L>
<L>Whanne, he seide, icham monne worst . &amp; worst habbe ido,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e sunne &thorn;at grettest is . mest penaunce mot &thorn;er to,</L>
<L>Whanne among alle men . mest sunfol icham, alas,</L>
<L N="100">Strengest penaunce ichulle take . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> euere ifounde was:</L>
<L>Ichulle take godes grace . and in his name wende<MILESTONE N="121" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To seint patrikes purgatorie, . sende what god me sende.</L>
<L>Ou, beu frere, qua&thorn; &thorn;at bischop, . beo stille! whi seistou so?</L>
<L>Crist for bede &thorn;at &thorn;ou neuer . such folie ne do!</L>
<L N="105">Vnne&thorn;e come&thorn; ani a&yogh;en . &thorn;at &thorn;ider de&thorn; wende;</L>
<L>Nolde god &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;ou it dust, . bodi and soule to schende!</L>
<L>And wend into religion, . &amp; lef &thorn;er to &thorn;i liues ende:</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;i sunne bete, . such grace god wole &thorn;e sende.</L>
<L>Certes, sire, qua&thorn; &thorn;e kni&yogh;t, . &thorn;ow mi&yogh;t as wel beo stille,</L>
<L N="110">Vor ichulle &thorn;at dede do, . do god bi me is wille;</L>
<L>So muche as ichabbe iserued, . ine may habbe of wo;</L>
<L>&thorn;er fore sei what ischal, . vor siker ichulle it go.
<PB REF="00000224.tif" N="180"></L>
<L>&thorn;e bischop prechede him faste, . vorte change is &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Ac ate laste, &thorn;o he sai&yogh; . &thorn;at it was al for nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="115">To &thorn;e prior of &thorn;e stude . lettres he made sone,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he scholde bi him do, . as bi such was to done.</L>
<L>&thorn;e priour of &thorn;e stude him prechede vaste . &amp; seide resouns inowe,</L>
<L>&yogh;if he mi&yogh;te chaunge is &thorn;ou&yogh;t, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he &thorn;er of wi&thorn; drowe.</L>
<L>Ac al was for nou&yogh;t, . as sei&thorn;(!) ate nende:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> sei&thorn; <I>fehlt</I> hit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="120">He nolde for no&thorn;ing leue . &thorn;at perylous wey to wende.<NOTE PLACE="foot">g <I>in</I> no&thorn;ing <I>&uuml;berschr</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e priour him nom bi&thorn;e hond . and to chirche him brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&thorn;er efel adoun akneo . &amp; oure lordes grace bi sou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>In fastinge and in orisons . viftene ni&yogh;t he lay,</L>
<L>To bidde oure lordes grace; . &amp; &thorn;e viftene&thorn;e day,</L>
<L N="125">&thorn;e couent com abouten him, . &amp; o&thorn;er prestes al so</L>
<L>And clerkes, wi&thorn; procession, . &thorn;e seruise vorte do.</L>
<L>Vor him heo songen an hei&yogh; masse. &amp; on god crieden vaste,</L>
<L>Oure lordes vlesch and is blod . heo &yogh;euen him ate laste,</L>
<L>And sprengden him mid holi water, . &amp; here orisons sede.</L>
<L N="130">Wi&thorn; crois and wi&thorn; procession . to &thorn;e put heo gonnen him lede,</L>
<L>And hei&yogh;e songe &thorn;e letanie, . &amp; holi water bere,</L>
<L>&amp; alle godes halewen beden . &thorn;at heo is help were.</L>
<L>&thorn;e prior vnlek &thorn;e puttes dore . among hem echon.</L>
<L>Beufrere, eseide, her is &thorn;i wey . &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> woldest gon;</L>
<L N="135">&yogh;if &thorn;ow wolt do bi red, . &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;ou schalt wende</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er manere &thorn;i sunnes bete, . as god wole grace sende;</L>
<L>Vor vewe &thorn;er come&thorn; a&yogh;en . of hem &thorn;at wenden yn bifore,</L>
<L>Ac for tormens and for wo . lif &amp; soule for lore.</L>
<L>Certes, sire, qua&thorn; &thorn;e kni&yogh;t, . rede what &thorn;ow me rede,</L>
<L N="140">&thorn;e wei ich nime in godes name, . to amende mi mis dede;</L>
<L>Vor is loue &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> vs bou&yogh;te . bidde&thorn; vor me echon!</L>
<L>Lif &amp; soule i<SUP>c</SUP> him bitake . &amp; in is name yn gon.</L>
<L>He blessede him, &amp; &yogh;eode yn, . &amp; bitok vlesch and bon.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> bitok <I>fehlt</I> god.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e prior sprengde holi water, . &amp; lek &thorn;e dore anon.</L>
<L N="145">&thorn;is gode kni&yogh;t wende for&thorn;, . baldeliche and vaste,</L>
<L>Bi an holw wey vnder er&thorn;e, . on god is herte ecaste;</L>
<L>He ne sei&yogh; not vor derkhede, . ac nou&yogh;t he him agaste.</L>
<L>So longe, him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, &thorn;at e sai&yogh; . vair li&yogh;t ate laste;</L>
<L>&thorn;ideward ewende, so &thorn;at ecom . &thorn;ere nei&yogh;.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> &thorn;ideward <I>st.</I> &thorn;iderward; <I>auch 241</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="150">&thorn;e faireste feld &thorn;at mi&yogh;te beo . ate wei&yogh;es ende e sei&yogh;.</L>
<L>&thorn;er inne he wente murie; . amidde &thorn;e feld e fonde</L>
<L>&thorn;e nobleste halle &thorn;at mi&yogh;te beo . a whare in ani londe.</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t cler nas &thorn;e weder nou&yogh;t, . bote as it were nei&yogh; eue.</L>
<L>To bi holde &thorn;at noble werk, . astounde he gan bi leue;
<PB REF="00000226.tif" N="182"></L>
<L N="155">&thorn;e walles were lowe, . ac &thorn;er aboute iwis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>steht unten am Rande.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Cointe pilers &thorn;er weren, . as monkes cloistre is.</L>
<L>In he &yogh;ede a godes name, . &amp; sat al one an hei&yogh;,</L>
<L>And bi huld abouten . and &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> werk isei&yogh;.</L>
<L>As he bi huld &thorn;us aboute, . &thorn;er com yn at &thorn;e on ende</L>
<L N="160">Twelf men in white vestimens, . swi&thorn;e fair &amp; hende,</L>
<L>Heore croune vaire ischore, . &amp; vaire heo him grette,</L>
<L>And seten alle faire adoun, . &amp; &thorn;is kni&yogh;t bi hem sette.</L>
<L>&thorn;o spak on, &thorn;at was maister, . mildeliche and stille:</L>
<L>Beu frere, hered beo god, . &thorn;at sende &thorn;e such wille,</L>
<L N="165">And lete &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast bi gonne . &thorn;orw is grace wel ende!</L>
<L>Beu frere, now &thorn;ou wolt &thorn;is wey . vor &thorn;i sunne wende:</L>
<L>O&thorn;er &thorn;ou most beo studefast . and nou&yogh;t torne &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O&thorn;er &thorn;ou wor&thorn; al ilore . &amp; adeuelewey ibrou&yogh;t;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> ilorore.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vor, whanne we go&thorn; henne, . deueles lu&thorn;ere and &thorn;icke<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Die Reime sind umzustellen.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="170">Wolle&thorn; come aboute &thorn;e . in &thorn;is hous wel wicke,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Die Reime sind umzustellen.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And do &thorn;e tormens inowe, . &amp; bihoten &thorn;e wel more;</L>
<L>Joie heo wolle&thorn; bi hote &thorn;e, . &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt leuen here lore;</L>
<L>And heo mid bi heste . mowe &thorn;e ouer come,</L>
<L>Siker &thorn;ou wor&thorn; lif and soule . a deuele wei inome;</L>
<L N="175">&yogh;if &thorn;ou art stable in &thorn;ou&yogh;t . and in ih&umacr; dest &thorn;enche,</L>
<L>Ne vor biheste ne vor no wo . vram him neltou blenche,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou wor&thorn; quit of &thorn;i sunnes, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast euere iwrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou schalt seo &thorn;e ioie . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> gode soules be&thorn; inne ibrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e pine &thorn;at lu&thorn;ere men . habbe&thorn; for here misdede;</L>
<L N="180">Ac, in what wo &thorn;at &thorn;ou art in, . &thorn;ench on god, ich rede!</L>
<L>Whanne heo &thorn;e tormente&thorn;, . crie ih&umacr; milce and ore,</L>
<L>And, &yogh;if &thorn;ou beo studefast, . hi ne schule tormente &thorn;e na more;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>We bi take&thorn; &thorn;e ih&umacr; crist, . we rede&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> do oure lore.</L>
<L>&thorn;o nuste he war heo bicome. . he sat and si&yogh;te sore,</L>
<L N="185">Elinge he sat al one, . ecriede on godes mi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And armede him mid holi bedes, . a&yogh;en &thorn;e deuelen to fi&yogh;te;</L>
<L>On &thorn;e holi gost e criede, . &thorn;at he him ne scholde faile.</L>
<L>He lokede, whanne deuelen come, . him forte asaile.</L>
<L>He sat in godes name, . bataile vorte abide.<MILESTONE N="122" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="190">&thorn;er com a sori deolfol cri . abouten in eche side,</L>
<L>As al &thorn;e world to borste, . and, as him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, also:</L>
<L>&thorn;ei&yogh; alle &thorn;e bestes of &thorn;e world . to gadere weren ido</L>
<L>An as grisliche as heo mi&yogh;ten . alle &yogh;ellinge were,
<PB REF="00000228.tif" N="184"></L>
<L>Hi ne mi&yogh;te nou&yogh;t alle make . so grisliche a bere;</L>
<L N="195">&yogh;if his hope &amp; is herte . &thorn;e more in ih&umacr; nere,</L>
<L>He hedde wod bicome . and lore is wit for fere.</L>
<L>Heo comen &thorn;icke abouten him . &amp; grisliche &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&yogh;ellinge and grennynge . mid wel sori chere.</L>
<L>Belami, qua&thorn; on of hem, . &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast ari&yogh;t ido;</L>
<L N="200">We au&yogh;ten wel honure &thorn;e alle, . vor to vewe don so;</L>
<L>O&thorn;er wolle&thorn; abide, . vorte here lif be hem bi nome,</L>
<L>And &yogh;et hit is a&yogh;en here wille, . ar heo hidere come;</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;ou comest bi &thorn;i self, . &amp; wi&thorn; gode wille al so;</L>
<L>Wel au&yogh;te we &thorn;i wille &yogh;elden, . &amp; gret &thorn;onk &thorn;e do;</L>
<L N="205">Whan &thorn;ou hast bodi and soule . bitake vs liue,</L>
<L>Saun&yogh; faile we were vnkunde, . bote we it &yogh;olde bliue;</L>
<L>&yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt on er&thorn;e . ioie &yogh;et habbe more,</L>
<L>Vor &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> &thorn;us to vs art come . al bi &thorn;in owe lore,</L>
<L>Sikere vs &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;ou wolt . in oure seruise bileue,</L>
<L N="210">And we wolle&thorn; a&yogh;en &thorn;e lede, . ar it come eue;</L>
<L>&thorn;ow schalt habbe ioie inow, . in halle and in boure,</L>
<L>Vor non nis so murie &thorn;er . as &thorn;ilke &thorn;at be&thorn; oure;</L>
<L>Noble mon &thorn;ow schalt beo, . &amp; men schulen honure &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art ded and hider comest, . &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt fare as wel as we.</L>
<L N="215">&thorn;is kni&yogh;t &thorn;ou&yogh;te in ih&umacr; crist, . he nolde change is wille,</L>
<L>Vor &thorn;reting ne vor bi heste, . ac sat him euer stille.</L>
<L>&thorn;o he nolde grante nou&yogh;t . &thorn;at he wolde to hem wende,</L>
<L>Heo grenneden on him foule, . &amp; fuir heo gonnen tende.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kni&yogh;t heo bounden fot and honden, . &amp; in &thorn;e fuir him caste;</L>
<L N="220">Wi&thorn; irene hokes &amp; newles . heo to drowen him faste.</L>
<L>&thorn;is kni&yogh;t, &thorn;o he sei&yogh; nede, . loude criede anon:</L>
<L>Ih&umacr;, ih&umacr;, help me now, . &amp; schilde me vram mine fon!</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;o &thorn;is was seid, . &thorn;e fuir aqueinte ech spronge;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> spronge <I>st.</I> spronke.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e deuelen drowe him na more. . oure lord he gan to &thorn;onke,</L>
<L N="225">And &thorn;e hardiere he was, . &thorn;o he &thorn;is isei&yogh;,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e lasse &thorn;e deuelen dradde, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> weren him so nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>Grisliche &thorn;e schrewen &yogh;olle . &thorn;at hem failede here mi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Heo vlowen out of &thorn;e halle, . &amp; drowe mid hem &thorn;e kni&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Heo drowen him a&yogh;en &thorn;e grount . bo&thorn;e fet and honde,</L>
<L N="230">Swi&thorn;e fer aboute . into a gret wast londe.</L>
<L>So blak and derk it was, . &thorn;at he no&thorn;ing ne say</L>
<L>Bote deuelen &thorn;at him to drowe, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> were him &thorn;icke &amp; nei&yogh;(!).
<PB REF="00000230.tif" N="186"></L>
<L>Ac a softe wind &thorn;er was, . &thorn;at he herde vnne&thorn;e;</L>
<L>So scharp and cold it blew, . hit brou&yogh;te him to de&thorn;e;</L>
<L N="235">Hit wende &thorn;orw is herte . and &thorn;orw bodi al so,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> bodi <I>fehlt</I> is.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> him were leuere &thorn;an al &thorn;e world, . &amp; &thorn;e pine were ido.</L>
<L>&thorn;us heo drowen him, as him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, . ri&yogh;t for&thorn; est iwis,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e sonne arise&thorn;, . whan &thorn;e day lengest is.</L>
<L>&thorn;o heo comen, as him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, . ri&yogh;t to &thorn;e worldes ende,</L>
<L N="240">Heo tornden bi abrod valei&yogh;e, . &amp; sou&thorn;ward gonnen wende,</L>
<L>&thorn;ideward as &thorn;e sonne . at midwinter de&thorn; arise;</L>
<L>Wo was him for drawe . &amp; pined on alle wise.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;ou&yogh;te him &thorn;at he herde fer, . bifore him as it were,</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e deolfol cri . and swi&thorn;e reu&thorn;fol bere;</L>
<L N="245">Euer &thorn;e ner &thorn;at he com, . &thorn;e reulokere was &thorn;e cri;</L>
<L>So longe &thorn;at him &thorn;ou&yogh;te . &thorn;at heo weren &thorn;er bi.</L>
<L>&thorn;o comen heo in to a feld; . more ne mi&yogh;te non beo,</L>
<L>So long it was in eche side, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he ne mi&yogh;te non ende seo.</L>
<L>Of men and wimmen &thorn;is feld . was fol in eche side,</L>
<L N="250">&thorn;e wombe toward &thorn;e grounde . abrod isprad wel wide,</L>
<L>Vet and honden al abrod . to &thorn;e er&thorn;e faste ibounde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; nailes of yre, al furi, . ismite &thorn;orw to &thorn;e grounde.</L>
<L>&thorn;es gostes &thorn;us ipined were . wi&thorn; yrenes al of fure;</L>
<L>So deolfol cri heo maden, . &thorn;at it was deol to hure;</L>
<L N="255">Heo crieden merci deolfoliche, . ac me nolde non hem do;</L>
<L>Vor anguise heo gnowe &thorn;e er&thorn;e . &amp; here tonges al so.</L>
<L>Deuelen ourne aboute . vpe hem al to grounde,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; newles heo hem to drowe . wi&thorn; moni a dep wounde.</L>
<L>Alas, whi ne beo &yogh;e war, . oure sunnes her to bete,</L>
<L N="260">Ar &yogh;e come to purgatorie, . wi&thorn; lu&thorn;er gostes to mete?</L>
<L>Vor in purgatorie heo be&thorn; . as wel as in helle,</L>
<L>And wor&thorn;e&thorn; forte &thorn;e dai of dome, . telle what me telle.</L>
<L>Heo seiden : as &thorn;ou sist &thorn;ese men pined, . &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt al so,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t turne . and after vs do.</L>
<L N="265">&thorn;o he nolde in no manere, . to grounde heo him caste,</L>
<L>To turmenten him, as o&thorn;er weren, . &amp; to nailen him faste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac he criede to ih&umacr; crist, . &thorn;o him smart so sore:</L>
<L>&thorn;er nas non of hem &thorn;o, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> mi&yogh;te greuen him more.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e schrewen ne mi&yogh;te . here wille habbe &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="270">Heo drowen him into ano&thorn;er feld, . ful of more wo,</L>
<L>Of men and wimmen fol, . vpri&yogh;t sprad to &thorn;e grounde,
<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="188"></L>
<L>Vet and honden vpri&yogh;t . to &thorn;e er&thorn;e ibounde,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; furi nailes of yre . nailed vaste &thorn;er to;<MILESTONE N="123" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Eddren furi vpen hem sete, . and toden grete al so<NOTE PLACE="foot">vpen <I>st.</I> vpon. <I>Die and. Mss.</I> crapoudes <I>st.</I> toden.</NOTE></L>
<L N="275">Somme eddren hem bi clipte . so vaste al aboute,</L>
<L>&thorn;at hem &thorn;ou&yogh;te hem scholde berste, . so hei grunte(!) wi&thorn; oute;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem <I>vor</I> scholde <I>st.</I> heo.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Somme sete anowarde, . and here vlesch to gnowe,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; al furi te&thorn; . wombe &amp; breste to drowe;</L>
<L N="280">Summe bounde, somme gnowe, . &amp; somme stronge bite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e todeden, &thorn;at weren so foule, . vpe here hertes sete,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> todeden <I>st.</I> toden.</NOTE></L>
<L>And stongen in &thorn;e hertes . wi&thorn; here hertes grete.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>das 2</I><SUP>te</SUP> hertes <I>st.</I> wrottes <I>verschrieben</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lu&thorn;ere gostes ourne al so . abouten hem inowe,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; newles and wi&thorn; scorges . &thorn;e wrecches al to drowe.</L>
<L N="285">&thorn;e wrecche soules, &thorn;at weren . in &thorn;e pines brou&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot">in <I>&uuml;berschr</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Heo &yogh;ollen &amp; crieden deolfoliche, . &amp; hem help ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&thorn;e deueles nome &thorn;e kni&yogh;t, . &amp; wolden him pine also,</L>
<L>Ac, &thorn;o he criede on ih&umacr; crist, . heo brou&yogh;ten him not &thorn;er to.</L>
<L>&yogh;ut deuelen him nome . &amp; to &thorn;e &thorn;ridde veld him drowe.</L>
<L N="290">&thorn;er he sei&yogh; in tormens . wrecche gostes inowe</L>
<L>I preoned to &thorn;e er&thorn;e . &amp; ismite &thorn;orw out echon,</L>
<L>As &thorn;icke nailes in ech stude, . as &thorn;er mi&yogh;te stiken on,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Im An|fang fehlt wol</I> wi&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> me ne mi&yogh;te finde place . in here bodi so lute,</L>
<L>&thorn;at me ne mi&yogh;te for &thorn;icke nailes . afingres ende pute.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne, <I>auch in Ms. Bodl., ist zu tilgen.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="295">A smart wind to o&thorn;er wo . on hem blew wel faste,</L>
<L>&thorn;at hem &thorn;ou&yogh;te heo for barnden . &thorn;orw out mid eche blaste.</L>
<L>Deuelen orne aboute . vram on to o&thorn;er inowe,</L>
<L>And here vlesch to o&thorn;er wo . mid newles al to drowe.</L>
<L>So weren &thorn;e wrecches ipined . &amp; in tormens brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="300">As heo mi&yogh;ten heo crieden; : vnne&thorn;<SUP>c</SUP> me herde hem ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Vor heo weren so ouercome, . &thorn;at heo ne mi&yogh;ten vnne&thorn;e</L>
<L>Bringen out ani vois, . bote as aman vpe &thorn;e point of de&thorn;e:</L>
<L>Al in &thorn;e &thorn;rote heo crieden, . as here streng&thorn;e were bi nome</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mid muche pine, &amp; no wonder . &thorn;ei heo weren ouer come.</L>
<L N="305">Deuelen nomen &thorn;is kni&yogh;t . and to grounde him caste;</L>
<L>Heo sworen, bote he tornde is &thorn;ou&yogh;t, . heo wolden him naile faste.
<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="190"></L>
<L>Ac he criede on ih&umacr; crist, . and nempnede is name;</L>
<L>&thorn;e deuelen nadden no power . to don him more schame.</L>
<L>Heo nomen &amp; drowen him . in &thorn;e fer&thorn;e felde,</L>
<L N="310">Of brimston al berninge, . hei&yogh;e sprong &thorn;e spelde.</L>
<L>Ech pine &thorn;at mi&yogh;te beo . in &thorn;ilke felde he sei&yogh;:</L>
<L>Somme wi&thorn; irene cheines, . al furi, henge an hei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Somme bi arme, somme bi fet, bi &thorn;e necke mani on,</L>
<L>And henge in strong fuir . of pich and brimston;</L>
<L N="315">Sume hunge bi hokes, . iput in ei&thorn;er ei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And &thorn;orw &thorn;e &thorn;rote somme . weren ihonged hei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Somme &thorn;orw &thorn;e derne limes, . &amp; somme &thorn;orw &thorn;e tete;</L>
<L>Hem were leuer &thorn;an al &thorn;e world, . here lif to lete;</L>
<L>Somme on gredirens of yren . irosted weren al so:</L>
<L N="320">Summe as gees in spites, . &thorn;orw out hem ido,</L>
<L>Somme lei&yogh;en vpard, . &yogh;eninde wel faste,</L>
<L>Deuelen wellinge led and bras . in here hei (!) caste.</L>
<L>He ne mi&yogh;te no pine &thorn;enche, . &thorn;at he ne sei&yogh; &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he sei&yogh; monie &thorn;er . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he knew on er&thorn;e here.</L>
<L N="325">Deuelen him casten a doun . among &thorn;e o&thorn;ere echon,</L>
<L>Ac he criede on ih&umacr; crist, . &amp; deliuered was anon.</L>
<L>&yogh;ut deueles &thorn;is kni&yogh;t . to ano&thorn;er place drowe.</L>
<L>&thorn;er inne he sei&yogh; agrisliche whel . wi&thorn; longe spoken inowe,</L>
<L>&thorn;e on ende toward &thorn;e grounde, . &thorn;e o&thorn;er vp an hei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="330">Aboute was fol of pikes, . as he &thorn;ere isei&yogh;.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> was <I>fehlt</I> hit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ese hokes &amp; &thorn;es pikes . weren riuen al so</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wrecche gostes also (!), . &thorn;er on weren ido.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Statt</I> also <I>haben die and. Mss.</I> aboute. <I>Vor</I> &thorn;er on <I>fehlt</I> &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al berninge was &thorn;e wheol, . &amp; stinkinge of brimston;</L>
<L>&thorn;e gostes &thorn;at &thorn;er on were . berninge were echon.</L>
<L N="335">&thorn;e deuelen wenden for&thorn; . &amp; hokes &thorn;eron caste</L>
<L>In ei&thorn;er side, and wheol . turnde aboute so vaste,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> wheol <I>fehlt</I> &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e gostes &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;eron honge . nou&yogh;t heo ne sei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>So vaste turnde &thorn;e wheol . aboute(!) berninge lei&yogh;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> aboute <I>fehlt</I> bote. <I>Ms. scheinbar</I> bei&yogh;e <I>st.</I> lei&yogh;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac deol foliche heo crieden . &amp; &yogh;olle ech in is ende.</L>
<L N="340">Allas, whi nelle men beo war, . ar heo henne wende?</L>
<L>Her heo mid lute pine . mi&yogh;ten beten here mis dede,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ere heo schulen deore abugge, . alas, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> wrechede.</L>
<L>Vendes nomen &thorn;is kni&yogh;t . &amp; on &thorn;e wheol him caste,</L>
<L>And mid o&thorn;er gostes him turnde aboute vaste;</L>
<L N="345">He criede on ih&umacr; crist, . and deliuered was anon.</L>
<L>&thorn;e deuelen stoden &amp; him bihelde . mid dreri mod echon.
<PB REF="00000236.tif" N="192"></L>
<L>&yogh;ut heo nome bitterliche . &amp; fer&thorn;ere him ladde,</L>
<L>Heo harleden him for&thorn;, . &amp; loude &yogh;olle and gradde.</L>
<L>A gret hous he sei&yogh; stonde, : long and brod inow;</L>
<L N="350">&thorn;e stench &amp; hete, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er out com, . him &thorn;ou&yogh;te almest him slow.</L>
<L>He wi&thorn; stod, &amp; nolde is &thorn;onkes . vor stench go no ner.</L>
<L>Vor&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt, &thorn;e deuelen seide, . &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> ne schalt abiden her;</L>
<L>A ba&thorn; it is &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> sist, . &thorn;er inne &thorn;ou schalt beo</L>
<L>And ba&thorn;ie mid o&thorn;ere &thorn;ere, . &thorn;ou ne schalt not vleo.</L>
<L N="355">&thorn;e gostes &thorn;at &thorn;er inne were, . deofoliche heo criede</L>
<L>And loude, as he herde, . abouten in eche side.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kni&yogh;t mid deueles . into &thorn;is hous com.</L>
<L>Of tormen &thorn;at he &thorn;er sei&yogh; . gret &yogh;eme he nom;</L>
<L>Vor vol of puttes &amp; of diches . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hous wi&thorn; inne was,</L>
<L N="360">And al fol of tormens, . empti non &thorn;er nas:</L>
<L>He weren fol of well(i)nge led, . and of brimston,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> wellnge <I>st.</I> wellinge.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="124" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of bras, and of o&thorn;er tormens, . berninge euer vchon.</L>
<L>Wrecche gostes &thorn;er inne he sei&yogh;, . turmens tilde so hei&yogh;e:<NOTE PLACE="foot">hei&yogh;e <I>mit unorgan.</I> h, <I>vgl. v. 322.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Somme al aboue &thorn;e heued, . &amp; somme to &thorn;e hei&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="365">Somme to &thorn;e nese, somme to &thorn;e mou&thorn;, . &amp; summe to &thorn;e swere,</L>
<L>And somme to &thorn;e brestes, . heo bou&yogh;ten here sunnes dere,</L>
<L>Somme to nauele, . and somme dounere more,</L>
<L>And somme to &thorn;e kneo, . heo crieden and wepten sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now &thorn;ou sist, &thorn;e deuelen seden, . whoder &thorn;ou schalt gon,</L>
<L N="370">Bote &thorn;ou ano&thorn;er speke . &amp; to vs torne anon.</L>
<L>Heo casten him in a put; . on ih&umacr; anon he criede,</L>
<L>And com vp al sound, . him ne luste no leng abide.</L>
<L>&thorn;e fendes in grete wra&thorn;&thorn;e . harleden vor&thorn;ere more<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlt</I> him <I>nach</I> harleden.</NOTE></L>
<L>And brou&yogh;ten him vpon agret hul, . ful of sorwe and sore.</L>
<L N="375">He bi huld al aboute, . &thorn;o he com vp an hei&yogh;;</L>
<L>Him wondrede of so fele gostes . &thorn;at he &thorn;er isei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle &thorn;at he sei&yogh; ra&thorn;ere . &thorn;er a&yogh;en no&yogh;t nere;</L>
<L>Vpe here ton heo seten i clu&yogh;t, . &amp; quakeden for fere.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e sou&thorn; half of &thorn;e hul . a dep water was &amp; lowe,</L>
<L N="380">&thorn;at voule stank &amp; caldere was . &thorn;an ani ys o&thorn;er snowe;</L>
<L>A nor&thorn;ere wind &thorn;er blew, . him &thorn;ou&yogh;te is vlesch rende.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlt</I> &thorn;at <I>vor</I> him.</NOTE></L>
<L>Euere sete &thorn;e gostes . &amp; a&yogh;en &thorn;e wind hem wende,</L>
<L>And quakeden vaste . vor drede &amp; pine stronge,</L>
<L>And abide as who sei&yogh; (!) time, . &thorn;e de&thorn; vorte afonge.</L>
<L N="385">Lo, qua&thorn; a foul fend, . &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> nost not what &thorn;is is;</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t turne, . &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt wite iwis.
<PB REF="00000238.tif" N="194"></L>
<L>He nadde bote &thorn;at word sed, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er ne com awind blowe</L>
<L>And smot alle &thorn;e gostes . into &thorn;e water al lowe.</L>
<L>&thorn;e nor&thorn;erne wind hem blew adoun, . alle mid one blaste,</L>
<L N="390">&thorn;e gostes &amp; &thorn;e kni&yogh;t . a midde &thorn;e water caste.</L>
<L>More pine ne mi&yogh;te beo . of chele and of stenche,</L>
<L>&thorn;an &thorn;e gostes &thorn;er hedde, . &thorn;er ne mi&yogh;te non ablenche.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e kni&yogh;t &thorn;is stronge pine . of &thorn;is water felde,</L>
<L>He gan to crie on ih&umacr; crist, . &thorn;at failede him wel selde:</L>
<L N="395">Anon wi&thorn; oute lette out of &thorn;e water edrow.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlt . nach der Halbz.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Ac &thorn;e gostes bi leuede &thorn;er in wo and serwe inow,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlt . nach der Halbz.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Vor in &thorn;e water, so colde, . &amp; so stinkinge al so,</L>
<L>&thorn;e gostes swommen vp &amp; doun, . here wo was neuer ido.</L>
<L>Deuelen orne on &thorn;e water, . as men do&thorn; on londe,</L>
<L N="400">And, whanne ani clambrede vp . mid vet and mid honde,</L>
<L>Anon heo drowen hem adoun,.&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er ne mi&yogh;te ascape non;</L>
<L>&thorn;er was wo and serwe inow . among hem echon.</L>
<L>&yogh;ut &thorn;e deuelen wenden for&thorn;, . &amp; &thorn;is kni&yogh;t heo nome</L>
<L>And drowe him in to astude, . &thorn;er heo nou&yogh;t er ne come.</L>
<L N="405">Heo comen and stoden ouer aput, . wid &amp; dep inow;</L>
<L>Berninge smoke, &thorn;at voule stonk, . out of &thorn;at put drow,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e kni&yogh;t vnne&thorn;e stod . vor sori stench ney.</L>
<L>Wrecche gostes vpe &thorn;e put . in &thorn;at smoke he sey</L>
<L>Vlen vp and doun, berninge, . as sparkles do&thorn; of fure,</L>
<L N="410">And in to &thorn;e put wenden a&yogh;en, . whan heo ne mi&yogh;ten no leng dure.</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he was nei&yogh; ouercome . vor &thorn;e blast &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er of drow,</L>
<L>&thorn;er bi he wuste &thorn;at in &thorn;e ground . was wo and sorwe inow.</L>
<L>&thorn;e deuelen asshden &thorn;e kni&yogh;t: . &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;e her of wonder,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e swartnesse(!)&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> her blowe&thorn;, . &amp; what beo her vnder?</L>
<L N="415">In &thorn;is put is oure woning, . vor helle &thorn;er vnder is,</L>
<L>And, for &thorn;ou art come hider, . her &thorn;ou schalt wone iwis,</L>
<L>Vor, who &thorn;at serue&thorn; vs wel, . hider he schal wende,</L>
<L>And, be &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> her inne brou&yogh;t, . &thorn;ou wor&thorn; wi&thorn; outen ende;</L>
<L>&thorn;er fore torn &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t . &amp; do vs here manrede,</L>
<L N="420">And &thorn;e wei as &thorn;ou come . al saf we schulen &thorn;e lede;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e tit on er&thorn;e al &thorn;i lif . richesse &amp; ioie al so,</L>
<L>Vor we &thorn;e schulen finde, . as ri&yogh;t is &thorn;at we do.</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;o he vor sok here bi heste, . as he hedde do lome,</L>
<L>Heo smiten doun in &thorn;is put, . &amp; &thorn;e kni&yogh;t mid hem nome.</L>
<L N="425">&thorn;e deppore &thorn;at heo &thorn;er inne come,.&thorn;e braddore &thorn;e put was,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> al &thorn;e wo &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he er sey . &thorn;er a&yogh;en no&yogh;t nas.</L>
<L>Of stench &amp; of o&thorn;er wo . &thorn;is kni&yogh;t was so ouercome,</L>
<L>&thorn;at is wit toward ih&umacr; crist . him was almest binome;
<PB REF="00000240.tif" N="196"></L>
<L>So muche pine nas neuere, . him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, as he felde,</L>
<L N="430">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he was vpe &thorn;e point . &thorn;e gost vorte &yogh;elde.</L>
<L>Ac oure lord in is wo . grace him &yogh;af ate laste,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he &thorn;ou&yogh;te on ih&umacr; crist . &amp; on him criede vaste.</L>
<L>A smoke &thorn;er com out smite, . and mid stronge blaste</L>
<L>&thorn;is kni&yogh;t aboue &thorn;e put, . &amp; moni gostes, caste;</L>
<L N="435">&thorn;e kni&yogh;t wirlede in &thorn;e wing, : as sparclen do&thorn;, wide,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> wing <I>st.</I> wind.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ate laste he li&yogh;te a doun . aboue &thorn;e put biside.</L>
<L>&thorn;er he stod and bihuld . as man &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> witles were,</L>
<L>Vor pine &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he hadde . he nuste how he com &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&thorn;o he hedde longe stonde . &amp; biholde aboute,</L>
<L N="440">&thorn;er com vp of &thorn;e put . od deuelen a gret route,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> od <I>st.</I> of, <I>durch Assimilation?</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And alle abouten him stode, . al newe as &thorn;ei&yogh; e were;</L>
<L>He sei&yogh; hem, as him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, . neuer bote &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Heo bi hulden him grisliche, . &amp; grenneden al a boute.</L>
<L>Whi stanstou &thorn;er? heo seiden, . com for&thorn; to oure route!</L>
<L N="445">What, tolden oure felawes . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e put of helle was &thorn;is?</L>
<L>Hit nis not so, ac &thorn;ou schalt . wite whare it is;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Or felawes lowen, . &thorn;is nis not &thorn;e put of helle,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt &thorn;ider wi&thorn; vs, . as so&thorn; as we &thorn;e telle.</L>
<L>Vendes harleden him for&thorn;, . wo was him to drawe:<MILESTONE N="125" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="450">Him were leuere &thorn;an ani &thorn;ing, . he were of lif dawe.</L>
<L>So heo comen to awater, . dep and brod inow;</L>
<L>A strong mist, &thorn;at stonk voule, . out of &thorn;e water drow</L>
<L>Of brimston &amp; of o&thorn;er wo, . such stench he neuer sei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Mid alle &thorn;e pine of &thorn;e world . he mi&yogh;te stonde &thorn;er nei&yogh;.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> he <I>fehlt</I> ne.</NOTE></L>
<L N="455">A brugge was ouer &thorn;e water, . smallere mi&yogh;te non beo;</L>
<L>&thorn;e smoke was so &thorn;icke, . vnne&thorn;e he mi&yogh;te it seo.</L>
<L>Lo, seide &thorn;e deuelen, . we sigge&thorn; &thorn;e iwis</L>
<L>&thorn;at vnder &thorn;is depe water . &thorn;e put of helle is;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou schalt iwite, . vor&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt anon<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> And <I>fehlt</I> &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L N="460">And ouer &thorn;is swete water . on &thorn;at brugge gon;</L>
<L>We &thorn;e schulle&thorn; sende awind, . amidde &thorn;e to caste,</L>
<L>And oure felawes bi ne&thorn;e . schulen &thorn;e holden vaste</L>
<L>And drawe &thorn;e wi&thorn; hem . to helle grounde anon;</L>
<L>Cum for&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt . vpe &thorn;e brugge gon.</L>
<L N="465">Heo nomen &thorn;e kni&yogh;t anon . &amp; to &thorn;e brugge drowe,</L>
<L>And bede him go &thorn;er on . wi&thorn; wrecchede inowe.</L>
<L>&thorn;reo &thorn;inges lu&thorn;ere inow . on &thorn;is brugge were:
<PB REF="00000242.tif" N="198"></L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> on was &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> it was so hei&yogh;, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> vnne&thorn;e me mi&yogh;te for fere</L>
<L>&thorn;er vpe go for hei&yogh; . to habbe &thorn;at grisli si&yogh;te;<NOTE PLACE="foot">for hei&yogh;, <I>mit unorgan</I>. h, = for eie <I>vor Furcht</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="470">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> o&thorn;er &thorn;at (it) was so narw, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> vnne&thorn;e me mi&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> o&thorn;er <I>fehlt</I> was, <I>nach</I> &thorn;at : it.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er vpe setten afot, . &thorn;at he ne felle anon;</L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;ridde &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> heo was so slider, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> me ne mi&yogh;te &thorn;er on gon,</L>
<L>Bote he slide and felle, . so wis neuer he nere.</L>
<L>&thorn;ese &thorn;inges brou&yogh;ten . &thorn;e kni&yogh;t in grete fere:</L>
<L N="475">Narw it was, slider, and hei&yogh;; . how so me euer telle,</L>
<L>&yogh;if he slide bi ani side, . he fulle into helle.</L>
<L>&thorn;er vpon he was brou&yogh;t . &amp; mad &thorn;er on to gon.</L>
<L>Such drede, as him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, . nadde neuer mon non.</L>
<L>Ac he &thorn;ou&yogh;te on ih&umacr; crist, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ofte him sauede er,</L>
<L N="480">He criede on is holi name, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he him holpe &thorn;er.</L>
<L>He &yogh;eode for&thorn; baldeliche, . &amp; &thorn;e innore &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ecom,</L>
<L>&thorn;e hardiore he was, . &amp; &thorn;e betere herte he nom,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e braddore was is (wei). . so longe vor&thorn; he &yogh;eode:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> is <I>fehlt</I> wei. <I>Die Verse</I> 485&mdash;567 <I>fehlen im Ms. Bodl. 779</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hit wax so brod, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er mi&yogh;te . gon acart for nede,</L>
<L N="485">And so longe &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> twei cartes mi&yogh;ten . meten wel inow.</L>
<L>&thorn;is kni&yogh;t wel baldeliche . vor&thorn; as maister him drow.</L>
<L>Deuelen stoden bi ne&thorn;e . and sei&yogh;e him vaste gon.</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;e wo &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> heo him duden . him ouer com not on.</L>
<L>Hoe &thorn;ou&yogh;ten, it was for nou&yogh;t . after to honti more;</L>
<L N="490">Grisliche heo gonnen &yogh;elle, . heo crieden &amp; wepten sore.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e &yogh;ellinge &thorn;at heo made . he hedde grettore fere,</L>
<L>&thorn;an of al &thorn;e o&thorn;er pines, . so grisliche was &thorn;e bere.</L>
<L>Neules &amp; hokes heo nome . &amp; to him casten an hei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Ac non mi&yogh;te him touche, . ne non come him nei&yogh;.</L>
<L N="495">So &thorn;at al saf wi&thorn; ioie . ouer &thorn;e water he drow.</L>
<L>Deuelen were bi hinde . wi&thorn; serwe &amp; sori inow;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heo letten him go for&thorn;, . &amp; fondeden him na more,</L>
<L>And hulden hem ouer come, . &amp; &thorn;at hem of &thorn;ou&yogh;te sore.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kni&yogh;t wende al saf, . &thorn;at he er deore abou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="500">And &thorn;onkede &yogh;erne ih&umacr; . &thorn;at heo him ne siwede nou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&thorn;e water he passede wel, . &amp; vor&thorn; is wei nom;</L>
<L>&thorn;e contrei him &thorn;ou&yogh;te murie . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he ouer com;</L>
<L>&thorn;e vor&thorn;ere &thorn;at he wente, . &thorn;e more ioie he sei&yogh;.</L>
<L>So longe &thorn;at he sei&yogh; awal, . swi&thorn;e noble and hei&yogh;;</L>
<L N="505">Such werk nas neuer sei&yogh;e, . him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, as &thorn;at was;</L>
<L>A noble &yogh;at he sei&yogh; &thorn;er on, . noblere neuer non nas;
<PB REF="00000244.tif" N="200"></L>
<L>&thorn;e &yogh;at schinede bri&yogh;te, . gold as it were,</L>
<L>ffol of preciouse stones, . &thorn;at none richere nere.</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, ar he &thorn;ider com, . his wei longe laste.</L>
<L N="510">&thorn;o he com alutel ner, . he stod &amp; bihuld vaste.</L>
<L>&thorn;e &yogh;at opnede a&yogh;en him, . &amp; mid &thorn;at selue dede</L>
<L>&thorn;er sprong out aswete smel, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> wide gan to sprede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, in al &thorn;e world . such spices nere</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> suc swetnesse mi&yogh;ten &yogh;eue, . as &thorn;at bre&thorn; &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="515">In such ioie him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he was, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP>, &thorn;ei&yogh; ehedde be brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>In al &thorn;e wo &thorn;at he sei&yogh; euer, . hit ne scholde him greue nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>In he bihuld ate &yogh;ate, . &thorn;o he com &thorn;er nei&yogh;:</L>
<L>More clernesse ne mi&yogh;te beo, : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, &thorn;an e sei&yogh;.</L>
<L>As he wolde in wende, . a&yogh;en him &thorn;er com gon</L>
<L N="520">A prosession fair inow, . of noble men echon,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; crois and wi&thorn; tapres, . wi&thorn; baners swi&thorn;e clere,</L>
<L>&thorn;at volk bihinde reuested, . euer vch bi is fere:</L>
<L>Bischops &amp; erchedeknes, . monkes &amp; eke frere,</L>
<L>And ech in &thorn;at abit . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he werede on er&thorn;e here.</L>
<L N="525">Mid &thorn;e meste ioie &thorn;at mi&yogh;te be . &thorn;is kni&yogh;t heo gonnen afonge,</L>
<L>And him yn mid ioie nome . of solas &amp; of songe.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e song was ido, . to him sone &thorn;er come</L>
<L>Twei&yogh;e, as heo maistres were, . &amp; bi &thorn;e hond him nome,</L>
<L>Heo welcomeden him faire, . &amp; &thorn;onkeden oure lord faste,</L>
<L N="530">&thorn;at &yogh;af him such bileue, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> so studefastliche laste.</L>
<L>Heo ladden him to schewe . &thorn;e lond fer &amp; ney:</L>
<L>So muche clernesse and ioie . him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he neuer sei&yogh;;<MILESTONE N="126" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As &thorn;e sonne binime&thorn; &thorn;e li&yogh;t . of &thorn;e candel at midday,</L>
<L>Also bi nom &thorn;e sonne lem . &thorn;e li&yogh;t &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he &thorn;er say.</L>
<L N="535">So muche &thorn;at place was, . &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te non ende se:</L>
<L>A meri mede wi&thorn; floures, swettore mi&yogh;te non be,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlt . nach der Halbz.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Tren al so wi&thorn; fruit, . &thorn;at smellede swete inow.</L>
<L>So gret swetnesse aboute . of ech place &thorn;er drow,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;er wi&thorn; oute ech mete, . him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, euer mo</L>
<L N="540">He mi&yogh;te euer libbe wi&thorn; ioie, . &yogh;if he mi&yogh;te &thorn;er among go.</L>
<L>Hit was euer iliche li&yogh;t, . &amp; euere &thorn;er was day.</L>
<L>So muche folk in o place . neuer he ne say;</L>
<L>Ech companie &thorn;er . murie to o&thorn;er drow</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; song &amp; wi&thorn; melodie . &amp; o&thorn;er ioie inow,</L>
<L N="545">&thorn;at ech of o&thorn;er mi&yogh;te . &thorn;e more ioie afonge.</L>
<L>Al mi&yogh;ti god heo herieden . ofte in here songe.</L>
<L>And, as somm sterre bri&yogh;tere . &thorn;an ano&thorn;er is,</L>
<L>Al so of hem somme schinede . bri&yogh;tere &thorn;an an o&thorn;er iwis;
<PB REF="00000246.tif" N="202"></L>
<L>Ak he &thorn;at derkest was, . him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, was more cler</L>
<L N="550">And bri&yogh;tere &thorn;an ani gold . &thorn;at he sei euer er.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlen 4 Verse, s. Ms. Laud.</I></NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Somme hadden crounen of gold . on &thorn;e hed ido,</L>
<L>Somme in honde beren . &yogh;erden of golde also.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;onkeden ih&umacr; crist, . &thorn;at studefast herte him sende,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e kni&yogh;t mid no pine . is herte ne wende.</L>
<L N="555">Echone &thorn;o for him . in &thorn;e more ioie were.</L>
<L>He bi huld &thorn;at ioie, . as &thorn;ei no wit in him nere.</L>
<L>&thorn;o bi gan agret maistere . vndo is mou&thorn; softe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> meiste <I>mit der Abk&uuml;rzung f&uuml;r</I> er.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; welcomede him faire, . &amp; &thorn;onkede oure lord ofte,</L>
<L>&thorn;at such &thorn;ou&yogh;t him hedde send, . &amp; such herte al so,</L>
<L N="560">&thorn;at he ne changede no&yogh;t . vor al &thorn;at him was do.</L>
<L>Beu frere, ihered be god, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e ha&thorn; hider ibrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And among alle &thorn;ine fon . so stude fast were of &thorn;ou&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> And <I>fehlt wol</I> &thorn;at &thorn;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e pine of sunfol men . fonded &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast inow;</L>
<L>&thorn;ine sunnes be&thorn; alle ibet, . vor elles it were wow;</L>
<L N="565">&thorn;ow mi&yogh;t here somdel seo, . &thorn;at &thorn;ou wilnest more,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ioie of gode soulen, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> come&thorn; to milce &amp; ore.</L>
<L>&thorn;is place, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> we inne be&thorn;, . &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> ne knowest nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Hit is er&thorn;liche paradis, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> adam was inne brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Her inne he was ipult, . ac su&thorn;&thorn;e for his mis dede</L>
<L N="570">I cast he was out vram henne . in alle wrechede;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e ioie, &thorn;at her is, . he hedde to is wille,</L>
<L>Ac, &thorn;o he was henne idriue, . hit nas not wor&thorn; afille.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e wrechede we be&thorn; kend, . &amp; of is sunfol blet come,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;at vs is bi godes grace . &thorn;orw godes grace(!) binome.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;orw godes grace <I>st.</I> &thorn;orw oure cristendom <I>verschrieben</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="575">And after oure cristendom . &thorn;e sunnes &thorn;at (we) wrou&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> wrou&yogh;te <I>fehlt</I> we.</NOTE></L>
<L>On er&thorn;e o&thorn;er in purgatorie . we it wel deore abou&yogh;te:</L>
<L>Vor we alle, as &thorn;ou sist, . &thorn;er for&thorn; hider come,</L>
<L>And oure sunnes &thorn;er bette, . &amp; harde penaunce nome,</L>
<L>We neren not elles her; . as god bi&thorn;e it is;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="580">And alle &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> &thorn;er isei&yogh;e . hider schulle&thorn; iwis,</L>
<L>Ac non not how longe . his bileuing is;</L>
<L>Ac, whose in er&thorn;e frendes ha&thorn;, . &thorn;e bet efare&thorn; iwis,
<PB REF="00000248.tif" N="204"></L>
<L>Vor mid massen, &amp; gode bedes, . &amp; mid almesdede</L>
<L>Me mai here pine alegge . &amp; &thorn;er of hem lede.</L>
<L N="585">Whan ani hider come&thorn;, . a&yogh;en him we wende&thorn; echon,</L>
<L>As we come a&yogh;en &thorn;e, . &amp; lede&thorn; him anon.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> him <I>fehlt</I> in.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac non of vs nis wur&thorn;e . &yogh;ut to heuene wende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> wende <I>fehlt</I> to; <I>so auch Ms. Bodl.</I>; <I>vgl.</I> v. 658.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne non not whanne oure lord . after him wole sende:</L>
<L>Ech &thorn;at to heuene schal . &thorn;orw purgatorie mot,</L>
<L N="590">And su&thorn;&thorn;e to er&thorn;liche paradis, . &thorn;er we be&thorn;, ichot;</L>
<L>Vor &thorn;is (is) oure eritage, . we weren wrou&yogh;t &thorn;er to,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> &thorn;is <I>fehlt</I> is.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vorte oure furste fader agulte; . &amp;, &yogh;if he nedde mis do,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> agulte <I>fehlt</I> it.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here we scholden habbe be bore, . &amp; liued oure lif also,</L>
<L>Vorte oure lord vs wolde . in more ioie habbe ido.</L>
<L N="595">Ac, whanne men be&thorn; out cast, . her for&thorn; heo moten wende</L>
<L>A&yogh;enward toward heuene, . after here liues ende.</L>
<L>Ac al &thorn;e ioie, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> her is, . amounte&thorn; not iwis</L>
<L>A&yogh;en &thorn;e leste ioie in heuene; . wel muche &thorn;e meste is.</L>
<L>Of heuene &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt somwhat seo . in aplace her nei&yogh;.</L>
<L N="600">He ladde him on an hei&yogh; hul, . &amp; bad him loke an hei&yogh;,</L>
<L>And aschte of what colour . heuene were &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>He seide: it &thorn;ou&yogh;te as gold, . &thorn;at wellinge were.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei seiden: &thorn;at it was . &thorn;e &yogh;at of heuene,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlen in Ms. Laud und Bodl.</I>; <I>sie sind Zusatz.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er &thorn;e soulen, &thorn;at gode weren, . scholden in fol euene;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlen in Ms. Laud und Bodl.</I>; <I>sie sind Zusatz.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="605">&thorn;at is &thorn;e &yogh;at of paradis, . &thorn;at wi&thorn; oute heuene is.</L>
<L>&thorn;e o&thorn;er seide: &thorn;is is &thorn;e wei . &thorn;at ge&thorn; to heuene blis.</L>
<L>Ech dai somme of purgatorie . come&thorn; hider vs to,</L>
<L>And somme of vs ech day . to heuene went al so,</L>
<L>So &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> we waxe&thorn; ech day . &amp; wanie&thorn; &thorn;er to;</L>
<L N="610">We nuten of vs whoch is next, . bote as god wol haue do.</L>
<L>Ech day, while we be&thorn; her, . oure lord vs fet ene</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; delicious mete of heuene, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> swete is &amp; clene;</L>
<L>What &thorn;ilk mete is, . ar &thorn;ow henne wende,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; vs &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt wite, . whan god it wole sende.</L>
<L N="615">Nadde he bote &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> word seid, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;er ne com a li&yogh;t</L>
<L>A maner bre&thorn; of heuene, . &thorn;at schinede swi&thorn;e bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ouer spradde al &thorn;at lond, . &amp; a cler leme &thorn;er wi&thorn; oute;<MILESTONE N="127" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vpe ech hed it li&yogh;te . clerore &yogh;et &thorn;an aboute,</L>
<L>And vpe &thorn;e kni&yogh;t eke . &thorn;e leme smot anon,</L>
<L N="620">&thorn;orw ech lime, him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, . &amp; &thorn;orw ech li&thorn; gan gon,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> in so muche delit and ioie, . him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, neuer e nas.
<PB REF="00000250.tif" N="206"></L>
<L>He stod, as he were inome, . he nuste whare ewas,</L>
<L>Ne, &yogh;if he were quic o&thorn;er ded, . bote in meting as he were.</L>
<L>Lord, muche is &thorn;i mi&yogh;te, . as &thorn;o was sene &thorn;ere!</L>
<L N="625">Hit ne laste bote astounde, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e leome ne wi&thorn; drow;<NOTE PLACE="foot">541-625 <I>fehlen in Ms. Ashm.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Ac, &thorn;ei&yogh; it lute while laste, . heo weren ful inow.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kni&yogh;t stod &amp; bihuld, . &amp; is stat vnderstod;</L>
<L>So fol he was of &thorn;e leme, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> delicious was &amp; god:</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, &thorn;ei&yogh; he liuede euer . &amp; no mete ne ete,</L>
<L N="630">He schulde to no mete luste . vor &thorn;e lem so swete.</L>
<L>Lo, seide &thorn;is maister . &thorn;at him schewede &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>Now &thorn;ou hast somdel isei&yogh;e . of oure lordes grace:</L>
<L>Of pine what wrecche gostes . habbe&thorn; for here misdede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> of of pine.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of &thorn;e ioie &thorn;at gode soules . in paradis do&thorn; lede,</L>
<L N="635">And somdel of &thorn;e ioie . &thorn;at in heuene is;</L>
<L>Eche day we be&thorn; ones fed . mid such ioie &amp; blis,</L>
<L>&thorn;anne we be&thorn; folle inow, . vorte god vs more sende;</L>
<L>And heo &thorn;at in heuene be&thorn; . han such wi&thorn; outen ende,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;ut in more, . vor it wane&thorn; neuer mo;<NOTE PLACE="foot">in <I>vor</I> more <I>ist zu tilgen</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="640">We be&thorn; bote enes ved adai, . vorte &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> we &thorn;ider go;</L>
<L>Whanne we &thorn;ider come&thorn;, . we schulen wi&thorn; outen ende,</L>
<L>And &yogh;if wolt(!) deserui, . &thorn;ider vorto wende;</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou wolt &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t do, . whan &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> comest to er&thorn;e iwis;</L>
<L>&thorn;ider &thorn;ou most anon a&yogh;e, . vor al time hit is;</L>
<L N="645">&yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt god lif lede, . &thorn;i mede &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t seo,</L>
<L>And also, whoche pines, . &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt lu&thorn;er beo.</L>
<L>A&yogh;en &thorn;ow most wende, . go vor&thorn; in godes name!</L>
<L>Go baldeliche, for no deuel . ne schal do &thorn;e no schame:</L>
<L>Adrad hi be&thorn; of &thorn;e, . &amp; aschamed bi eche side;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor und nach</I> &yogh;if <I>fehlt</I> &thorn;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L N="650">A godes name go &thorn;i wey, . &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> ne schalt no leng abide!</L>
<L>Sire, merci, qua&thorn; &thorn;e kni&yogh;t, . what so me euer bitide,</L>
<L>A fote inelle henne go, . wrechede ge&thorn; so wide;</L>
<L>Lat me bi leuen her, . vor, &yogh;if i<SUP>c</SUP> from &yogh;ou wende,</L>
<L>Adrad icham of &thorn;e deuelen . mid sunne wolle&thorn; me schende.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In der 2. Halbz. fehlt</I> &thorn;at <I>oder</I> heo.</NOTE></L>
<L N="655">Beu frere, qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, . &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t as wel be stille,</L>
<L>Vor &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt to er&thorn;e go, . &thorn;er &thorn;ow mi&yogh;t do &thorn;i wille;</L>
<L>&yogh;if &thorn;ou seruest oure lord, . siker &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t beo</L>
<L>A&yogh;en to come to vs, . &amp; su&thorn;&thorn;e to heuene vleo;</L>
<L>In godes half wende a&yogh;en, . vor siker &thorn;ou schalt so.</L>
<L N="660">Alas, alas, qua&thorn; &thorn;e kni&yogh;t, . what schal i now do?</L>
<L>&thorn;e ioie &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ich now isei&yogh;e . wor&thorn; me now bi nome,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e wrecchede of &thorn;e world, . alas, ischal come.
<PB REF="00000252.tif" N="208"></L>
<L>Al wepinge out ate &yogh;ate . brou&yogh;t e was ate laste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o he was wi&thorn; oute, . heo maden &thorn;e &yogh;ate faste.</L>
<L N="665">As he com &thorn;ideward, . &thorn;e wei a&yogh;en he nom.</L>
<L>Ac, whanne ani deuel . a&yogh;en him owhare com,</L>
<L>As wode schrewen heo flowen . &amp; dorsten abide nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kni&yogh;t was ate laste . to &thorn;e halle a&yogh;en brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;er &thorn;e holi companie . to him &thorn;ere wende.</L>
<L N="670">A doun e sat softe, . vorte god him grace sende.</L>
<L>As he sat and bihuld, . sone &thorn;er comen yn &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e noble companie, . comen as heo duden ere(!).<NOTE PLACE="foot">comen <I>&uuml;berfl&uuml;ssig</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Heo honoureden him faire, . &amp; hereden god faste,</L>
<L>Ih&umacr; crist, godes sone, . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> his bi leue so wel laste.</L>
<L N="675">Beu frere, he seide, now &thorn;ou hast . such penaunce idriue,</L>
<L>Siker be &thorn;e &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;i sunnes . be&thorn; clanliche for &yogh;iue;</L>
<L>Loke, whanne &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> comest hom, . clene lif &thorn;ou lede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> neuer in pine come . vor no misdede;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou most &thorn;e hi&yogh;en, vor atom in &thorn;i londe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlt . nach der Halbz</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="680">Hit dawe&thorn; cler, &amp; is day, . as ich vnderstonde;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> day <I>fehlt</I> nei.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e prior wi&thorn; procession . to &thorn;e &yogh;ate come&thorn; sone,</L>
<L>To loke &yogh;if &thorn;ou beo come, . as ri&yogh;t is to done;</L>
<L>&yogh;if he ne finde&thorn; &thorn;e nou&yogh;t, . he make&thorn; &thorn;e &yogh;at sone anon</L>
<L>And loke&thorn; after &thorn;e namore, . ac dreri hamward gon(!).<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Trotz der Ver&auml;nderung der ganzen Stelle ist</I> gon <I>stehen geblieben</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="685">&thorn;is kni&yogh;t heo brou&yogh;ten for&thorn;, . &amp; blesseden him echon,</L>
<L>And bitau&yogh;ten him god, . soule, bodi, and bon.</L>
<L>Vor&thorn; he wende his wey, . he moste nede do.</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t as he com to &thorn;e &yogh;ate, . &thorn;e priour com al so</L>
<L>A&yogh;en him wi&thorn; procession, . to loken hou it were.</L>
<L N="690">&thorn;o he hedde &thorn;e &yogh;at vnloke, . &thorn;e kni&yogh;t he fond &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&thorn;er was ioie and blisse, . &thorn;o heo to gedere come.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; song &amp; wi&thorn; orisons . &thorn;e kni&yogh;t out heo nome,</L>
<L>And ladden him to chirche, . &amp; hereden god faste.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kni&yogh;t bi fore &thorn;e weued . anon on kneo him caste,</L>
<L N="695">And stabliche in orisons . viftene dawes he lay,</L>
<L>And heriede oure swete lord . vaste ni&yogh;t and day.</L>
<L>And su&thorn;&thorn;e on is bare vlesch . &thorn;e holi crois enom,</L>
<L>He &yogh;eode into &thorn;e holi londe, . &amp; holi mon bicom;</L>
<L>And tolde not of &thorn;e world, . ac euere he was in &thorn;ou&yogh;te;</L>
<L N="700">He &yogh;ede euer simple liche, . as him nou&yogh;t ne rou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Ac ofte he tolde of &thorn;e men . &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> in paradis were;
<PB REF="00000254.tif" N="210"></L>
<L>As him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, grei&yogh;e monkes . in mest ioie he sei&yogh; &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>None in so grete ioie, . ne in so gret honour esei&yogh;:<MILESTONE N="128" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>No wonder nis sikerliche, . vor &thorn;e ordre is so hei&yogh;.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> nis <I>fehlt</I> it.</NOTE></L>
<L N="705">Now &yogh;e habbe&thorn; iherd, . hou oure lord sende is grace</L>
<L>Seint patrik, to finden . &thorn;e purgatorie in &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>Vor to warnie men aboute . here sunnes to bete,</L>
<L>An to leue on ih&umacr; crist, . &amp; on is moder swete.</L>
<L>Bete we our sunnes her, . as god wole grace sende,</L>
<L N="710">&thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> we wi&thorn; oute o&thorn;er pine . to paradis henne wende.</L>
<L>God vs lete oure sunnes bete, . vor is holi wounde,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at we in purgatorie . bileue lutel stounde. Amen.</L>
</LG>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000221.tif" N="[177]">
<HEAD>c. aus Ms. Laud 108. <B>Purgatorium sci Patrici abbatis.</B><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So der Titel in rother Schrift rechts am Rande; links steht in schwarzer kleiner Schrift</I> De purgatorio sci patrici. <I>Die ersten 2 Verse sind Zusatz.</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Ms. Laud beginnt sofort mit dem Fegfeuer; die in den andern Mss. vorhergehenden 54 Verse fehlen.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint paterik &thorn;oru godes grace : makede ane put in Irlonde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at seint patrike purgatorie is icleoped : &yogh;eot, ase ich onder stonde,</L>
<L>Ore louerd him bi tok ane staf : mid is owene honde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he fond &thorn;ulke purgatorie with, : i hered beo godes sonde!</L>
<L N="5">In Irlonde is &yogh;eot &thorn;ilke staf i wust : derewor&thorn;eliche i nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>For gret relike he is i holde, : and elles it were wou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Seint paterik in &thorn;ulke stude, : &thorn;at his purgatorie is,</L>
<L>Of religion bi gan an hous, : &thorn;at &yogh;eot stant i wis;</L>
<L>Ant Chanoynes &thorn;are inne he makede, : ase &yogh;eot &thorn;are beoth al so.<NOTE PLACE="foot">nt <I>in</I> ant <I>ist klein &uuml;bergeschr.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="10">&thorn;ane put he let faste closi a boute, : &thorn;at noman ne come &thorn;ar to.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e churche &yogh;erd is &thorn;at ilke putt, : ri&yogh;t toward &thorn;e Est side,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t est fram &thorn;e hei&yogh;e Au&yogh;ter, : &thorn;at manie men &yogh;wylene sou&yogh;ten wide.</L>
<L>He is bi walled faste a boute, : and faste i loke &thorn;e &yogh;ate;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> abooute.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e prior haueth &thorn;e kei&yogh;e in warde, : &thorn;at no man ne mot In &thorn;ar ate.</L>
<L N="15">Al bi seint paterikes dai&yogh;e : men wenden &thorn;udere i lome,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e also mani on, : and fewe a&yogh;en &thorn;are come.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;ulke &thorn;at &thorn;are comen a&yogh;en, : of &thorn;at heo i sei&yogh;en, heo tolde,</L>
<L>Ase it is in &thorn;e house i write : and in priue conseile i holde.</L>
<L>&thorn;e manere is of euerech man : &thorn;at for so&thorn;e &thorn;udere i went,<MILESTONE N="97" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="20">&thorn;at it beo to bete is sunnes, : &yogh;if ore louerd him grace (sent).<NOTE PLACE="foot">sent <I>am Ende fehlt im Ms.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e bischope of &thorn;e lond : furst he schal him schriue,</L>
<L>And bidde him leue &thorn;ene wey to go, : in amendement of is liue.
<PB REF="00000223.tif" N="179"></L>
<L>Ake &thorn;e bischop schal rede heom &thorn;are a&yogh;ein : and manie resones schewe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">heom <I>st.</I> him.</NOTE></L>
<L>And segge &thorn;at manie &thorn;udere wendeth, : and a&yogh;ein &thorn;are comieth fewe.</L>
<L N="25">Ake, &yogh;if he is stable in is &thorn;ou&yogh;t, : for al &thorn;at men him habbez i bede,</L>
<L>&thorn;e bischop him wole is lettre make : to &thorn;e prior of &thorn;e stude.</L>
<L>&thorn;e prior him wole al so rede i nov&yogh; : for to chaungi is &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And, &yogh;wane he si&yogh;kz him studefast, : &thorn;at he nele bi leue it nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In to churche he wole him lede : and sette him a doun a kne;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ff. <I>Diese Reihenfolge der Verse ist un|zweifelhaft die richtige.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="30">Fiftene dawes he schal &thorn;are : in is oresones beo.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if heo ne mouwen for no &thorn;ing : maken chaungi is &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>With gret procession of preostes : to &thorn;e putte he worth i brou&yogh;t;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> precession.</NOTE></L>
<L>With &thorn;e croiz and with &thorn;e haliwatur : heo schullen blessi him ech on,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Zusatz, fehlen in den and. Mss.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Him sulf he schal him blessi al so, : and &thorn;anne into &thorn;e putte gon;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Zusatz, fehlen in den and. Mss.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">into <I>aus</I> inte <I>corr.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="35">And &thorn;at procession schal tuyrne a&yogh;en, : ase ri&yogh;t is for to done.</L>
<L>A moruwe In &thorn;ulke tyme : heo schullen come &thorn;udere eft sone,</L>
<L>And, bote heo finden him &thorn;anne a&yogh;en i come, : with gret deol and sor</L>
<L>Heo schullen tuyrne a &yogh;ein, and sikere beoth : &thorn;at he ne comez a&yogh;en non more.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hit bi fel bi &thorn;e kingus dai&yogh;e steuene, : &thorn;at nov&thorn;e late was,</L>
<L N="40">Of a kni&yogh;t, &thorn;at hei&yogh;te sire Ovwayn, : a swi&thorn;e wonder cas.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e bischop &thorn;is kni&yogh;t eode, : and to schrifte to him he cam,</L>
<L>In grete repentaunce of is sunnes : deol and sorewe to him he nam.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bischop bi gan to chide faste : for &thorn;at he hadde mis do,</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at he was manne worst, : for to sunegun so,</L>
<L N="45">And seide &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te so muche schame a fonge, : &thorn;at he nere wuyr&thorn;e more.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kni&yogh;t sat with careful heorte, : he si&yogh;te and weop ful sore.</L>
<L>Sire, seide &thorn;e kni&yogh;t, &yogh;wan ich habbe : manne worst ido,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e sunne &thorn;at grettest is, : mest penaunce mot &thorn;ar to,</L>
<L>And &yogh;if ich a mong alle men : mest sunful am, alas,</L>
<L N="50">&thorn;e gretteste penaunce ichulle take : &thorn;at euere bi founde was:</L>
<L>Ichulle me take to godes grace : and in is name i wende</L>
<L>Into seint paterikes purgatorie, : and take &thorn;at god me wole sende.</L>
<L>Ov, beu frere, quath &thorn;e bischop, : be stille! &yogh;wi seist&thorn;ov so?<NOTE PLACE="foot">v <I>in</I> seist&thorn;ov <I>klein &uuml;bergeschr.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Crist for beode &thorn;at &thorn;ov euere : swuch folie do!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> eure <I>mit &uuml;bergeschr.</I> e.</NOTE></L>
<L N="55">Onne&thorn;e comez &thorn;are ani a &yogh;en : &thorn;at doth &thorn;are In i wende;</L>
<L>Nolde god &thorn;at &thorn;ov &thorn;e dede dudest, : bodi and soule to schende!</L>
<L>Ake wend into religion, and bi lef &thorn;are : to &thorn;ine liues ende:</L>
<L>&thorn;ine sunnes &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t bete wel, : &yogh;if god &thorn;e wole grace sende.</L>
<L>Certes, sire, quath &thorn;is kni&yogh;t, : ase wel &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t beo stille,</L>
<L N="60">For &thorn;ulke penaunce ichulle do, : &yogh;if it is godes wille;</L>
<L>For ase muche ase ich habbe of serued, : Ine mai nou&yogh;t habe of wo;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> habe <I>st.</I> habbe.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ere fore sei&yogh;e &yogh;wat i schal, : for &thorn;udere ichulle go.
<PB REF="00000225.tif" N="181"></L>
<L>&thorn;e bischop prechede him faste i nov&yogh;, : for to chaungi is &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Ake at &thorn;e laste, &thorn;o he isai&yogh; : &thorn;at it was al for nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="65">To &thorn;e prior of &thorn;e stude : his lettres made sone,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> made <I>fehlt</I> he.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at he scholde bi him do, : ase bi swuch a man was to done.</L>
<L>&thorn;e prior prechede him faste i nov&yogh; : and schewede him resones i nowe,</L>
<L>&yogh;if he mi&yogh;te changi is &thorn;ou&yogh;t, : &thorn;at he him with drowe.</L>
<L>Bote is prechinge was al for nou&yogh;t, : ase he sai&yogh; at&thorn;enende,</L>
<L N="70">&thorn;at he nolde lete for no &thorn;ing : &thorn;ene perilouse wei to wende.</L>
<L>&thorn;e prior nam him bi &thorn;e hond : and in to churche him brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&thorn;are he ful akne adoun : and ore louerdes grace bi sou&yogh;te;<NOTE PLACE="foot">: <I>doppelt, hinter</I> akne <I>und</I> adoun.</NOTE></L>
<L>In fastingues and in oresones : fourtene ni&yogh;t he lai,</L>
<L>Forte bidde ore louerdes grace; : and in &thorn;e fourte&thorn;e dai</L>
<L N="75">&thorn;at Couent cam a boute him, : and o&thorn;ere preostes al so</L>
<L>And clerkes, with procession, : &thorn;e seruise for him to do.</L>
<L>For him heo songun &thorn;e hei&yogh;e masse : and to ore louerd criden faste,</L>
<L>And ore louerdes flechs and is blod : heo &yogh;euen him at&thorn;e laste,</L>
<L>And spreinden him with holi watur, : and heore oresones heo seide.</L>
<L N="80">With Croiz and with procession : to &thorn;e put heo gonne him lede,</L>
<L>And hei&yogh;liche songun &thorn;e letanie, : and holi water with hem bere,</L>
<L>And alle louerdes halewe beden : &thorn;at heo heore help were.<NOTE PLACE="foot">heore <I>st.</I> his.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e prior on lek &thorn;e puttes dore : bi fore heom ech on,</L>
<L>And seide : beu frere, lo here &thorn;e wei : &thorn;at &thorn;ou wilnest for to gon;</L>
<L N="85">Ake &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt bi ore rede do, : &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;ou schalt wende</L>
<L>And in o&thorn;ur manere &thorn;ine sunnes bete, : ase god &thorn;e grace wole sende;</L>
<L>Fewe here comen euere a &yogh;en : &thorn;at wenden here In bi fore,</L>
<L>Ake heo beoth for tormentingue and for wo : lif and soule for lore.</L>
<L>Certes, sire, quath &thorn;is kni&yogh;t, : rede &yogh;wat &thorn;ov me rede,</L>
<L N="90">In ore louerdes name &thorn;ane wei ich take : to bete mine mis dede;</L>
<L>Ake, for is loue &thorn;at us deore bou&yogh;te, : biddez for me ech on!</L>
<L>Lif and soule god ich bi take, : and In his name ichulle In gon.</L>
<L>He blessede him, and wende forth In, : and bi tok god is flesch and is bon.</L>
<L>&thorn;e prior spreinde him with holi water, : and lek &thorn;e dore a non.</L>
<L N="95">&thorn;is goude kni&yogh;t wende him forth, : wel baldeliche and faste,</L>
<L>In one holewe weie onder eor&thorn;e, : and to god is heorte caste;</L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e deork it was, &thorn;at he ne say ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t, : ne no &thorn;ing him ne a gaste.</L>
<L>So longe &thorn;at him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he i sai&yogh; : wel feor li&yogh;t at&thorn;e laste.</L>
<L>&thorn;uderward he wende baldeliche, : so &thorn;at he cam &thorn;ere nei&yogh;.</L>
<L N="100">&thorn;e faireste feld &thorn;at mi&yogh;te beo : at&thorn;e wei&yogh;es ende he isei&yogh;.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Am Rande</I> : pulcher via.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;are Inne he wende murie inov&yogh;, : and a midde &thorn;e felde he fond</L>
<L>&thorn;e faireste halle and &thorn;e nobleste : &thorn;at mi&yogh;te beo in ani lond.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;et weder nas nou&yogh;t cler, : bote ase it were nei&yogh; eue.</L>
<L>Forto bi holde &thorn;at noble weork, : ane stounde he gan bi leue;
<PB REF="00000227.tif" N="183"></L>
<L N="105">&thorn;e walles neren nou&yogh;t ihole, : ake al a boute i wis</L>
<L>With pilers and with qvoynte Arches, : ase &thorn;is Monekene cloistre is.<NOTE PLACE="foot">v <I>in</I> qvoynte <I>&uuml;bergeschr</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>In he wende a godes name, : and sette him al one an hei&yogh;;</L>
<L>He bi heold a boute in to eche huyrne : and &thorn;at quoyte weork he sei&yogh;.<NOTE PLACE="foot">quoyte <I>st.</I> quoynte.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ase he bi heold al so a boute, : &thorn;are come In at &thorn;e on ende</L>
<L N="110">Twelf men in &yogh;wite clo&thorn;es, : swi&thorn;e faire and hende,</L>
<L>Alle heore crounes weren newe schaue; : and suy&thorn;e faire heo him gretten,</L>
<L>And alle heo seten faire a doun, : and &thorn;ane (kni&yogh;t) bi heom heo setten.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> &thorn;ane <I>fehlt</I> kni&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o seide on of heom, ase &thorn;ei it &thorn;e prior were, : wel mildeliche and stille:</L>
<L>Bev frere, ihered beo Ih&umacr; crist, : &thorn;at on &thorn;e brou&yogh;te swuche wille,</L>
<L N="115">And late &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh; agodes name hast bi gonne : for is holi grace wel ende!</L>
<L>Leue bro&thorn;ur, &yogh;wane &thorn;ou woldest &thorn;is wei : for &thorn;ine sunnes wende:</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur &thorn;ov most beon studefast and hardi : and in none manere tuyrne &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur &thorn;ov worst for lore lif and soule : and sone to &thorn;e deuel i brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>For, also sone ase we beth heonne i went, : &thorn;e feondes lu&thorn;ere and wicke</L>
<L N="120">Heo wollez come a boute &thorn;e : In to &thorn;is hous ful &thorn;icke,</L>
<L>And don &thorn;e tormens and wo i nov&yogh;, : and bi hote &thorn;e wel more,</L>
<L>And heo wollez also bi hote &thorn;e Joye inov&yogh;, : &yogh;if &thorn;ov wolt leue heore lore;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if heo mouwen &thorn;oru&yogh; ani bi heste,: o&thorn;ur enie gile, &thorn;e ouer come,</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e &thorn;ov worst lif and soule : a deuele wei al clene i nome;</L>
<L N="125">Ake &yogh;if &thorn;ov art studefast of heorte : and on Ih&umacr; crist wolt &thorn;enche,</L>
<L>Ne for bi heste ne for wo : fram him &thorn;ou nelle blenche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> bi heste heste.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ou worst quit of alle &thorn;ine sunnes, : &thorn;at &thorn;ov hast euere i wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ov schalt iseo alle &thorn;e Joies : &thorn;at guode men beoth inne i brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And al so &thorn;e pine &thorn;at lu&thorn;ere men : habbez for heore mis dede;</L>
<L N="130">Ake, in &yogh;wat wo &thorn;at &thorn;ov euere art, : euere &thorn;ench on god, ich rede,</L>
<L>And euere, &yogh;wane heo tormentiez &thorn;e, : cri Jesu milce and ore,</L>
<L>And, &yogh;if &thorn;ou art studefast in gode bi leue, : heo ne schullen defouli &thorn;e non more;</L>
<L>We bi takez &thorn;e god of heuene, : and ich rede &thorn;ov do bi ovre lore.</L>
<L>&thorn;o nuste &thorn;e kni&yogh;t &yogh;ware heo bi comen, : he sat and si&yogh;te sore,</L>
<L N="135">Elinge he bi lefte alone : and cride on godes mi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And Armede him with holie beden, : a&yogh;en &thorn;e deuelene to fi&yogh;te;</L>
<L>On &thorn;e holi gost he cride faste, : &thorn;at he ne scholde him faile.</L>
<L>He lokede euere, &yogh;wane heo comen, : him for to a saille.</L>
<L>Ase he sat a godes name, : &thorn;e bataille forto a bide,</L>
<L N="140">&thorn;are cam a sori reuful cri : a boute in eche side,</L>
<L>Ase al&thorn;e world to borste and to breke; : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, it was also,</L>
<L>&thorn;at, &thorn;ei alle &thorn;e bestes of &thorn;e worlde : to gadere weren ido,</L>
<L>Ase loude and ase grisliche ase heo mi&yogh;ten, : &yogh;eollinde ech one heo were:
<PB REF="00000229.tif" N="185"></L>
<L>Ake heo ne mi&yogh;ten a mong heom alle : make so grisliche bere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Im Anfang fehlt</I> and.</NOTE></L>
<L N="145">&thorn;at is hope and is heorte on ih&umacr; crist : euere more heo were,(!)<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> &thorn;at <I>fehlt wol</I> bote (<I>oder</I> welle?); <I>die Construktion ist</I> verderbt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Elles he hadde wod bi come : and i lore is wit for fere.</L>
<L>&thorn;o comen heo a bouten him : &thorn;icke and grisliche &thorn;ere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> dyaboli.</NOTE></L>
<L>&yogh;eonijnde and grenninde on him : with ful lodlich chere.</L>
<L>Bel ami, quath &thorn;e on of heom, : &thorn;ou hast a ri&yogh;t ido;</L>
<L N="150">We owez wel alle anouri &thorn;e, : for alto fewe doth so,</L>
<L>For alle o&thorn;ere men wollez a bide : &thorn;at heore lif heom beo bi nome,</L>
<L>And &yogh;eot it is a&yogh;en heore wille : &thorn;at heo schullen hidere come,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ov art i come al bi &thorn;ine liue, : and bi &thorn;ine guode wille also;</L>
<L>Wel ou&yogh;te we &thorn;ine mede &yogh;elde : and gre(t) &thorn;onk also &thorn;e do;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> gre <I>st.</I> gret.</NOTE></L>
<L N="155">&yogh;wane &thorn;ov hast bo&thorn;e bodi and soule : i&yogh;yuen us bi &thorn;ine liue,</L>
<L>Saunt faille we ne beoth nou&yogh;t so onkuynde : &thorn;at we it nellez &yogh;elde &thorn;e bliue,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e kundenesse &thorn;at &thorn;ov to us come : al bi &thorn;ine owene lore;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sind in den and. Mss. umgesetzt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ake na&thorn;eles, &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt on eor&thorn;e : habbe Joye more,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sind in den and. Mss. umgesetzt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sikere us an hond &thorn;at &thorn;ov wolt : In ore seruise bi leue,</L>
<L N="160">And we &thorn;e wollez a&yogh;en to eor&thorn;e bringe, : al sauf, are hit beo eue,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ov schalt habbe &thorn;are Joye inou&yogh;, : in halle and eke in boure,</L>
<L>For none men ne fareth so murie &thorn;are : ase &thorn;ulke &thorn;at beoth ovre;</L>
<L>Hei&yogh; man and noble &thorn;ov schalt beo, : and alle men schullen honouri &thorn;e;</L>
<L>&yogh;wane &thorn;ov art ded ant comest to us, : &thorn;ou schalt habbe ase guod ase we.</L>
<L N="165">&thorn;is kni&yogh;t &thorn;ou&yogh;te euere on Jesu crist, : and nolde chaungi is wille,</L>
<L>For &thorn;retninge ne for fair bi heste, : ake sat him euere stille.</L>
<L>&thorn;o he nolde graunti nou&yogh;t : to heom for to wende,</L>
<L>Heo &yogh;ollen and grenneden on him foule, : and strong fuyr bi gonne forto tiende.</L>
<L>&thorn;is kni&yogh;t heo bounden honden and fet, : and a midde &thorn;e fuyre him caste;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> prima pena. <I>Im Ms. undeutlich ob</I> fot <I>oder</I> fet.</NOTE></L>
<L N="170">With Irene Ovles and pikes : heo to drowen him wel faste.</L>
<L>&thorn;is kni&yogh;t hadde gret pine; : wel loude he cride a non:</L>
<L>Jhesus, Jhesus, help me nou&thorn;e, : and do a wei mine fon!</L>
<L>Anon so hadde &thorn;is word iseid, : &thorn;at fuyr a queinte ech spronke,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> hadde <I>fehlt</I> he.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e deuelene ne mi&yogh;ten him non more to drawe. : ore louerd he gan &thorn;onke,</L>
<L N="175">And &thorn;e hardiore he was i nou&yogh;, : &thorn;o he &thorn;is i sei&yogh;,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e lasse he was of heom a drad : &thorn;at weren him so nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>Wel grisliche heo &yogh;ollen, &thorn;e schrewes, : &thorn;o heom faillede heore mi&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms. urspr.</I> mi&yogh;te, e <I>ist ausradirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And flouwen echone out of &thorn;e halle, : and drowen with heom &thorn;is kni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>A&yogh;en &thorn;e grounde heo drowen him harde : bo&thorn;e bi fet and honde,</L>
<L N="180">Longe, him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, and swi&thorn;e feor, : al a boute in a waste londe.</L>
<L>So blac and deork was al &thorn;at lond, : &thorn;at no &thorn;ing he ne sei&yogh;</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;e feondes &thorn;at him to drowen, : &thorn;at so &thorn;icke weren him nei&yogh;.
<PB REF="00000231.tif" N="187"></L>
<L>Ake swi&thorn;e softe wind &thorn;are was, : &thorn;at he heorde onne&thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> swi&thorn;e <I>fehlt</I> a.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ake so scharpe he bleu&yogh; and colde, : &thorn;at brou&yogh;te him nei&yogh; to de&thorn;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> brou&yogh;te <I>fehlt</I> he.</NOTE></L>
<L N="185">Ri&yogh;t colde he wende &thorn;oru&yogh; is heorte, : and &thorn;oru&yogh; al is bodi also,</L>
<L>&thorn;at him were leouere &thorn;ane al &thorn;e world, : &thorn;at &thorn;e pine were ido.</L>
<L>&thorn;us colde heo drowen him, ase heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te, : forth ri&yogh;t est i wis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">heom <I>st.</I> him.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ase &thorn;e sonne a rist in somer, : &yogh;wane &thorn;e dai lengest is.</L>
<L>&thorn;o heo comen, ase heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te, : ri&yogh;t to &thorn;e worldes ende,<NOTE PLACE="foot">heom <I>st.</I> him.</NOTE></L>
<L N="190">Bi a brod valeie heo torneden heom, : and southward gonne i wende,</L>
<L>To ward &thorn;e stude &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne : In winter doth a rise;</L>
<L>&thorn;is seli kni&yogh;t was i drawe : and i pined in fale wise.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;ou&yogh;te him &thorn;at he i heorde feor, : bi fore him ase it were,</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e deolful cri and wop, : and swy&thorn;e revful bere;</L>
<L N="195">Euere &thorn;e neor &thorn;at heo comen, : &thorn;e revlokur was &thorn;at cri;</L>
<L>So longe drowen him, &thorn;at him &thorn;ou&yogh;te : &thorn;at heo weren ri&yogh;t &thorn;er bi.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> drowen <I>fehlt</I> heo.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o comen heo into a wid feld; : non more ne mi&yogh;te beo,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> Se(cun)da pena. <I>Ms.</I> wid <I>st.</I> wild.</NOTE></L>
<L>So long and brod in eche side, : &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te non ende iseo.</L>
<L>Of men and of wummen &thorn;is feld was : ful in eche side,<NOTE PLACE="foot">n <I>in</I> and <I>&uuml;berschr</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="99" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="200">&thorn;e wombene to ward &thorn;e grounde : i spradde a brod ful wide,</L>
<L>Hondene and fet al a brod : to &thorn;e eor&thorn;e faste i bounde</L>
<L>With Irene nailles, al fuyrie, : i smite &thorn;oru&yogh; heom to grounde.</L>
<L>&thorn;is wrechche gostes weren so i pinede : with Irene and with fuyre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">weren <I>Zusatz</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>So deolful cri heo maden &thorn;are, : &thorn;at gret deol it was to huyre;</L>
<L N="205">Heo criden merci deolfulliche, : Ake no merci men nolde heom do;</L>
<L>For Anguische &thorn;e eor&thorn;e heo freten, : and hore tongene gnowen al so.</L>
<L>&thorn;e deoulene ornen opon hem, : and treden heom to &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L>And with Ovles swi&thorn;e kene : maden heom mani a wounde.</L>
<L>Allas, &yogh;wy nellez men beon i war, : and heore sunnes here bete,</L>
<L N="210">Are heo comen to purgatorie : and with &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere gostes mete?</L>
<L>For ase wel beth &thorn;e schrewes in purgatorie, : and ouer al, ase in helle,</L>
<L>And schullen, for to &thorn;e dai&yogh;e of dome come, : telle &yogh;wat men telle.</L>
<L>&thorn;e feondes seiden : ri&yogh;t ase men beoth i pinede, : &thorn;ov schalt beo also,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;ov wolle &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t wende : and after ovre rede do.</L>
<L N="215">And &thorn;o he nolde in none manere, : to grounde harde heo him caste,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> tertia pena.</NOTE></L>
<L>And tormenteden him, ase &thorn;e o&thorn;ere weren, : and to &thorn;e eor&thorn;e naileden him faste.</L>
<L>Ake he criede a non to ih&umacr; crist, : &thorn;o him smert so sore:</L>
<L>&thorn;are nas non of &thorn;e schrewes &thorn;o : &thorn;at mi&yogh;ten serui him so more.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e schrewes i sei&yogh;en &thorn;at heo ne mi&yogh;ten : heore wille habben &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="220">Heo drowen him into an o&thorn;ur felde, : wel ful of more wo:</L>
<L>Of Men and wummen it was ful, : opri&yogh;t i sprad to grounde,
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="189"></L>
<L>Fet and hondene a to i drawe : and to &thorn;e eor&thorn;e faste i bounde,</L>
<L>With glowinde biendes al of Ire : i nailede heo weren &thorn;er to;</L>
<L>Al fuyrie naddrene ope heom seten, : and foule crapoudes al so:</L>
<L N="225">Some of &thorn;e naddrene bi clupten heom : so faste al a boute,</L>
<L>&thorn;at heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te heo scholden to berste, : so streite heo gurden heom with oute;</L>
<L>Some seten ope heom, : and heore flesch alto gnowe,</L>
<L>And with kene tieth al fuyrie : wombe and breoste to drowe;</L>
<L>Some with hore scharpe tounges : &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e heorte sore heom smite;</L>
<L N="230">Some heo gnowen, and some heo stounge, : and some with scharpe tieth heom bite.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> stoungee, <I>aus</I> stounde <I>corr.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e Crapoudes al so, &thorn;at weren so foule, : op on heore breostene sete,</L>
<L>And stoungen heom &thorn;oru&yogh; heore heortene : with heore foule wrottes grete.</L>
<L>&thorn;e lu&thorn;ere gostes ornen al so : a boute heom i nowe</L>
<L>With hokes and with ou&yogh;les, : a with gret eir heom to drowe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">a <I>st.</I> and, <I>so auch v. 286.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="235">&thorn;e wrechche gostes, so for pinede, : in swuch torment weren i brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Heo criden alle deolfulliche, : ake hit ne halp heom nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&thorn;e feondes nomen &thorn;is seli kni&yogh;t, : and wolden him pini al so,</L>
<L>Ake anon, so he cride on Ih&umacr; crist, : ne mi&yogh;ten heo bringe him &thorn;er to.</L>
<L>&yogh;eot &thorn;e feondes eft sone him nomen : and to &thorn;e &thorn;ridde feld him brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L N="240">In stronge pine he sai&yogh; &thorn;are wrechche gostes, : &thorn;at of heom self luyte rou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&thorn;at weren ispradde on &thorn;e eor&thorn;e abrod, : and i smiten &thorn;oru&yogh; out ech one</L>
<L>With nailes &thorn;icke al abrod, : ase &thorn;are mi&yogh;ten stikie one,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> &thorn;icke <I>fehlt</I> as. one <I>st.</I> on.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at man ne mi&yogh;te finde ane amtie place : on al heore bodie so luyte,</L>
<L>&thorn;at man mi&yogh;te for &thorn;e &thorn;icke nailles : a fingres ende to heom puyte.</L>
<L N="245">A smart wind also to o&thorn;ur wo : on heom bleu&yogh; wel faste,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> quarta pena.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te heo weren i barnd : &thorn;oru&yogh; out with eche blaste.</L>
<L>&thorn;e feondes ornen faste a boute : fram ech to o&thorn;ur i nowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">n <I>in</I> feondes <I>&uuml;berschr.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And heore wrechche flesch with o&thorn;ur wo : mid Ovles heom to drowe.</L>
<L>&thorn;eos wrechche gostes, so fur pinede, : and in swuch torment ibrou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> fur pinenede <I>mit weg|punktirtem</I> ne.</NOTE></L>
<L N="250">Revliche heo criden ase heo mi&yogh;ten, : ake it ne halp heom ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For heo weren so clene ouer come, : &thorn;at heo ne mi&yogh;ten onne&thorn;e</L>
<L>Ani voiz out bringe, bote ase aman : &thorn;at were ope &thorn;e pointe of de&thorn;e:</L>
<L>In heore &thorn;rote heo criden dimmeliche, : for heore streuc&thorn;e heom was bi nome</L>
<L>With muche pine, and no wonder it nas : &thorn;ei heo weren ouer come.</L>
<L N="255">&thorn;e feondes nomen &thorn;is seli kni&yogh;t : and to grounde him caste,</L>
<L>And seiden, bote he wolde turne is &thorn;ou&yogh;t, : heo wolden naili him &thorn;are wel faste.
<PB REF="00000235.tif" N="191"></L>
<L>Ake he cride on ih&umacr; crist, : and nemde is holi name;</L>
<L>&thorn;e schrewes ne hadden none mi&yogh;te &thorn;o : to don him more schame.</L>
<L>&yogh;eot heo nomen and drowen him : into &thorn;e feor&thorn;e felde,</L>
<L N="260">Ful of brumston, al brenninde : with stronge lei&yogh;e and spelde.</L>
<L>Ech manere pine, &thorn;at mi&yogh;te beo, : In &thorn;ulke felde he sei&yogh;:</L>
<L>Some with chaines of Ire, : al fuyrie, hengen on hei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Some bi Armes, some bi fet, : and bi &thorn;e necke mani on;</L>
<L>Heo weren an hangede in stronge fuyre : of pich and eke brumston;</L>
<L N="265">Some hengen bi stronge crokus, : I pulte &thorn;oru&yogh; ei&thorn;ur Ey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e &thorn;rote some also, : and &thorn;oru&yogh; ei&thorn;ur ere wel hei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And some &thorn;oru&yogh; heore derne limes, : and some &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e tete,</L>
<L>&thorn;at leuere heom were &thorn;ane al &thorn;e world, : heore lyf to habbe i lete;</L>
<L>Some op on grediles of Ire : i rostede weren also:</L>
<L N="270">Some, ase gyes, &thorn;e spites of Ire : &thorn;oru&yogh; out heom i do,</L>
<L>Some leyen opri&yogh;t a &yogh;ein &thorn;e grounde, : &yogh;eonijnde wel faste,</L>
<L>&thorn;e feondes welden led and bras : and in heore mou&thorn;es caste.</L>
<L>He ne mi&yogh;te bi &thorn;enche no manere pine, : &thorn;at he ne sai&yogh; mo &thorn;er.</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he sai&yogh; &thorn;are mani on : &thorn;at he knev on eor&thorn;e her.</L>
<L N="275">&thorn;e feondes him casten a midde &thorn;is pine : a mong &thorn;is o&thorn;ere ech on,</L>
<L>And he cride on Jesu crist, : and was deliured a non.</L>
<L>&yogh;eot &thorn;is feondes &thorn;is selie kni&yogh;t : into an o&thorn;ur place huy drowe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> Sexta pena.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;are Inne he isai&yogh; a grislich &yogh;weol : with spokene longe i nowe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at on ende hangede toward &thorn;e grounde, : &thorn;at o&thorn;ur op on hei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="280">Ful it was of hokes and pikes : wel &thorn;icke, ase he i sei&yogh;;</L>
<L>&thorn;is hokes and &thorn;is pikes weren : faste i riuen also</L>
<L>With wrechche gostes al a boute, : &thorn;at &thorn;aron weren ido.</L>
<L>Al brenninde was &thorn;is sorie &yogh;weol, : and stinkinde of brumston;</L>
<L>&thorn;e wrechche gostes &thorn;at &thorn;ar on hengen : brenninde weren ech on.</L>
<L N="285">&thorn;is feondes wenden forth a non : and heore hokes &thorn;aron caste</L>
<L>In ei&thorn;ur side, a turden a boute : &thorn;is sori &yogh;weol so faste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a <I>st.</I> and. turden <I>st.</I> turnden.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at of &thorn;e gostus &thorn;at &thorn;aron hengen : no &thorn;ing heo ne sei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>So faste heo torneden &thorn;at &yogh;weol a boute, : bote &thorn;e brenninde lei&yogh;e;</L>
<L>Ake deolfulliche heo criden and &yogh;ollen, : euer ech in is ende.<MILESTONE N="100" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="290">Alas, &yogh;wi nellez men beon i war, : are heo heonnes wende,</L>
<L>&yogh;wane he mi&yogh;ten here with a luytel pine : bete heore misdede,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are heo schullen so bitere a bugge, : alas, &thorn;e wrechhede?</L>
<L>&thorn;is feondes nomen &thorn;is seli kni&yogh;t : and on &thorn;is &yogh;weol him caste,</L>
<L>And with &thorn;is o&thorn;ere wrechche gostes : torneden him a boute faste;</L>
<L N="295">Sone he cride on Ih&umacr; crist, : deliuered he was a non.</L>
<L>&thorn;e feondes stoden and bi heolden : with dreori mod ech on.
<PB REF="00000237.tif" N="193"></L>
<L>Eft heo nomen him bitterliche : and ferrore &yogh;uyt him ladde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> septima pena.</NOTE></L>
<L>And harleden him forth wel revfulliche, : and loude &yogh;ollen and gradde.</L>
<L>Bi fore him he sai&yogh; an hous stonde, : long and brod i nov&yogh;;</L>
<L N="300">Stunch and hete, &thorn;at &thorn;arof cam, : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te al mest a slou&yogh;.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> a slou&yogh; <I>fehlt</I> him.</NOTE></L>
<L>He with stod, and nolde is &thorn;onkes : for stunche gon non ner.</L>
<L>Ferrore &thorn;ov schalt, &thorn;e fendes seiden, : &thorn;ou ne schalt nou&yogh;t a bide her;</L>
<L>A bath it is &thorn;at &thorn;ov isijcst, : and &thorn;arinne &thorn;ov schalt beo</L>
<L>And ba&thorn;i with o&thorn;ere &thorn;at &thorn;are beoth; : ne schalt &thorn;ov nou&yogh;t so fleo.</L>
<L N="305">&thorn;e gostes &thorn;at &thorn;are inne weren : wel deolfulliche cride</L>
<L>And &yogh;ollen loude, ase he i heorde, : a boute in eche side.</L>
<L>&thorn;is kni&yogh;t with &thorn;is foule wi&yogh;tes : Into &thorn;e grete house cam.</L>
<L>Of tormens, &thorn;at he &thorn;are isai&yogh;, : gret gome with alle he nam.</L>
<L>Ful of puttes and of diches : &thorn;at hous with inne it was;</L>
<L N="310">More seoruwe ne more stunch : neuere i sei&yogh;e nas:</L>
<L>Heo weren folle of stronge tormens, : boillinde euer ech on,</L>
<L>Of wallinde led, and i fulde heo weren : of piche and brumston.</L>
<L>Wrechche gostus &thorn;are inne seten, : &thorn;e torment tilde wel hei&yogh;e:</L>
<L>Some a boue &thorn;e heued, : and some ri&yogh;t to &thorn;e Ey&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="315">Some to &thorn;e nose, and some to &thorn;e mouth, : and some op to &thorn;e swere,</L>
<L>And some to heore breostene, : and a bou&yogh;ten heore sunnes ful deore,</L>
<L>And some to heore nauele, : and some ne&thorn;errore more,</L>
<L>And some stoden op to heore knen, : and criden and weopen sore,</L>
<L>And some stoden In with bo&thorn;e fet, : and some with &thorn;at on;</L>
<L N="320">Deolfolliche heo weopen and criden : and &yogh;ollen euerechon.<NOTE PLACE="foot">n <I>in</I> and <I>&uuml;berschr</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nov &thorn;ov i sixt, que&thorn;en &thorn;e feondes, : &yogh;woder In &thorn;ov schalt gon,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;ov wolle an o&thorn;ur speke : and to us tuyrne a non.</L>
<L>Heo nomen and casten him In a putte; : on Jesus a non he cride,</L>
<L>Op he cam a non a &yogh;en, : and no lengore he ne moste &thorn;are a bide.</L>
<L N="325">Heo nomen him in grete wrath&thorn;e : and harleden him ferrere more,</L>
<L>And brou&yogh;ten him opon a swy&thorn;e gret hul, : ful of sorewe and sore.</L>
<L>He stod and bi heold a boute, : &thorn;o he cam &thorn;are op an hei&yogh;;</L>
<L>Him wondrede of &thorn;e manie gostes : &thorn;at he &thorn;are isei&yogh;.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e pinene &thorn;at he hadde er i sei&yogh;e : &thorn;are a&yogh;en nou&yogh;t nere;</L>
<L N="330">I clui&yogh;te heo seten ope heore ton, : and quakeden revliche for fere.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e south half of &thorn;e hul : a deop water &thorn;are was and lou&yogh;,</L>
<L>&thorn;at foule stonk and caldore was : &thorn;ane ani ys o&thorn;ur snov&yogh;;</L>
<L>A nor&thorn;erne wind faste blev&yogh;, : &thorn;at him &thorn;ou&yogh;te is flesch to rende.</L>
<L>Euere &thorn;are seten gostes : and a&yogh;ein &thorn;e winde heom wende,</L>
<L N="335">Heo quakeden and chyuereden faste : in grete pine and stronge,</L>
<L>Ase ho so seith a bidet &thorn;are heore time, : heore deth for to a fonge.</L>
<L>Lo, seide on of &thorn;e feondes, : &thorn;ov nost nou&yogh;t &yogh;wat is tis;<NOTE PLACE="foot">istis <I>st.</I> is &thorn;is.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bote &thorn;ov torne &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t sone, : &thorn;ou schalt i wite i wis.
<PB REF="00000239.tif" N="195"></L>
<L>Ne hadde he bote &thorn;is word i seid, : &thorn;at &thorn;are ne cam a wind blowe</L>
<L N="340">And drof alle &thorn;is wrechche gostes : into &thorn;e deope watur ful lowe.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Nor&thorn;erne wynd drof heom a doun : al mid one blaste,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e gostes and &thorn;ene kni&yogh;t : a midde &thorn;e watere hem caste</L>
<L>More pine ne mi&yogh;te non beo : of stronge chele ne of stunche,</L>
<L>&thorn;ane &thorn;is gostes &thorn;arinne hadden, : &thorn;are ne mi&yogh;te non at blenche.</L>
<L N="345">&thorn;o &thorn;e kni&yogh;t &thorn;e stronge pine : of &thorn;is water i felde,</L>
<L>He gan to crie on Ih&umacr; crist, : &thorn;at faillede him ful selde:</L>
<L>A non ri&yogh;t with oute lette : op of &thorn;is watere man him drov&yogh;.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;is wrechche gostes lefden &thorn;ere : with sorewe and wo i nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>For in &thorn;at water, &thorn;at was so cold : and so foule stonk also,</L>
<L N="350">&thorn;is gostes swymden op and doun : in muche sorewe and wo;</L>
<L>&thorn;e feondes ornen opon &thorn;e watere, : so men doth on &thorn;e londe,</L>
<L>And, &yogh;wane ani wolde coueri op : with fote o&thorn;ur with honde,</L>
<L>Heo pulten him a doun a &yogh;en, : &thorn;at &thorn;are ne a scapede non;</L>
<L>&thorn;are was wo and sorewe i nou&yogh; : a mong heom euerechon.</L>
<L N="355">&thorn;is feondes wenden forth a non, : and &thorn;e seli kni&yogh;t eft nome</L>
<L>And drowen him into a sori stude, : &thorn;are neuer er heo ne come.</L>
<L>Heo comen and stoden ouer a put, : wyd it was and deop i nov&yogh;;</L>
<L>A brenninde smoke, &thorn;at foule stonk, : op of &thorn;e putte drov&yogh;,</L>
<L>&thorn;at onne&thorn;e &thorn;e kny&yogh;t mi&yogh;te stonde : for sori stunch &thorn;are nei&yogh;.</L>
<L N="360">Wrechche gostes in &thorn;is put : in &thorn;at sori smoke he sei&yogh;</L>
<L>Fleo op and doun, al brenninde, : ase speldene doth of fuyre,</L>
<L>And in to &thorn;e putte eft fullen a doun,:&thorn;o heo ne mi&yogh;ten no leng duyre.</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he was al ouer come : for &thorn;e stunche &thorn;at &thorn;arop of drov&yogh;,</L>
<L>&thorn;are bi him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at in &thorn;e grounde : was soruwe and deol i nov&yogh;.</L>
<L N="365">&yogh;wy stanst &thorn;ov so? &thorn;e fendes seiden, : &thorn;inch&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;arof wonder,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is swete smoke &thorn;at here bloweth, : and &yogh;wat put beo &thorn;are onder?</L>
<L>In &thorn;is put is ovre woneingue, : for &thorn;e put of helle it is,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A. R.:</I> puteum Inferni.</NOTE></L>
<L>And, for &thorn;ov us hast i serued wel, : here &thorn;ov schalt wonie iwis,</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at us seruieth wel, : hidere heo schullen wende,</L>
<L N="370">And, &yogh;if &thorn;ov comest here in with us, : &thorn;ov worst here with outen ende;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;if <I>a. R. nebengeschr</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;are fore i rede, torne &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t : and do us here man rede,</L>
<L>And we schullen &thorn;ene wei ase we conne : al sauf a &yogh;en &thorn;e lede;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> conne <I>st.</I> come.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ov schalt on eor&thorn;e al &thorn;i lijf habbe : richesse and Ioye al so,</L>
<L>For we schullen on eor&thorn;e &thorn;e finde i nov&yogh;, : ase ri&yogh;t is &thorn;at we do.</L>
<L N="375">&thorn;o &thorn;e kni&yogh;t for sok heore bi heste, : ase he hadde er ilome,</L>
<L>Heo smiten heom a doun into &thorn;e putte,:and &thorn;ene kni&yogh;t with heom nome.</L>
<L>&thorn;e deoppore &thorn;at heo comen, : &thorn;(e) braddere &thorn;e put was;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> &thorn; braddere.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ake al &thorn;e wo &thorn;at he isai&yogh; er : a &yogh;ein &thorn;at nou&yogh;t it nas.</L>
<L>Of stunch, of brenninge, and of o&thorn;ur wo : &thorn;e kni&yogh;t was so ouer come,<MILESTONE N="101" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="380">&thorn;at is &thorn;ov&yogh;t toward Jesu crist : nei&yogh; him was bi nome;
<PB REF="00000241.tif" N="197"></L>
<L>So muche pine nas neuere i sei&yogh;e; : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, ase &thorn;ei he felde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ei <I>nach</I> as <I>fehlt in den and. Mss.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at he was nei&yogh; ope &thorn;e pointe : &thorn;ene gost op to &yogh;elde.</L>
<L>Ake ore louerd a mong al is wo : grace him &yogh;af at&thorn;e laste,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he &thorn;ou&yogh;te on Ih&umacr; crist : and to him cride at&thorn;e laste.<NOTE PLACE="foot">at&thorn;e laste <I>st.</I> faste.</NOTE></L>
<L N="385">A smoke &thorn;are cam smite up a non, : mid one wel stronge blaste<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> mid <I>fehlt</I> and.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ene kni&yogh;t an hei&yogh; a boue &thorn;e putte, : and manie o&thorn;ere gostes, caste;</L>
<L>&thorn;e kni&yogh;t &yogh;wirlede op in &thorn;is blast, : ase speldene doth, wel wide,</L>
<L>At&thorn;e laste he li&yogh;te a doun : a boue &thorn;e putte bi side.</L>
<L>&thorn;are he stod and bi heold a boute : ase man &thorn;at witles were,</L>
<L N="390">&thorn;at, for &thorn;e pine &thorn;at he hadde i haued, : he nuste hov he cam &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&thorn;o he hadde longe istonde al one : and bi holde a boute,</L>
<L>&thorn;are comen blaste op of &thorn;e putte : deuelene a gret rou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And bi him al a boute, : al newe as &thorn;ei heo were;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> him <I>fehlt</I> stode.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ase him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, he ne sai&yogh; hem : neuer er bote &thorn;o &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="395">Heo bi heolden him wel grisliche : and grenneden on him al a boute,</L>
<L>And seiden: &yogh;wi stanst &thorn;ov here al one? : &thorn;ov most come into ovre rovte!</L>
<L>Heo seiden: tolden ore felawes &thorn;e : &thorn;at &thorn;is was &thorn;e put of helle?</L>
<L>Hit nis nou&yogh;t so, ake we wollez sone : for ri&yogh;te so&thorn;e &thorn;e telle;</L>
<L>Nost&thorn;ov nou&yogh;t &thorn;at it is ore ri&yogh;te : to li&yogh;en euere mo,</L>
<L N="400">And &thorn;at we with lesingues bi traieth men, : bote it mowe o&thorn;ur go?</L>
<L>And so ore felawes louwen &thorn;e : &thorn;at &thorn;is was &thorn;e put of helle;</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;ov schalt come &thorn;udere with us, : and &thorn;e so&thorn;e we wollez &thorn;e telle.</L>
<L>&thorn;is deouelene harleden &thorn;ane kni&yogh;t forth, : &thorn;at wo was him to drawe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at him were leouere &thorn;ane ani &thorn;ing : &thorn;at he hadde i beo of lif dawe.</L>
<L N="405">So &thorn;at heo comen to a swy&thorn;e gret watur, : deop and brod i nov&yogh;;</L>
<L>A strong mist, &thorn;at foule stonk, : op of &thorn;is watere drov&yogh;</L>
<L>Of brumston and of o&thorn;ur wo, : so strong stunch neuere he ne sei&yogh;,</L>
<L>&thorn;at mid al &thorn;e pine of &thorn;e world : onne&thorn;e he stod &thorn;ere nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>A brugge &thorn;are was ouer &thorn;at watur, : smallere ne mi&yogh;te non beo,</L>
<L N="410">&thorn;e smoke was so &thorn;icke alaboute, : &thorn;at onne&thorn;e he mi&yogh;te i seo.</L>
<L>&thorn;o seiden &thorn;e sorie fendes: : we seggez &thorn;e i wis</L>
<L>&thorn;at onder &thorn;is deope watere : &thorn;e put of helle so is;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ov schalt sone i wite, : for &thorn;ov schalt sone a non</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;is watur, &thorn;at is so deop, : opon &thorn;is brugge gon,</L>
<L N="415">And we schullen &thorn;e sende swuch a wynd, : &thorn;at schal &thorn;e amidde caste,</L>
<L>And ore felawes, &thorn;at beoth bi neothe, : schullen &thorn;e nime wel faste</L>
<L>And drawe &thorn;e doun forth with hem : Into helle grounde a non;</L>
<L>Cum nov&thorn;e forth, and &thorn;ou&yogh; schalt : op on &thorn;is brugge gon.</L>
<L>Heo nomen &thorn;is seli kni&yogh;t : and op on &thorn;is brugge drowe,</L>
<L N="420">And maden him go &thorn;ere is on &thorn;onkes : with wrechhedes i nowe.</L>
<L>&thorn;reo &thorn;ingus vuele i nowe : on &thorn;is brugge were:
<PB REF="00000243.tif" N="199"></L>
<L>&thorn;at on was for heo was so hei&yogh;, : &thorn;at no gost ne mi&yogh;te for fere</L>
<L>&thorn;are oppe gon, and so deope a doun : habbe so grisliche si&yogh;te;</L>
<L>&thorn;at o&thorn;ur was for heo was so narov&yogh;, : &thorn;at onne&thorn;e ani &thorn;ing mi&yogh;te</L>
<L N="425">&thorn;are oppe sette ani fot, : &thorn;at he ne fulle a doun a non;</L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;ridde &thorn;at heo was so slider, : &thorn;at man ne mi&yogh;te &thorn;are oppe gon,</L>
<L>Bote he slide and felle a doun, : so slei&yogh; man neuere nere.</L>
<L>&thorn;eos &thorn;reo &thorn;inges &thorn;esne selie kni&yogh;t : brou&yogh;ten in grete fere,</L>
<L>For heo was narov&yogh;, and slider, and hei&yogh;, : &thorn;at he ne scholde him so bi telle,</L>
<L N="430">&yogh;if &thorn;at he glufte in ani half, : &thorn;at he ne fulle in to helle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> glufte, <I>aus</I> gulte <I>corr., u. a. R. nebengeschr.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;are oppe he was with strenc&thorn;e i brou&yogh;t : and &thorn;are oppe i maket to gon.</L>
<L>So gret drede, ase him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, : ne hadde he neuer er non.</L>
<L>Ake sone he &thorn;ou&yogh;te on ih&umacr; crist, : &thorn;at so ofte him sauede er,</L>
<L>And cride on is holie name, : &thorn;at he were is helpe &thorn;er.<NOTE PLACE="foot">l <I>in</I> helpe <I>&uuml;berschr.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="435">He eode forth we(l) baldeliche, : and &thorn;e innore &thorn;at he cam,<NOTE PLACE="foot">we <I>st.</I> wel.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e hardiore him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he was, : and &thorn;e betere heorte to him he nam,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> &thorn;eb betere.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e braddore was is wei, : so longe forth he eode,</L>
<L>&thorn;at it was so brod, &thorn;at &thorn;ere mi&yogh;te : a carte gon for neode,</L>
<L>And so longe &thorn;at tuei cartes mi&yogh;te : meten heom wel i nov&yogh;.</L>
<L N="440">&thorn;e kni&yogh;t &thorn;o wel baldeliche : ase a maister forth him drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&thorn;e feondes stoden bi ne&thorn;e &thorn;e brugge : and sei&yogh;en him so faste gon,</L>
<L>And for al &thorn;e wo &thorn;at heo him duden : ne ouer cam him nou&yogh;t on;</L>
<L>Heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te, it was al for nou&yogh;t : after him to honten more.</L>
<L>Grisliche heo gonne forto &yogh;eolle : ant to crie and wepe suy&thorn;e sore,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> goune.</NOTE></L>
<L N="445">&thorn;at for &thorn;e &yogh;eollinge &thorn;at heo maden : he hadde wel more fere,</L>
<L>&thorn;ane of al &thorn;e pine &thorn;at he hadde er, : so lodlich was &thorn;e bere.</L>
<L>Heore Oules heo nomen and heore hokes, : and toward him casten an hei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;are nas non &thorn;at him touchi mi&yogh;te, : ne no &thorn;ing come him nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at al sauf with alle Joye : ouer &thorn;is watere he him drov&yogh;,</L>
<L N="450">And &thorn;e feondes lefden bi hinde : with grete soruwe ant sor i nou&yogh; &mdash;</L>
<L>In helle is heore kuynde heritage, : and elles for so&thorn;e it were wov&yogh;; &mdash;</L>
<L>Heo leten him go &yogh;wodere he wolde, : and ne fondeden him non more,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh; <I>in</I> &yogh;wodere <I>&uuml;berschr.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And heolden heom cleneliche ouer come : for al heore false lore.</L>
<L>&thorn;is kni&yogh;t wende him forth sauf i nou&yogh;, : &thorn;at he hadde erore deore a bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="455">And &thorn;onkede &yogh;eorne Ih&umacr; crist : &thorn;at &thorn;e feondes ne siweden him nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&thorn;at watur he passede sauf inov&yogh;, : and for&thorn;ere &thorn;ene wey he nam;</L>
<L>&thorn;e contrie him &thorn;ou&yogh;te murie inou&yogh;, : &thorn;are forth &thorn;at he cam;</L>
<L>&thorn;e for&thorn;ere &thorn;at he wende, : &thorn;e more murev&thorn;e he sei&yogh;.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he i sai&yogh; ane wal, : swi&thorn;e noble and hei&yogh;;</L>
<L N="460">So riche weork nas neuere i sei&yogh;e, : ase him (&thorn;ou&yogh;te) &thorn;at &thorn;ar on was;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> him <I>fehlt</I> &thorn;ou&yogh;te.</NOTE></L>
<L>And swy&thorn;e fair &yogh;at &thorn;aron he sai&yogh;, : &thorn;at neuere swuch i sei&yogh;e nas;
<PB REF="00000245.tif" N="201"></L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;at schon swy&thorn;e bri&yogh;te, : ase &thorn;ei it al gold were,</L>
<L>Folle of derewur&thorn;e stones i pi&yogh;te, : none richere neuere nere.</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, are he &thorn;udere cam, : is wei ful longe laste.</L>
<L N="465">&thorn;o he cam for&thorn;ere a luytel wi&yogh;t, : he stod and bi heold it faste.</L>
<L>&thorn;at (&yogh;at) wende op a&yogh;en him, : and a non ri&yogh;t with &thorn;e dede<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> &thorn;at <I>fehlt</I> &yogh;at.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;are cam smite out a swote smel, : and wide a boute gan sprede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, &thorn;ei al &thorn;e world : swote spices were,</L>
<L>So muche swotnesse ne mi&yogh;te &yogh;iuen, : ase &thorn;at suote smul dude &thorn;ere.<MILESTONE N="102" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="470">In so gret Joye him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he was, : &thorn;at, &thorn;ei he hadde beo i brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>In to al &thorn;e soruwe &thorn;at he was er, : it ne schulde him habbe i greued nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>He bi heold in at &thorn;is &yogh;ate, : &thorn;o he cam &thorn;er nei&yogh;:</L>
<L>More clernesse nas neuere i sei&yogh;e, : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, &thorn;ane he &thorn;ere i sei&yogh;.</L>
<L>Ase he wolde &thorn;are In wende, : a&yogh;ein him &thorn;are cam gon</L>
<L N="475">A procession fair i nov&yogh;, : of noble men ech on,</L>
<L>With creoiz and with taperes : and with baneres clere;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>am Rande nebengeschr.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>I reuested faire muche folk was, : and ech hadde is fere:</L>
<L>Some were bischopus and Ercedeknes, : and some Monekes and freres,</L>
<L>And euerech, him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, hadde &thorn;e Abite : &thorn;at heo wereden here.</L>
<L N="480">With &thorn;e meste Joye &thorn;at mi&yogh;te beo : &thorn;is kni&yogh;t was onder fonge,</L>
<L>And i lad In with Joye i nov&yogh;, : mid solas and murie songe.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;is murie song was i do, : to him sone &thorn;are come</L>
<L>Tweien, ase it maistres weren, : and bi &thorn;e honde him nome,</L>
<L>And wel comeden him wel mildeliche : and &thorn;onkeden ore louerd faste,</L>
<L N="485">&thorn;at him sende so guode bi leue, : so stableliche for to laste.</L>
<L>Heo ladden him a boute and scheweden him : &thorn;at lond fer and ner:</L>
<L>So muche Joie and clernesse : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he ne sai&yogh; neuer er;</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;e sonne bi nimez &thorn;e li&yogh;t : of Candle a boute Midday,</L>
<L>Also it bi nam &thorn;e sonne hire leom, : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, ase he &thorn;are isai&yogh;(!).</L>
<L N="490">So long and brod &thorn;e place was, : &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te non ende i seo;</L>
<L>A fair Medwe he sai&yogh; with swete floures, : swottere ne mi&yogh;te non beo,</L>
<L>Treon al so with noble fruyt, : &thorn;at smulde swote Inov&yogh;.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e swotnesse of euer ech stude : al a boute op drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;are with oute mete and drunch, : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, euere mo</L>
<L N="495">He mi&yogh;te libbe with alle Joie, : &yogh;if he moste &thorn;are Inne go.</L>
<L>It was &thorn;ere euere i liche li&yogh;t, : and euere it was dai.</L>
<L>So muche folk in none place him &thorn;ou&yogh;te : neuer er he ne sai&yogh;;</L>
<L>Ech Compaygnie to o&thorn;ur drov&yogh;, : and ech bi o&thorn;ur stod,</L>
<L>With murie song and Melodie, : and gladnesse in heore mod,</L>
<L N="500">&thorn;at ech of o&thorn;ur &thorn;e more Joye : to gadere heo mi&yogh;ten a fonge.</L>
<L>Al mi&yogh;ti god, &thorn;at heom schop, : heo hereden In heore songe.</L>
<L>And, ase sum steorre, &thorn;at &yogh;e i seoth, : bri&yogh;tore &thorn;ane o&thorn;ur is,</L>
<L>Also was bi heom, for some weren : clerore &thorn;ane some i wis;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> was <I>fehlt</I> it.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000247.tif" N="203"></L>
<L>Ake &thorn;ulke &thorn;at mest dosk was, : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, was more cler<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms. urspr.</I> clere <I>und</I> 505 ere, e <I>ist ausradirt.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="505">And bri&yogh;tore schon &thorn;ane ani gold : &thorn;at he i sai&yogh; euer er.</L>
<L>Ech werede clo&thorn;es of &thorn;e en taile, : &thorn;at heo wereden on eor&thorn;e here:</L>
<L>Monekes ase it to Monek bi feol, : and freres ase to frere,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo hadden heore ri&yogh;te fourme, : ake wel bri&yogh;tore was hore hev,</L>
<L>Ant, &yogh;wat men heo were on eor&thorn;e, : bi heore clo&thorn;inge he knev.<NOTE PLACE="foot">506-509 <I>fehlen in Ms. Egert.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="510">Some hadden &thorn;e croune of golde : an ouewarde &thorn;e heued ido,</L>
<L>And some beren in heore hond : &yogh;eordene of golde also.</L>
<L>And alle heo &thorn;onkeden <ABBR>Jhu</ABBR> crist, : &thorn;at so studefast heorte him sende,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kni&yogh;t for al &thorn;e pine &thorn;at he hadde : is heorte enes ne wende.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Im Anfange fehlt</I> &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ech one heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at for him : In &thorn;e more Joye heo were.</L>
<L N="515">He stod and bi heold al &thorn;is Joie, : as &thorn;ei no wit on him nere.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms. urspr.</I> with, h <I>ist ausradirt.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e on, ase it heore maister were, : is Mouth ondude wel softe,</L>
<L>And welcomede him wel mildeliche, : and &thorn;onkede ore louerd ofte,</L>
<L>&thorn;at swuch porpos him hadde i send, : and studefast heorte al so,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ne chaungede nou&yogh;t is &thorn;ou&yogh;t, : for al &thorn;at him was ido.</L>
<L N="520">Bev frere, he seide, i herd beo god, : &thorn;at &thorn;e hauez hidere i brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And a mong alle &thorn;ine stronge fon : studefast i wust &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e pine of sunfule gostes : I fondet &thorn;ov hauest inou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are with &thorn;ine sunnes i bet, : and elles it were wou&yogh;;</L>
<L>&thorn;ov mi&yogh;t here sumdel i seo, : &thorn;at &thorn;ov wilnest more,</L>
<L N="525">Of &thorn;e Joye &thorn;at guode soulene habbez, : &thorn;at comieth to milce and ore.</L>
<L>&thorn;is place, &thorn;at we inne beoth, : ich wene &thorn;ov ne knowest nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>It is eor&thorn;elich parays, : &thorn;at Adam was Inne i brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he was Inne ymad, : and seth&thorn;e for is mis dede</L>
<L>He was i cast out &thorn;ar of, : and we al so, : on eor&thorn;e into alle wrechche hede;</L>
<L N="530">Al &thorn;e Joye, &thorn;at &thorn;ov i sixt her, : he hadde to is wille,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e Joye <I>am Rande nebengeschr.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Ake he ne mi&yogh;te, &thorn;o he was out icast, : &thorn;ar of i seo wurth a fille.</L>
<L>Of wrechhede we beoth i kened, : and of sunful blode i come,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at us is &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace : ant &thorn;oru&yogh; ore cristinedom bi nome.</L>
<L>Ak &thorn;at we, aftur ore cristindom, : of sunne on eor&thorn;e wrou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="535">On eor&thorn;e o&thorn;ur in purgatorie : wel deore we it bou&yogh;te:</L>
<L>For we alle, &thorn;at &thorn;ou here i sixt, : &thorn;are forth hidere come,</L>
<L>And ore sunnes &thorn;are betten : and harde penaunce nome,</L>
<L>Ne mi&yogh;te we elles here come; : ase guod bi &thorn;e it is:</L>
<L>For, &yogh;if &thorn;ine sunnes nere for &yogh;iue, : &thorn;ov ne come nou&yogh;t here i wis.<NOTE PLACE="foot">u. 41 <I>fehlen im Ms. Egert.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="540">And alle &thorn;at &thorn;ov &thorn;are isei&yogh;e : to us &thorn;udere heo schullen wende,</L>
<L>And al dai doth some, &yogh;wane heo habbez : heore penaunce i brou&yogh;t to ende.</L>
<L>Neuer on not hov longe he schal : &thorn;are bi leue i wis;</L>
<L>For, ho so ani freond on eor&thorn;e hath, : mid him &thorn;e betere it is:
<PB REF="00000249.tif" N="205"></L>
<L>&thorn;oru&yogh; massene, and &thorn;oru&yogh; o&thorn;ur beden, : and &thorn;oru&yogh; almes dede</L>
<L N="545">Man mai hore pine muche a legge : and &thorn;e sonore ovt &thorn;ar of heom lede.</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane ani of heom hidere comez, : a&yogh;en him we wendez ech on,</L>
<L>Ase we duden a &yogh;ein &thorn;e, with Joye, : and ledez him In a non.</L>
<L>Ake non of us nis &yogh;uyt wuyrth&thorn;e : in to heuene for to wende,</L>
<L>Ne neuere on not &yogh;wane ovre louerd : after ani of us wole sende;</L>
<L N="550">For ech man &thorn;at in to heuene schal : &thorn;oru&yogh; purgatorie mot,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e into eor&thorn;eliche parays, : ase we beoth nov&thorn;e, wel ich wot,</L>
<L>For &thorn;is is ovre kuynde heritage; : iwrou&yogh;t we weren &thorn;ar to,</L>
<L>Al forto ore furste fader it a gulte, : and for to he hadde mis do;</L>
<L>Here we scholden alle habbe i beon i bore, : and i leoued ore lif also,</L>
<L N="555">For ore louerd wold &thorn;at we weren : In &thorn;e more Joye i do.<NOTE PLACE="foot">For <I>st.</I> for to.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ei men beon ovt heonnes i cast, : here forth heo moten wende</L>
<L>And a&yogh;en(!), ar heo to heouene come, : aftur heore liues ende.</L>
<L>Ake al &thorn;e Joye, &thorn;at is here, : nis no &thorn;ing i wis</L>
<L>A &yogh;ein &thorn;e leste Joye of heouene; : wel muche &thorn;e meste is.</L>
<L N="560">Sum &thorn;ing &thorn;ov schalt of heuene iseo : In a place here nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>He ladde him op on an hei&yogh; hul, : and bad him bi holde on hei&yogh;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> bad him him.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="103" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And axede him of &yogh;wuch colur were : heuene op ri&yogh;t &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>He seide: him &thorn;ou&yogh;te ri&yogh;t ase gold, : &thorn;at puyr wallinde were.</L>
<L>&yogh;e, seide &thorn;is o&thorn;ur, &thorn;is is &thorn;e wei : &thorn;at geth ri&yogh;t to heuene blis,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="565">And &thorn;at is &thorn;e &yogh;at of parays, : &thorn;at with oute heuene &yogh;eond is.</L>
<L>Ech day some of purgatorie : comez hidere us to,</L>
<L>And some of us to heuene wendez : euer eche daye also,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at (we) wexez eche daie : and waniez, &thorn;ov sixt lo;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlt</I> we.</NOTE></L>
<L>We nutez &yogh;wuch of us it schal beo next, : bote as god wole habbe ido.</L>
<L N="570">Ech dai, &thorn;e &yogh;wuyle we here beoth, : ore louerd us fedez ene</L>
<L>With riche metes of heuene, : &thorn;at swete is and clene;<NOTE PLACE="foot">metes <I>st.</I> mete.</NOTE></L>
<L>&yogh;wuche &thorn;ulke metes beon, : are &thorn;ov heonnes wende,</L>
<L>With us &thorn;ov schalt sone i wite, : &yogh;wane god it wole us sende.</L>
<L>Ne hadde he bote o word i seid, : &thorn;at &thorn;are ne cam a li&yogh;te</L>
<L N="575">A manere brez fram heouene a doun, : &thorn;at schon wel clere and bri&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ouer spradde al &thorn;at lond, : and a cler leome &thorn;are with oute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlen in Ms. Bodl.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And opon euereches heued a li&yogh;te a doun : wel faire, with outen doute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlen in Ms. Bodl.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And op on &thorn;is kni&yogh;tes heued al so, : an &thorn;oru&yogh; him smot a non,</L>
<L>And &thorn;oru&yogh; euerech lime and lith of him : &thorn;at swete li&yogh;t gan gon,</L>
<L N="580">&thorn;a(t) so muche wille and Joye, : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, neuere he nadde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> &thorn;a <I>st.</I> &thorn;at.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000251.tif" N="207"></L>
<L>He stod, ase &thorn;ei he were i nomen : for Joye &thorn;at he &thorn;o hadde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Die 2. Halbz. passt nicht; auch Ms. Bodl.</I> : he nyste wher he was.</NOTE></L>
<L>&yogh;we&thorn;ur he were quik o&thorn;ur ded, : bote ase he in metingue were.</L>
<L>Louerd, murie is &thorn;e Joye of heuene, ase he i felde wel &thorn;ere.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlt</I> :.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ake it ne laste heom bote luytele &yogh;wile, : &thorn;at &thorn;e leome ne with drov&yogh;;<NOTE PLACE="foot">495-584 fehlen in Ms. Ashm.</NOTE></L>
<L N="585">And na&thorn;eles, &thorn;ei it luyte laste, : &thorn;at of heo weren fulle i nov&yogh;.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kni&yogh;t stod and bi heold a boute, : and is ri&yogh;te stat onder stod;</L>
<L>So fol he was of &thorn;at holi leome, : &thorn;at so swete was and guod:</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, &thorn;ei he leouede euere more : and neuereft more ne ete,</L>
<L>Ne scholde him neuer eft to mete luste, : so guod was &thorn;e leome and swete.</L>
<L N="590">Lo, seide &thorn;is o&thorn;ur gost : &thorn;at schewede him al &thorn;is place,</L>
<L>Sum del &thorn;ov hast nou&thorn;e isei&yogh;e : of ore louerdes grace:</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e pine &thorn;at &thorn;e wrechche gostes : habbeth for heore mis dede,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e Joye &thorn;at guode gostes : in parays doth lede,</L>
<L>And sum del of &thorn;e grete Joie : &thorn;at in &thorn;e ri&yogh;te heuene is;</L>
<L N="595">Eche dai&yogh;e we beoth ifedde : ones with swuche Joye and blis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne beo we al dai fulle i nov&yogh;, : for to ore louerd more us sende:</L>
<L>In swuche Joie heo beoth &thorn;at beoth in heouene, : and wor&thorn;ez with oute ende,</L>
<L>And &yogh;uyt sum del in more, : it ne faillez heom neuere mo;</L>
<L>And we ne beoth a day bote enes, : for to we &thorn;udere go,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> enes <I>fehlt</I> ifed.</NOTE></L>
<L N="600">And, &yogh;wan &thorn;at we &thorn;udere comieth, : we schulle with outen ende,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou, &yogh;if &thorn;ov a seruest heuene forth : &thorn;udere for to wende;</L>
<L>&thorn;ov mi&yogh;t don ase &thorn;ov wolt, : &yogh;wane &thorn;ov comest to eor&thorn;e i wis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;udere anon a&yogh;en &thorn;ou most, : for so&thorn;e at &thorn;e time it is;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ov wolt guod lif lede, : &thorn;ine mede &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t i seo,</L>
<L N="605">And, &yogh;wat pine heo habbez, &thorn;ov hast i seie, : &thorn;at lu&thorn;ere wollez beo.</L>
<L>A &yogh;ein &thorn;ou most wende a non; : go forth a godes name!</L>
<L>For sikerliche &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t gon, : &thorn;e feondes ne mowen don &thorn;e no schame:</L>
<L>Heo beoth adradde wel sore of &thorn;e, : and a schamede in eche side;</L>
<L>A godes name go forth &thorn;i wei, : &thorn;ov ne mi&yogh;t no leng here a bide!</L>
<L N="610">A, sire, merci! quath &thorn;is kni&yogh;t, : bi tide &yogh;wat me bi tide,</L>
<L>A fote i nelle fram eov go, : for wrechche hede goth so wide,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> wrechche hedede.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ake soffriez me bi leue here with ov, : for, &yogh;if ich fram eov wende,</L>
<L>A drad ich am of &thorn;e feondene mi&yogh;te : laste heo with sunne me schende.</L>
<L>Do wei, beu frere, &thorn;is o&thorn;ur seide, : ase wel &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t beo stille;</L>
<L N="615">A &yogh;en &thorn;ov schalt to eor&thorn;e a non, : and &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t don &thorn;are &thorn;ine wille;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ov seruest wel ore louerd &thorn;ere, : siker &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t beo</L>
<L>To comen a &yogh;ein hidere to us, : and seth&thorn;e to heuene fleo;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms. scheinbar</I> steo <I>st.</I> fleo.</NOTE></L>
<L>A godes half wend a &yogh;en a non, : for so&thorn;e &thorn;ov schalt so.</L>
<L>Alas, alas, quath &thorn;is kni&yogh;t, : &yogh;wat schal ich nou&thorn;e do?</L>
<L N="620">Al &thorn;e Joye &thorn;at ich habbe nou&thorn;e isei&yogh;e, : it worth me bi nome,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e wrechhede of &thorn;e worlde, : alas, schal ich nov&thorn;e come.
<PB REF="00000253.tif" N="209"></L>
<L>Ovt ate &yogh;ate heo brou&yogh;ten him, : wepinde, at &thorn;e laste,</L>
<L>And beden him gon wel hardiliche : and herien ore louerd wel faste.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlen in den and. Mss.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>A non so he was with oute i gon, : &thorn;at &yogh;at heo maden wel bliue.</L>
<L N="625">With dreori mod he wende a&yogh;en, : and was a drad of is liue.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlen in den and. Mss.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Ase he cam er, with careful mod : &thorn;ene wei a &yogh;ein he nam.</L>
<L>And, &yogh;wane ani deuel &thorn;at him pinede er : ou&yogh;were a &yogh;en him cam,</L>
<L>Ase wode schrewene heo flouwen faste, : and ne dorsten a bide him nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>So at&thorn;e laste &thorn;is kni&yogh;t was : to &thorn;e halle a &yogh;ein i brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="630">&thorn;are as &thorn;e holie compaygnie : &thorn;uder ward to him wende,</L>
<L>And sat him a doun wel softe &thorn;ere, : for to ore louerd him grace sende.</L>
<L>Ase he sat and bi heold a boute, : to him heo comen &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at faire compaygnie : &thorn;at a &yogh;ein him cam er,</L>
<L>And honoureden him wel faire : and conforteden him wel faste,</L>
<L N="635">And &thorn;onkeden Jesus, godes sone, : &thorn;at his bi leue so wel i laste.</L>
<L>Bev frere, heo seiden, &yogh;wane &thorn;ov hast : swuch penaunce i driue,</L>
<L>Siker beo &thorn;ou &thorn;at &thorn;ine sunnes : al clene &thorn;e beoth for &yogh;iue;</L>
<L>Loke, &yogh;wane &thorn;ov comest to eor&thorn;e a&yogh;en, : &thorn;at &thorn;ov clene lif lede,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ov neuer eft in pine ne come : for sunne ne for mis dede;</L>
<L N="640">&thorn;ov most don &thorn;e heonnes a non, : for at hom in &thorn;ine londe</L>
<L>Hit dawez clere, and is nei&yogh; dai, : ase ich me onder stonde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e prior with procession : to &thorn;e &yogh;ate comez wel sone</L>
<L>To loki &yogh;we&thorn;ur &thorn;ov beo i come, : ase ri&yogh;t is forto done,</L>
<L>And, bote he &thorn;e finde &thorn;ere, : he wole maken &thorn;at &yogh;at a non,</L>
<L N="645">And wole beo siker &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne comest non more, : and sori wole a &yogh;en gon.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Am Rande nebengeschrieben.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ene kni&yogh;t heo brou&yogh;ten out of &thorn;e halle, : and blesseden him ech on,</L>
<L>And bi tei&yogh;ten god bo&thorn;e lif and soule, : fel and flesch and bon.</L>
<L>Forth he wende wel dreoriliche, : bote ase he nede moste it do.</L>
<L>And, ri&yogh;t ase he cam to &thorn;e &yogh;ate, : &thorn;e prior cam al so</L>
<L N="650">A &yogh;ein him with procession, : to loke hou it were.</L>
<L>A non so he hadde &thorn;e &yogh;ate on loke, : &thorn;ene kni&yogh;t heo founden &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&thorn;are was Joye and blisse i nov&yogh;, : &thorn;o huy to gadere come.<MILESTONE N="104" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>With song and o&thorn;ur melodie : &thorn;ane kny&yogh;t &thorn;are out huy nome,</L>
<L>Ant ladden him forth to churche a non, : ant &thorn;onkeden god wel faste.</L>
<L N="655">&thorn;is kni&yogh;t bi fore &thorn;e hei&yogh;e auctere : a knes wel sone him caste,</L>
<L>Ant stableliche in his oresones : fiftene dawes he lay,</L>
<L>And &thorn;onkede ore louerd &amp; on him cride : bo&thorn;e ny&yogh;t and day.</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e on his bare flesch : &thorn;e holie croiz he nam,</L>
<L>And wende to &thorn;e holie lond, : ant suy&thorn;e holi man bi cam.</L>
<L N="660">He ne tolde neuere eft nou&yogh;t of &thorn;e world, : bote ase he were euere in &thorn;ou&yogh;te</L>
<L>Ake wende euere forth wel stilleliche, : as he of no &thorn;ing ne rou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Ofte he tolde of alle &thorn;e men : &thorn;at in parays were;<NOTE PLACE="foot">p <I>in</I> parays <I>ist unn&ouml;thig mit dem Zeichen der Abk&uuml;rzung f&uuml;r</I> ar <I>versehen</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000255.tif" N="211"></L>
<L>As him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, grei&yogh;e monekes : mest Joye hadden &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>None manere men in so gret Joye, : ne in so grete honour he ne sei&yogh;:</L>
<L N="665">Hit nis no wonder sikerliche, : for &thorn;e ordre is noble and hei&yogh;.</L>
<L>Nov&thorn;e &yogh;e habbez alle i heord, : &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes grace</L>
<L>Hou seint paterik &thorn;ulke purgatorie : founde in &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>Forto warni men a boute : heore sunnes here to bete,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e loue of Jesu crist : and of is moder swete,</L>
<L N="670">Alle ower sunnes betez here, : as god ov wole grace sende,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e mouwen with oute pine : to parays hennes wende.</L>
<L>God leue us ovre sunnes here so biete, : for is holie wounde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at we ne &thorn;oruen in purgatorie : bi leue bote luyte stounde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
