<L>Men hem buried . bo&thorn;e in saam</L>
<L>Whon kyng Barachye . &thorn;er of herde.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a gret host . &thorn;ider he ferde</L>
<L>And brouhte &thorn;e bodies . in to &thorn;e Cit&eacute;&eacute;.</L>
<L N="790">Wi&thorn; muche Reuerence . and noblete.</L>
<L>And at heore toumbe . mony on</L>
<L>Miracle is wrouht . &thorn;orwh Godus loon.</L>
</LG>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000270.tif">
<HEAD>B. De sanctis Berlam &amp; Josaphat<LB>aus Ms. Harl. 4196, fol. 199 b. (im n&ouml;rdlichen Dialekt)</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Im Ms. beginnen die Verse gew&ouml;hnlich mit kleinen Anfangsbuchstaben.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>A</B> grete clerk, Damacene, gert writ</L>
<L>How saint barlam, &thorn;e gude hermit,</L>
<L>Techid Josaphat, a kynges sun,</L>
<L>&thorn;e law of crist how he solde kun.</L>
<L N="5">&amp; in his buke &thorn;us makes he mynde.</L>
<L>It bi fell when &thorn;e land of ynde</L>
<L>With cristen folk was all fulfild,</L>
<L>To serue god, als him seluyn willd:</L>
<L>A kyng &thorn;ar was &thorn;at did &thorn;am noy,<NOTE PLACE="foot">noy <I>f&uuml;r</I> anoy <I>auch</I> V.238.671.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10">And cristen folk fain walde he stroy,</L>
<L>&thorn;at to crist had deuociowne,</L>
<L>And namely monkes of religiowne.</L>
<L>He had a lady, meke and mylde,</L>
<L>Bot long &thorn;ai lifed with outen childe;</L>
<L N="15">&thorn;ai murned for &thorn;ai myght none gete.</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e last his wife wex grete,</L>
<L>And was deliuerd of a sun.</L>
<L>A fairer childe myght none be fun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng was fain, so was &thorn;e quene,</L>
<L N="20">For &thorn;ai had ane ayre &thorn;am bi twene.</L>
<L>&thorn;ai named him Josaphat in hy</L>
<L>Efter &thorn;aire law of mawmetri.</L>
<L>&thorn;an gert &thorn;e kyng sone efter send</L>
<L>All &thorn;e clerkes in &thorn;at cuntre kend,</L>
<L N="25">Bi fore his mawmettes to make mirth</L>
<L>In honore of &thorn;at childes birth.</L>
<L>&thorn;an cald he maysters of clergy,</L>
<L>Of art and of Astronomy;</L>
<L>He chesed of all fyfty &amp; fyue,</L>
<L N="30">And bad &thorn;ai solde luke by &thorn;aire liue,</L>
<L>And say &thorn;e suthe &amp; in nothing hide,</L>
<L>What of his &yogh;ung sun sold by tyde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In</I> sun <I>ist</I> u <I>aus</I> o <I>corrigirt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ai went &amp; soght omang &thorn;aire spels.</L>
<L>And sum of &thorn;am to &thorn;e kyng tels:</L>
<L N="35">His son sulde be of grete powere</L>
<L>And lyf in lykyng mony a zere;</L>
<L>Sum said he solde haue grete riches</L>
<L>And be honorde of more and les.</L>
<L>So was &thorn;are one &thorn;at mekill cowth,</L>
<L N="40">He said: syr, &thorn;is childe in his zowth</L>
<L>Sall cast him for to wit al wise</L>
<L>&thorn;e law &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;i self despise,</L>
<L>He sall noght dwell in &thorn;i kyngdom,</L>
<L>Bot to ane gretter sall he cum,</L>
<L N="45">And he sall ger &thorn;at law encrese</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou has soght ay to ger sese.</L>
<L>Of him self said he noght &thorn;us wele,</L>
<L>Bot of &thorn;e haly gast sumdele,</L>
<L>For, all yf he ware vnworthy,</L>
<L N="50">God lete him his counsail descry.</L>
<L>&thorn;an &thorn;e kyng had mekill care,</L>
<L>And thoght how it sulde for&thorn;er fare.</L>
<L>He ordand be his high counsaill</L>
<L>How he myght ger &thorn;at purpose fail,</L>
<L N="55">By tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e childe come of eld</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he myght him seluin weld.</L>
<L>Was ordand in &thorn;at same cete</L>
<L>A palais, where his sun suld be
<PB REF="00000271.tif" N="227"></L>
<L>Nurist up with mete and drink,</L>
<L N="60">&thorn;e best &thorn;at men myght efter think;</L>
<L>And with him did he childer zing,</L>
<L>&thorn;at wele couth harp sitoff and sing,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sitoff, <I>sonst</I> sitholl, afrz. citole, an instrument.</NOTE></L>
<L>And zong men, his seruandes to be.</L>
<L>And un to &thorn;am &thorn;us cumand he:</L>
<L N="65">&thorn;at noman sulde neuyn in &thorn;at stede</L>
<L>Now&thorn;er of sekenes, elde, ne dede,</L>
<L>Ne pouert, ne of ne desese,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne <I>vor</I> disese <I>st.</I> no.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at to his son myght oght displese,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at &thorn;ai solde both nyght &amp; day</L>
<L N="70">Make him mery all &thorn;at &thorn;ai may;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he solde on ilk a side</L>
<L>With myrth euermore be ocupide.</L>
<L>For so sall his hert haue no tome</L>
<L>To think on thinges &thorn;at er to come.</L>
<L N="75">Who so es seke, luke ze &thorn;am send</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e court, or it be kend,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at my sun no sekenes se,</L>
<L>Wharthurg he myght abaisced be.</L>
<L>Of crist &thorn;at noman to him neuyn,</L>
<L N="80">Ye tell him now&thorn;er of hell ne heuyn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ye. y <I>u.</I> &thorn; <I>sind im Ms. vollst&auml;ndig gleich; obwohl sonst anlaut. &yogh; nur durch z ausgedr&uuml;ckt wird, gibt nur</I> ye <I>einen passenden Sinn, wenn es nicht etwa statt</I> Ne <I>verschrieben ist.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Luke all swilk fare fro him be hid!</L>
<L>And als he bad, right so &thorn;ai did.</L>
<L>Ful mekill myrth was &thorn;am o mell.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e mene tyme &thorn;us bi fell:</L>
<L N="85">A knyght in court with &thorn;e kyng dweld,</L>
<L>&thorn;at cristes law full hertly held;</L>
<L>He luffed him lely als him list,</L>
<L>Bot noman wolde he &thorn;ar of wist.</L>
<L>In court he was most principal,</L>
<L N="90">And mayster of &thorn;e knyghtes all.</L>
<L>So on a day fell &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng</L>
<L>And &thorn;is ilk knyght went on huntyng</L>
<L>In to a forest &thorn;am to play.</L>
<L>And als &thorn;ai went so by &thorn;e way,</L>
<L N="95">&thorn;e knyght fand a man ligand &thorn;ore</L>
<L>&thorn;at with wilde bestes was wonden sore.</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e knyght hertly he praid</L>
<L>Him forto help, and &thorn;us he said:</L>
<L>Sum day, sir, haply sall &thorn;ou se</L>
<L N="100">&thorn;at my counsaile my comforth &thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">my <I>st.</I> may.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e kynght said: I will help gladly,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> kynght <I>st.</I> knyght.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot of &thorn;i help no nede haue I.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> if <I>st.</I> of.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e man answerde and said o none:</L>
<L>I am a leche of wurde allone;</L>
<L N="105">Who sum with wordes has any grege,<NOTE PLACE="foot">grege <I>st.</I> greue = grief.</NOTE></L>
<L>My medcyn may him sone releue.</L>
<L>&thorn;e knyght no tent &thorn;erto gun take;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Bei</I> &thorn;erto &thorn;erfore &thorn;eron <I>ist im Ms. h&auml;ufig das Zeichen der Abk&uuml;rzung f&uuml;r</I> er <I>ausgelassen; so</I> &thorn;to <I>auch</I> 663. 1119, &thorn;fore 175. 195. 308. 354. 383. 385. 528. 532. 713. 834. 1091. 1152, &thorn;on 338; <I>umgekehrt findet sich f&auml;lschlich das Zeichen der Abk&uuml;rzung f&uuml;r</I> er <I>bei</I> &thorn;e 405, &thorn;at 244. 876, &thorn;an 1111.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot souerainly for goddes sake</L>
<L>Vnto his hows he has him sent,</L>
<L N="110">And bad his seruandes to him tent</L>
<L>And ger him haue with more &amp; les</L>
<L>&thorn;at socoure myght be to his sekenes;</L>
<L>Grete kyndnes unto him he kyd.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e mene tyme &thorn;us bytyd:</L>
<L N="115">His enmyes had grete tene &thorn;at he</L>
<L>With &thorn;e kyng was so preue;</L>
<L>&thorn;arfore &thorn;ai cumpast on all wise</L>
<L>How &thorn;ai myght make &thorn;am full enmyse.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e kyng in priuete &thorn;ai tolde</L>
<L N="120">&thorn;at &thorn;is kynght desayue him wolde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> kynght <I>st.</I> knyght.</NOTE></L>
<L>To get his kyngdom, yf he may,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he lifed on cristes lay,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at mony ware of his assent</L>
<L>ffor to fulfill his fals entent.</L>
<L N="125">And, sir, &thorn;ai say, yf &thorn;ou will wit</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is be suth, we say &thorn;e zit,
<PB REF="00000272.tif" N="228"></L>
<L>Call him bi twene zow two allone</L>
<L>And say him &thorn;ou has new purpose tone,</L>
<L>How &thorn;is life es bot vanite</L>
<L N="130">And sodainly sall endid be,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou will leue &thorn;i kyndom,</L>
<L>And cristen man &thorn;o will be cum,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o <I>st.</I> &thorn;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou will take monkes wede</L>
<L>And make amendes in worde &amp; dede</L>
<L N="135">Vnto all &thorn;os &thorn;ou has repreued</L>
<L>For &thorn;at ilk saw &thorn;at &thorn;ow has loued;</L>
<L>And of counsail &thorn;ou sall him pray,</L>
<L>&thorn;an sall &thorn;ou se what he will say.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng did all efter &thorn;aire rede.</L>
<L N="140">He toke &thorn;e knyght in a preue stede</L>
<L>And tolde to him fro top and taile</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai had gyffen him in counsaile.</L>
<L>&thorn;e knyght, &thorn;at of no tresoun kend,</L>
<L>When he had herd &thorn;ir tales till end,</L>
<L N="145">He gert fro ioy, so was he paid.<NOTE PLACE="foot">gert <I>st.</I> gret.</NOTE></L>
<L>And to &thorn;e kyng all &thorn;us he said:</L>
<L>Loued be &thorn;e lord, &thorn;at &thorn;e has lent</L>
<L>His grace to take so trew entent!</L>
<L>And yf &thorn;ou be in so gude will,</L>
<L N="150">I rede &thorn;at &thorn;ou it sune fulfill,</L>
<L>For &thorn;an &thorn;ou sall haue mekil mede;</L>
<L>And in lang bidyng ligges drede.</L>
<L>&thorn;us when &thorn;e kyng his counsail knew,</L>
<L>&thorn;an trowed he wele &thorn;aire tales war trew:</L>
<L N="155">&thorn;ai tolde &thorn;e knyght wolde do him skathe.</L>
<L>And be his sembland semyd he wrathe;</L>
<L>Bot no &thorn;e lese zut said he noght.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e knyght sone him bi thoght</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e kyng was noght wele paid</L>
<L N="160">Of &thorn;o wordes &thorn;at he had said,</L>
<L>And wele he wend for to haue blame.</L>
<L>&thorn;an thoght he how he had at hame</L>
<L>A man &thorn;at cowth gyf medcyn gude</L>
<L>For wordes &thorn;at moued a mans mode.</L>
<L N="165">He went and tolde to &thorn;e seke man</L>
<L>&thorn;is tale als clerely als he can,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e kyng all how it ferd,</L>
<L>And on what manere he answerde.</L>
<L>&thorn;e man said: sir, &thorn;is I &thorn;e say:</L>
<L N="170">&thorn;e kyng trowes &thorn;ow wyll him bitray;</L>
<L>Bot sen I am of wordes leche,</L>
<L>Take tent and do als I &thorn;e teche!</L>
<L>&thorn;i counsail bus &thorn;e nedes mayntene,</L>
<L>&thorn;at no deceayt be in &thorn;e sene,</L>
<L N="175">And &thorn;erfore do als I &thorn;e tell,</L>
<L>&amp; furth in dainte sall &thorn;ow dwell:</L>
<L>Ger cut &thorn;ai hare and shaue &thorn;i crown,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ai <I>st.</I> &thorn;i.</NOTE></L>
<L>Like unto men of religione,</L>
<L>And do oway &thorn;i clething faire</L>
<L N="180">And cleth &thorn;e in sek or in hayre,</L>
<L>And cum so arely to morn</L>
<L>In &thorn;e palays &thorn;e kyng biforn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">bi forn. <I>der Strich &uuml;ber</I> n, <I>sonst</I> n <I>bezeichnend, findet sich bei</I> biforn <I>noch</I> V. 882. 1079. 1144, <I>bei</I> unicorn 589.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sun will he spir of &thorn;ine array;</L>
<L>&amp; unto him &thorn;an sall &thorn;ou say:</L>
<L N="185">Lo, lord, I am redy bowne</L>
<L>With &thorn;e to fare in felde &amp; town,</L>
<L>All yf &thorn;e way &thorn;at &thorn;ou will wende</L>
<L>Be un esy to fo or frende,</L>
<L>Yt sall be esy unto me,</L>
<L N="190">Als lang als I may wende with &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;ou in welthes vouched saue</L>
<L>Felawship of me to haue,</L>
<L>I sall be redy forto take</L>
<L>All erthly sorows for &thorn;i seke;<NOTE PLACE="foot">seke <I>f&uuml;r</I> sake, <I>wie</I> V. 672 scheme <I>f&uuml;r</I> schame.</NOTE></L>
<L N="195">&thorn;erfore graith &thorn;e &amp; lat us gang,</L>
<L>Wharto solde we tary lang?</L>
<L>&amp;, sir, yf &thorn;ou will dwell at hame</L>
<L>I am redy to do &thorn;e same,</L>
<L>For alway will I redy be</L>
<L N="200">In welle and wo to wende w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&thorn;an bi &thorn;ir wordes &thorn;e kyng wele knew</L>
<L>&thorn;at his knyght to him was trew.
<PB REF="00000273.tif" N="229"></L>
<L>And of &thorn;am &thorn;at had him acused</L>
<L>All &thorn;aire counsaile he refused,</L>
<L N="205">And said: omys &thorn;ai gun &thorn;am mell</L>
<L>Of his trew knyght swilk tales to tell.</L>
<L>&thorn;an was &thorn;e knyght in daynte more</L>
<L>&amp; ner frende &thorn;an he was bi fore.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is knyght now lat we be,</L>
<L N="210">&amp; to &thorn;e kyng son will we se,</L>
<L>&thorn;at in likyng his life gun lede,</L>
<L>Vnto he was past his barnhede.</L>
<L>&thorn;an in his hert wunder him thoght</L>
<L>Whi his fader so with him wroght,</L>
<L N="215">&amp; whi he toke swilk apurpose</L>
<L>To halde him &thorn;ore so lang in close.</L>
<L>To his menze he made his mone,</L>
<L>&amp; said: he liffed so lang allone</L>
<L>&amp; had none ayre of erth ne flode,</L>
<L N="220">&thorn;at mete ne drink did him no gude,</L>
<L>He had no talent to his mete,</L>
<L>For he no kyndely ayre myght gete.</L>
<L>&amp; sone when &thorn;ai &thorn;ir wordes herd,</L>
<L>&thorn;ai tolde his fader all how it ferd,</L>
<L N="225">&amp; how he had ferly wharfore</L>
<L>&thorn;at his fader so held him &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he myght noght be at &thorn;e large.</L>
<L>&thorn;is was to him a heuy charge.</L>
<L>When his fader &thorn;ir tales herd,</L>
<L N="230">He said he suld no more be sperd.</L>
<L>Horses and hernays ordand he,</L>
<L>&thorn;e semeliest &thorn;at men myght se,</L>
<L>&thorn;at his sun myght on playing ride;</L>
<L>&amp; mynstralsy on ilk a syde;</L>
<L N="235">&amp; men he had solde go bifore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">had <I>st.</I> bad <I>auch</I> V. 1145.</NOTE></L>
<L>To serche &thorn;e way &amp; seke aywhore,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at his sun no syght solde se</L>
<L>&thorn;at unto him myght noyand be.</L>
<L>&thorn;us raide he furth bi diuers days,</L>
<L N="240">&amp; had sere solace by sere ways.</L>
<L>And on a day so als he rade</L>
<L>And his menze grete myrthes made,</L>
<L>Two men bi fore him gun he find,</L>
<L>&thorn;at one was leper, &thorn;e to&thorn;er blind.</L>
<L N="245">He had meruayl what it myght mene,</L>
<L>For sekenes had he neuer sene.</L>
<L>He askid his men whi &thorn;ai ware so.</L>
<L>&amp; sone one of &thorn;am tolde him to:</L>
<L>Sir, &thorn;ai haue sekenes, wele we ken,</L>
<L N="250">&thorn;at cumes oft tymes to erthly men.</L>
<L>He askid yf all men so sulde be.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai said nay. and &thorn;an said he:</L>
<L>Whareby may ze knaw &thorn;e man<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> wharely.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at sall be &thorn;us? say, yf ze can;</L>
<L N="255">And whe&thorn;er &thorn;is sekenes sal be mend,</L>
<L>Or it sall last with outen end?</L>
<L>&thorn;ai say: sir, now&thorn;er olde ne zing</L>
<L>Wote what sall be in tyme cumyng.</L>
<L>When Josaphat &thorn;is understode,</L>
<L N="260">&thorn;is meteyng meruaild all his mode</L>
<L>&amp; put mekill of his myrth owai.</L>
<L>&amp; als he went a no&thorn;er way,</L>
<L>He met a man, was wonder old,</L>
<L>Croked and cumberd, koghand for cold,</L>
<L N="265">Lame he was in lith and lim,</L>
<L>With nese dropand &amp; eghen dym;</L>
<L>His handes tremblid, his teth roted,</L>
<L>He spak so dym men demyd he doted.</L>
<L>When Josaphat &thorn;is sight had sene,</L>
<L N="270">He had meruail what it myght mene,</L>
<L>&amp; said to &thorn;am &thorn;at war bi side:</L>
<L>What gers zon man swilk tenes bi|tyde?</L>
<L>&thorn;ai said: syr, he es of grete elde,</L>
<L>And mony zeres makes him vnwelde.</L>
<L N="275">In how fele zeres, &thorn;an askes he,</L>
<L>Sall a man cum to swilk degre?</L>
<L>&thorn;ai say: in foure score zere, we kest,</L>
<L>Or els in fyue score at &thorn;e ferest.</L>
<L>He askis &thorn;an: what sall for&thorn;erfall?</L>
<L N="280">&thorn;ai said: syr, ded es end of all.</L>
<L>And zit he askis &thorn;am in &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> stede:</L>
<L>How may ze knaw who ssal be dede?</L>
<L>&thorn;ai say: sir, ded, right wele we ken,</L>
<L>Es comun to all erthly men;</L>
<L N="285">To riches takes he no reward,<NOTE PLACE="foot">reward = regard <I>auch</I> V. 474.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne for pouert sall none be spard.
<PB REF="00000274.tif" N="230"></L>
<L>&thorn;an of &thorn;is thing so thoght &thorn;is childe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he refusid all werkes wilde,</L>
<L>&amp; hertly couayt he to here</L>
<L N="290">Swilk lessons, whore he myght &thorn;am here.</L>
<L>All yf men made him myrth &amp; play,</L>
<L>He thoght euer how it solde oway</L>
<L>With elde &amp; euyll &amp; sorows sere;</L>
<L>&thorn;at merrid him oft of mery chere.</L>
<L N="295">Bot euermore in his fader sight</L>
<L>Shewed he myrth with all his myght,</L>
<L>&thorn;at it solde noght be knawen ne kid</L>
<L>What will with in his hert was hid.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at same tyme bi fell it so:</L>
<L N="300">In a forest, noght fer &thorn;ar fro,</L>
<L>Wond a monk, &thorn;at Berlam hight,</L>
<L>&thorn;at honord god both day &amp; nyght.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is ilk kyng oft of herd he tell,</L>
<L>And of his sun how it bi fell.</L>
<L N="305">Thurgh &thorn;e haly gast he had warnyng</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e childes purpose in all thing,</L>
<L>How he wolde luf &thorn;e werld nomore.</L>
<L>And sone he ordand him &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>How he myght with sum suttil gin</L>
<L N="310">Entre &thorn;at childe palays with in,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e childe to speke sumdele;</L>
<L>For so he hopid all solde be wele.</L>
<L>He ordand him a marchand wede,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;at same Cete he zede,</L>
<L N="315">And to &thorn;at palays gun he pas</L>
<L>Whare Josaphat in wunand was.</L>
<L>One of his men sone he mett,<NOTE PLACE="foot">semyng <I>st.</I> semyd <I>verschrieben?</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And on &thorn;is manere he him grett.</L>
<L>He said: sir, I am a marchand,</L>
<L N="320">&thorn;at has traueld in diuers land;</L>
<L>A precius stone I haue to sell,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e uertuis I sall &thorn;e tell:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> uertius; <I>daf&uuml;r</I> uertus V. 342. 478.</NOTE></L>
<L>To blind men will it gyf &thorn;e sight,</L>
<L>And make dom men to speke ful right,<NOTE PLACE="foot">dom <I>st.</I> domb.</NOTE></L>
<L N="325">Defe men will it make to here,</L>
<L>And gyf unwisemen wit ful clere;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e kynges son I will it gyf</L>
<L>To make him more in likyng lyf;<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyf <I>aus</I> luf <I>corr.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;arfore lede me to him &thorn;is tyde!</L>
<L N="330">&thorn;e to&thorn;er said: sir, nay, habide!<NOTE PLACE="foot">habide <I>mit unorgan.</I> h, <I>wie</I> V. 639 holde <I>st.</I> olde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Yf &thorn;ou to him will haue entre,</L>
<L>&thorn;i precius stone &thorn;ou lat me se,</L>
<L>Yf it be trew I here &thorn;e tell,</L>
<L>For of swilk maters I me mell.</L>
<L N="335">Berlam said: &thorn;at will I wele,</L>
<L>Bot first I say &thorn;e for &thorn;i sele</L>
<L>Swilk a condicion has my stone:</L>
<L>What man or childe so lokes &thorn;eron,</L>
<L>Bot yf his eghen be gude &amp; clere</L>
<L N="340">Wit outen euyll on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>And bot him self be clene &amp; chaste,</L>
<L>Els all his uertus will it waste;</L>
<L>&thorn;arfore, yf &thorn;ow defaud oght fele<NOTE PLACE="foot">defaud <I>st.</I> defaut; 733 defautes.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;ine eghen, &thorn;at &thorn;ou se noght wele,</L>
<L N="345">Or els unchaste yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>Couait noght my stone to se!</L>
<L>And to me semyng it bi &thorn;i chere</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ine eghen war noght ful clere;</L>
<L>&amp; yf &thorn;ou be chaste of body,</L>
<L N="350">&thorn;at wote &thorn;i self better &thorn;an I;</L>
<L>&thorn;e kynges son es bot a childe,</L>
<L>With filth of sin es he noght filde,</L>
<L>His eghen er clere &amp; nothing dym;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore my stone es gude for him.</L>
<L N="355">&thorn;e seruande said: yf it so be,</L>
<L>I pray &thorn;e shew it noght to me;</L>
<L>Of my mayster &thorn;ou may haue mede.</L>
<L>&thorn;an in to hall he gun him lede.</L>
<L>&amp; sune when Josaphat gun him se,</L>
<L N="360">He hopid &thorn;at a haly man was he;</L>
<L>He welkumd him full wirshiply.</L>
<L>&amp; Berlam said to him in hy:</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou with wirship welkums me,</L>
<L>Ensample, sir, I sall tell &thorn;e</L>
<L N="365">And a tale for &thorn;i welkumyng,</L>
<L>How it fell ones with a kyng.
<PB REF="00000275.tif" N="231"></L>
<L>A reall kyng in riche wede</L>
<L>To pouer men did swilk a dede:</L>
<L>Bi fell a day furth gun he fare,</L>
<L N="370">Rideand in a reall chare.</L>
<L>&thorn;are come o gains him in &thorn;e way<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> o ganis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pouer men, ragged in euyll aray,</L>
<L>Sore, and unsemely to syght.</L>
<L>&amp; sone &thorn;e kyng him self doun light;</L>
<L N="375">He kneled &thorn;ore bi fore &thorn;aire fete</L>
<L>&amp; kissed &thorn;am with sembland swete,</L>
<L>Of his gude he gaf &thorn;am &thorn;are;</L>
<L>&amp; went ogaine &thorn;an to his chare.</L>
<L>&thorn;an o&thorn;er princes &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> with him zede</L>
<L N="380">Had grete dedeyne of &thorn;is ilk dede,</L>
<L>&amp; said: for &thorn;at he light so doun,</L>
<L>He did dishonure un to &thorn;e crown.</L>
<L>Full euyll apaid &thorn;erfore ware &thorn;ai;</L>
<L>Bot to him durst &thorn;ai nothing say.</L>
<L N="385">&thorn;erfore to his bro&thorn;er &thorn;ai went</L>
<L>&amp; tolde to him all &thorn;aire entent,</L>
<L>How &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng did in &thorn;e gate</L>
<L>&thorn;at was gretely o gains his state,</L>
<L>&amp; prays him &thorn;at he wald him blame,</L>
<L N="390">&thorn;at he nomore sold do &thorn;at same.</L>
<L>His bro&thorn;er &thorn;an went to &thorn;e kyng</L>
<L>&amp; tolde unto him of &thorn;is thing,</L>
<L>&amp; said: sir, for &thorn;ine awin bi houe</L>
<L>So to &thorn;i self no siche reproue.(!)<NOTE PLACE="foot">So <I>st.</I> Do?</NOTE></L>
<L N="395">&thorn;e kyng graunted als he wold bid,</L>
<L>And in his hert all still he hid;</L>
<L>He walde noht blame for his saw,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fehlt</I> him.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot wele he thoght to ger him knaw</L>
<L>&thorn;at pouerte was more to prais</L>
<L N="400">&thorn;an werldly riches bi sere wais.</L>
<L>Acustum used &thorn;ai in &thorn;at stede:</L>
<L>When any man was demyd to ded,</L>
<L>A beme solde blaw his dur bi forn,</L>
<L>When he solde be ded on &thorn;e morn.</L>
<L N="405">&thorn;e kyng ordand at euyn late</L>
<L>&amp; gert blaw &thorn;at beme in &thorn;e gate</L>
<L>Euyn bi fore his bro&thorn;er dure.</L>
<L>&amp; when his bro&thorn;er herd how it fure,</L>
<L>Allas, he said, &thorn;at I was born!</L>
<L N="410">&thorn;is menes I mun be ded to morn;</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng, my bro&thorn;er, es with me wrath,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at I warned him of his skath.</L>
<L>His wife was wo &amp; will of rede</L>
<L>&thorn;at hir lorde sulde be done to ded.</L>
<L N="415">His testament &thorn;an gun he make,</L>
<L>&amp; all &thorn;at nyght with wo &thorn;ai wake.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e morn &thorn;ai cled &thorn;am all in blak,</L>
<L>His wyfe &amp; childer &amp; all &thorn;e pak,</L>
<L>&thorn;ai went un to &thorn;e kynges zate</L>
<L N="420">&amp; stode &thorn;ore greteand in &thorn;e gate.</L>
<L>&amp; when &thorn;e kyng wist he was &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>He bad bring him furth him biforn.</L>
<L>He kneled and cried mercy him to.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng said: fole, whi fares &thorn;ou so?</L>
<L N="425">sen &thorn;ou so dredes &thorn;i bro&thorn;er warnyng,</L>
<L>To wham &thorn;ou has trispast nothing,</L>
<L>Whi blames &thorn;ou me &thorn;an, if I drede</L>
<L>Or to &thorn;e warnyng walde take hede<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> orto.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of my lord, &thorn;at last sall ay,</L>
<L N="430">To wham I trispas ilk a day?</L>
<L>&thorn;at blawes to me with diuers blast</L>
<L>&amp; warnes me of dome &thorn;at sal be last,</L>
<L>Whore ilk a man a count sal zelde</L>
<L>Of all his dedes in zowth and elde.</L>
<L N="435">&thorn;an gert &thorn;e kyng in &thorn;at same nyght</L>
<L>Ordaine a kyst of siluer bright;</L>
<L>&thorn;ai gylt it nobilly for &thorn;e nones,</L>
<L>&amp; fild it full of ded men bones</L>
<L>&thorn;at now ware taken out of &thorn;e molde,</L>
<L N="440">&amp; lokkid with a kay of golde.</L>
<L>A no&thorn;er kyst &thorn;an gert he make,</L>
<L>&amp; all with out was pik ful blak,</L>
<L>With in it was faire for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L>&amp; fild with gold and precius stones.</L>
<L N="445">&thorn;an for &thorn;e men he efter sent</L>
<L>&thorn;at first unto his bro&thorn;er went,</L>
<L>Wharfore &thorn;at he him blamed so.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai ware cumen, he said &thorn;am to:</L>
<L>&thorn;ir kistes &thorn;at er wroght on &thorn;is wise,</L>
<L N="450">Gose prays &thorn;am to &thorn;e uerray prise!
<PB REF="00000276.tif" N="232"></L>
<L>&thorn;e kyst of golde, &thorn;ai understode,</L>
<L>Might wele be prayessed to mekyl golde;</L>
<L>&amp; sethin &thorn;ai say: &thorn;e kyst of blak</L>
<L>Es noght to prayse, bot more to lak.</L>
<L N="455">So when &thorn;e kyng &thorn;aire willes wist,</L>
<L>He gert opin &thorn;e fairer kyst:</L>
<L>&amp; of it come so ful a smell</L>
<L>&thorn;at no man myght nereand it dwell,</L>
<L>So stynkyd &thorn;e bones &thorn;arin war done.</L>
<L N="460">&amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e kyng said unto &thorn;am sone:</L>
<L>Lo, sirs, he said, &thorn;is kist es lyke</L>
<L>Unto zoure self, for ze er slike:</L>
<L>With outen faire with cloth &amp; skyn,</L>
<L>With in ful ful with filth of syn.</L>
<L N="465">&thorn;at o&thorn;er kist &thorn;an cumand he,</L>
<L>&thorn;at simple semyd, sulde opin be:</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;erof come a full swete are,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ar&eacute; <I>st.</I> aire, <I>wie</I> v. 554 &thorn;are <I>st.</I> &thorn;aire.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; tresore was &thorn;arein full fayre.</L>
<L>&thorn;an said &thorn;e kyng: sirs, swilk er &thorn;ai</L>
<L N="470">&thorn;at I did wirship in &thorn;e wai:</L>
<L>All yf &thorn;ai foul with outen seme,</L>
<L>With in &thorn;ai er full faire to deme;</L>
<L>Wharfore ilk man &thorn;at witty es</L>
<L>Sulde take reward to &thorn;aire worthines.</L>
<L N="475">And, syr, &thorn;is es fulfild in &thorn;e,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou with wirschip welcumd me</L>
<L>&thorn;at semes to &thorn;e a simple knaue,</L>
<L>For uertus &thorn;at &thorn;ou hopes I haue.</L>
<L>&thorn;e childe was of &thorn;ir wordes wele paid.</L>
<L N="480">&thorn;an berlam more un to him sayd:</L>
<L>He tolde him how &thorn;is werld bigan,</L>
<L>&amp; so furst of &thorn;e syn of man,</L>
<L>How crist was born here of oure kyn</L>
<L>So for to saue man saul of syn,</L>
<L N="485">How he on rode was ded with payn,</L>
<L>&amp; sethyn how right he rase o gain;</L>
<L>&amp; sethin he carpid what was to com,</L>
<L>Of ded and of &thorn;e day of dome,</L>
<L>And who ilk man solde haue mede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">who <I>st.</I> whore <I>auch</I> V. 814.</NOTE></L>
<L N="490">Be saued or dampned efter his dede,</L>
<L>&amp; sethin, how it es grete foly</L>
<L>To trow or trist in maumettry,</L>
<L>Or to &thorn;aire tales for to take hede,</L>
<L>Or couait of &thorn;am any mede:</L>
<L N="495">For to a man es foly grete</L>
<L>To couayt &thorn;at he may noght gete,</L>
<L>Or for to trow all &thorn;at he heres,</L>
<L>Namely of &thorn;am &thorn;at lesynges leres.</L>
<L>And, sir, he said, &thorn;at shew I sale</L>
<L N="500">By any ensample of a tale:</L>
<L>Unto a foster so it be tyd:<NOTE PLACE="foot">foster <I>st.</I> forster.</NOTE></L>
<L>O mang his gamin he toke a brid.</L>
<L>&amp; als he walde &thorn;e brid haue slone,</L>
<L>&thorn;e brid spak and said onone:</L>
<L N="505">Yt helpes &thorn;e noght to haue me ded,</L>
<L>&amp; my lyfe may stand &thorn;e in stede;</L>
<L>I am noght worth &thorn;i wombe to fill,</L>
<L>&amp; wit can I lere &thorn;e, yf &thorn;ou will.</L>
<L>&thorn;e forster said: &thorn;at walde I fayne.</L>
<L N="510">&amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e brid answerde ogaine:</L>
<L>Gyf me leue to lyght on zon tre,</L>
<L>&amp; I sall &thorn;e thece wisdomes thre.<NOTE PLACE="foot">thece <I>ist &uuml;bergeschrieben; mit</I> h <I>auch</I> V. 1059 thechid.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e forster said &thorn;an: er tow sleghe!</L>
<L>On &thorn;at forwarde he lete him fleghe.</L>
<L N="515">On &thorn;e tre &thorn;an sat &thorn;e nyght gale,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e forster he tolde &thorn;is tale,</L>
<L>&thorn;at es contened here in two vers,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;in in ynglys to rehers:</L>
<L>Non pro amissis doleas nec omne quod andis</L>
<L>Credas nec cupias id quod h(ab)ere nequis:</L>
<L>Man, murn &thorn;ou noght on euyn ne morn</L>
<L N="520">For thing &thorn;ou wate &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;ou haues lorn;</L>
<L>Ne trow noght all &thorn;at &thorn;ou heres say;</L>
<L>Ne zern noght &thorn;at &thorn;ou noght get may.</L>
<L>And yf &thorn;ou think wele on &thorn;ir thre,</L>
<L>Oft tymes &thorn;e may &thorn;e better be.</L>
<L N="525">&thorn;e foster held him full wele payd.<NOTE PLACE="foot">foster <I>st.</I> forster.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;an &thorn;e brid more to him said:
<PB REF="00000277.tif" N="233"></L>
<L>Man, and &thorn;ou wist what &thorn;ou has lorn,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou walde nothing be fain &thorn;er forn</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou walde lat me go so tyte:</L>
<L N="530">In my wombe es a margarite,</L>
<L>A precius stone, and it es more</L>
<L>&thorn;an es a gripe egg; and &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>A grete los has &thorn;ou lost &thorn;is day.</L>
<L>&thorn;an &thorn;e forster to him self gan say:</L>
<L N="535">Walde god I had &thorn;e here o gaine!</L>
<L>And to take it he did his paine,</L>
<L>And said: walde &thorn;ou cum me untill,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou solde wende at &thorn;ine awin will,</L>
<L>I sall do all what &thorn;ou will bid.</L>
<L N="540">&amp; on &thorn;is wise answerde &thorn;e brid:</L>
<L>&thorn;ou ert a fole, &thorn;at se I wele:</L>
<L>My wisdomes prophetes &thorn;e no dele:<NOTE PLACE="foot">prophetes <I>st.</I> profites.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ou zernes me &thorn;at &thorn;ou may noght gete,</L>
<L>&amp; trows I haue a stone so grete,</L>
<L N="545">When all my body es noght to se</L>
<L>So grete als half an egg solde be;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou murnes for I am went &thorn;e fro;</L>
<L>All my thre wisdoms loses &thorn;ou so,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;i wit &thorn;ou ert bygilde.</L>
<L N="550">&thorn;an said berlam unto &thorn;e childe:</L>
<L>Sir, &thorn;ai do right swilk foly</L>
<L>&thorn;at trowes in tales of mawmettry,</L>
<L>&thorn;at wirships and giffes &thorn;are ofrandes</L>
<L>To &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ai wirk w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;aire handes,</L>
<L N="555">Or say &thorn;at &thorn;aire mawmettes &thorn;am saues,</L>
<L>Of wham &thorn;am self &thorn;e kepeyng haues.</L>
<L>&thorn;an tolde he of &thorn;e uanite</L>
<L>&amp; wrechidnes &thorn;at in werld may be,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;am &thorn;at foloes &thorn;aire flessh &amp; will</L>
<L N="560">&amp; suffers &thorn;e sawl perish &amp; spill,</L>
<L>&amp; takes more tent to uanite</L>
<L>&thorn;an to &thorn;e blis &thorn;at euer sall be,</L>
<L>&amp; will noght knaw what es to cum,</L>
<L>Of ded, ne of &thorn;e day of dome.</L>
<L N="565">He said: syr, &thorn;ai &thorn;at will do so</L>
<L>May wele be like a man un to,</L>
<L>&thorn;at in a forest here biforn</L>
<L>Was pursued with ane unicorn.</L>
<L>&amp; als he feld &amp; he toke no kepe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">feld <I>st.</I> fled.</NOTE></L>
<L N="570">He fell in to a dyke full depe;</L>
<L>Obut he wayted with mekil wogh,</L>
<L>&amp; gat hald bi a litell bogh;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> boght.</NOTE></L>
<L>His fete he fest in &thorn;e dyke side.</L>
<L>&amp; be &thorn;at bogh als he gun bide,</L>
<L N="575">He saw a blak mows &amp; a white</L>
<L>Obout &thorn;at bogh so fast gun bite</L>
<L>&thorn;at almost had &thorn;ai ettyn it sunder;</L>
<L>Bi neth he saw a no&thorn;er wonder:</L>
<L>Doun in &thorn;at pit a dragon grete,</L>
<L N="580">Gapeand wide him for to gete;</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;e bank his fete obout</L>
<L>Foure serpent heuedes he saw cum out;</L>
<L>&amp; a bogh obouen his hand:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> haud.</NOTE></L>
<L>A hony camb &thorn;are saw he stand,</L>
<L N="585">&thorn;at couaited he in hand to hent,</L>
<L>To o&thorn;er perils he toke no tent.</L>
<L>By sum men here so es it sene,</L>
<L>For &thorn;us &thorn;is tale es for to mene:</L>
<L>&thorn;e unicorn &thorn;at call I dede,</L>
<L N="590">&thorn;at pursues us in ilk a stede;</L>
<L>&thorn;e dike whore we fall, when we fle,</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;is werld may likkend be,</L>
<L>&thorn;at full of angers euer es talde;</L>
<L>Bot bi a bogh &thorn;an take we halde:</L>
<L N="595">&thorn;at es oure life, whorein we traist;</L>
<L>Bot two mise bud make us a bayst,</L>
<L>&thorn;e blak and white, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> on it knaws:<NOTE PLACE="foot">knaws <I>st.</I> gnaws.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at es &thorn;e nyght &amp; day &thorn;at daws,</L>
<L>Whilk two will neuer more stand in stede,</L>
<L N="600">Bot flit us furth, till we be dede;</L>
<L>&thorn;e hill, whore he saw foure serpentes,</L>
<L>Es mans body of foure Elementes,</L>
<L>Thurgh whilk, yf it be gouerned ill,</L>
<L>&thorn;e body in litell space may spill;</L>
<L N="605">&thorn;e dragon may be like &thorn;e fende,
<PB REF="00000278.tif" N="234"></L>
<L>&thorn;at euer es faine us for to shende</L>
<L>&amp; for to wyn us in to his wombe;</L>
<L>&thorn;an may men mene &thorn;e hony combe</L>
<L>Un to welth of &thorn;is werldes riches,</L>
<L N="610">&thorn;at so swete to sum men es,</L>
<L>&thorn;are to take &thorn;ai so mekill hede</L>
<L>&thorn;at of no perils haue &thorn;ai drede,</L>
<L>Now&thorn;er of god, ne of &thorn;e day of dome,</L>
<L>Ne of perils &thorn;at er to come.</L>
<L N="615">&amp; who so with &thorn;e werld so lendes,</L>
<L>Or tristes in luf of lifand frendes,</L>
<L>He may be likkend un to a man,</L>
<L>Of wham ensaumple tell I can:</L>
<L>A kyng sum tyme of grete powere</L>
<L N="620">Had a sun, was to him dere,</L>
<L>To wham he gaf riches plente,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;i fader has done to &thorn;e;</L>
<L>He bad him wax and multipli.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;an &thorn;is childe fell to foly,</L>
<L N="625">&amp; wrong his fader gude he spend.</L>
<L>And fell ogains &thorn;e zeres end:</L>
<L>&thorn;at kyng warned his sun to cum</L>
<L>Un to his court, to here his dome</L>
<L>&amp; graith a count &thorn;ore for to zelde</L>
<L N="630">Of godes &thorn;at he had in his welde.</L>
<L>&thorn;an had &thorn;e kynges sun mekil care,</L>
<L>For all his gudes so wasted ware.</L>
<L>He thoght &thorn;at he had frendes thre,</L>
<L>&amp; in his nede proue &thorn;am will he;</L>
<L N="635">To &thorn;am he had gyfen grete riches,</L>
<L>&thorn;arfore his trist more in &thorn;am es.</L>
<L>&thorn;e first he had gyfen mekill pelf</L>
<L>&amp; lufed him wele more &thorn;an him self,</L>
<L>&thorn;e secund lufed he holde &amp; zing</L>
<L N="640">Euyn als him self in alkyn thing,</L>
<L>&thorn;e third frende lufed he noght so wele,</L>
<L>Bot les &thorn;an him self bi sum dele.</L>
<L>Un to &thorn;e first frende first he went,</L>
<L>&amp; tolde un to him his entent,</L>
<L N="645">And prayd him for to be his belde</L>
<L>Un to &thorn;e court a count to zelde,</L>
<L>&amp; help him in his sorows strang,</L>
<L>Sen he had shewed him luf so lang.</L>
<L>He answerde &amp; said: sertes, nay,</L>
<L N="650">With my frendes make I fest &thorn;is day,</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore I may noght pas &thorn;is stede,</L>
<L>&amp; I wote wele &thorn;ou mun be dede;</L>
<L>Haue here a cloth to couer &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;ine awin syte sal noght se,</L>
<L N="655">&amp; o&thorn;er help hete I &thorn;e none.</L>
<L>&thorn;an went he furth full wil of wone.</L>
<L>Sone come he to his secund frende,</L>
<L>&amp; tolde un to him &thorn;is tale til ende</L>
<L>How he was cald a count to zelde,</L>
<L N="660">And prayd him for to be his belde,</L>
<L>Als he to him bifore was bayn.</L>
<L>&thorn;at o&thorn;er said: I walde ful fain,</L>
<L>Bot now I may noght tent &thorn;erto</L>
<L>For charge and thing I haue to do;</L>
<L N="665">I will wende with &thorn;e all &thorn;e gate</L>
<L>Till &thorn;ou cum to kynges zate,</L>
<L>Bot home ogaine &thorn;an bus me turne.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kynges sun &thorn;an sore gan murne.</L>
<L>Un to &thorn;e third frende went he sone</L>
<L N="670">For wham he had ful litell done,</L>
<L>His noy he tolde to him by name,</L>
<L>&amp; said: sir, I may noght for scheme</L>
<L>Hertly helping of &thorn;e craue,</L>
<L>For littell on &thorn;e I uouched saue,</L>
<L N="675">&amp; &thorn;ai &thorn;at l gafe gude plente</L>
<L>Full fantly now has failed me;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fantly <I>st.</I> faintly. v. 999.</NOTE></L>
<L>I may noght ask of &thorn;e bi skill,</L>
<L>Bot it &thorn;ou wolde of &thorn;i gude will,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> it <I>st.</I> if.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wende with me a litell space</L>
<L N="680">&amp; help to get my fader grace.</L>
<L>He answerd &thorn;an with meri chere,</L>
<L>&amp; said: &thorn;i dedes er to me dere,</L>
<L>I know &thorn;e for my faithfull frende,</L>
<L>And gladly will I with &thorn;e wende</L>
<L N="685">And pray for &thorn;e &thorn;i fader un to,</L>
<L>And els what &thorn;ou will bid me do.</L>
<L>Berlam said: sir, &thorn;is was a frende!</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;us &thorn;is tale may be remende:</L>
<L>God es &thorn;is kyng, sir, wele we ken,</L>
<L N="690">And his suns er all cristen men,
<PB REF="00000279.tif" N="235"></L>
<L>To wham he gifes all erthly thing;</L>
<L>Bot sethin he calles us to rekenyg,<NOTE PLACE="foot">rekenyg <I>st.</I> rekenyng.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at es with ded when &thorn;is life endes;</L>
<L>&thorn;an nedes us for to seke oure frendes;</L>
<L N="695">&thorn;e first frende es &thorn;is werldely gude,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ebbes &amp; flowes here als &thorn;e flode,</L>
<L>Whore in we trist, &amp; folows fast,</L>
<L>Bot, when &thorn;e ded cum es at &thorn;e last,</L>
<L>We get no help of him &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L N="700">Bot of a cloth, oure cors to hide.</L>
<L>&thorn;e secund frende &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> we trist in</L>
<L>Er wyfe and childer and o&thorn;er kyn:</L>
<L>&thorn;ai help us noght when we nede haue,</L>
<L>Bot with us wende &thorn;ai to oure graue,</L>
<L N="705">And &thorn;e&thorn;(i)n oway &thorn;ai wende ful swyft<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> &thorn;e&thorn;n <I>st.</I> &thorn;e&thorn;in.</NOTE></L>
<L>Home ogaine, oure gude to skyft.</L>
<L>&thorn;e third frende &thorn;at es charite,</L>
<L>And with us alway wendes he:</L>
<L>&thorn;at es prayers and almusdedes,</L>
<L N="710">&thorn;ai may us help in all oure nedes</L>
<L>And hertly hope &thorn;at we sall haue</L>
<L>In god, &thorn;at he oure sawles will saue.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore oure mys we solde amend</L>
<L>&amp; almus fast bifore us send,</L>
<L N="715">To serue us whore we soiorn sale.</L>
<L>So may men lere by a tale:</L>
<L>In a cete nobill for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L>&thorn;is custum used &thorn;ai ilk zere ones:</L>
<L>A kyng to make, noght of &thorn;aire awin,</L>
<L N="720">Bot of a strange man &amp; unknawin;</L>
<L>To pouert solde &thorn;ai take no hede</L>
<L>Bot cleth him sone in kynges wede,</L>
<L>And gif him and plain powere(!)<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vor</I> and <I>fehlt ein Sbst</I>. (aught?).</NOTE></L>
<L>To do what him list all &thorn;at zere;</L>
<L N="725">At his dome solde be all bi dene.</L>
<L>Bot sethin, when &thorn;at he lest sold wene,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e Cytezayns he solde be tone</L>
<L>&amp; fro &thorn;at Cete led allone,</L>
<L>He solde be nakynd in &thorn;at wile</L>
<L N="730">And put in to ane un cuth yle,</L>
<L>Whore he solde dy for faut of fode.</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e last ane under stode</L>
<L>&thorn;at he solde swilk defautes fele;</L>
<L>&thorn;arfore he did wisely and wele:</L>
<L N="735">Sere gudes he sent oft sithes bifore,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he myght haue, when come &thorn;ore.</L>
<L>Sethin when his pople had him repreued,</L>
<L>With his awin gudes he was releued.</L>
<L>Sir, so solde ilk man him awise</L>
<L N="740">And in &thorn;is werld wirk als &thorn;e wise,</L>
<L>To send bi fore sum almus dede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at may him help when he has nede.</L>
<L>When berlam &thorn;us w<SUP>t</SUP> wordes bolde<NOTE PLACE="foot">740-743 <I>sind enger zusammengeschrieben, wie auch</I> v. 887-890.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e kynges sun &thorn;ir tales had tolde,</L>
<L N="745">&thorn;e childe said he walde w<SUP>t</SUP> him wende</L>
<L>&amp; now&thorn;er let for fo ne frende,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng his fader he wolde forsake</L>
<L>&amp; berlam furth his fader make.</L>
<L>&thorn;an said berlam: yf &thorn;ou will so,</L>
<L N="750">Ensaumple sall I tell &thorn;e un to,</L>
<L>How it bi fell with swilk a childe</L>
<L>&thorn;at gaf him fro all werkes wilde.</L>
<L>A prince son of a gude cete,</L>
<L>&thorn;at with riche ayres myght maried be,</L>
<L N="755">Als he went on a day playand,</L>
<L>A pouer mans dogter saw he stand,</L>
<L>Wirkand hir werk with eger mode</L>
<L>And loueand god euer als sho stode.</L>
<L>&thorn;e zong childe stode and bihelde</L>
<L N="760">What thankyng scho to god gun zelde.</L>
<L>In his hert he was wele paid.</L>
<L>&amp; all &thorn;us un to hir he said:</L>
<L>Woman, what menes &thorn;ou in &thorn;i mode</L>
<L>&thorn;at loues god with hert so gude?</L>
<L N="765">&thorn;ou thankes him in &thorn;i myscheue,</L>
<L>Als he had gifen &thorn;e grete releue;</L>
<L>Say me &thorn;e suth whi &thorn;ou dose so.</L>
<L>&thorn;e mayden answerde &thorn;us &thorn;ar to:
<PB REF="00000280.tif" N="236"></L>
<L>A litell salue, sir, suth it es,</L>
<L N="770">May medcyn a full grete sekenes:</L>
<L>So pouer prayers and pouer dede</L>
<L>Of god may get us ful grete mede;</L>
<L>Here of oure self we haue bot syn,</L>
<L>Oure gudenes of god bus bigyn;</L>
<L N="775">To me grete giftes gyfen has he,</L>
<L>For to his liknes made he me</L>
<L>&amp; gaf me wit &amp; resoun right,</L>
<L>&amp; heuyn blis he has me hight;</L>
<L>To him me aw wirshpid to do<NOTE PLACE="foot">wirshpid <I>st.</I> wirship.</NOTE></L>
<L N="780">&thorn;at swilk grete giftes has gifen me to.</L>
<L>Hir stabill faith &thorn;us when he felde,</L>
<L>His hert gun haly to hir helde.</L>
<L>Vn to hir fader he went bilyue</L>
<L>And said he walde wed hir to wiue.</L>
<L N="785">Hir fader was &thorn;arof full faine;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;us he answerde him ogaine:</L>
<L>To wed hir, sir, will noght a cord,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou es sun to a grete lord</L>
<L>And we er pouer in simple state;</L>
<L N="790">&thorn;ow will nogh(t) wed hir, wele I wate.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> nogh <I>st.</I> noght.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e childe said how his hert was set,</L>
<L>&amp; hir to haue none solde him let.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pure man saw &thorn;an purpose,</L>
<L>And his werk was him lath to lose.</L>
<L N="795">He said: sir, all yf &thorn;ou hir wed,</L>
<L>So may noght be furth with &thorn;e led:</L>
<L>O&thorn;er help bot of hir haue I none,<NOTE PLACE="foot">so = scho.</NOTE></L>
<L>Scho may noght leue me here allone.</L>
<L>&thorn;e childe said: sir, with gud chere</L>
<L N="800">I sall dwell here with zow in fere,</L>
<L>&amp; confourme me to zoure astate,</L>
<L>&amp; do zoure will arely and late.</L>
<L>In pouer wede sone he him cled,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e pouer woman so he wed.</L>
<L N="805">&thorn;ai lifed and died in goddes law.</L>
<L>And, sir, I se wele by &thorn;i saw</L>
<L>&thorn;at to &thorn;is same &thorn;ou profers &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&thorn;at sais &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;ou will wend w<SUP>t</SUP> me</L>
<L>To wildernes, and wote noght whare,</L>
<L N="810">&amp; leue &thorn;i welth and &thorn;i wele fare.</L>
<L>&thorn;an Josaphat un to him said:</L>
<L>&thorn;is tale may wele to me be laid:</L>
<L>All likyng will I leue here stil</L>
<L>And wende with &thorn;e who so &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> will.</L>
<L N="815">Bot, fader, tell me, and none els,</L>
<L>How olde &thorn;ou ert, and whore &thorn;ou duels?</L>
<L>Berlam answerde on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>I am olde fourety and fyue zere,</L>
<L>In wildernes I dwell sertaine.</L>
<L N="820">&thorn;an Josaphat answerde ogaine:</L>
<L>Fader, &thorn;ine elde yf &thorn;ou wolde ken,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou semes of sexty zeres and ten.</L>
<L>&thorn;an berlam sais: yf all ware tolde</L>
<L>Sen I was born, I am so olde;</L>
<L N="825">Bot ferrer zeres none tell I can</L>
<L>Bot sen tyme I was cristes man;</L>
<L>&thorn;at o&thorn;er tyme I tell for dede,</L>
<L>For to me standes it in no stede.</L>
<L>&thorn;an Josaphat fast made him boun</L>
<L N="830">With berlam for to wende of toun</L>
<L>To wildernes, whore he wolde go.</L>
<L>He said: sun, it may noght be so,</L>
<L>We myght noght so escape fro skath;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore es better for us bath</L>
<L N="835">&thorn;at &thorn;ou at home here hald &thorn;e still</L>
<L>And cum to me sethin at &thorn;i will.</L>
<L>He baptist him &thorn;ore with his hend</L>
<L>And trouth of crist clerely him kend;</L>
<L>He kissed him &thorn;an als custum es,</L>
<L N="840">And went ogain to wildernes.</L>
<L>And Josaphat &thorn;are dwellid still,</L>
<L>And loued god euer loud and still.</L>
<L>Till at &thorn;e last his fader herd</L>
<L>Of his dere sun how &thorn;at it ferd,</L>
<L N="845">And berlam &thorn;ore had him baptist</L>
<L>And turned him to &thorn;e laws of crist.</L>
<L>So mekill sorow in hert he had</L>
<L>&thorn;at nonekyns myrth myght mak him glad.</L>
<L>His mane un to a frende he mase</L>
<L N="850">And askes his counsaill in &thorn;at case,</L>
<L>In &thorn;is bale what ware best to do.</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he answerde him un to:
<PB REF="00000281.tif" N="237"></L>
<L>My counsaill I tell &thorn;is tyde:</L>
<L>I knau ane hermyt here bi syde</L>
<L N="855">Lyke un to berlam les ne more,</L>
<L>Bot his right name es nachor,</L>
<L>He es like to berlam bot &thorn;e name:</L>
<L>&thorn;i son sall wene he be &thorn;e same</L>
<L>&thorn;at bifore un to him aperd;</L>
<L N="860">And &thorn;at Ermyt &thorn;us sall be lerd:</L>
<L>To &thorn;i sun sall be first declare<NOTE PLACE="foot">be <I>st.</I> he.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e law &thorn;at berlam lered him are,</L>
<L>Sethin sall he o&thorn;er cases controue</L>
<L>And say &thorn;at law es to reproue,</L>
<L N="865">&amp; &thorn;at his techeing was in uaine;</L>
<L>So (s)all &thorn;i son be getyn ogaine.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> so all <I>st.</I> so sall.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here to assent &thorn;ai les and more.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;is frende ordand fast &thorn;erfore:</L>
<L>He tolde &thorn;e childe how &thorn;e kyng had wroght</L>
<L N="870">&thorn;at berlam solde to court be broght;</L>
<L>He gederd him grete company</L>
<L>Efter berlam to spir and spi.</L>
<L>&thorn;ai broght &thorn;is Ermyt nachor hame,</L>
<L>&amp; tolde &thorn;at &thorn;ai had broght berlam.</L>
<L N="875">When Josaphat herd tithinges tell</L>
<L>&thorn;at his mayster was &thorn;am omell,</L>
<L>Full mekill sorow in hert he had.</L>
<L>Bot or &thorn;e morn he was more glad:</L>
<L>&thorn;e haly gaste in preuete</L>
<L N="880">Warned him &thorn;at Jt was noght he.</L>
<L>&thorn;an come &thorn;e kyng sone on &thorn;e morn,</L>
<L>&amp; cald his son furth him biforn.</L>
<L>Dere sun, he sais, efter men tels</L>
<L>In grete erroure and drede &thorn;ou dwels,</L>
<L N="885">And, tite bot &thorn;ou turn &thorn;i thoght,</L>
<L>In mykell bale &thorn;ou has me broght:</L>
<L>Oure goddes, &thorn;ai say, &thorn;ou has forsaken</L>
<L>And to fals law turned and taken,</L>
<L>&thorn;ow leues &thorn;e law &thorn;at turnes to lyght,</L>
<L N="890">And merres me of mayn a myght;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou makes myne eghen both myrk &amp; dym.</L>
<L>&thorn;an Josaphat said &thorn;us to him:</L>
<L>Fader, I haue forsaken myrknes</L>
<L>&amp; taken to lyght &thorn;at lastand es,</L>
<L N="895">Of erroure haue I left &thorn;e law,</L>
<L>&amp; sothfastnes full wele I knaw;</L>
<L>Trauell no more with wordes in uaine,</L>
<L>Fro criste &thorn;ou gettes me neuer ogaine;</L>
<L>&thorn;i hand to &thorn;e heuyn better myght &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> heue</L>
<L N="900">&thorn;an make me cristes law to leue,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e it war a les maystry</L>
<L>&thorn;e mekyll se for to make dri</L>
<L>&thorn;an fro criste for to turn my mode.</L>
<L>&thorn;an &thorn;e kyng for wo was wode.</L>
<L N="905">Allas, he said, who may it be</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is myschefe has made to me?</L>
<L>To &thorn;e more kyndnes haue I kyd</L>
<L>&thorn;an euer fader to his sun dyd,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou has with &thorn;i wikked rede</L>
<L N="910">Made me dole un to &thorn;e dede;</L>
<L>Full suthly was it said bi forn</L>
<L>With clerkes wise, when &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> was born,</L>
<L>&thorn;ai said &thorn;ou solde wirk in &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>Ogaine &thorn;i kyn unright to rise</L>
<L N="915">&amp; to &thorn;i helpers take no hede;</L>
<L>Now find I it fulfild in dede;</L>
<L>&amp; tite bot if &thorn;ou turn &thorn;i thoght,</L>
<L>With bitter bale it sall be boght:</L>
<L>All as I bi fore haue bene &thorn;i frende,</L>
<L N="920">So sall I now schap &thorn;e to shende,</L>
<L>&amp; moste felly &thorn;ou sall be flayd.</L>
<L>&thorn;an Josaphat full softly said:</L>
<L>Sir kyng, whi makes &thorn;ou mykell care</L>
<L>&amp; es so wroth for I wele fare?</L>
<L N="925">Unfaythful fader he es to fele</L>
<L>&thorn;at es wo for his sun es wele;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> sun es <I>st.</I> sunes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Yf &thorn;ou will so ogains me hald,</L>
<L>My fader &thorn;ou sall no more be tald,</L>
<L>Bot fro &thorn;i drede I will draw me</L>
<L N="930">Als I wald fro a nedder fle.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng &thorn;an had so mekyll wo
<PB REF="00000282.tif" N="238"></L>
<L>&thorn;at wordes myght he spede na mo.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> spede <I>st.</I> speke.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot home he hied un to his toure,</L>
<L>&amp; tolde un to his counseloure</L>
<L N="935">All hou he with his sun had spoken,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he wolde on him be wroken.</L>
<L>He answerde &thorn;an &amp; said: sir, nay,</L>
<L>All softly sall &thorn;ou first assay,</L>
<L>For childer er ether for to teche</L>
<L N="940">With wordes fayre &thorn;an w<SUP>t</SUP> full speche.</L>
<L>Sone on &thorn;e morn when it was day,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng to his sun toke &thorn;e way;</L>
<L>He halsed him &amp; kyssed oft,</L>
<L>&amp; sethin he said with wordes soft:</L>
<L N="945">Dere sun, he said, &thorn;ou solde take kepe</L>
<L>&thorn;i fader to honure &amp; to wirshipe,</L>
<L>&amp; namely me, a man of elde;</L>
<L>Who bot my barn solde be my belde?</L>
<L>Sun, wolde &thorn;ou wit what mede it were</L>
<L N="950">&thorn;i fader &amp; moder to wirship here,</L>
<L>&amp; how ill it es &thorn;am to despite,</L>
<L>&thorn;an walde &thorn;ou noght wirk on his wise<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> his <I>st.</I> &thorn;is.</NOTE></L>
<L>To make me haue swilk bitter braid.</L>
<L>&thorn;an answerde Josaphat and said:</L>
<L N="955">Tyme es of luff in ilk a stede</L>
<L>&amp; tyme es als so of hatrede,</L>
<L>Tyme es of pes &amp; tyme of were,</L>
<L>&amp; all euyll tyme es for to forbere,</L>
<L>Bot in no tyme aw us to bow</L>
<L N="960">To &thorn;am &thorn;at in god will noght trow,</L>
<L>Bot titter sall we fro &thorn;am fle,</L>
<L>Fader or moder, who&thorn;er euer it be.</L>
<L>&thorn;an said &thorn;e kyng: sen it es so</L>
<L>&thorn;ow will noght meke &thorn;e me un to,</L>
<L N="965">&thorn;ou sall now&thorn;er haue &thorn;i will, ne I,</L>
<L>Bot bothe acord us to clergy;</L>
<L>I haue berlam in my presoun,</L>
<L>Take zoure counsaile &amp; mak zow bown!</L>
<L>&amp; my counsaile I sall do call,</L>
<L N="970">&amp; lat &thorn;am luke omang &thorn;am all</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er I haue &thorn;e wrang, or &thorn;ow;</L>
<L>&amp; als &thorn;ai tell so sall we trow:</L>
<L>Yf berlam tales be funden trew,</L>
<L>&thorn;an sall I lere &thorn;at law o new;</L>
<L N="975">&amp; yf his fare be funden fals,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou sall trow my law, &amp; he als.</L>
<L>Josaphat said: sir, I assent.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e kyng fast home he went.</L>
<L>His counsaill un to him he cald;</L>
<L N="980">&amp; all assent &thorn;ai for to hald</L>
<L>&thorn;at coueand, &thorn;at was made bifore,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> coneand.</NOTE></L>
<L>How &thorn;at &thorn;e fals Ermyt nachore</L>
<L>Solde first comend fast cristes name,</L>
<L>&amp; sethin he solde reproue &thorn;e same</L>
<L N="985">&amp; graunt him conuicte in &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> case,</L>
<L>&amp; turn &thorn;e child so to his trace.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e morn was all &thorn;is graid.</L>
<L>&amp; Josaphat to nachore said,</L>
<L>Als he his mayster had noght myst,</L>
<L N="990">For all &thorn;aire purpose wele he wist:</L>
<L>My mayster berlam, luke &thorn;ou be</L>
<L>Trew to &thorn;at law &thorn;ou lered me,</L>
<L>&amp; luke fully &thorn;ou it defend</L>
<L>&amp; mayntene it als &thorn;ou me kend,</L>
<L N="995">&amp;, yf &thorn;e will &thorn;e gyf &thorn;ar to,</L>
<L>I sall it luf ay whis I lyf,<NOTE PLACE="foot">whis <I>st.</I> whils.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; I sall styfly with &thorn;e stand</L>
<L>&amp; may(n)tene &thorn;e with hert &amp; hand;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.</I> maytene <I>st.</I> mayntene.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; yf &thorn;ou faintly it for sake,</L>
<L N="1000">On &thorn;e wightly I sal take wrake:</L>
<L>&thorn;i tong w<SUP>t</SUP> my hend I sal out draw</L>
<L>&amp; gyf &thorn;i hert to hundes at gnaw,</L>
<L>&thorn;at o&thorn;er men may ensaumple take</L>
<L>&thorn;aire awin sawes for to forsake,</L>
<L N="1005">Or any kyng sun to bigyle,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ou has done to me &thorn;is while.</L>
<L>&thorn;an nachore understode wele &thorn;are</L>
<L>&thorn;at he was takin in his awin snare,</L>
<L>&amp; fallen he was in his owin pit;</L>
<L N="1010">&thorn;arfore he kest in his awin wit</L>
<L>To &thorn;e kynges son war him better assent
<PB REF="00000283.tif" N="239"></L>
<L>&thorn;an &thorn;ore for to be shamely shent.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng wist how &thorn;ai had puruayd;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore on heght to him he said:</L>
<L N="1015">Let noght oure law for to defend,</L>
<L>Gain call &thorn;at &thorn;ou my sun has kend.</L>
<L>One of &thorn;e maysters stode up &thorn;an,</L>
<L>&amp; said: es &thorn;ou noght &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> same man,</L>
<L>Berlam, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> has &thorn;is wunder wroght</L>
<L N="1020">&amp; &thorn;e kyng son in erroure broght?</L>
<L>Sen kyng &amp; duke &amp; clerk &amp; knyght</L>
<L>Honurs oure goddes, moste of myght,</L>
<L>How durst &thorn;ou take opon &thorn;e so</L>
<L>To exite &thorn;e kyng son &thorn;arfro,</L>
<L N="1025">&amp; so in erroure him to draw?</L>
<L>Nachore answerde un to &thorn;at saw:</L>
<L>Sirs, he said, I am &thorn;at same,</L>
<L>Bot wrangwisely here ze me blame:</L>
<L>None erroure to &thorn;is childe I kend,</L>
<L N="1030">Bot fro erroure I him defend,</L>
<L>I haue him lered ay lastand law;</L>
<L>For all zoure custums wele I knaw:</L>
<L>To rightwise god ze take no kepe,</L>
<L>To diuers thinges ze do wirshipe,</L>
<L N="1035">&thorn;at ze make w<SUP>t</SUP> zoure awin hend,</L>
<L>&amp; trowes &thorn;o mawmettes may zow mend;</L>
<L>&thorn;e caldeis, &thorn;ai will leue and lout<NOTE PLACE="foot">caldeis Chaldaei.</NOTE></L>
<L>To Elementes &thorn;at gose obout;</L>
<L>&thorn;e grekes has loueyng more &amp; les</L>
<L N="1040">In lustes &amp; likynges of &thorn;aire flessh,</L>
<L>Als for &thorn;aire god &thorn;aire hertes &thorn;ai fest</L>
<L>In thing &thorn;at &thorn;aire flessh likes beste;</L>
<L>&amp; folk of Egyp, &thorn;ai enclyne</L>
<L>Un to bestes, als to shepe or swyne,</L>
<L N="1045">And to calues make &thorn;ai sacrifies:</L>
<L>&thorn;us diuers folk on diuers wise</L>
<L>To diuers goddes &thorn;ai do wirshipe;</L>
<L>Bot to a god &thorn;ai solde take kepe;</L>
<L>All cristen men honurs anely</L>
<L N="1050"><ABBR>Jhu</ABBR> crist, god sun all mygty,</L>
<L>&thorn;at for &thorn;aire sake fro heuyn descend</L>
<L>&amp; in a maiden liked to lend,</L>
<L>&amp; sethin of hir he walde be born,</L>
<L>To saue &thorn;am &thorn;at ware fallen biforn,</L>
<L N="1055">Als adam &amp; all his ofspring,</L>
<L>&amp; so to blis &thorn;am for to bring,</L>
<L>Whilk blis sall w<SUP>t</SUP> outen end;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nach</I> sall <I>fehlt</I> be <I>oder</I> laste.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng son &thorn;us haue I kend,</L>
<L>&thorn;us haue I thechid him for to trow,</L>
<L N="1060">&amp; &thorn;is trowth will I euer auow.</L>
<L>&thorn;an was Josaphat full faine</L>
<L>&amp; loued god w<SUP>t</SUP> all his mayne</L>
<L>&thorn;at shewed his law so opinly</L>
<L>Thurgh him &thorn;at was &thorn;arto enmy,</L>
<L N="1065">For he &thorn;at crist had first reproued</L>
<L>Ogains mawmettes swilk maters moued,</L>
<L>&thorn;at all &thorn;o maisters ware so mased</L>
<L>&thorn;at dom &thorn;ai stode als &thorn;ai ware dased:<NOTE PLACE="foot">dom <I>st.</I> domb.</NOTE></L>
<L>So on &thorn;is meruaile all &thorn;ai mused.</L>
<L N="1070">And &thorn;e kyng was so confused:</L>
<L>He ne wist in werld what he myght say.</L>
<L>Bot zit he made a new delay.</L>
<L>Home he bad all men solde wend,</L>
<L>&amp; on &thorn;e morn &thorn;ai solde make end</L>
<L N="1075">&amp; ordaine fully for &thorn;is thing.</L>
<L>&thorn;an Josaphat said to &thorn;e kyng:</L>
<L>Sir, he said, &thorn;an es it right</L>
<L>&thorn;at berlam be with me all nyght,</L>
<L>&thorn;at we may be a wised bi forn</L>
<L N="1080">Of oure answer ogaine to morn;</L>
<L>&amp; cal un to &thorn;e &thorn;i counsaille</L>
<L>To luke what may &thorn;e moste auale,</L>
<L>Or what &thorn;am think es best to do;</L>
<L>&amp;, sir, yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou will noght so,</L>
<L N="1085">Leue &thorn;i counsaile here with me</L>
<L>&amp; lat berlam wend home w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e;</L>
<L>&amp; bot &thorn;ir, sir, yf &thorn;ou refuyces,<NOTE PLACE="foot">bot <I>st.</I> bothe?</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;an malice &amp; no right &thorn;ou vses.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng &thorn;an thinkes in &thorn;a wile</L>
<L N="1090">&thorn;at nachor solde him zut bigyle,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;erfore berlam grauntes he
<PB REF="00000284.tif" N="240"></L>
<L>All &thorn;at nyght with his son solde be.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng &amp; his counsaile went home;</L>
<L>&amp; with &thorn;e childe &thorn;e Ermet come,</L>
<L N="1095">&amp; &thorn;erfore was &thorn;e childe wele paid.</L>
<L>&amp; als sone un to him he said:</L>
<L>Trowes &thorn;ou noght I wote full wele</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i deszaite euer ilk a dele?</L>
<L>To me was warned fulwele bifore:</L>
<L N="1100">&thorn;ou was noght berlam, bot nachore;</L>
<L>I wate my maister berlam es</L>
<L>Wunand all in wildernes;</L>
<L>Luf cristes law now, rede I &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Als my maister has techid me.</L>
<L N="1105">He enfouremed him goddes law to fele.</L>
<L>&amp; nachore grauntes euerilkadele;</L>
<L>He toke baptym w<SUP>t</SUP> gude entent,</L>
<L>&amp; so to wildernes he went;</L>
<L>He honord god on alkyns wise,</L>
<L N="1110">&amp; lifed &amp; enddid in his seruyse.</L>
<L>&thorn;an in &thorn;at cuntre wunand was</L>
<L>A terrand &thorn;at hight theodeas.</L>
<L>When he herd tell of all &thorn;is thing,</L>
<L>He hied him fast un to &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L N="1115">&amp; said: sir kyng, I undertake</L>
<L>&thorn;at I sall ger &thorn;i son for sake</L>
<L>&thorn;e maters &thorn;at he w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e has meld,</L>
<L>&amp; hald &thorn;e law &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> oure faders held;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;erto will I do my paine.</L>
<L N="1120">&thorn;is tithing made &thorn;e kyng ful faine.</L>
<L>Maister, he said, yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou may</L>
<L>Turn my sun to trow oure lay,</L>
<L>I sall do make in &thorn;is same cete</L>
<L>Ane ymage of golde in mynde of &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="1125">I sall make sacrifice &thorn;ar to</L>
<L>And cumand all men to do so.</L>
<L>&thorn;is lurdan &thorn;an &thorn;e kyng &thorn;us leres:</L>
<L>Sir, do down all his officers</L>
<L>&amp; all men &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> now with him dwelles,</L>
<L N="1130">&amp; ger him haue gay damaysels</L>
<L>&amp; ladys, lufliest in land,</L>
<L>Vn to him for to be seruand,</L>
<L>At burd &amp; bed with him to be,</L>
<L>Arely &amp; late, in all degre;</L>
<L N="1135">&amp; I sall ger a spirit gang</L>
<L>Als a chefe mayden &thorn;am omang,</L>
<L>&amp; exite him un to lichery;</L>
<L>So sall he fall sone to foly:</L>
<L>Nothing so sone dessayue him sale.</L>
<L N="1140">&thorn;at sal I proue &thorn;e by a tale:</L>
<L>A king sumtyme in cuntre was,</L>
<L>&amp; had a sun als &thorn;ou now has.</L>
<L>&amp; sone when &thorn;is ilk sun was born,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng cald his clerkes him bi forn,</L>
<L N="1145">He had &thorn;am luke &amp; tell him all</L>
<L>What thing solde of his sun bi fall.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ai said on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>&thorn;is childe bi houes be tendid ten zere</L>
<L>&thorn;at he nouther se son ne mone,</L>
<L N="1150">For, yf he do, he sall als sone</L>
<L>Lose his syght for euermore.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;us &thorn;e kyng ordand &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>To kepe him in ahows of stone,</L>
<L>To ten winters war fully gone.<NOTE PLACE="foot">To <I>st.</I> Forto.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1155">&thorn;ore was he kepid w<SUP>t</SUP> candels lyght,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he of sun had neuer syght;</L>
<L>Of werldly syght &thorn;ore saw he none.</L>
<L>&amp; when ten zeres ware fully gone,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng gert set his sun &thorn;arout,</L>
<L N="1160">&amp; bad bring sere bestes him obut,</L>
<L>&amp; fissh &amp; fewles, wilde &amp; tame,</L>
<L>&amp; gert men neuyn &thorn;am alle bi name.</L>
<L>Siluer &amp; golde he gert furth bring,</L>
<L>Pelure, perre &amp; riche clething.</L>
<L>. . . . .</L></LG>
<P><I>Hiermit bricht das Gedicht leider unvollendet ab; das folgende Blatt fehlt im Ms.</I></P>

